Role of segmental and suprasegmental cues in the perception of Maghrebian accent in French<sep> 1. Introduction<sep> What is commonly meant by “foreign accent” results from the confrontation of two phonological systems in contact — from a mother tongue (L1) and a target language (L2).<sep> Beyond the relations which exist between these languages, a number of psycho- and socio-linguistic factors may come into consideration (even in the perception of a foreign accent ) [8].<sep> This article is devoted to Maghrebian accent (Arabic or Berber) in French.<sep> Is it by chance that the term accent has been chosen to designate a foreign way of speaking?<sep> To this question, which also applies to regional and social accents [15], some authors such as Rossi seem to answer it in the negative [17].<sep> And invariants probably exist, beyond regional differences, between a Parisian and a person from Marseilles speaking English.<sep> If the information carried by the segmental content (properties linked to the sound patterns) often enables us to identify a specific accent , prosody is also essential in language acquisition, and may trigger certain adjustments during second language learning.<sep> While the melodic and rhythmic patterns characteristic of the mother tongue are extracted very early by infants [16], prosody is one of the most long-lasting elements and the most difficult to transmit in a second language.<sep> If phonemic characteristics and prosodic dimensions are important, a foreign accent should reflect both segmental and suprasegmental difficulties (i.e. superimposed on phonemic segments).<sep> Recent studies thus approached the contribution of prosody to the perception of a foreign accent [5; 6].<sep> Likewise, some investigations brought to light the important or even major role of prosody in the identification of regional accents or dialectal varieties [7; 8].<sep> The TIE network (Tone and Intonation in Europe) [10] aims at providing a platform to coordinate the prosodic analyses of European languages and non-standard varieties (including immigrant communities).<sep> A number of studies especially within the framework of the IViE project (Intonational Variation in English) revealed how certain intonational patterns are specific to some English varieties [10].<sep> The AMPER [11] multimedia prosodic atlas of the Romance languages considers French among others: it is a continuation of a series of inquiries concerning different stress patterns in patois from the North/North-East of France, and more generally from the whole French-speaking area [12; 13].<sep> Let us cite a few additional studies on the identification of Arabic dialects [1; 11].<sep> The latter study [15] was carried out using procedures put forth in Ramus’s dissertation [4] on the different rhythmic classes.<sep> Others attempt to elucidate the role of intonation rather than rhythm (TIE and IViE projects in particular).<sep> However, Arabic and Berber prosody has barely been tackled, and remains somewhat of an unexplored field — not to mention analyses of Arabs and Berbers speaking French.<sep> With over 900,000 adult speakers living in Metropolitan France, Arabic is nonetheless the main language other than French spoken in France, before Alsacian (600,000 speakers), according to a recent inquiry [16].<sep> For a discussion on Berber and in particular on Kabyle (Algerian Berber), one can refer to [4].<sep> For our study, aiming to appreciate what constitutes the Maghrebian accent, around 20 native speakers of Arabic, Kabyle and French were recorded.<sep> A perceptual study was conducted to sort out what is perceived when the segmental and suprasegmental features of the different speakers are crossed.<sep> The proposed experiment is described in the following section, with an accent degree evaluation task performed by French listeners and an origin identification task performed by Algerian listeners.<sep> Results are provided in section 3: they suggest that the voice takes precedence over prosody to identify a Maghrebian accent.<sep> 2. EXPERIENCE<sep> 2.1. Material<sep> We instructed 18 speakers to read a 400 word text: 6 Arab (2 Moroccan, 2 Algerian and 2 Tunisian), 6 Kabyle and 6 French speakers living in the Paris region.<sep> The subjects were 25 years old on average, and the Maghrebians had arrived in France for 2 years on average.<sep> Six other speakers of these different origins were recorded, for a learning phase.<sep> All of them were students or young doctors, and there were as many males as females in each group.<sep> The speakers had no precise idea on the present study.<sep> They were requested to read the text of the PFC project (Phonology of Contemporary French) [19], which was split into sentences: this way, if they came up against a sentence or hesitated, they would resume the reading from the beginning of the sentence.<sep> The recordings, made in Orsay in a soundproof booth with a high-quality microphone, were digitised at 22.05 kHz, 16 bits, mono.<sep> We extracted a dozen sentence pairs (the ones stemming from Maghrebian speakers, the others from French speakers or Maghrebian speakers of different origins), normalised the energy and crossed the segmental and suprasegmental characteristics of the different populations.<sep> The sentences were selected on the basis of 3 criteria: - presence of presumed typical (supra)segmental feature, as in previous studies [14]; - matching realisations of liaisons and schwas; - matching realisation of pauses and pitch — even if we can play on the latter parameters.<sep> The sentences, which ranged from 2.4 to 15.7 seconds, were 8.7 seconds long on an average.<sep> 2.2. Prosody transposition: methodology<sep> In order to copy the prosodic parameters from a speaker to another one, a script was written for the PRAAT software (http://www.fon.hum.uva.nl/praat/), which enables signal handling and re-synthesis with the help of the PSOLA algorithm.<sep> It follows the following scheme: extraction and then transplantation, phoneme by phoneme, of durations and then pitch.<sep> Figure 1: Prosody transposition.<sep> Before starting on this phase, a segmentation into phonemes is required: it was made by an expert, under PRAAT, on the basis of perceptual and visual clues — on spectrograms.<sep> The analysis of phoneme durations, pauses and fundamental frequency ( F 0) is then automatic.<sep> After possible manual retouches, the transposition of these parameters amounts to: - checking that the number of segments in the two sentences of the chosen pair are equated; - calculating lengthening or shortening coefficients for each phoneme or pause of a speaker with respect to another one; - for each phoneme or pause, building new durations which will replace the original durations of either sentence; - grafting F 0 from one of the sentences onto the other one, and vice versa.<sep> Two new stimuli are thus obtained: the block diagram of Fig. 1 displays the different steps of the process.<sep> 2.3. Perceptual tests<sep> In order to disentangle the influence of segmental vs. suprasegmental feature in the perception of Maghrebian accent in French, two types of perceptual tests were run: the first one concerns French listeners (with an accent degree estimation task); the second one involves Algerian listeners (with an origin identification task).<sep> The choice in favour of this second population is dictated by their geographical position in the heart of Maghreb and their familiarity with Kabyle.<sep> Not counting a learning phase (or more exactly of familiarisation with the type of stimuli), each test counted about 40 stimuli, whether original or resulting from the different prosody transpositions.<sep> Each experiment lasted about 15 minutes.<sep> The listeners, who were not paid, not specialists in linguistics and had no known hearing problems, could take as much time as they wanted to answer, but were only allowed to listen once.<sep> The tests were conducted in the Paris region, in a quiet room, over headphones, through the E-prime software, which offers a user-friendly interface to read the instructions, listen to the stimuli and capture the answers.<sep> Firstly, native French listeners were asked to rate the degree of accentedness on a 9-point scale (from 0 to 8).<sep> 0 represents standard Parisian French, without any marked accent; 1 designates a very mild accent (only punctually marked); 2 a mild accent; 3 a moderate accent; 4 an average accent; 5 a rather strong accent; 6 a strong accent; 7 a very strong accent; and mark 8 designates so strong an accent that it poses intelligibility problems.<sep> The learning corpus is composed of 10 stimuli, providing landmarks to assess the degree of accentedness of male and female natural voices as well as prosody modifications not used in the sequel.<sep> As for the test, it comprises 42 randomised stimuli (18 originals + 24 French-Maghrebian crossings).<sep> Secondly, 15 native Algerian listeners were asked to identify the origin (Kabyle, Moroccan, Algerian or Tunisian Arab) of the speakers they would hear.<sep> The listeners, who had arrived in France for 3 years on average, did not know the used voices.<sep> The learning corpus is composed of 4 stimuli, giving a sample of male and female voices of Moroccan, Algerian, Tunisian or Kabyle Arabian origin, as well as prosody transplantations not used in the remainder of the trial.<sep> As for the test, it comprises 40 randomised stimuli (12 Maghrebian originals + 12 Maghrebian-French crossings + 16 inter-Maghrebian crossings).<sep> 3. Results<sep> 3.1. Test with French listeners<sep> The test conducted with French listeners shows that the Maghrebian accent , rated as average (about 4 out of 8) is judged as stronger after prosody modification: this artifact is due to the acoustic degradation, which listeners judge even though their orders were not to concentrate on it.<sep> The weak degree (<1) attributed to the original French speakers reassures us about the methodology.<sep> But above all, if we compare all other things being equal, a Maghrebian voice with a French prosody is judged as having a stronger accent degree than a French voice with a Maghrebian prosody.<sep> The difference is highly significant according to a bilateral paired t -test ( df =179; p <0.01), and it is more important than between original/modified Maghrebian voices (see Table 1).<sep> Table 1 : Degree of accentedness judged by 15 French listeners, on a 0-8 scale.<sep> This tendency in favour of a greater role played by segmental cues is illustrated by the Maghrebians’ tendency to pronounce [i] for /e/, for example in the word télévision .<sep> Formant measures confirm this fact (with F1 values in the order of 300 Hz for Algerians), while if we compare F 0 targets and phoneme durations, we can see that these ones are very close even between sentences which seemed to indicate a reliable effect of prosody.<sep> If segmentals override suprasegmentals in what is perceived as a Maghrebian accent , the question which naturally arises is to know to what extent the articulation of phonemes enables us to identify the origin within Maghreb of this accent .<sep> Preliminary tests showed that French listeners albeit familiarised with the Maghrebian accent found it hard to distinguish Arabian and Kabyle accents : hence the follow-up test.<sep> 3.2. Test with Algerian listeners<sep> The results of the test conducted with Maghrebian listeners reveal the difficulty in identifying the origin of the stimuli taken as a whole, even for Algerians (see Table 2).<sep> This is at variance with the listeners’ impression that they can easily recognise a Kabyle speaker, for instance, whose L1 is not Arabic.<sep> Now the Kabyle origin is not better recognised than chance level (25%).<sep> Only the Moroccan origin (by more than 56%) is well recognised, and highly significantly better than chance (according to a ² test, df =3, p <0.01).<sep> As for the speakers’ origin with respect to their prosody, it is even more poorly recognised.<sep> Table 2 : Identification scores of the origin of 12 speakers with respect to their segmentals — in row the origin of voices, in column responses (%).<sep> A principal component analysis was performed, so as to determine the influence of sentence length and accent degree (rated by the 15 French listeners) on the Algerian listeners’ judgements, in terms of correct answers on the voices of various origins.<sep> The following r correlation coefficients were found: respectively -0.15 (no correlation) and 0.40 (weak correlation, as confirmed by a comparison with Student’ s t - distribution tables [ t 0.95>1.39; p >0.05]).<sep> Table 3 : Identification scores of the origin of the Maghrebian speakers having a strong accent with respect to their segmentals.<sep> Percentages are given with respect to 15 listeners × 4 types of prosody per voice.<sep> If however we extract the speakers of each origin judged as having the strongest accent according to the French listeners, we can observe better origin identification scores — even if these ones are established from smaller data.<sep> The accent degrees are 4.2 for the Moroccan speaker, 4.0 for the Algerian Arab speaker, 7.0 for the Kabyle speaker and 4.5 for the Tunisian speaker.<sep> Results on the basis of their sole voices (their segmentals, whatever the prosody) are very revealing (see Table 3): the identification scores of the Moroccan and Kabyle origins are highly significantly above chance (according to a X2 test, df =3, p <0.01).<sep> The Tunisian origin is also recognised with scores significantly above chance (according to a ² test, df =3, p <0.05).<sep> Only the Algerian Arabian origin is poorly recognised.<sep> By and far, also, the prosody of these speakers having a rather strong accent , when applied to various voices, is not so well recognised in the confusion matrix of Table 4 below as it is in Table 3.<sep> The same happens with Kabyle, which again suggests that the very strong accent degree (7 out of 8) would be due to segmentals rather than suprasegmentals.<sep> The Moroccan and Tunisian origins are rather well identified, but the results are not (highly) significant.<sep> The Algerian Arab origin, for its part, remains poorly recognised.<sep> Table 4 : Identification scores of the origin of the Maghrebian speakers having a strong accent with respect to their prosody.<sep> Percentages are given with respect to 15 listeners × 3 voices per type of prosody.<sep> 4. Conclusion<sep> At the end of this analysis and given the achieved results, segmental factors seem to be more relevant than prosody in the perception of Maghrebian accent in French.<sep> Segmental parameters take the first place a fortiori when speakers have a strong accent .<sep> Nevertheless, the accent origin identification, except for the strongest accents , proves delicate: this is in keeping with earlier studies on the identification of Maghrebian dialects , within which a considerable variability is prevalent [14].<sep> Interestingly however, the Moroccan accent origin is honourably recognised: better than the Kabyle origin, despite a lower accent degree, and although Kabyle speakers have a mother tongue which distinguishes them from other Maghrebian speakers, of Arabic L1.<sep> The question this raises deserves to be addressed more thoroughly, as well as the perception of Maghrebian vs Middle Eastern accents in French, with more speakers and listeners.<sep> And perhaps the results would be different on spontaneous speech rather than read speech: it is fitting to remain cautious.<sep> THANKS<sep> We thank C. Gendrot for the script under PRAAT.
In this paper we propose a new approach to language modeling based on dynamic Bayesian networks.<sep> 1. Introduction<sep> The role of a statistical language model is to model different linguistic events in a language.<sep> This is achieved by assigning a probability to each word sequence hw t (where h represents the history of word wt ).<sep> These probabilities are estimated using a Markov chain of some fixed order ( usually 1 or 2 ).<sep> n-grams formulated as Markov chains are the most widely used language models.<sep> Based on the observation that certain words have similar behavior, one can think of clustering words into classes and construct n-class models to substitute or complement n-grams.<sep> The objective is to reduce the complexity of the basic models, to generalise them, to go beyond the limits of missing data and to introduce more important linguistic knowledge (morphological, syntactic, semantic and others).<sep> The exploitation of different linguistic knowledge can be done by a simple linear combination of different language models [4] or by the use of maximum entropy [7].<sep> As it will become clear in the following sections, n- gram and n-class models are actually particular cases of dynamic Bayesian networks (DBN).<sep> In this paper we propose to use the DBN formalism in order to achieve a better exploitation of each linguistic unit considered in modeling.<sep> We develop a unifying approach that processes each of these units in one model and construct new language models with improved performance.<sep> The principle of our approach is to construct DBNs in which a variable (word, class or any other linguistic unit) may depend on a set of context variables.<sep> These dependence links between linguistic units can be determined automatically or manually.<sep> Our ultimate goal is to propose an automatic scheme to learn the optimal DBN structure from a training corpus.<sep> With this goal in mind, in this paper we investigate the feasibility of our approach by first testing models for which the structure of the corresponding RBD is specified manually.<sep> The advantage of our approach with respect to linear interpolation is that, instead of using a weighted average of models constructed over words and classes separately, our approach integrates all linguistic units in one model without any distinction between classes and words.<sep> Compared to the maximum entropy principle, we can say that our approach yields models that are much easier to interpret.<sep> 2. Dynamic Bayesian networks<sep> Our approach is based on the framework of dynamic Bayesian networks (DBNs) which is a generalization of Bayesian networks (BNs) to dynamic processes.<sep> Briefly, the Bayesian networks formalism consists of associating a directed acyclic graph to the joint probability distribution (JPD) P ( X ) of a set of random variables X = {X 1 , …, Xn} .<sep> The nodes of this graph represent the random variables, while the arrows encode the conditional independences (CI) which (are supposed to) exist in the JPD.<sep> A Bayesian network is completely defined by a graph structure S and the numerical parametrization Θ of the conditional probabilities of the variables given their parents.<sep> Indeed, the JPD can be expressed in a factored way as P ( X ) = Π ni =1 [P][(] [X][i][|][Π] [i][)], where Π [i] denotes the parents of [ X][i] in [ S] .<sep> A DBN encodes the joint probability distribution of a time evolving set X [ t ] = {X 1 [ t ] , … , Xn [ t ] } of variables.<sep> If we do not fix T, the DBN can be considered as a (static) BN with T × n variables.<sep> Using the factorization property of BNs, the joint probability density of X [T] 1[=]<sep> where Π it denotes the parents of Xi [ t ].<sep> In the literature, DBNs are defined using the assumption that X [ t ] is Markovian (Friedman et al., 1998).<sep> In this paper, we relax this hypothesis to allow non-Markov processes and we consider that the process X [ t ] satisfies:<sep> for some positive integers τp and τf .<sep> Graphically, the above assumption states that a variable at time t can have parents in the interval [ t − τp, t + τf ] (see (Deviren and Daoudi, 2001) for details).<sep> From this perspective, it is obvious that classical language models can be represented as DBNs.<sep> Indeed, n -gram models assume that the probability of a word sequence is factorized over the conditional probabilities of each word in the sequence given its recent history of n− 1 words.<sep> That is, if W is the word vocabulary and w 1 [T][=][w][1] […w][T][∈] [W][ T] is a word sequence, one assumes that:<sep> Thus, if Wt is a discrete random variable taking its values in V for every t , n -grams can be represented as the DBN shown in Fig. 1-(a) (for n = 3, i.e., trigram).<sep> Class-based approaches represent the history on word classes rather than words.<sep> That is, if C = {l 1 , …, lm} is the set of class labels and c[T] 1[=] [c][1] […c][T][∈] [C][T] is an observed class sequence, one assumes that:<sep> Thus, if Ct is a discrete random variable taking its values in C for every t , n -class models can be represented as the DBN shown in Fig. 1-(b) (for n = 2, i.e., bi-class).<sep> Figure 1: tri-gram and bi-class models<sep> 3. DBNs for language modeling<sep> n-gram and n-class models are the most commonly used language models in state-of-the-art speech recognition systems.<sep> N-grams have proven their efficiency when they are learned on large data sets.<sep> The principle inconvenience of these models is that they are computationally very demanding given that they require |V |[n] probabilities to be estimated, where V is the vocabulary and n is the model order.<sep> Despite the “cut-off” techniques that reduce the complexity, these models remain extremely complex.<sep> On the other hand n-class models are less complex since the number of classes is generally much smaller than the vocabulary size.<sep> They also allow for better generalization.<sep> Nevertheless, they are less accurate and their perplexity is higher.<sep> For this reason they are often combined with n-grams.<sep> In such circumstances the realization of a language model is performed first by specifying the model order ( n ) and then the two models ( n-gram and n- class) are trained individually using maximum likelihood criteria.<sep> The next step is to linearly combine the models or integrate their respective characteristics in a single architecture using maximum entropy techniques.<sep> This approach yields quite interesting results, however if we want to better exploit the lexical and syntactic information, a solution would be to consider them in a unique model that is trained within a single procedure.<sep> In the approach we propose, we first want the “order” of the model to be determined automatically from the learning data.<sep> Then, since a word is influenced by its lexical and syntactic context, we propose to take this linguistic influence directly into account in the estimation of the word to predict.<sep> The DBN formalism provides a theoretical and computational framework to achieve our goal.<sep> Our principle idea is to impose no a priori hypothesis on the way a language should be represented but to consider all available data (words, classes, …) as observations of the dynamic system {Wt, Ct} . Our goal then is to find the model that has the best description (in terms of perplexity) of these observations.<sep> In this way, we let data dictate what influences the pronunciation of a word.<sep> In Bayesian networks terminology this is the structure learning problem: find the graph structure (and its numerical parameterization) that explains the data at ‘’best”.<sep> There are algorithms [6] that attempt to solve this (difficult) problem and that work more or less well depending on the applications.<sep> Our objective in this paper is not to use these algorithms (knowing that our ultimate goal is to develop a structure learning algorithm that is well adapted to language modeling).<sep> Our objective is rather to check whether our approach could effectively compete with classical n-gram and n-class models.<sep> To do this, we consider a rich set of graph structures that we judge to be plausible for language modeling.<sep> We then evaluate the performance of several DBNs in this set on a concrete application and compare them to n-gram and n-class models.<sep> 3.1. Proposed set of structures<sep> In order to define a set of graphical structures plausible for language modeling, we need to specify CI assertions that are linguistically informative and easy to interpret.<sep> To do so we start by relaxing the CI assumptions of n-class models. We assume that a word does not only depend on its class but also on the classes of words in a limited past and/or future context.<sep> To incorporate the properties of n-grams, we also authorize the dependence of a word to its lexical history.<sep> And finally we consider that a class may not only depend on its history but also on the current word and/or other words in a limited past and/or future context.<sep> Figure 2 shows an example of a possible RBD in our modeling.<sep> FIG. 2: RBD where each word (resp. class) depends on the previous, present and future class (resp. previous).<sep> TABLE 1: Perplexity of Dynamic Bayesian Networks<sep> The joint probability for a specific model is expressed as:<sep> where πwt (resp. πct ) is a realization of the parents Π Wt (resp. Π Ct ) of Wt (resp. Ct ).<sep> The numerical parameterization of the model is given by conditional probability tables (independent of time t ) P ( wt|πwt ) and P ( ct|πct ) that we note, for Xt ∈ {Wt, Ct}, by:<sep> These parameters are estimated using maximum likelihood criterion that yields :<sep> where Nx,j, k is the number of realizations of Xt = j, Π Xt = k .<sep> The classical “discounting”, “smoothing” and “back-off” techniques remain applicable to this type of models.<sep> 3.2. Experiments and evaluation<sep> The training and test corpus are extracted from Le monde newspaper.<sep> We used 22M words for training and a test corpus of 2M words.<sep> The vocabulary consists of the most frequent 5000 words.<sep> The training corpus has been labeled automatically by a set of 200 syntactic classes set by hand (Sma¨ıli et al., 1999).<sep> All models used in the experiments are smoothed using the absolute discounting method (Ney et al., 1994).<sep> Table 1 shows the perplexity results of 14 different dynamic Bayesian networks.<sep> The models DBN1, DBN2 and DBN3 correspond to bi-gram, bi-class and triclass models respectively.<sep> In order to achieve our objective to find the best language models, we took the biclass model as a baseline and extended it incrementally by incorporating additional lexical and/or syntactic context.<sep> We also introduce the concept of right context of a word.<sep> This is the case of the RBD6 model that integrates not only the left context of the class of a word but also its right syntactic context.<sep> We obtain a 16.6% improvement with respect to DBN4 that proves the importance of right context.<sep> It is true that linguistically this is not a surprising result.<sep> On the other hand, it is difficult to realize the use of right context in speech recognition, but this could be achieved with a multi-pass decoding scheme.<sep> On the other hand, the RBD5 model shows that the influence of the left context is important, which is why its omission reduces the results by 7.8%.<sep> A significant perplexity reduction is observed if a word not only depends on its syntactic but also lexical context.<sep> Indeed, DBN11 yields an improvement of 24.6% with respect to DBN4.<sep> This confirms that lexical history is indispensable and that syntactic history provides a significant contribution.<sep> Pushing this strategy even further, we have achieved a model that is not only much better than the bi-class but also better than the bi-gram.<sep> Indeed, the model RBD14, whose graphic structure is shown in figure 3, improves by 57.9% with respect to RDB2 and 2.4% with respect to RBD1 (bi-gram).<sep> Even if the improvement compared to the bigram is not significant (in this application), this result (in addition to the previous ones) shows above all that our approach can indeed lead to new categories of language models that can compete with classical categories.<sep> Figure 3: DBN structure that yields smaller perplexity w.r.t. bi-gram.<sep> 4. Conclusion and perspectives<sep> We presented a new approach for language model construction based on dynamic Bayesian networks formalism.<sep> This approach has several advantages with respect to classical techniques.<sep> First of all, it infers the best model for language from training data in such a way that the resulting model is the best explanation of the corpus and it is not constrained by a priori assumptions.<sep> Another advantage is that all linguistic units considered in modeling are handled in one procedure.<sep> Hence the resulting models are consistent and easy to interpret.<sep> In this paper we tested different DBN structures in order to evaluate the potential of our approach.<sep> The results are promising and further detailed experiments are necessary to obtain better performance.<sep> Other experiments of the same kind must obviously be carried out to better analyse the behaviour of this technique.<sep> But our main objective is to develop an algorithm that automatically infers the best DBN for the language under consideration from training data.<sep> This will be the main direction of our future work.
Prosodic aspects of spoken French in Alsace, Belgium and Switzerland<sep> ABSTRACT<sep> These descriptions are lacking in precision.<sep> Singy's, for example [11], may suggest an initial accent, but does not allow the departure with a specific melodic pattern on the penultimate syllable.<sep> The considerable resources we have at our disposal today and the advances in the field of automatic speech processing allow us to test different linguistic hypotheses.<sep> In the following, we will examine the prosodic configurations in the initial and penultimate syllables through a large corpus that allows us to compare Alsatian, Belgian and Swiss French with "standard" French.<sep> We will first describe the corpus analyzed.<sep> We will then successively address initial stress and the behavior of the penultimate syllable, before concluding.<sep> 1. Introduction<sep> This article is a corpus-based study of prosodic variation in the French language as spoken in Alsace, Belgium and Romand Switzerland.<sep> Linguistic publications concerning these regions essentially focus on language contact, diglossia and resulting code switchings [2][7][11].<sep> Some work on phonetic/ phonological pecularities exists [13][10], but there are fewer prosodic studies.<sep> Other languages [12] or French varieties [4] have been approached from the angle of prosody.<sep> Carton et al. [4] in particular highlighted the role of penultimate syllable in the perception of an eastern (Lorraine) or northern French accent.<sep> The lengthening of the vowel nuclei of penultimate and final syllables has also been studied for the French variety spoken in Belgium (especially Liège) [7].<sep> Concerning the prosody of Alsatian French, it has been noted that the Germanic stress, usually word-initial, sharply contrasts with the word-final French stress [13].<sep> For the French variety spoken in Romand Switzerland, a resistance to the standard French accentual scheme or a tendency to initial stress in disyllabic words may be mentioned [11].<sep> According to other scholars, this Swiss variety presents a more marked melodic movement on penultimate syllables than standard French [6] or a "pitch rise on the syllable preceding word-final stress" [10] (a feature shared with other varieties according to the latter author).<sep> 2. Corpus and method<sep> 2.1. Corpus<sep> The main corpus stems from the “Phonology of Contemporary French” (PFC) project [5].<sep> This project has undertaken to cover a wide territory, through informants (about ten per investigation point) who are firmly rooted geographically.<sep> For the present study, data were analysed from 11 investigation points: 6 in the North of the Loire, considered as standard French (Brécey, Brunoy, Dijon, Lyon-Villeurbanne, Roanne, Treize-Vents), 1 in Alsace (Boersch), 3 in Belgium (Tournai, Gembloux, Liège) and 1 in Romand Switzerland (Canton de Vaud).<sep> The data come from over 150 speakers, as many males as females of different age categories (45 years old on average).<sep> For each speaker, we have at our disposal scripted speech (the reading of a 20-sentence text), as well as 10 minutes of spontaneous speech (directed interviews and free conversations).<sep> The total amount of data represents almost 100 hours of speech.<sep> For this study, we have not analysed the spontaneous speech of the PFC project Alsatian speakers.<sep> On the other hand, we completed our corpus by adding 40 telephone conversations between Alsatian speakers (1/3 male).<sep> The average duration of a conversation is 13 minutes, totalling about 4 hours of speech.<sep> From the same corpus, telephone conversations between standard French speakers (over 30 hours of data) were also used for comparison.<sep> The figures recorded in the following tables, however, all refer to the PFC corpus, except for Alsatians’ spontaneous speech.<sep> 2.2. Automatic alignment and feature extraction<sep> The orthographically transcribed corpus was phonemically segmented by automatic alignment [1], using different context-independent acoustic models adapted to telephone or non-telephone speech.<sep> The segmentation allows us to calculate the average durations of the phonemes (see Table 1).<sep> Whether considering all phone segments (pauses excluded) or only vowels or consonants, the Swiss and Alsatian speakers show a slightly slower speech rate than the other speakers, particularly in spontaneous speech.<sep> This feature is sometimes cited as characteristic of the Swiss accent (or at least its representations); here it is also observed for Alsatians.<sep> Table 1. Average segment duration [standard deviations] (in ms) for the text reading and spontaneous speech (for vowel, consonant, both).<sep> The fundamental frequency ( F 0) was extracted by using the standard options of the PRAAT software (www.praat.org): for instance, values under a 75 Hz threshold are considered as undefined.<sep> The mean value of measurements taken every 10 ms was then computed in order to obtain one F 0 value per phone segment.<sep> 3. Word-initial stress<sep> To characterise initial stress, clitic–nonclitic sequences, which are good candidates to receive a stress on the nonclitic wordinitial syllable [1] were examined.<sep> For clitics, we kept a set of about 30 monosyllabic words among the most frequent French words: le, la, les (“the) , un, une (“a”) , de (“of”) , du, des (“some”) , en (“in”) , pour (“to”) … These words allow for a good coverage of the selected pattern [3].<sep> For non-clitics, we have restricted the study to polysyllabic words (without counting the final schwa which can be pronounced).<sep> F 0 and duration variations between the clitic vowel and the first vowel of the following nonclitic word were measured, as well as the duration of the nonclitic onset.<sep> For example, in the case of the sequence pour trouver (/pu t uve/, “to find”), the vowel nuclei are the two /u/s and the onset is /t /.<sep> 3.1. Differences in F0<sep> We computed the cumulative percentages of occurrences in which the fundamental frequency F 0 = F 0 non-clitic – F 0 clitic in semitones (ST) was greater than a given threshold.<sep> Table 2 shows results for F 0 percentages greater than 1, 2 and 3 semitones (3 semitones corresponding to the threshold above which a prosodic prominence can play a linguistic role [14]).<sep> The numbers of occurences from which percentages are computed are also reported, for the read texts and spontaneous speech.<sep> For all speech styles and thresholds, it can be seen that percentages are greater for the Swiss than for the other speakers.<sep> The phenomenon can easily be observed in the distribution curve (not shown here due to lack of space).<sep> It is however more marked for the text read: in Table 2, the difference with standard French reaches 20%, as compared to 14% for spontaneous speech.<sep> On the contrary, the values obtained for Alsace and Belgium are lower than those of standard French.<sep> As a comparison, the values computed on the telephone speech corpus for standard French are the same as the ones presented here within a margin of 3%.<sep> Table 2. Number of occurrences and percentage of non-clitic clitic F 0 greater than a given threshold.<sep> Results go the same way when the analysis is restricted to non-clitic words of at least 3 syllables instead of considering all polysyllabic words. (The number of occurrences is of course lower.)<sep> The ranking is preserved: Switzerland, standard French, Belgium and Alsace from the greatest to the lowest percentages.<sep> 3.2. Differences in duration<sep> The difference Δduration = duration nonclitic – duration clitic was calculated for vowels.<sep> Results for polysyllabic and at least trisyllabic words are presented in Table 3.<sep> Alsatians show the highest percentage of time above each of the proposed thresholds (0 and 20 ms) in spontaneous speech and to a lesser extent in reading.<sep> The same tendency is observed with a 30 ms threshold.<sep> When the nonclitics are restricted to at least trisyllabic words, which allows us to distinguish between initial and penultimate syllables, the difference between Alsatians speakers and the others is more marked.<sep> Table 3: Number of occurrences and percentage of non-clitic (polysyllabic and at least trisyllabic) clitic duration above a given threshold.<sep> In the standard French telephone corpus, the values obtained are similar to those of Table 3 (within 5%).<sep> Percentages of the PFC corpus, which leaves a 10% difference between Alsatian and standard French.<sep> We may consider that the difference observed is not only due to the corpus.<sep> Average durations of the clitic vowels and the subsequent nonclitic word-initial vowels are given in Table 4.<sep> The average duration of the clitic nucleus is indicated even though it does not add much information: we simply notice that there is little cross-region variation of this average duration, especially in spontaneous speech.<sep> As for the first vowel of the content word that follows, it behaves as expected from calculations: Alsatians have the longest average durations, which is not only attributable to a slower speech rate because Swiss speakers, who also have a slow speaking rate, exhibit a very different behaviour when reading texts.<sep> 3.3. Lengthening of the attack<sep> According to [9][8], onset lengthening is a correlate of wordinitial stress.<sep> The average duration of content word onsets following a clitic were measured: results are given in Table 4 (also restricted to simple onsets).<sep> The number of contexts considered in each case can be deducted from the figures reported in Table 3, from which clitic–nonclitic sequences without onset (about 15% of cases) must be subtracted.<sep> Contexts with a simple onset represent about 2/3 of the numbers of occurrences given in Table 3.<sep> Alsatians, who produce the longest polysyllabic wordinitial vowels following clitics, do not seem to lengthen onsets,whereas the Swiss tend to have longer onsets.<sep> Thus, initial stress for the Swiss speakers seems to be achieved by a pitch rise and a slight onset lengthening — features which are well described in the literature [9][8].<sep> Alsatians instead show polysyllabic word-initial vowel lengthening.<sep> Whether these features should be interpreted in terms of word-initial stress or differently, our results suggest that acoustic correlates differentiate the prosody of French varieties spoken in Alsace and Romand Switzerland.<sep> Belgium shows little specificity compared to standard French with regard to these parameters; but it might be distinguished by other prosodic features.<sep> Table 4: Mean duration in ms of the core of the clitic (Vc), the core (Vnc) and the onset of the first syllable of the non-clitic, polysyllabic or at least trisyllabic.<sep> In parentheses, only simple attacks are taken into account.<sep> 4. PREPAUSED SYLLABLES<sep> The behaviour of penultimate and final syllables before a pause was examined.<sep> We did not observe marked regiondependent tendencies concerning pitch variation between penultimate and final syllables.<sep> Nevertheless, the percentage of penultimate vowels that are longer than final vowels (schwa excluded) allows us to capture a kind of penultimate lengthening.<sep> This percentage is given for each region in Table 5 with the average durations of the vowel nuclei of the two syllables preceding a pause (we considered as pauses the silences of more than 50 ms).<sep> Similar patterns are obtained when the duration of each vowel is normalised by its average duration computed on the whole corpus.<sep> In reading, the percentages are quite close between regions, whether or not one limits oneself to words of three syllables or more.<sep> This configuration avoids confusion between initial and penultimate lengthening.<sep> Results differ more on spontaneous speech: Belgian speakers (from Liège, Tounai and Gembloux) realise more f = durationpenultimate – durationfinal > 0 ms than standard French speakers (around 10% difference), while Alsatian and Swiss speakers produce fewer penultimate lengthenings.<sep> Yet the differences observed should be taken with caution as far as Alsatians’ spontaneous speech is concerned.<sep> Indeed, if the figures for standard French were very close between PFC and the telephone corpus regarding initial stress, considerable variation is here observed, with 12–18% lower percentages for the telephone corpus.<sep> These differences may be due to the type of interaction which, in telephone conversations, favours final lengthening especially at the end of speaker turns.<sep> Table 5. Number of occurrences and percentage of duration of f (penultimate–final) positive before a pause, as well as the durations of the last two vowels in ms.<sep> Nasal vowels are known to be longer than oral vowels (112 vs 80 ms on average, in our corpus).<sep> Indeed, the gap slightly widens (reaching 15%) between Belgian and standard French speakers when considering polysyllabic words whose penultimate vowel is a nasal vowel.<sep> On average, the Swiss have quite long final vowels.<sep> In comparison to standard French, they also have long penultimate vowels, which explains the lower f values.<sep> The latter result does not support a tendency toward penultimate lengthening in Romand Switzerland.<sep> It seems that the Swiss lengthen both the antepenultimate and the last vowel.<sep> 5. Discussion and perspectives<sep> Automatic alignment of large spoken corpora and pitch tracking enabled us to reveal or at least quantify prosodic differences between French varieties spoken in Alsace, Belgium and Romand Switzerland.<sep> While prepausal penultimate vowel lengthening seems to be typical of Belgian speech, lengthening the last two syllables and a tendency to initial stress (pitch rise and onset lengthening) would rather characterise Romand Swiss contrary to certain predictions.<sep> In Alsace, what can also be interpreted as initial stress under the influence of language contact would be manifested by wordinitial vowel lengthening.<sep> In spite of different data sources for Alsace (which may also be viewed as an additional validation), these acoustic correlates appear to be relatively robust to style changes (scripted or spontaneous speech).<sep> The study should of course be continued for this region and enriched by consonant devoicing cues.<sep> Voicing rates, zero-crossing rates and the alignment of voiced consonants as unvoiced should allow this devoicing to be measured.<sep> Finally, the same type of analysis may be extended to the intensity parameter.<sep> 6. Acknowledgements<sep> This work was carried out as part of the ANR PFC-Cor project.<sep> We are grateful to A-C Simon for the recordings made in Alsace applying the PFC protocol.<sep> Our thanks also go to the leaders of this vast project.
Lexical-phonetic automata for spoken utterance indexing and retrieval<sep> ABSTRACT<sep> This paper[1] presents a method for indexing spoken utterances which combines lexical and phonetic hypotheses in a hybrid index built from automata.<sep> The search is done by a semi-imperfect lexical-phonetic matching that tolerates certain imperfections to improve the recall.<sep> A feature vector, containing edit distance scores and a confidence measure, weights each transition to help the filtering of the candidate utterance list for a more precise search.<sep> Experiment results show that the lexical and phonetic representations are complementary and their interest in searching for named entity queries.<sep> Index Terms : information retrieval, speech indexing, lexical-phonetic automata, confidence measures, edit distances, supervised learning<sep> 1. Introduction<sep> Spoken content retrieval [1] relies on the fields of automatic speech recognition (ASR) and information retrieval (IR).<sep> However, IR tools made for text are not adapted to automatic transcripts which are particularly noisy due to their incomplete and uncertain nature.<sep> Indeed, these transcripts contain many recognition errors affecting notably out-of-vocabulary words (OOV) and named entities (NE) that convey important discourse information (e.g. , person names, localisations, organisations) necessary for IR.<sep> Two kinds of approaches can be used to attenuate these drawbacks.<sep> First, the recall can be improved by using a lower level of representation consisting in sub-words ( e.g. , syllables, phonemes) to represent OOV words and, more generally, all types of lexical errors.<sep> Representations denser than a simple transcript can also be used, such as graphs, confusion networks and N-best lists.<sep> Second, the precision can be improved by estimating confidence measures that indicate the degree of reliability of the recognition, thus allowing to filter out the noise.<sep> We are interested in combining the two approaches for a task of spoken utterance retrieval.<sep> This task consists in retrieving, in a spoken content set, all the segments (called utterances) containing a given textual query.<sep> Two strategies are used in state-of-the-art systems to combine efficiently both lexical and phonetic levels for searching.<sep> The first one considers two separated indexes used in “cascade”, i.e. , the search is, by default, based on the lexical index and can fall back on the phonetic one if necessary (Saraclar et Sproat, 2004), which allows to avoid the noise of the phonetic search in most cases.<sep> The second approach models the two levels in one hybrid index [3, 4], offering the advantage of a possible lexicon-phonetic matching between the query and the index.<sep> The proposed method takes up the idea of a hybrid index because it can tolerate lexical-phonetic matchings that are impossible with two separate indexes.<sep> The index structure is based on automata as they can represent all types of ASR outputs.<sep> The originality of the method consists in the weighting of automaton transitions with a vector of descriptors that can be used to estimate the relevance of the candidate utterances for a given query.<sep> The features used include: edit distance scores (counts of correct symbols, deletions, insertions, substitutions) calculated by a semi-imperfect matching transducer that tolerates certain imperfections of the representations; and a confidence measure indicating the reliability of the recognized symbols.<sep> The experiments conducted compare the performances between the cascaded and hybrid searches to retrieve named entity queries.<sep> We will first present the method (section 2), then the results of the experiments (section 3) and finally conclude the paper (section 4). FIG. 1 – General view of the proposed method.<sep> 2. Method proposed<sep> The proposed method is based on the general indexing of weighted automata presented by Allauzen et al. [5] and adapted for the case of lexical-phonetic automata (see figure 1 for an overview of the method).<sep> From the ASR outputs, we build the lexical-phonetic automata to be indexed (section 2.1).<sep> The textual query is phonetized and represented by a lexical-phonetic automaton as well.<sep> A more or less imperfect matching is possible by composing successively the query, an edit transducer and the index (section 2.2).<sep> This process returns a list of candidate utterances that can be filtered thanks to the feature vector weighting each utterance (section 2.3).<sep> 2.1. Lexical-phonetic automata<sep> In this paper, a lexical-phonetic automaton simply denotes a weighted finite-state automaton whose symbols are either from a lexical alphabet Σ [lex] or a phonetic alphabet Σ [ph] , and whose weights are multi-dimensional.<sep> Thus, a lexical-phonetic automaton can have concurrent lexical and phonetic paths weighted by a vector of various features ( e.g. , see figure 2).<sep> If defined over the tropical semi-ring, then the weight of a path is the sum of its transition weights and the shortest path is the one with the minimum weight.<sep> The shortest path can always be determined if the weights are always comparable, i.e. , if they are totally ordered.<sep> This is precisely the case when the lexicographic order (also known as the alphabetical order) is considered as in [6].<sep> Each transition corresponds to a symbol (either lexical or phonetic) recognized between the start time ts and the end time te with an associated confidence measure c .<sep> The weight of the transition is the following :<sep> where wconf[lex][+] [ph] is the lexical-phonetic confidence score because it is common to both lexical and phonetic levels.<sep> The confidence score is proportional to the duration of the symbol so that concurrent lexical-phonetic paths of different numbers of symbols can be comparable.<sep> Once built, the automaton is turned into a corresponding factor transducer that accepts all the sub-sequences of the automaton in input and gives the utterance identifier in output.<sep> The index consists in the union of all the factor transducers (Allauzen et al., 2004).<sep> FIG. 2 – Example of a lexico-phonetic automaton accepting 4 paths: 1 lexical (“l’ ena”), 1 phonetic (“_l _E _n _a”), and 2 lexico-phonetic (“l’ _E _n a” and “l ena”).<sep> The weights are of the form (0,0,0,0,0, wconf[lex][+] [ph] ).<sep> 2.2 Lexical-phonetic matching<sep> The matching between the query R and the index I can be realised by the simple automaton-transducer composition R ◦ I .<sep> It is however possible to get a more flexible matching using an edit transducer E by the successive composition R ◦ E ◦ I [7].<sep> We present three types of lexical-phonetic edit transducers corresponding to perfect, imperfect and semi-imperfect matchings. They calculate the edit distance scores in the vector consisting in the counts of correct words, correct phonemes, and phonetic deletions, insertions and substitutions.<sep> The perfect matching transducer only counts correct words and phonemes.<sep> The count of correct words is chosen to be the first dimension of the vector in order to favour the lexical matching rather than the phonetic matching when both are possible.<sep> No imperfections are allowed, which makes this transducer particularly restrictive.<sep> The imperfect matching transducer is able to count, besides correct words and phonemes, also phonetic deletions, insertions and substitutions.<sep> The problem is that the matching is done without any constraints and, thus, all imperfections are tolerated (e.g. paths with no correct symbols), which makes this transducer quite greedy.<sep> A good trade-off between the two previous extreme approaches can be to count the imperfections under certain constraints.<sep> The proposed semi-imperfect matching transducer takes into account the a priori phonetic variability to limit the imperfection possibilities : “in a sliding window of α phonemes, the rate of correct phonemes must be greater than ρ”.<sep> In this paper, the parameters are arbitrarily set to α = 2 and τ = 1 / 2 for preliminary experiments.<sep> Further research will be needed to pin them down correctly.<sep> Figure 3 illustrates these three types of transducers for a small lexical-phonetic alphabet.<sep> FIG. 3 – Editing transducers for perfect (a), imperfect (b) and semi-imperfect (c) lexico-phonetic matches in the case where Σ [lex] = {ab , ba} and Σ [ph] = { a_ , b}_ .<sep> The weights are of the form ( wcor[lex][,] [ w] cor[ph][,] [ w] sup[ph][,] [ w] ins[ph][,] [ w] sub[ph][,0][)][.]<sep> 2.3. Filtering of candidate segments<sep> After matching and projection on the output label, we obtain a list of weighted utterances ranked according to the lexicographic order.<sep> Thus, each candidate utterance is associated to a vector of 7 features :<sep> Determining if an utterance contains (or not) the query from these features can be posed as a binary classification problem solvable by any learning method ( e.g. , decision trees).<sep> The estimated probability of an utterance to contain the query can then be threshed according to the desired recall-precision trade-off.<sep> 3 Experiments<sep> In this section, we present the experimental setup (section 3.1) to implement the proposed method and carry out two experiments, one on the complementarity of the lexical and phonetic levels (section 3.2) and a second one on spoken utterance retrieval (section 3.3).<sep> 3.1. Experimental protocol<sep> The audio data used for the experiments consists of 6 hours of French radio broadcast news material extracted from the ESTER2 corpus [8] containing reference transcripts with manually annotated named entities.<sep> The ASR system is a large vocabulary (65k words) transcription system for which the word error rates on this corpus vary between 16.0% and 42.2%.<sep> The data are automatically segmented into 3447 utterances.<sep> The N-best hypotheses are then re-ordered using a morpho-syntactic tagger [9].<sep> The lexical level is made only of the 1-best hypothesis.<sep> The phonetic level is obtained by forced alignment between the audio signal and the pronunciation of the lexical level.<sep> Lexical and phonetic confidence measures are calculated from the a posteriori probabilities and the entropy between the different hypotheses [10].<sep> To avoid matching problems that might appear due to morphological variations, words are turned into lemmas with TreeTagger[2] . The automata have been implemented with OpenFST[3] . The respective sizes of the lexical, phonetic and hybrid indexes are 9.9, 32.8 and 47.6 MB.<sep> To estimate the probability of a candidate segment to be relevant given the set of descriptors, we used a bagging over 20 decision trees (Bonzaiboost[4] ).<sep> The evaluation is done according to a 5-fold cross-validation using 80% of the candidate set for training and 20% for testing.<sep> The queries are all named entities extracted from the transcripts of reference.<sep> The pronunciation of the query is given by the phonetic lexicon ILPho[5] .<sep> If a certain word doesn’t belong to the lexicon, multiple pronunciations of it are generated by the phonetizer Lia phon[6] .<sep> In addition to the usual sets of IV and OOV queries, we propose a third set of queries made of both IV and OOV words ( e.g. , an IV first name followed by an OOV family name).<sep> These mixed IV/OOV queries are interesting because they represent an intermediate level of difficulty (a priori more difficult than IV queries but less difficult than OOV ones) and they are more frequent than the OOV queries.<sep> Table 1 shows the query distribution.<sep> The performance of spoken utterance retrieval is evaluated in terms of mean average precision (MAP) corresponding to the area under the recall/precision curve.<sep> 3.2. Complementarity of lexical and phonetic representations<sep> This preliminary experiment consists in measuring the quality of the lexical and phonetic representations and their complementarity.<sep> For each utterance, we align the lexical-phonetic automata of reference and hypothesis with an imperfect edit transducer to obtain Table 2, which gives the correct symbol rate on named entities.<sep> On the one hand, the lexical level is used on areas correctly recognized. On the other hand, the phonetic level is used on mis-recognized areas.<sep> We note that 73.89% of the lemmas are well recognized.<sep> For the mis-recognized lemmas, we can fortunately fall back on the phonetic level for which 67.73% of the phonemes are correct.<sep> This shows that the lexical and phonetic levels are complementary and justifies their combination to search for named entities.<sep> 3.3. Spoken utterance retrieval<sep> The goal of this experiment is to compare the spoken utterance retrieval for different indexes, queries, matches and filters.<sep> We distinguish between research using a lexical index, a phonetic index, two indexes in cascade (state-of-the-art method consisting of searching in the phonetic index only if the lexical search has not yielded any results) and a hybrid lexical-phonetic index.<sep> The queries are IV, OOV or IV/OOV while the matching is perfect or semi-imperfect.<sep> The imperfect matching has been discarded because it is too greedy in terms of calculation time.<sep> Two filtering methods are considered using a simple threshold either over the lexicalphonetic confidence score (th-conf) or over the probability estimated by the decision trees using all the features (dt-all).<sep> The baseline corresponds to a cascade search with perfect matching and filtering based on a threshold of the confidence score.<sep> Table 3 reports the obtained performances.<sep> TABLE 1 – Distribution of requests according to type and length in number of words.<sep> TABLE 2 – Complementarity of lexical and phonetic representations for named entities.<sep> TAB. 3 – MAP evaluation of the search for speech segments: reference method, better than the reference, best result(s).<sep> Generally, we first notice that the baseline can easily be improved for all types of queries using a semi-imperfect matching and supervised filtering (the filtering on the confidence score is not sufficient).<sep> Second, the hybrid search (accompanied by supervised filtering) obtains better or equivalent performances than lexical and phonetic searches, which justifies the hybrid combination.<sep> More specifically, the hybrid search obtains the best results for IV queries.<sep> For OOV queries, the hybrid, cascaded and phonetic search are equivalent as they can only use the phonetic level.<sep> For mixed IV/OOV queries, it is surprising that the phonetic search is better than the hybrid one.<sep> This is due to the fact that the ranking gives too much importance to lexical match even if this one is not really relevant (mis-recognized or very frequent words).<sep> We think that adding a tf*idf score in the feature vector and using better confidence measures will help to deal with these cases.<sep> Finally, the hybrid search (with the semi-imperfect matching and the supervised filtering) offers the best overall performances.<sep> 4. Conclusion<sep> We have presented a method to index and search for spoken utterances represented in the form of lexico-phonetic automata.<sep> The results demonstrate the complementarity of the lexical and phonetic levels (extracted from the 1-best speech recognition hypothesis) and the advantage of using a hybrid index. The use of a semi-imperfect matching and a supervised filtering (combining edit distance scores and a confidence measure) significantly improves the search in terms of MAP.<sep> In perspective, many aspects of the method are still to be improved.<sep> One can envisage an improvement of the recall by better adaptation of the semi-imperfect matching transducers and the use of denser representations (e.g., N best hypotheses);<sep> but also an improvement in precision by using better quality confidence measures (Fayolle et al., 2010) and by enriching the descriptor vector with other types of information (e.g., tf*idf scores).<sep> 1 This work was partly achieved as part of the Quaero Programme, funded by OSEO, French State agency for innovation.<sep> 2 http://www.openfst.org/ 3 http://www.ims.uni-stuttgart.de/projekte/corplex/TreeTagger/<sep> 4 http://bonzaiboost.gforge.inria.fr/<sep> 5 http://catalog.elra.info/product info.php?products id=760<sep> 6 http://www.atala.org/LIA-PHON
Distant Speech Recognition in a Smart Home: Comparison of Several Multisource ASRs in Realistic Conditions<sep> ABSTRACT<sep> The smart home domain has developed to improve assistance to people with reduced autonomy. Automatic speech recognition (ASR) is starting to be used, but remains behind other technologies.<sep> This paper presents the SWEET-HOME project whose aim is to make it possible for frail persons to control their domestic environment through voice interfaces.<sep> Several state-of-the-art and novel approaches are evaluated on realistic data acquired in a multiroom smart home.<sep> The distant speech corpus, recorded with 21 speakers, simulates scenarios integrating daily activities in an apartment equipped with several microphones.<sep> Techniques operating during decoding and using a priori knowledge give very interesting results compared to a classical RAP system.<sep> 1. Introduction<sep> Recent advances in ubiquitous systems have led to new concepts of home automation: the smart home.<sep> These are homes equipped with sensors, actuators, automated devices and centralised software, which control the increasing amount of household appliances ranging from lights, automatic motorised blinds… to Hi-Fi systems, PCs, alarms systems, etc.<sep> These smart homes represent a promising solution to support the elderly and disabled persons in living in their own home as autonomously as possible.<sep> Among all the interaction and sensing technologies used in smart home, speech processing technology has a great potential to become one of the major interaction modalities in smart home. Indeed, voice interfaces are much more adapted to disabled people and the ageing population who have difficulties in moving or seeing, than tactile interfaces (e.g., remote control) which require physical and visual interaction [1, 2].<sep> Moreover, voice command is particularly suited to distress situations. A person, who cannot move after a fall but being conscious, may have still the possibility to call for assistance.<sep> Despite these aspects, automatic speech recognition (ASR) has rarely been used in this context (Vovos et al., 2005; Hamill et al., 2009).<sep> This is partly due to the difficulty of implementing a RAP system in a real environment (Vacher et al., 2011).<sep> The Sweet-Home project[1] started in 2010 and addresses several challenges.<sep> One of the major issues that prevents the development of speech technology in real home setting is the poor performance of Automatic Speech Recognition (ASR) in noisy environment [3]. Indeed, ASR systems have reached correct performances with close talking microphones (e.g. head-set), but the performance decreases significantly as soon as the microphone is moved away from the mouth of the speaker.<sep> In realistic conditions, this deterioration is accentuated by other effects (Vacher et al., 2008) such as reverberation, background noise (TV, radio, works...) etc.<sep> All these problems, related to the so called ‘distant speech’ context, should be taken into account in the home context [5].<sep> While, user linguistic preferences, dialogues and age dependant voice interfaces have been studied during this decade [1, 2, 6], distant speech in smart home received attention very recently within the speech processing community [7].<sep> This paper presents state-of-the-art results and new techniques using ASR on data recorded in realistic conditions.<sep> Section 2 presents the project and the associated corpus. Section 3 presents the different techniques used.<sep> Then, Section 5 presents the experimental framework and the experiments performed with their results and finally, we conclude and propose some perspectives.<sep> 2. SWEET-HOME project and corpus<sep> FIGURE 1 – Position of the 7 microphones in the DOMUS apartment<sep> The SWEET-HOME project (sweet-home.imag.fr) aims at designing a new smart home system based on audio technology focusing on three main aspects: to provide assistance via natural man-machine interaction (voice and tactile command), to ease social e-inclusion and to provide security reassurance by detecting situations of distress.<sep> The aim is therefore that the user can control their environment at any time from anywhere in the house, and in the most natural way possible.<sep> The targeted smart environment uses a SRAP operating throughout all rooms via microphones placed in the ceilings.<sep> This configuration raises problems related to distant speech where microphones are far from the speaker and record very varied external sounds.<sep> The work done in this field has focused on one room [1] or an unspecified number of microphones [2, 6].<sep> To develop this project, a test apartment (project DOMUS) was equipped to acquire a realistic corpus and to experiment with different techniques.<sep> This smart home was set up by the Multicom team of the Laboratory of Informatics of Grenoble, partner of the project.<sep> The apartment is about 34 m[2] in full height. It includes a bathroom, a kitchen, a bedroom and a living room. Each room is equipped with presence detectors, cameras (used only for annotation) etc.<sep> In addition, seven microphones were set in the ceiling.<sep> An experiment was conducted to acquire a representative speech corpus composed of utterances of several categories: domotic, distress call and casual sentence.<sep> 21 persons (including 7 women) participated in the recordings, playing activities of daily life.<sep> The average age of the participants was 38 . 5 ± 13 years (22-63, min-max).<sep> To ensure that the audio data acquired would be as close as possible to real daily living sounds, the participants were asked to perform several daily living activities in the smart home. A visit, before the experiment, was organized to make sure that the participants will find all the needed items to perform the activities.<sep> No instruction was given to any participant about either how they should speak or in which direction.<sep> Consequently, the participants did not necessarily speak in the direction of the microphones and they could move around when they spoke.<sep> The shortest distance between a microphone and the speaker is about 2 meters.<sep> The sounds were recorded in real-time on 7 channels using a dedicated machine with an 8-channel sound card (Vacher et al., 2011).<sep> The first phase (P1) consisted in following a scenario of activities freely and without time constraints (having lunch or a shower, taking a nap, vacuuming the flat, etc.).<sep> During this phase, participants uttered 40 predefined casual sentences (e.g., “Allo”, “J’ai eu du mal à dormir”), with the freedom to utter them wherever they wanted.<sep> The second phase (P2) was based on the reading of 44 sentences, 9 of which were distress sentences (e.g., “Call a doctor”, “I’m in pain”) and 3 were domotic orders (e.g., “Turn on the light”, “Turn on the computer”).<sep> In this paper, the results are restricted to the non-noise part of the corpus (without TV, radio or vacuum cleaner).<sep> Finally, the Sweet-home corpus contains 862 phrases (38 minutes 46s per channel in total) for P1 and 917 phrases (40 minutes 27s per channel in total) for P2.<sep> Each sentence has been recorded on all channels and manually annotated.<sep> The best Signal to Noise Ratio (SNR, by selecting the best channel) is on average 20.3 db, an acceptable condition for making RAP.<sep> However, in our experiments, we used all 7 microphones.<sep> 3. Proposed approaches<sep> The detection of domotic commands in the SWEET-HOME context is based on a three-stage approach.<sep> The first one detects audio activity and classifies it as speech or other sound, the second one extracts the utterances using an ASR system and the last one recognizes a vocal command or a distress situation from the decoded utterances.<sep> This paper focuses on the two last stages. The first stage is described in [4].<sep> To address the issues related to the context (noise, distance) while benefiting from the recording conditions (several microphones recording continuously), we propose to test the impact of state-of-the-art techniques that allow the merging of streams of information at different levels of automatic speech processing: acoustic, speech decoding and at the output of the SRAP.<sep> The next section presents the different techniques considered for obtaining a robust ASR.<sep> 3.1 Merging of acoustic streams<sep> At the acoustic level, it may be interesting to fuse the different channels in order to enhance the signal.<sep> However, a simple sum of signals would result in a worse single channel with echoes and amplified noise.<sep> That is why we were interested in the use of a beam-forming algorithm [8] designed to correctly merge different channels recording the same source at different distances.<sep> This method involves reasonable calculations while allowing an efficient combination of several streams.<sep> The algorithm used here is based on the theory of channel weighting and summation.<sep> Given M microphones, the signal output y [ t ] is computed by: where Wm [ t ] is the weight for microphone m at time t , knowing that∑ [M] m =1 [W][m][ [t]] = 1, the signal of the m[th] channel is xm [ t ] and D[(] [m,ref][)] [ t ] is the delay between the m[th] channel and the reference channel.<sep> In our case, the reference channel is the one with the best SNR (it can therefore vary). The 7 channels were thus combined for each speaker: once the signal y was calculated, it can be used as a classic monosource signal.<sep> 3.2 Guided Decoding<sep> At the decoding level, a novel version of the Driven Decoding Algorithm (DDA) was proposed. DDA aims to align and correct auxiliary transcripts by using a speech recognition engine [9, 10].<sep> This algorithm improves the quality of the primary system by relying on the availability of auxiliary transcripts.<sep> DDA acts at each new generated assumption of the ASR system. The current ASR assumption is aligned with the auxiliary transcript (from a previous decoding pass).<sep> Then a matching score α is computed to weight the language model [9]: P[˜] ( wi|wi− 1, wi− 2) = P[1] [−][α] ( wi|wi− 1, wi− 2) where P[˜] ( wi|wi− 1, wi− 2) is the weighted probability of the word wi knowing the history wi− 2, wi− 3, and P ( wi|wi− 1, wi− 2) is the initial probability of the trigram.<sep> FIGURE 2 – Microphone-guided decoding (left) and decoding with a priori information (right)<sep> We then propose a variant of the DDA where the output of the first microphone is used to drive the output of the second one (cf. Figure 2).<sep> This approach presents two main benefits: - The second ASR system speed is boosted by the auxiliary transcript (only 0.1x the real time (RT)), - DDA merges truly and easily the information from the two streams while voting strategies (such as ROVER) do not merge ASR systems outputs.<sep> The DDA-based strategy is dynamic and used for each decoded phrase. The first decoding is done on the best RSB channel and the DDA is applied on the second.<sep> This approach was extended to take into account a priori knowledge about the expected utterances.<sep> The ASR system is then guided by patterns identified on the first microphone.<sep> This method called DDA 2-level projects the segments recognized during the first pass into a confusion network (RC) comprising the three best expected sentence hypotheses. This RC is then used to guide the SRAP (Figure 2).<sep> 3.3 Vote by consensus<sep> To perform a post-SRAP combination, we used a ROVER method (Fiscus, 1997) which allows to improve the quality of several SRAP outputs by performing a consensus vote at the word level.<sep> The principle is to merge the outputs into a RC system where each word is weighted according to its presence in the different systems.<sep> The word with the best score is selected.<sep> This approach necessitates high computational resources, since each channel must be decoded with an ASR (in our case, 7 ASR systems must operate concurrently).<sep> Our ROVER reference system uses all available channels without a priori knowledge.<sep> Then, we introduced a confidence measure based on the RSB: for each decoded segment si from the i[th] ASR system, the associated confidence score φ ( si ) was computed as follows: φ ( si ) = 2 [R][(] [s][i][)] /∑[7] j =1[2] [R][(] [s][j][)] where R () is the function computing the RSB of a segment and si is the segment generated by the i[th] ASR system.<sep> For each sentence a silence period Isil at the beginning and the end is added to the speech signal period Ispeech .<sep> The SNR is thus evaluated as: R ( S ) = 10 ∗ log ( ∑n∈I|pIaroleparole[S] |[ [n] ][2] / ∑n∈I|silIsil[S] |[ [n] ][2] ).<sep> Finally, a ROVER using only the two best channels overall was tested in order to check the degree of redundancy between the different channels. This 2-channel ROVER also allows to obtain correct results with a reasonable amount of calculations.<sep> 4. Detection of domotic orders and distress sentences<sep> We propose to automatically phonetize each target sentence. Thus, all expected sentences are represented in the form of a phoneme graph (with variants of pronunciation).<sep> The number of sentences to detect is 12 (3 domotic orders + 9 distress sentences).<sep> Automatic transcripts have also been phonetically transcribed in the same way.<sep> In order to locate domotic orders into automatic transcripts T of size m , each sentence of size n is aligned to T using a phonetic editing distance.<sep> The deletion, insertion and substitution costs were computed empirically.<sep> The cumulative distance γ ( i, j ) between Hj and Ti is computed as: γ ( i, j ) = d ( Ti, Hj ) + min{γ ( i − 1 , j − 1) , γ ( i − 1 , j ) , γ ( i, j − 1) }<sep> Each domotic order is aligned and associated with an alignment score: the percentage of well aligned symbols.<sep> The domotic order with the best score is then selected for decision according a detection threshold.<sep> This approach takes into account some recognition errors or pronunciation based on phonetic proximity.<sep> 5. Experiments and results<sep> In all experiments, the Phase 1 corpus was used for development and training whereas the Phase 2 corpus served for the evaluation.<sep> This section presents the ASR tuning and the experimental results of the proposed approaches.<sep> 5.1 The Speeral ASR system<sep> The LIA (Laboratoire d’Informatique d’Avignon) has developed its own SRAP: Speeral (Linarès et al. , 2007).<sep> The latter was used throughout the work presented here. One of the main advantages of Speeral is that it implements DDA.<sep> Speeral relies on an A[∗] decoder with HMM-based context-dependent acoustic models and trigram language models.<sep> Acoustic vectors are composed of 12 PLP (Perceptual Linear Predictive) coefficients, the energy, and the first and second order derivatives of these 13 parameters.<sep> In the study, the acoustic models were trained on about 80 hours of annotated speech.<sep> In the context of the Sweet-Home project, we used a 1x real-time version, which applies many cuts during decoding.<sep> Acoustic models were adapted for each of the 21 speakers by using the Maximum Likelihood Linear Regression (MLLR) and the annotated Phase 1 corpus.<sep> MLLR adaptation is a good compromise while only a small amount of annotated data is available.<sep> A 3-gram language model (LM) with a 10K lexicon was used.<sep> This language model is interpolated between a generic model (10%) and a specialized model (90%).<sep> The generic ML was estimated on about 100M words from the French newspapers Le Monde and Gigaword.<sep> The specialized model was estimated from the expected domotic orders or distress phrases.<sep> 5.2 Results<sep> Results of the approaches are presented in table 1.<sep> The ASR stage was evaluated using the Word Error Rate (WER) whereas the vocal order recognition (classification) stage was evaluated using recall/precision/F-measure triplet: the number of domotic orders is about 10. Domotic orders were manually specified by annotating all sentences.<sep> During the detection, if a marked order is detected: it is considered as detected.<sep> In all other cases, a detected order is considered as a false alarm.<sep> The results are presented for all 21 speakers (with the associated standard deviation for the WER).<sep> The baseline system is based on the selection of the output that offers the best SNR (among the 7 channels).<sep> Table 1: TEM and detection of domotic orders according to the approaches<sep> The baseline system achieved a 18.3 % WER (best SNR channel).<sep> The SNR-based approaches presented a clear improvement.<sep> Beamforming led to a 8.1% relative gain.<sep> This result shows that combining all channels increases the ASR task robustness.<sep> The DDA method showed a 37.8% relative improvement by using the SNR.<sep> The 2 level DDA presented a 52 % relative improvement with a very high stability (SD=3.7): this gain is easily explained as the second decoding pass was perfused with a priori knowledge (i.e., domotic orders) triggered by the first pass.<sep> Finally, the SNR-based ROVER led to a 33.4% relative improvement.<sep> In all configurations, the accuracy of the recognition of orders was good: the baseline recognition gave an F-measure of 89.2%.<sep> We also observe a correlation between the WER and the task of recognizing orders.<sep> However, ROVER and the DDA-based methods significantly improved the F-measure by about 7% absolute.<sep> The gain brought by beamforming was not significant.<sep> We also note that the ROVER allows to obtain results similar to those of the DDA, but requires a colossal calculation cost (decoding of all channels).<sep> Finally, the best configuration was based on the 2 level DDA leading to a 96.8% F-measure.<sep> 6. Conclusion<sep> Several approaches were presented to perform accurate vocal order recognition in multi-room smart-homes where audio information is captured by several microphones in a distant speech context.<sep> The proposed approaches were acting at the three main levels of the ASR task: acoustic, decoding and hypothesis selection.<sep> We also presented a method introducing a priori knowledge directly into the decoding such as the SNR or predefined order patterns.<sep> Results confirmed that the use of all the microphones improved the ASR accuracy.<sep> Beamforming improved the WER (16.8%), however its performance were very close to the baseline one (18.3%).<sep> This is probably due to the distance between the microphones, which does not provide enough redundancy to improve the signal.<sep> The Driven Decoding Algorithm gave the best performance with a 11.4% WER and 95.3% F-measure for vocal order classification.<sep> The results obtained by the DDA are slightly better than those of the ROVER, but their computational cost is much lower (decoding of 7 channels with the ROVER).<sep> Moreover, we proposed a 2-level DDA approach, introducing a priori knowledge in the decoding. This method improves both the TEM (8.8%) and the F-measure which becomes more stable than that of the reference system.<sep> However, this improvement will mainly concern the domotic orders contained in the test data.<sep> In the context of the application, only these orders should be recognised and this represents an advantage in terms of the acceptance of the system by users.<sep> This study also showed that the use of multiple streams systematically improves the quality of decoding, whatever the strategy.<sep> We plan to adapt these approaches to noisy conditions notably by applying source separation techniques to real daily living records composed of uncontrolled noise.<sep> 1. This study was funded by the French National Research Agency (ANR-2009VERS-011) as part of the Sweet-Home project.<sep> We would like to thank in particular the various people who agreed to participate in the recordings.
Towards fully automatic annotation of audiobooks for TTS<sep> ABSTRACT<sep> Building speech corpora is a first and crucial step for every text-to-speech synthesis system.<sep> Nowadays, the use of statistical models implies the use of huge sized corpora that need to be recorded, transcribed, annotated and segmented to be usable.<sep> The variety of corpora necessary for recent applications (content, style, etc.) makes the use of existing digital audio resources very attractive. Among all available resources, audiobooks, considering their quality, are interesting.<sep> It is in this context that our proposal for an acquisition, segmentation and annotation chain for audiobooks is made. This proposal tends to be fully automatic.<sep> The proposed process relies on a data structure, ROOTS, that establishes the relations between the different annotation levels.<sep> This methodology has been applied successfully on 11 hours of speech extracted from an audiobook.<sep> A manual check on a part of the annotated corpus showed the efficiency of the process.<sep> 1. Use of Large Corpora for Speech Synthesis<sep> The use of statistical models, mainly from the speech recognition field, occurs in all the automatic language and speech processing disciplines.<sep> Learning such models on speech units needs a large number of observations and implies the use of large speech corpora.<sep> A direct consequence of the size of corpora is that conventional methods used to build, segment and annotate them have shown their limits.<sep> In summary, the unit is generally a phoneme taken in a precise linguistic and acoustic context.<sep> Representing in a database the whole set of the units generated by the combination of all the linguistic and acoustic features (about 50 features are used in HTS (Tokuda et al., 2000)) is impossible.<sep> Nonetheless, learning models of the units that are present in the target language can be done by the analysis of large natural speech corpora.<sep> The generalisation of digitised resources promotes the availability of data from large corpora of natural speech.<sep> Their natures are very varied, they can be accompanied or not by text, monolingual or multilingual, amateur or professional, representing a spontaneous or read voice, etc.<sep> In the framework of speech synthesis, we consider the use of audiobooks which enables to have recordings, read by a professionnal speaker and with a good acoustic quality, accompanied with the script.<sep> Audiobooks have a lot of benefits and can complete or even replace ad-hoc corpora.<sep> We can find different audio books recorded by the same speaker which increases the variety of speaking and literary styles, or we can find the same book recorded by different speakers and thus enabling studies using parallel data.<sep> In addition, a specificity of textual data associated to audiobooks is that they are nearly constant from one recording to another.<sep> However, possible variations may exist in the case of multiple editions (translations, unfinished manuscripts, etc.).<sep> An important step to build a new voice is the annotation of the text associated with the speech signal.<sep> This step may appear simple if it is limited to the synchronisation of words onto the signal, but uses complex temporal relation when it comes to dealing with other levels of analysis, as semantic, lexical, grammatical, syntactical, phonetic or prosodic annotations.<sep> For each of these annotation levels, previous works found in the literature proposed automatic annotation systems that define labels to place on the text linked to the signal.<sep> Generally, these systems have been built separately and, consequently, use different description formats but not the same time scale.<sep> Their use on a corpus often requires a lot of conversions and generates a lot of heterogeneous and scattered files.<sep> In order to avoid desynchronized descriptions, we have recently proposed a solution based on relations between sequences, ROOTS (Barbot et al., 2011).<sep> This approach enables to define a minimal set of relations that exist between levels of description.<sep> Primitive relations are first defined and then a mechanism of composition of relations allows, by algebraic rules, to define all the desired relations between two sequences of annotation.<sep> The aim of this study consists in describing the process used to build speech corpora from audiobooks.<sep> The automatic annotation process is applied to several dozen hours of continuous speech.<sep> This study is restricted to mono-speaker recordings but the only constraint is to have an acoustic content and the corresponding text.<sep> The output of the system, according to the annotation levels required, is a set of ROOTS files, stored as XML files. These files put together give the structure of all the relations from text to signal.<sep> In part 2, the proposed annotation process is described.<sep> The structure representing the information linked to the utterance is then introduced in part 3.<sep> This structure is used by the text splitting and alignment processes, detailed in section 4, and also to keep all the information obtained form the annotation step, section 5.<sep> Part 6 illustrates the whole process with an application of the methodology.<sep> 2. Annotation Process<sep> The implementation of the annotation process has to fulfill a number of constraints that come from the use of annotated corpora and performance control.<sep> The first one concerns the text that has to be kept under its original form and the differences introduced by the reader have to be tagged.<sep> The second one concerns the corpus splitting.<sep> Our goal being to annotate a corpus on several levels, we have to manipulate speech fragments and text fragments of variable size.<sep> Indeed, it is desirable for a syntactical analysis to have a complete sentence while the segmentation into phones is more efficient when applied on short extracts.<sep> The text and the recorded tracks will be split with a granularity sufficiently fine to enable working on short fragments that may be, if needed, merged together to build a sentence or just a longer fragment under the condition of keeping coherence of the text.<sep> Lastly, to garantee the annotation quality, a manual intervention is possible, and is guided by confidence indicators given by the different tools used during the process.<sep> The annotation process, shown on figure 1, is composed of two main steps: the first one consists in splitting several hours of a long speech recording into short tracks and associating to each of them the corresponding text.<sep> This step, as time consuming as the signal cutting is thin, needs the use of a speech recognition system to find anchors of the corresponding textual transcription in the entire text.<sep> The extracts obtained are then merged to rebuild the sentences of the original text.<sep> The second step is the annotation of the text sentences and the signal fragments that have been put into correspondance during the first step.<sep> Data representation using ROOTS is done from the audiobook splitting step.<sep> It is enriched as data annotation is done by the addition of new description sequences and relations between them.<sep> 3. Corpus Representation<sep> ROOTS is a software library designed to handle a coherent set of data structures built to describe and annotate speech and linguistic contents (Barbot et al., 2011).<sep> Each type of annotation corresponds to a sequence of items.<sep> An item is an object whose nature may vary a lot, for example, a transcription of text, a label, an acoustic segment, etc.<sep> The only constraint to respect, to insure consistency of the sequences, is that all the items in one sequence are always of the same type.<sep> Relations allow to connect sequence items in a n-to-m manner.<sep> ROOTS produces XML files that give a complete description of the corpus, but may also provide files in well-known formats to guarantee interoperability with existing tools such as Wavesurfer or Transcriber (Barras et al., 2001).<sep> FIGURE 1 – Processus d’annotation d’un livre-audio<sep> Another positive point brought by ROOTS is that its modular structure allows to keep several sequences of the same type in parallel.<sep> For example, it is important to keep the original text, the spoken text (which may contain corrections of misspelled words or specific pronounciation) and finally the output of syntax analysis (for example, “j’avais” corresponds to two words). For each previous type of text, a particular sequence is associated.<sep> Those three types of text correspond to three sequences of items linked together by relations, as shown on figure 3, which give a precise correspondence between items.<sep> Thus, this point of view enables to keep all the information untouched and to keep, in a unique structure, various utterance annotations. Furthermore, information can be split into several files while the coherence is also preserved.<sep> 4. Speech Signal Split and Alignment with the Text<sep> Many papers are dealing with the alignment of large texts and their corresponding audio.<sep> (Braunschweiler et al., 2010) has proposed an automatic system which aligns text parts of an audiobook for TTS applications.<sep> Other systems deal with approximate transcriptions (Tao et al., 2010) or align the text without splitting it (Moreno and Alberti, 2009)(Prahallad et al., 2007).<sep> In our case, the text must be segmented to perform the different analyses and to facilitate its representation, especially in the case of manual verification.<sep> We have chosen to realise the text alignment with the signal in three steps: 1. Split the signal on large acoustic pauses, 2. Find the corresponding text description of the signal by using Automatic Speech Recognition (ASR) System, 3. Align the recognized text with the original one.<sep> The cutting of the recording is based on the observation of energy levels and lengths of silent pauses.<sep> Thresholds are determined and adjusted by the current speaking rate and recording levels.<sep> The ideal is to obtain a sound segment below the sentence, thus allowing to reconstruct the sentences while keeping anchor points within each sentence in the case of long sentences.<sep> Text recognition of each signal fragment is achieved by using the Nuance ASR system (Nuance, 2010).<sep> Models are speaker independent and the language model is learnt on the text extracted from the whole analyzed audiobook.<sep> By comparing the original text with the recognized one, we can determined word error rates.<sep> These errors can result from a failure of the recognition system or a mistake made while the speaker reads the text (like a bad pronunciation or a text replacement).<sep> The differences between the recognized text and the original text can be signalled to allow an operator to check the passages concerned.<sep> The text provided by the recognition system is then aligned with the original text using a Levenstein distance computed at a word level.<sep> The recognized snippets are processed in the order of the text, which allows processing of occurrences of the same text fragment located in different places in the statement.<sep> When the position of the first segment in the original text is determined, it is associated with the sound file and then deleted from the original text.<sep> This process is repeated for the following extracts until the end of the text.<sep> Finally, to preserve as much as possible the text structure, segments are brought together into sentences by using major punctuation marks.<sep> When a segment is not ended by a terminal punctuation mark, it is simply grouped with the next one.<sep> However, the information about the boundary between the two clips is preserved.<sep> The segmented text and signal are then adapted for Transcriber (Barras et al., 2001).<sep> A speech turn is composed of a single sentence or a set of undivided adjacent sentences. This prevents dividing segments too early in the chain of processing.<sep> Synchronization points define boundaries between two consecutive audio segments.<sep> The use of transcriber also allows to place tags indicating the disagreements between the original text and the recognized text, especially when they occur at the border between two excerpts, which can call into question the relevance of the text segmentation in relation to the speech signal.<sep> The alignment of the segmented text and signal is then automatically converted into the ROOTS format.<sep> 5. Data Annotation<sep> In a second stage, ROOTS provides acoustic and textual data in an appropriate format to the annotation tools that return their own analysis.<sep> Currently, the annotation levels used are the following: named entities extraction, syntactic analysis, part of speech tagging, phonetic segmentation and prosodic prominence extraction.<sep> The grammatical and syntactical analyses are produced using a Synapse Developpement software, (Synapse, 2011) (Developpement, 2011) while acoustic analysis is done with our own tools.<sep> The information provided by each analysis is included into the ROOTS file, thereby refining the corpus description and allowing the generation of new relations between items of different annotations.<sep> For example, after a complete analysis, one can easily find for a given phoneme the word to which it belongs and its corresponding POS tag.<sep> 6. Application<sep> The complete annotation process was experimented on a Marcel Proust’s literary work called “Albertine disparue”.<sep> This book contains around 120 , 000 words and its duration is 11 hours and 43 minutes.<sep> Since Proust had rewritten some parts of the book, the version of the text has been checked to ensure it.<sep> Audio tracks were split on silences whose duration was longer than one second.<sep> The split step has produced 11,693 files that correspond to phrases or groups of breaths with an average duration of 3 seconds.<sep> Then, files were analyzed by the ASR system.<sep> The differences between the text output by the recognition system and the original text account for 5.2% of the words, which includes differences in the spelling of words and their grammatical agreements.<sep> This rate could be reduced by adapting the models to the speaker from a few sentences in the book.<sep> Text obtained in output of the ASR system is then used to split the original text to match the signal tracks.<sep> When a conflict is detected on a starting segment or an ending segment word, particularly when the conflict is an insertion or a deletion, the alignment does not guarantee a suitable split of the text for this word.<sep> The case is then reported to allow manual intervention.<sep> This problem appeared 969 times out of the 11 , 693 files which represent 8,3% of the segments.<sep> A manual check established that a real splitting error occured in 8% of the alerts (78 files).<sep> The high number of false alerts comes from the fact that all the disagreements on the segment border are signalled (insertion, elision, substitution), but many substitutions do not lead to a bad alignment.<sep> The files are then grouped into Transcriber files (one file per CD track, which represents, generally, fifteen minutes of speech).<sep> The texts have been grouped into rounds according to their punctuation.<sep> We obtain a total of 3 , 340 turns whose durations are between 660ms and 1min22s.<sep> One turn contains around 3.5 segments defined in the previous step. As we have specified, the anchor positions of these segments are kept.<sep> After the Transcriber file creation, all the conflicts between the original text and the ASR output are identified by using a specific tag.<sep> The operator can then add new tags to indicate reading mistakes or bad pronounciation.<sep> In our case, 86 lexical tags (replacing a word or expression by another) and 213 pronunciation tags were added, and 78 corrections were made to the text layout.<sep> The corpus thus cut and aligned is then put into a ROOTS structure that is then interrogated by the various annotation systems.<sep> Currently, the linguistic analysis has not been validated but the phoneme segmentation has been manually checked on a part of the corpus lasting 2 hours and 16 minutes. FIGURE 2 – Representation of an annotated sentence of the corpus.<sep> The automatic segmentation is achieved by using Markov models (a model for each phone, a model for the short and long pauses, a model for the inspiration, a model for the beginning and end of the sentence, a total of 40 different models) on a phonetisation graph.<sep> Models are context-independent and they are trained on observation vectors of 39 coefficients (12 MFCC, the first order and second order derivative, and energy). These vectors are computed on 30ms frames using a 10ms shift.<sep> The phonetisation graph is obtained by the text phonetisation achieved by Liaphon (Bechet, 2001) which has been completed by variations of some phonemes: /ø/ and /@/ are optional for a majority of words, connections are optional too and may be preceded or followed by short silences. Finally, pauses can be replaced by inspirations.<sep> The speech segments used for segmentation are as short as possible in order to increase the complexity of the graphs by adding variants without compromising the efficiency of the alignment algorithms.<sep> The text used by the segmentation process does not take into account the lexical and pronunciation tags inserted in the Transcriber files, but takes into account the manual corrections of text splitting.<sep> The result of automatic segmentation led to the annotation of 419,742 segments (phones and silences).<sep> Out of 82,936 phonetic units manually checked, 94% were correctly labeled, 2.5% are missing and 3.3% were replaced by another label.<sep> Furthermore, we can mention that 2 . 77% of phone insertion occurs.<sep> A great part of elisions involves /ø/ (46%), this phoneme is generally optional, and 24% of its occurrences were not detected.<sep> The majority of substitutions (41%) concerns the substitution of /e/ by /E/ which is the result of a specific pronounciation. The second important part of substitutions (19%) deals with pauses and inspirations.<sep> Insertions are mainly composed of pauses and inspirations (72% of insertions).<sep> These results are correct but they can be improved by adding variants adapted to the speaker's pronunciation and by post-processing on pauses and inspirations.<sep> The alignment of phonemes on the signal is also correct, we have 86% of the phoneme boundaries that are placed at less than 20 ms of the position defined by the human operator, the average distance is about 8.7 ms which is less than a shift between two frames of observation.<sep> These measures were also taken before the manual correction of the text alignment. In that case, the proportion of correct labels was 91% and the proportion of boundaries placed at less than 20ms was 86%.<sep> The ROOTS structure is then enriched with the information provided by the annotation systems.<sep> By linking this information, it is possible to know for each text or sound fragment all the tags to which it is associated.<sep> Figure 2 shows an example of a sentence where the text is represented in several sequences: the Transcriber text divides the text according to spaces, while the Synapse text separates the elements according to their nature.<sep> 7. Conclusion<sep> The automation of the whole process that converts an audiobook to a corpus annotated at several levels gives a quick access to large corpora.<sep> The time reduction gained with this methodology to build new speech synthesis voices is considerable when we take into account the time saved for both corpus recording and corpus annotation.<sep> The corpus representation generated by ROOTS removes the problems related to the heterogeneity of the files provided by each annotation systems and simplifies its handling.<sep> However, the annotation process has to be reinforced by confidence indicators for each annotation step, either to remove uncertain areas, or to enable a supervised modality. In that case, the indicators would be given to an operator to guarantee a fast intervention as well as data in an appropriate format for the validation tools.
Robustness and portability of spoken language understanding systems across languages and domains: the PORTMEDIA corpora<sep> ABSTRACT<sep> The PORTMEDIA project aimed to complete the MEDIA corpus in order to promote the development of efficient methods, particularly statistical, for the automatic understanding of speech in the context of human-machine dialogue systems.<sep> The main axes treated are: robustness to speech recognition errors, multilingual portability, multi-domain portability and high-level semantic representation.<sep> Thus, while developing elements of solutions to these problems within the project, we mainly focused on developing data and meta-data to allow other research groups to evaluate their own proposals in the best possible conditions.<sep> 1. Introduction<sep> With the ever growing spread of human-machine communications (call centers, telephone services, smartphones, etc.), Spoken Language Understanding (SLU) received an increasing interest over the past few years.<sep> SLU systems have been deployed on real world applications but with a limited success so far.<sep> Firstly SLU systems are usually available in only one language and don’t support multilinguality.<sep> Secondly existing services with SLU components are very constrained and restricted by the task or the domain of application.<sep> Finally the quality of the user-system interaction is still far from being easy and natural.<sep> The PORTMEDIA project tries to address some remaining issues by developing new corpora targeting three distinct but complementary objectives:<sep> - Robustness of SLU systems to recognition errors.<sep> Errors due to automatic speech recognition must be taken into account in the understanding process and thus automatic transcripts must be made available with training data.<sep> - Multilingual and multi-domain portability.<sep> SLU systems are very language and domain dependent.<sep> Adapting a system to a new domain or a new language usually requires the very costly collection of a new large database of dialogues of the target domain/language and an important development effort.<sep> PORTMEDIA aims to allow the evaluation of the genericity and portability of new approaches for SLU systems.<sep> - High level semantic knowledge representation.<sep> High Level Semantic (HLS) representation is needed to take into account the semantic composition process occurring inside and between consecutive user’s interactions.<sep> - The PORTMEDIA project (2009-12) is a continuation of the MEDIA project (2003-07) during which a corpus of 1258 dialogues in French for the tourism domain was produced.<sep> The project partners are: the University of Avignon, ELDA, the LIG, the LIUM and the LORIA.<sep> 2. The PORTMEDIA spoken dialogue databases<sep> State of the art SLU systems use statistical models that need to be trained on large corpora of dialogues.<sep> There are very few publicly available corpora of Human-Computer spoken dialogues.<sep> Indeed, unlike other types of speech, like read speech or broadcast news, the only large spoken dialogue corpus publicly available through LDC[1] are Human-Human dialogues (e.g. CallHome, CallFriend, Fisher corpus).<sep> The lack of data can be explained by the difficulty of collecting such corpora.<sep> It is necessary to develop a first CAP system to collect data using an operational dialogue system.<sep> To overcome this difficulty, it is also possible to simulate the machine through a Wizard-of-Oz (WOZ) protocol in which a human agent replaces the machine while trying to reproduce its behavior (in order to ensure the realism of the data).<sep> Once the data is collected, meta-data must be added.<sep> While orthographic transcription is a well defined task, setting-up a semantic annotation framework is non trivial and requires a lot of expertise.<sep> Under these conditions, it seems natural that the largest dialogue corpora have been developed by the telecom industry using prototypes or deployed systems, like AT&T how may I help you? (Gorin et al., 1997) or France-Télécom.<sep> PORTMEDIA has produced two new corpora to study the portability of SLU systems across domains and languages.<sep> The first corpus is made of 604 dialogues for the Italian language on the touristic domain.<sep> The second one includes 700 dialogues in French for ticket reservation in the scope of the 2010 Festival d’Avignon.<sep> Detailed statistics on the corpus are given in Table 1.<sep> 2.1. PM-LANG : the PORTMEDIA Italian corpus<sep> The Italian database, called PM-LANG, has been recorded, transcribed and annotated with the same specifications and configurations as the MEDIA corpus.<sep> The only difference between the MEDIA and PM-LANG corpora is the language spoken by the speakers.<sep> In 2004, to collect the MEDIA corpus, 250 scenarios were used and a telephony recording platform was set-up.<sep> The platform includes an automatic (textual) sentence generator to help the agents in their responses.<sep> For the Italian database, the same tools, protocols, scenarios and constraints were used to collect the dialogues.<sep> The only adaptation was to translate the prompts and the scenarios from French to Italian, but no changes were made to the content of the scenarios (including the named entities which were kept as they were, for example the names of places, hotels...).<sep> The recording protocol is detailed in (Devillers et al., 2004).<sep> The annotation procedure and guidelines are described in (Maynard et al., 2005).<sep> The resulting database is a corpus of 604 dialogues orthographically transcribed and semantically annotated.<sep> 2.2. PM-DOM : the PORTMEDIA new domain corpus<sep> To study new techniques for portability between domains, we developed a French Human-Computer dialogue corpus (PM-DOM) with the same paradigm and specifications as MEDIA but on a different domain.<sep> While MEDIA was addressing the touristic information domain , the French PORTMEDIA corpus addresses ticket reservation within the 2010 Festival d’Avignon.<sep> We tried to remain as close as possible to the specifications, tools and paradigm of MEDIA and to minimize the differences between the two databases (other than the domain, which already implies a great intrinsic variability of course).<sep> The only adaptation was to create new scenarios for the callers, to adapt the dialogue management system for the agents and to develop the ontology of the domain for semantic annotation.<sep> This corpus is made of 700 dialogues with orthographic transcription and semantic annotation.<sep> 3 Pre-transcriptions and pre-semantic annotations of the PM-LANG and PM-DOM corpora<sep> The transcriptions and semantic annotations of PM-LANG and PM-DOM have been done in a semi-automatic way.<sep> Thanks to the availability of the MEDIA corpus, LIUM developed a speech recognizer to transcribe the PM-DOM corpus.<sep> Once the data was transcribed, it has been manually corrected by human transcribers.<sep> The corrections were sent back to LIUM to retrain models and improve the speech recognition system.<sep> Then a new batch of data was automatically transcribed, manually corrected and sent back for system improvement.<sep> More details on the LIUM speech recognition system can be found in 3.1.<sep> For semantic annotations, LIA/LIG pre-annotated both databases automatically.<sep> The pre-annotation was then corrected manually by two linguists per language (French for PM-DOM and Italian for PM-LANG.<sep> The same iterative process as for the transcription task took place.<sep> Details on the CAP modules used by the LIA and the LIG are given in Section 3.2.<sep> TABLE 1 – Statistics for the MEDIA, PM-LANG and PM-DOM corpora.<sep> 3.1. Speech recognition system for French<sep> The LIUM-PM ASR system is a five-pass system based on the open-source SPHINX system (versions 3 and 4), similar to the LIUM’08 French ASR system described in (Deléglise et al., 2009):<sep> The first pass uses generic acoustic models and a 3-gram language model.<sep> The best hypotheses generated by the first pass are used to compute a CMLLR transformation for each speaker.<sep> Using SAT and MPE acoustic models and CMLLR transformations, the second pass generates word graphs.<sep> In the third pass, word-graphs are rescored by using a better inter-word acoustic scoring: same acoustic and linguistic models as the ones used during the previous pass are used, but the decoding algorithm is different.<sep> The next pass recomputes the scores of the word graphs with a 4-gram language model.<sep> Finally, the last pass generates a confusion network from the word-graphs and applies the consensus method to extract the final one-best hypothesis (Mangu et al., 2000).<sep> Acoustic models were estimated on the ESTER 1 corpus (Galliano et al., 2005), the ESTER 2 corpus (Galliano et al., 2009) and the EPAC corpus (Estève et al., 2010): this constitutes a data set of almost 280 hours of broadcast news.<sep> Language models and vocabulary were extracted directly from the MEDIA corpus (in accordance with the results of (Lefèvre et al., 2005) on multi-source learning).<sep> In order to process the first data set of audio recordings of the PM-DOM data, the LIUM-PM ASR system used a vocabulary of 5k words and 4-grams were learned on the MEDIA training data.<sep> The word error rate of this ASR system on the MEDIA test corpus was 25.2% on the caller utterances only (i.e. without taking into account the turns of speech of the agents who are generally better recognised because they are very formatted).<sep> Table 2 shows the error rates achieved by the successive versions of the recognition system after each iteration of the pre-transcription process presented in Section 3.<sep> Four data sets were automatically processed.<sep> For each iteration, language models and ASR vocabulary were updated according to the manual correction of the previous iteration.<sep> TABLE 2 – Word error rate of the automatic pre-transcription for each iteration.<sep> The sentences of the WoZ and the caller are calculated separately.<sep> 3.2. SLU systems for French and Italian<sep> In order to perform the semantic pre-annotation of the French and Italian corpora, we used a CAP tagger based on a statistical method: the conditional random fields (CRFs).<sep> A semantically annotated corpus is needed to train this system.<sep> For the French PM-DOM corpus, models were trained directly on the MEDIA data and new named entities were added simultaneously to take into account the new data.<sep> Pre-annotation is a combination of the outputs proposed by CAP and named entity detection systems.<sep> For PM-LANG since we did not have an initial comparable corpus in the target language, we proposed to automatically port the French MEDIA corpus to Italian.<sep> Multiple approaches for the portability of a CAP system between languages were investigated and evaluated (Jabaian et al., 2010; Lefevre et al., 2010) and the best one was applied to create a new annotated corpus.<sep> The retained approach consists in automatically translating the French MEDIA corpus into Italian and then to port the semantic annotation to the Italian data.<sep> The automatic translation was carried out by a phrase-based statistical machine translation system trained on a parallel corpus (obtained by manually translating a subset of the French data).<sep> The annotation transfer was based on the automatic alignment between French and Italian sentences.<sep> In other words, this method consists in a concept projection using word to word alignments between French and Italian sentences.<sep> Since the French training corpus was already annotated at the segmental level, we proposed to use the alignment information between this corpus and its translation to match directly the semantic concepts to the chunks in the Italian corpus.<sep> To do so, we have developed an algorithm that uses alignment information and segmentation: for each conceptual segment in French, the algorithm associates the corresponding words in Italian by referring to the alignment.<sep> This strategy allowed to annotate the entire Italian translated corpus (including both the initial manually-translated part and the subsequent automatically translated subset).<sep> The Italian corpus is then used for training a semantic tagger which can be used to perform the first iteration of Italian pre-annotation.<sep> For the second and third iterations, the manual correction of the pre-annotation is added to the training data and the models are relearned.<sep> An assessment of the performance of the Italian CAP model is described in Table 3.<sep> Only the error rates in concept with or without the use of the PM-LANG and MEDIA corpora translated for model training are reported (the rates measured on the manually translated MEDIA test are given for reference).<sep> The best result on the PM-LANG test, 17.6%, is obtained by a combination of the two corpora.<sep> For the PM-DOM corpus, the model trained with the corpus data obtains a CER of 19.1%.<sep> TABLE 3 – Evaluation (CER %) of Italian CAP models according to the learning set.<sep> 3.3. Productivity gains<sep> During the transcription and semantic annotation processes we regularly compared the productivity gains due to the semi-automatic transcription/annotation.<sep> In this purpose, the following protocol was implemented.<sep> During each iteration a set of 10 dialogues was transcribed (resp. annotated) twice by two different annotators.<sep> The first annotator did the transcription (resp. annotation) from the pre-transcription (resp. pre-annotation) while the second annotator transcribed (resp. annotated) the same 10 dialogues from scratch.<sep> The measured productivity gains are plotted in Figure 1.<sep> For the transcriptions, the time to transcribe a whole dialogue was halved using the automatic pre-transcriptions.<sep> For semantic annotations, the productivity gains are superior to 50% for Italian and 40% for French.<sep> FIGURE 1 – Productivity gains (in %) for the transcription and semantic annotation of the two PM-LANG and PM-DOM corpora.<sep> 4. High-level semantic annotation<sep> The use of a high-level semantic (HLS), a hierarchical semantic representation, has been investigated for the annotation of the MEDIA corpus.<sep> For this purpose, we referred to the MultiModal Interface Language (MMIL) for generating ontology-oriented structures that bear relevant linguistic information from syntax up to discourse.<sep> Therefore, fine-grained features describing dialogue acts, predicates and arguments were correctly defined for the spoken utterances in the corpus.<sep> However, this annotation is a real challenge.<sep> To begin with, we treated the most complex sentences, containing overlapped predicates and arguments, as well as elliptical phrases containing either implicit predicates or implicit arguments.<sep> We elaborated the annotation guidelines and manually annotated a subset of utterances which were supposed to be representative of the most complex aspects of the HLS annotation, in terms of their semantic constituents (Rojas-Barahona et al., 2011), using a specifically developed graphical tool.<sep> An incremental architecture was then elaborated for the semi-automatic annotation of the complete corpus, as well as the means to evaluate the annotation provided (Rojas-Barahona and Quignard, 2011).<sep> This annotation is being corrected by expert annotators in order to provide a gold standard for the entire corpus.<sep> This gold standard will serve to implement and test supervised learning methods for the automatic annotation of this complex semantics.<sep> 5. Conclusion<sep> In this article, we have presented the different contributions of the PORTMEDIA project aimed at promoting the development of statistical methods for the understanding of speech.<sep> The work has mainly taken the form of the provision of corpora allowing for a relevant and easy evaluation of the methods studied.<sep> Thus, 4 main axes were covered:<sep> - robustness to recognition errors: provision of automatic transcriptions with a state-of-the-art data system<sep> - multilingual portability: collection of a new corpus in Italian, including a test set and an adaptation set;<sep> - multi-domain portability: collection of a new corpus on a new domain (booking of tickets), with a set of tests and adaptation;<sep> - hierarchical semantic annotation: development of a high-level semantic representation allowing for the inclusion of information at the level of the complete sentence (the specifications are ready, the complete MEDIA corpus is currently being annotated).<sep> - Finally, a series of assessments was carried out on the new data provided, in particular to verify their quality.<sep> These evaluations will be continued with the search for external collaboration on the project in order to provide data with a performance reference. The entire corpus thus created will join the ELDA catalogue in the course of the year.<sep> Acknowledgements<sep> This work is partially funded by the National Research Agency: PORTMEDIA project (ANR 08 CORD 026 01).<sep> For more information about the PORTMEDIA project, please visit the project website, www.port-media.org> 4<sep> 1 Linguistic Data Consortium<sep> 2. http://catalog.elra.info/
Continuous contextual models for person name recognition in automatic transcriptions<sep> ABSTRACT<sep> The detection of person names in audio streams is a critical problem in speech recognition and understanding, especially because these names carry essential information about the semantic content of the document.<sep> The difficulty of recognition comes from their number, their diversity and the unpredictable nature of their context of appearance: they are often linked to a one-off news item.<sep> These characteristics make it difficult to design recognition lexicons that are sufficiently comprehensive. We address this problem by proposing a method of modelling the lexical contexts associated with personal names; these context models should make it possible to evaluate the probability of a name by analysing the lexical context of its occurrence.<sep> Our first experiments were carried out in the context of the ANR REPERE challenge. They validated both the interest of the approach and the relevance of the proposed models.<sep> 1. INTRODUCTION<sep> Detecting person names in audiovisual documents is a critical problem for spoken content analysis, as these names carry essential information for the intelligibility of the document.<sep> In the context of audio indexing or searching for information in spoken documents, proper names are often directly linked to the user's expectation, either as elements of the query or as being indirectly linked to it.<sep> The natural language processing community has devoted many studies to the detection of named entities, often on relatively well-structured data.<sep> The detection of proper names in speech poses particular problems related to the nature of the data and the components involved in the detection systems. The standard approach is to rely on an automatic speech recognition system (ASR) whose lexicon includes all the names that must be detected.<sep> In a real context, this technique encounters a major difficulty linked to the number, the diversity of proper names and the fact that they are often attached to particular events or places, which limits the frequency of a name and increases the difficulty of its statistical modeling.<sep> In fact, the construction of exhaustive lexicons of proper names is impossible.<sep> Most of the proposed methods in speech recognition have focused on either automatic (or semi-automatic) updates of lexicons or acoustic search methods in recognition graphs, which allow searching in databases previously decoded with an incomplete lexicon. This last method is based on the idea that, although we do not have a priori data allowing the integration of all possible names in dictionaries and language models, phonetic search remains possible and often sufficient.<sep> Our work is based on the context of finding names in large databases that are automatically transcribed by an ASR whose lexicon does not cover all the names of people contained in the audio stream. The initial idea is that missing names are generally rare and often attached to particular contexts (news, infrequent themes, etc.).<sep> This characteristic implies a strong dependence between a name and the overall context in which it is pronounced.<sep> This is the dependence that we want to model and then exploit to enable the detection of names that would not have been recognized by an ASR.<sep> Most of the methods proposed in the past for context representation rely either on short-term statistics, typically n-gram models, or on a bag-of-words approach in which the temporal structure of contexts is lost. Here, we present a method of context representation that integrates both this temporal structure and that allows to capture, in a relatively simple formalism, short and long term dependencies. This method is based on the projection of lexical contexts in a continuous low-dimensional space.<sep> The next section provides a short overview of the different approaches proposed in the literature for person name detection (i.e. section 2).<sep> Section 3 describes the original approach we suggest for continuous lexical context modelling. Section 4 presents the experiments conducted and analyses the first results obtained.<sep> The last section concludes and presents some perspectives opened by this study.<sep> 2. Modelling contexts: state of the art<sep> Most of Named Entity Detection systems rely on an efficient capture of relevant pieces of information from lexical contexts where proper names occur. Differences between existing techniques mainly stand within the kind of model and the nature of this information, either lexical, structural, syntactic or semantic.<sep> In particular, N-gram models have been widely used to represent the sequentiality of the N words occurring before a given name.<sep> In (Béchet et al., 2000), the named entities are automatically extracted to learn a statistical classifier.<sep> In both cases, the temporality of words present in the contexts is captured, but only on windows of fairly small sizes; however, the lexical dependencies in the longer term carry information about the subject or the global context in which the noun appears...<sep> An alternative commonly used is to consider the frequencies of the words in the context without taking into account their sequentiality; this approach based on the vectorial representation of a bag-of-words is a standard in automatic language processing (Pedersen et al., 2005) and information retrieval (Pedersen et al., 2006; Kozareva et Ravi, 2011). It has the advantage of a certain robustness and ease of estimation, but the temporal structure of the context (or document) is lost.<sep> Furthermore, this approach can allow the estimation of distributional models of contexts (Miller and Charles, 1991; Harris, 1968).<sep> 3. Temporal and lexical context<sep> The approach proposed in this paper relies on the assumption that a person name is related to the lexical context it appears in.<sep> In order to model these name-to-context dependencies, we propose to consider a proper name as a latent variable occurring in various observable contexts.<sep> With regards to this hypothesis, a person name should be discovered in speech recognition outputs by considering its context, even if the name has not been proposed by the ASR system.<sep> This is particularly true for proper names, since many of them are not in the vocabulary of the transcription system and will therefore never be recognized.<sep> Our approach consists in capturing name-to-context dependencies by using statistical models.<sep> Classical techniques rely on short-term context-modeling, or on long-term cooccurrences represented in a Vector Space Model (VSM).<sep> On the one hand, short-term context models are generally based on n-gram statistics, where n is lower than 6 due to complexity reasons.<sep> Consequently, these models miss long-term word dependencies that bring semantic and pragmatic information.<sep> On the other hand, co-occurrence models represent a document as a bag of words, without any information related to its temporal structure.<sep> Therefore, the estimate of co-occurrence statistics in VSM is possible on relatively limited corpus, but critical information, such as word sequentiality notably, is definitely lost.<sep> Here, the focus is made on the extraction of discriminant information held by the words surrounding proper names.<sep> Indeed, we consider the temporality of words in contexts as an important feature, just as in N-grams and rule-based methods.<sep> Moreover, we assume that medium- and long-term word dependencies could bring relevant information to the latent proper name.<sep> This is especially true for television broadcasts, where many OOV names appear exclusively in a specific context.<sep> For these reasons, we propose a vector representation holding information relative to the positions of words in the contexts, coupled with a larger context window comparable to those used in approaches based on bag-of-words representation.<sep> FIGURE 1 – General framework for the extraction and modelling of the lexical contexts of proper names<sep> Indeed, this window allows to take into account the case where the discriminant information is located in sentences several tens of words away from the person's name.<sep> This original approach, illustrated in Figure 1, is carried out in three steps, described below, for the modelling of contexts for one given person name from examples found in a text database.<sep> 3.1. Context Characterization<sep> Let’s consider one given person name W , and assume that we dispose of a corpus of errorless text documents.<sep> The first step consists in estimating, from this collection of name contexts, the model that will be able to spot the missing proper name W from ASR outputs.<sep> In a formal manner, a context is a sequence of 2 N + 1 words centred on one person name.<sep> The system first extracts from documents of the database, all the contexts CW associated with W .<sep> This set of contexts is denoted SCW .<sep> Documents of the corpus have been pre-processed by removing punctuation marks and by turning texts to lower case, like in ASR outputs.<sep> In a second time, a morpho-syntactic tagger (Schmid, 1994) is applied on the contexts.<sep> The words tagged as NOUN, VERB and ADJECTIVE are kept but replaced by their lemmatized forms.<sep> The words that do not match these POS are substituted with the tag ’NULL’.<sep> Finally, this process removes function words, and reduces the lexicon of SCW by considering the canonical forms of words.<sep> At the end of this second step, we build an overall lexicon LW by considering all the lemmatized words occurring at least one time in the contexts of SCW .<sep> The lexicon LW holds the lexical information of our context representation.<sep> By definition, a context is a sequence of words w[(] [i][)] centred around W , where i is for the relative position of wi comparing to W :<sep> Words are weighted according to their positions in the context.<sep> The weighting takes into account that words closer to W should be more characteristic to this person name than further words in the context.<sep> For a word w[(] [i][)] situated at the position i , the weight Pw ( i ) is computed with<sep> The function is not defined in 0 since the latent word W is supposed to be unobserved.<sep> By combining the lexicon LW and weighted words of each context CW of SCW we build a matrix denoted MW , in which a line represents one context, a column corresponds to one word of LW , and the cells are filled with its weighted position Pwi .<sep> When a word appears several times in one context, the word will be considered only one time with its occurrence closest to W .<sep> If a words of LW does not appear in a context, its corresponding cell in MW is set with the 0 value.<sep> 3.2. Dimension Reduction<sep> The preceding step has produced a matrix MW with dimensions C × L , where C is the number of contexts extracted from the training document set, and L is the size of the overall lexicon.<sep> Since this matrix contains an important proportion of values equal to 0, a dimension reduction strategy is necessary.<sep> Here, a Singular Value Decomposition (SVD) is applied. It aims at reducing the sparsity of data while decreasing the dimension of the lexicon.<sep> The dimension reduction is achieved by separating the matrix MW into three different matrices :<sep> where Σ stands for a diagonal matrix, and U and V are orthogonal matrices.<sep> Vectors composing Σ are re-ordered according to the highest singular values.<sep> The dimension reduction is, then, achieved by deleting the dimensions that present the least variation.<sep> The matrix transformation is obtained with the product of MW by V .<sep> The SVD has been done with the SVDLIBC toolkit.<sep> 3.3. Name Spotting<sep> The reduced space resulting from SVD allows to map each word sequence in a low dimension feature vector.<sep> The spotting process will operate at this level, by searching a matching context in the feature vector stream obtained from the ASR output word stream.<sep> The contextual name model is trained to detect whether an unknown lexical context corresponds or not to a given name in the feature vector stream.<sep> We chose to use a Linear Support Vector Machine classifier with a 2-class SVM.<sep> Our classification strategy relies on the concurrence between two contradictory context matrices.<sep> The first context matrix is MCW , it contains the contexts centred on the person name W . This is called the acceptance matrix of W .<sep> The second is a rejection matrix of W .<sep> It has been built with contexts where the name W is not present.<sep> The SVM classification has been done thanks to the libSVM tool [22].<sep> 4 Experiments<sep> 4.1 Experimental context<sep> The experiments presented in the paper have therefore been done with the data from the REPERE evaluation campaign (Kahn et al. , 2012).<sep> The contexts used to build the acceptance and rejection matrices are taken from three different kinds of document sets.<sep> The first set is composed of around 135,000 news texts produced by AFP (Agence France Presse) in 2009 and 2011.<sep> The second set is from Wikipedia (2012).<sep> It contains around one million and two hundred thousand articles.<sep> A last set contains the manual transcriptions of 280 hours from French Radio and TV shows from past French evaluation campaigns (ESTER1&2, EPAC, ETAPE and previous documents provided by the REPERE challenge).<sep> In these experiments, test data are taken from a development corpus provided by REPERE’s organizers.<sep> It counts 135 audio files for a total of 24 hours of annotated speech initially including 4,172 annotations of spoken person names.<sep> We have reduced this set to 4,130 spoken name occurrences by removing persons for which the real identity cannot be established.<sep> In the end, this set of names corresponds to 845 different identities among which we find mainly the journalists of the shows, French and foreign politicians, sportsmen, famous people, etc.<sep> In this test set, 40% of the identified persons account for 85% of the annotated names.<sep> Names of the last 60% are not pronounced more than twice.<sep> Automatic transcriptions were produced using the LIA transcription system (Nocera et al., 2002).<sep> The ASR output scoring tool reports a 29.4% WER.<sep> We note that 66% of the identities contained in our test corpus are found in the dictionary of the transcription system.<sep> In this experiment, we set the length of the observation windows used for context extraction to 201 words (i.e. a 2 N + 1 word window centred on a person name with N = 100).<sep> At the end of the context extraction, we observed that no context at all have been found for 83 person names.<sep> Moreover, from the set of 845 person names present in the manual annotation, only 323 names (38 . 2% of the person names) count more than 100 extracted contexts.<sep> This 323-speaker set covers 63.3% of the overall number of spoken name occurrences of the test data (2,615 occurrences on a total of 4,130).<sep> This observation led us to limit ourselves to these 323 names for our experiments.<sep> For each of them, contexts are then used for the model training.<sep> Once built, each context matrix is reduced to 100 dimensions by SVD.<sep> At the classification step, in order to learn a more discriminant SVM classifier, for a given name W , we build the corresponding rejection matrix using a random sampling of the contexts of person names different from W .<sep> 5 Results<sep> We propose to achieve spoken name recognition and localization in the ASR output stream at the scale of speech segments.<sep> Our baseline system consists in directly looking for the person names in the 1-Best ASR output using regular expressions.<sep> Since our method assumes that a person name can be discovered in ASR results even if the spoken name is not present in the automatic transcriptions, we are interested in evaluating if our temporal and lexical context representation has captured enough contextual information to learn discriminant model.<sep> On the other hand we also want to evaluate the complementarity of the baseline with our proposition.<sep> The scoring is done by considering in the manual reference only the 323 person names for which we have been able to learn a context model.<sep> The test set therefore contains 2 , 615 spoken occurrences.<sep> The evaluation reports that 21% (549 occurrences) of spoken names cannot be found either in the ASR outputs, nor with the context model.<sep> We have also evaluated that 40% of the spoken names can be found directly either in automatic transcriptions, or by using context models.<sep> Our context based method is unable to find 14% of the occurrences while the spoken name has been found using regular expression.<sep> However, a very interesting result is that 25% of spoken names can be correctly extracted using our approach, while this results cannot be found in the ASR outputs.<sep> This last result confirms the validity of our fundamental assumption.<sep> Finally, by considering the combination of these two approaches (baseline + context), we have found that 79% of the considered spoken names have been correctly discovered.<sep> 6. CONCLUSION AND PERSPECTIVES<sep> In this paper, we have presented a context-based method for retrieving spoken person names in the 1-Best ASR outputs of broadcast TV shows.<sep> Our approach assumes that the occurrence of a person's name is dependent on the lexical context in which it appears, and the modeling of name-to-context dependencies could help the spotting of person names in ASR outputs.<sep> Starting from this idea, we proposed a modeling paradigm where contexts are represented by feature vectors that integrate the temporal structure of large-span lexical contexts.<sep> These vectors are reduced by a classical SVD process, and SVM models are trained to identify the targeted person names in the low-dimension feature-vector space.<sep> Experiments have been conducted on the data sets of the REPERE evaluation campaign.<sep> Results validate our hypothesis of departure: our method improves from 54% to 79% the detection rates of person names.<sep> Future works will focus on increasing the number of person names considered, since our experiments only concern 323 person names for the moment.<sep> We will as well investigate the use of confidence measures provided by the ASR systems in order to increase our system accuracy.<sep> Moreover, once spoken names have been detected, we could try to investigate how to answer the questions "Who is talking to who?" and "About who are people speaking about?" by applying methods like those found in [25, 26].<sep> This work was carried out in the context of the ContNomina project funded by the French National Research Agency (ANR) under contract ANR-12-BS02-0009.
ROOTS: a toolkit for easy, fast and consistent processing of large sequential annotated data collections<sep> ABSTRACT<sep> Many automatic speech and natural language processing tools now allow documents to be annotated, both written and spoken.<sep> However, this software richness leads to a great diversity of file formats and types of information. Due to this heterogeneity, the development of complex processing processes often requires the conversion and alignment of numerous information, sometimes repeatedly.<sep> To circumvent this problem, this paper presents ROOTS, a free toolkit dedicated to the homogeneous manipulation of annotated sequential data.<sep> Written in C++ and with an API in several languages, ROOTS is fast and easy to use. These properties are supported by two sample applications.<sep> 1. Introduction<sep> The development of new methods for automatic speech or natural language processing (NLP) often involves, beyond scientific aspects, the resolution of various technical and practical data management problems.<sep> First, the type of data, their distribution and the nature of the descriptors required for two different tasks are rarely the same.<sep> For instance, in the field of NLP, developing a named entity extractor on texts mainly requires morphosyntactic and syntactic annotations, and relies on corpora with a high proportion of named entities.<sep> While the learning of a phonetician requires above all a corpus aligned with graphemes and phonemes, possibly augmented with etymological information on the words represented, the a priori distributions of these different elements remain of lesser importance.<sep> Second, many dedicated systems or expert resources exist to provide annotations, e.g., part of speech (POS) taggers, named entity extractors, pronunciation dictionaries, list of proper names, etc. However, most of these tools use different file formats, time scales, or alphabets of tags.<sep> This assessment also stands for manual annotation tools since many of them coexist without sharing interoperable formats.<sep> This heterogeneity frequently causes long and tedious work when converting and aligning information from different tools.<sep> Possibly, some information is altered, simplified or even lost, while some other is redundantly stored over different files.<sep> Beyond the waste of time, this data management complexity can lead to errors in programs and in results, all the more frequently that addressed tasks are nowadays more and more elaborate.<sep> The objective of this paper is to introduce a toolkit, called ROOTS, which homogenizes the management of such annotated data and thus simplifies application developments, especially for research purposes, in the frame of speech processing and NLP.<sep> ROOTS is the result of several years of internal development and, as we believe it should benefit the community, it has recently been freely downloadable on the Internet (http://roots-toolkit.gforge.inria.fr).<sep> This paper presents this first public version of the tool.<sep> Precisely, Section 2 details the architecture of ROOTS.<sep> The following sections then compare our tool to other existing tools in section 3, and then illustrate its practical functioning and performance in section 4 through two tasks: the unsupervised annotation of a large corpus of digital books and the extraction of statistics from annotations.<sep> 2. Presentation of the Roots tool<sep> In order to homogenize and to synchronize different annotation levels, (Barbot et al., 2011) have initially proposed ROOTS as a theoretical solution based on matrix algebraic relations.<sep> A Perl prototype of this solution has been validated in (Boëffard et al., 2012) by implementing an automatic audiobook corpus construction process for text-to-speech (TTS).<sep> This process was taking advantage of ROOTS to consistently represent numerous annotation levels.<sep> Since, a new implementation in C++ has been developed, and ROOTS is now a complete user-friendly toolkit able to efficiently process large collections of annotated sequential data, in particular from oral or written documents.<sep> This section provides an overview by presenting its logical data architecture, the features made available to users and its storage capabilities.<sep> 2.1 Logical data architecture<sep> Figure 1: Hierarchical organization of data in ROOTS.<sep> FIGURE 2 – Example of 3 sequences linked by 2 relations, R[[mot]]<sep> As summarized in Figure 1, data are organized hierarchically in ROOTS.<sep> As a fundamental concept, data in ROOTS is modeled as sequences of items.<sep> These items can be of many types, e.g., words, graphemes, named entity classes, signal segments, etc., and can thus represent various annotation levels of the same data.<sep> Correspondences between items from different sequences are then defined as algebraic relations, leading to a graph where nodes are items and edges are derived from relations.<sep> The composition of the algebraic relations that form the shortest path between two sequences makes it possible to find correspondences between items even in the absence of a direct relationship.<sep> An example of a sequence of words annotated with POS and phonemes is given in Figure 2.<sep> Interested readers will find all theoretical details in (Barbot et al., 2011).<sep> Sequences of the same content are gathered into utterances, or statements in ROOTS terminology.<sep> They can correspond to any relevant unit for a given domain (an isolated word, a sentence, a breath group, etc.).<sep> Finally, a list of utterances forms a corpus.<sep> Many structures can be modelled as a corpus: paragraphs, book chapters, news reports, broadcast news shows, etc.<sep> To hierarchize structures, a corpus can be chunked into subcorpora, for instance to represent a chapter as a list of paragraphs.<sep> These "vertical" divisions of a corpus (see figure 1) are called chunks in ROOTS.<sep> Finally, besides this “vertical” slicing, corpora can also be partitioned “horizontally” into layers.<sep> These layers allow, if necessary, to isolate certain annotations from the same level of abstraction.<sep> For instance, if dealing with broadcast news shows, it may be interesting to cut the corpus into 3 layers: one for acoustic and phonetic information (fundamental frequencies, spectra, allophones...).<sep> another one grouping the linguistic information (orthographic transcription, POS tagging, syntax trees...) ;<sep> A last one for metadata (time of broadcast, location of a report...). FIGURE 3 – Example of structuring files for a corpus of daily broadcast news shows.<sep> 2.2 API and tools<sep> ROOTS is based on a library written in C++ and gathers a set of utilities.<sep> The library represents about 33K lines of code.<sep> It comes with a rich and widely documented API that offers the following features for the different elements manipulated:<sep> - Item: get and set the content or characteristics, e.g., gender, number for POS ; get items which are in relation with another item ; dump[2] .<sep> - Relation: test, get the related items; link or unlink items;<sep> - Sequence: add, remove, get, and update one or several items ; dump.<sep> - Utterance: add, remove, extract and update sequences and internal relations ; get direct or composed relations between sequences ; combine, split and save.<sep> - Corpus: add, remove, get, and update an utterance ; add and remove a chunk or a layer ; dump.<sep> For simple and fast prototyping, a Perl binding of this API is also available. This binding has been generated by the open source automatic interface generator SWIG[3] .<sep> Thus, ROOTS can be ported to many other programming languages at lower costs.<sep> In particular, a port to the Python language is planned.<sep> Utility scripts based on the Perl API are available for the most useful operations (merging and splitting corpora, searching a corpus, textual and graphical visualization of data, etc.).<sep> Other scripts enable commandline imports and exports with the standard speech and language processing tools HTK (Young et al., 2009), Praat (Boersma, 2002), Transcriber (Barras et al., 2001), and WaveSurfer (Sj¨olander and Beskow, 2000).<sep> ROOTS makes it easy to add other formats, such as CSV.<sep> All sources, documentation and tutorials are freely available online at http://roots-toolkit.gforge.inria.fr.<sep> 2.3 Data storage<sep> The information is saved in files in ROOTS, not in databases.<sep> Thus, rudimentary operations on files (move, delete, copy...) are known by all users and do not require any particular skill.<sep> By default, a corpus is simply stored as a single file containing all the statements, sequences, items and relations. If the corpus is structured into sub-corpora or layers, a file is created for each subdivision.<sep> This strategy allows to lighten the reading and writing operations by targeting only some useful portions of the entire corpus. Moreover, each sub-file is itself seen as a ROOTS corpus and can therefore be used independently.<sep> This allows, for example, to test and adjust a program on only a fraction of a vast corpus before launching it on its entirety.<sep> Taking the example of a corpus of television news broadcasts, we can imagine a file distribution such as that presented in figure 3.<sep> The file at the entry point (on the left) represents the entire corpus. It simply lists the files containing the annotations of the journal for each day. Similarly, each of these files points to the files containing its different layers of information, subject by subject.<sep> In practice, this structuring of the files is transparent for users who wish to consult the corpus.<sep> Finally, the use of resources is optimized by a cache on the chunks, which delays the loading of files as much as possible, and therefore the corresponding memory allocations.<sep> Two file formats are currently available: XML and JSON.<sep> They are readable without special tools and are suitable for the implementation of web services.<sep> Other formats will be added in future versions, including a binary format that is desirable for developing very fast applications.<sep> 3 Comparison with existing tools<sep> Other tools allow the processing of annotated data.<sep> Among them, the GATE system (Cunningham, 2002) proposes to interconnect annotation flows for the development of TAL bricks. However, GATE relies on an integrated development environment and therefore does not easily integrate third-party tools.<sep> More recently, the NXT toolbox has been proposed for the management of multimodal corpora (Carletta et al., 2005; Calhoun et al., 2010).<sep> This project is interested in large, multiply annotated corpora, proposing a generic model for organizing data.<sep> This model is similar to that of a database, with access to the data by means of a query language.<sep> ROOTS, on the other hand, leaves it up to the user to browse the data as they see fit.<sep> Furthermore, the mechanisms that allow the annotations of different orders to be linked are not optimised in NXT, whereas this aspect is at the heart of our tool.<sep> In a more general approach, UIMA (Ferrucci and Lally, 2004; Ferrucci et al., 2006) proposes software engineering standards for the management of unstructured data, including their annotation and processing.<sep> However, UIMA is, in our opinion, too technically elaborate to allow for the rapid and easy prototyping of ideas for solutions, as is often required in research work.<sep> It is therefore rather dedicated to industrial developments.<sep> In addition, UIMA advocates a common format for data processing tools while the philosophy of ROOTS is to allow the construction of bridges between the specific formats of these tools at a lower cost. In this spirit, ROOTS is close to the work done in the context of the Festival speech synthesis system (Black et al., 2002).<sep> This system is based on the HRG formalism, for Heterogenous Relation Graphs, which aims to offer a unique way of representing the different levels of information involved in a synthesis system (Taylor et al., 2001).<sep> HRG thus proposes a C++ library that groups classes for multiple linguistic, phonological, acoustic structures, etc., and their relationship.<sep> Our tool is nevertheless distinguished from HRG because ROOTS is completely autonomous while HRG is an integral part of the Festival system.<sep> Furthermore, ROOTS has a real programming interface (API), in C++ and Perl. Finally, it should be noted for all useful purposes that the problems caused by the manipulation of very large volumes of data (Jacobs, 2009), of the order of petabytes, are not deliberately taken into account, either in this article or in ROOTS more generally.<sep> FIGURE 4 – Schematic view of the relationships between sequences.<sep> 4 Examples of applications<sep> ROOTS has been developed to help users create and process corpora with a large variety of information coming from various dedicated data analysis tools.<sep> This section demonstrates these capabilities on an example of building such a corpus, and then on a task of calculating statistics from a corpus created via ROOTS.<sep> The experiments were performed on a machine equipped with 64 Intel Xeon cores clocked at 2 GHz and 120 GB of RAM.<sep> 4.1. Construction of an annotated corpus of digital books<sep> Based on a raw text in French, we designed an automatic processing chain which produces and links the following information: graphemes, POS, lemmas, named entities, syntax trees, phonemes, non speech sounds and syllables.<sep> As shown in Figure 4, this is achieved by augmenting a rudimentary textual layer containing the sole sequences of raw words and corresponding graphemes with a linguistic and a phonological layer.<sep> These two last layers are produced respectively from the results of two specialized tools: a software suite for TAL from the company Synapse Développement and a phonetization web service from the company Voxygen.<sep> As often, each tool relies on its own specific word tokenization[2] . Three different sequences of words are stored (raw words, words from linguistic processing or words from the phonetizer) and are related using graphemes as pivots.<sep> Outputs of the annotation tools are converted into ROOTS objects using Perl scripts written for the occasion (about 2,000 lines of code).<sep> TABLE 1 – Number of automatically generated items in the corpus of digital books.<sep> TABLE 2 – List of the 12 most frequent syllables at the end of words in the corpus of books.<sep> The automatic annotation process described above has been applied to 1,300 free e-books in French collected from http://www.ebooksgratuits.com.<sep> The raw text of these books was thus transformed into a ROOTS corpus whose statistics are presented in Table 1.<sep> This corpus is spread over 35,388 JSON files for a total disk usage of about 220 GB. Processing time was about 15 hours. Individually, this is about 27 files, 173 MB, and 45 min per e-book.<sep> This size could be greatly reduced by compression since JSON is a verbose format.<sep> The time taken to execute the annotation process was fifteen hours and is mainly due to calls to external tools such as the online phonetization service.<sep> 5.1. Statistics extraction<sep> This section now demonstrates the simplicity of using the ROOTS API. To do this, and in order to best illustrate the basic features, we assume that we want to list and count the syllables at the end of words in a corpus, except for monosyllabic words.<sep> This task is realized using the short script presented in Algorithm 1.<sep> It is composed of two parts: the function count last syllables (lines 3-16) and the main code (l. 18-27).<sep> The main code declares a map %frequency to store syllable counts (l. 20). Then, a ROOTS corpus is created and populated by loading a JSON file (l. 22).<sep> The corpus is then browsed, phrase by phrase, as follows: a copy of each phrase is retrieved (l. 21), the table is updated by the function compter_dernieres_syllabes (l. 22), then the copy is destroyed to free up memory (l. 23).<sep> Finally, all encountered syllables and their respective number of occurrences are displayed (l. 25-27).<sep> The function count_last_syllables takes as input the reference to the table of accounts and a reference to an utterance object, containing a sentence (l. 4-5).<sep> The word sequence of this utterance is retrieved (line 6) and all the words are browsed (line 7).<sep> For each word, the list of related syllables is computed (l. 8).<sep> After checking if the word is not monosyllabic (l. 11), the last syllable is accessed and its string value is got (l. 12). Finally, the frequency of the current syllable is either initialized or updated (l. 13-15).<sep> This script was applied in parallel on each digital book of the corpus described in section 4.1. Algorithm 1: Perl script using the ROOTS API to count syllables.<sep> The overall execution has lasted about 20 min, with a duration of 1 min and a 300 MB memory usage on average per e-book.<sep> The result of the 12 most frequent syllables is given in Table 2.<sep> A quick analysis of these results shows that most words end with /m˜A/, which is a typical ending for adverbs in French, or with /e/ or /E/, which are verb inflection marks in French for past participles and the imperfect tense, respectively.<sep> Hence, the results are consistent with the narrative style of the corpus.<sep> 5. Conclusion and further developments<sep> In this paper, we have presented a powerful toolkit called ROOTS which enables easy, fast and consistent generation, management and processing of large annotated sequential data collections, mainly from oral or written data.<sep> After presenting the tool and comparing it to the existing ones, its performance was demonstrated through two application examples.<sep> ROOTS is fully operational, open source and easy to extend.<sep> For these multiple reasons, we think it should be profitable to the community.<sep> In future versions, a graphical user interface allowing manual editing and new import/export features will be added.<sep> It is also envisaged to extend the notion of sequence to that of lattice, useful for modelling the uncertainty of certain information.<sep> Finally, corpora generated using ROOTS on free data sets will be made available soon. Especially, the corpus of French e-books presented in our experiments.<sep> 1. Under the GNU Lesser General Public Licence (LGPL) v3.0.<sep> 2. For example, one may keep acronyms as one word while the other may explode them into sequences of initials.
Classification of imperfect automatic transcriptions: Should the calculation of the word error rate be adapted?<sep> ABSTRACT<sep> Automatic speech recognition (ASR) systems are now very efficient. However, the quality of transcription is strongly degraded in very noisy environments, which affects the performance of applications using them, such as classification tasks.<sep> In this paper, we propose to identify themes in telephone conversation services using the classical Term Frequency-Inverse Document Frequency method with Gini purity criteria (TF-IDF-Gini) and with a Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) approach.<sep> These two representations are then used in a classification process using SVM to find the theme present in the conversation.<sep> Finally, we propose to discuss the quality, in terms of error rate, of the words identified as discriminative and non-discriminative by the methods of representation of dialogues studied in this article.<sep> 1. Introduction<sep> The application considered in this paper concerns the automatic analysis of telephone conversations between an agent and a customer in a customer care service of the Paris transportation system.<sep> The agent follows a particular protocol during the conversation to address customer requests or complaints.<sep> This paper presents a system for the automatic extraction of themes from telephone conversations.<sep> A single theme is then proposed for each conversation.<sep> In this particular task, conversations may contain very noisy segments, which results in a significant degradation of their automatic transcription quality using an Automatic Speech Recognition (ASR) system.<sep> In the context of Information Retrieval (IR) tasks, the main feature used is the word term frequency .<sep> This specific feature allows to obtain a subset of discriminative words for a considered class (a “theme” in this study).<sep> Finally, this set of discriminative words should permit to compose a vector representation of conversation themes in the semantic space.<sep> While the term frequency is a performant feature in the context of manually written texts or transcripts, its application to automatic transcriptions seems to be more difficult since transcription errors are inevitable.<sep> Indeed, these errors would lead to an incorrect representation of the discriminative words.<sep> For this reason, the projection of the automatically transcribed words in a more abstracted space could increase the robustness of the applications to the ASR errors.<sep> In this paper, we propose to compare two unsupervised representations of discriminative words in highly imperfect transcriptions (i.e. very high word error rate) with the aim of automatically identifying themes of telephone conversations.<sep> The classical Term Frequency-Inverse Document Frequency with Gini purity criteria (TF-IDF-Gini) method (Robertson, 2004) is firstly applied to extract discriminative words for each theme to identify from transcriptions.<sep> We secondly propose to explore a topic space representation of discriminative words with the use of the Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) approach (Blei et al., 2003).<sep> Each representation is finally used to train a Support Vector Machine (SVM) classifier to automatically associate a theme to a conversation.<sep> Finally, we also propose in this article a discussion about the classification performance impact of discriminative and nondiscriminative words chosen by both methods of representation studied.<sep> The following section presents previous work done in this area.<sep> Part 3 introduces the methods of word representation studied.<sep> The experimental results are presented in part 4.<sep> A discussion of the accuracy of the transcription of the discriminant words is proposed in section 4.3, before concluding in section 5.<sep> 2. Related work<sep> Different summaries of recent works have been carried out around the analysis of conversations (Tur and De Mori, 2011), the processing of speech (Melamed and Gilbert, 2011), the identification (Hazen, 2011) and the segmentation of topics (Purver, 2011).<sep> The classical Term Frequency-Inverse Document Frequency (TF-IDF) (Robertson, 2004) has been widely used for extracting discriminative words from texts.<sep> Improvements were found when associating the Gini purity criteria (Dong et al., 2011).<sep> Other approaches proposed to consider the document as a mixture of latent topics.<sep> These methods, such as Latent Semantic Analysis (LSA) (Deerwester et al., 1990; Bellegarda, 1997), Probabilistic LSA (PLSA) (Hofmann, 1999) or Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) (Blei et al., 2003), build a higher-level representation of the document in a topic space.<sep> The documents are then considered as a bag-of-words (Salton, 1989); the performance of these methods has been demonstrated on many tasks.<sep> LDA is a generative model that considers that a theme is associated with each occurrence of a word composing the document, rather than associating a topic with the complete document.<sep> Thereby, a document can change of topics from a word to another.<sep> However, the word occurrences are connected by a latent variable which controls the global respect of the distribution of the topics in the document.<sep> These latent topics are characterized by a distribution of word probabilities which are associated with them.<sep> PLSA and LDA models have been shown to generally outperform LSA on IR tasks (Hofmann, 2001).<sep> Moreover, LDA provides a direct estimate of the relevance of a topic knowing a word set.<sep> Support Vector Machines (SVM) are a set of supervised learning techniques.<sep> Knowing a sample, SVMs determine a separation plan between parts of the sample called support vector .<sep> Then, a separating hyperplane that maximizes the margin between the support vectors and the hyperplane separator (Vapnik, 1963) is calculated.<sep> SVMs were used for the first time by (Boser et al., 1992) both in regression (M¨uller et al., 1997) and in classification (Joachims, 1999) tasks.<sep> The SVM popularity is due to the good results achieved in these two specific tasks and the low number of parameters requiring adjustment.<sep> An LDA-based approach combined with a SVM classification process has recently been studied in various domains, such as text classification (Zrigui et al., 2012), stylometry (Arun et al., 2009), information retrieval (Kim et al., 2009), social event detection (Morchid et al., 2013), or image detection (Tang et al., 2009).<sep> To our knowledge, a combined LDA-SVM approach has not yet been applied to theme classification of highly imperfect automatic transcriptions but was used in the context of keyword and keyphrase extraction in automatic transcriptions (Sheeba and Vivekanandan, 2012).<sep> The TF-IDF extraction method coupled with a SVM classification, which constitutes our baseline system, has been widely studied in text classification such as (Lan et al., 2005; Georgescul et al., 2006).<sep> 3. Theme identification methods<sep> This section presents the proposed theme classification system using discriminative words extracted from highly imperfect transcriptions.<sep> The system is composed of two main parts.<sep> The first one creates a vector representation of words with two different unsupervised approaches: a term frequency Okapi/BM25 vector (Robertson, 2004) with the TFIDF-Gini method (Dong et al., 2011) and a topic space representation with the LDA approach (Blei et al., 2003).<sep> The second part uses the extracted vectors to learn SVM classifiers.<sep> Figure 1 presents the global architecture of the proposed classification system using manual (MAN) and automatic (ASR) transcriptions.<sep> Figure 1: General approach of the classification system.<sep> 3.1. Description of dialogue features<sep> 3.1.1. Frequency representation of words<sep> Let’s consider a corpus D of dialogues d with a word vocabulary V = {w 1 , … , wN } of size N where d is seen as a bag-of-words (Salton, 1989).<sep> A term of V is chosen according to its importance δt in the theme t by calculating its Term Frequency (TF), its Inverse Document Frequency (IDF) (Robertson, 2004) and the Gini purity criteria (Dong et al., 2011) that is common for all the themes.<sep> This set of scores δ composes the frequency model f :<sep> Then the words with highest scores ∆ for all themes T are extracted and constitute a discriminative word subset V∆ (each theme t ∈ T has its own score δt ) and its own frequency γ in the model f (Morchid et al., 2013b):<sep> For each dialogue d ∈ D , a semantic feature vector Vd[s] is determined.<sep> The n[th] (1 ≤ n ≤| V∆ | ) feature Vd[s][[] [n][]][,] is composed with the number of occurrences of the word wn ( |wn| ) in d and the score ∆ of wn (see eq 1) in the discriminative word set V∆ :<sep> 3.1.2 Topic representation by space<sep> The topic representation is performed using a Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) based approach (see section 2.).<sep> A thematic space m of n topics is then obtained with, for each theme z , the probability of each word w of V knowing z ( P ( w|z ) = Vz[w]) and for the entire model [ m], the probability of each theme z knowing the model m ( P ( z|m ) = Vm[z]).<sep> For every dialogue d of a corpus D , a first parameter θ is drawn according to a Dirichlet law of parameter α .<sep> A second parameter φ is drawn according to the same Dirichlet law of parameter β .<sep> Then, to generate every word w of the document d , a latent topic z is drawn from a multinomial distribution on θ .<sep> Knowing this topic z , the distribution of the words is a multinomial of parameters φ .<sep> The parameter θ is defined for all documents from the same initial parameter α .<sep> This allows to obtain a parameter binding the documents all together (Blei et al., 2003).<sep> Mapping of conversations/topic space:<sep> The Gibbs sampling algorithm (Griffiths and Steyvers, 2002) was used to infer a dialogue d with the n topics of the thematic space m .<sep> This algorithm is based on the Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) method.<sep> Thus, the Gibbs sampling allows to obtain samples of the distribution parameters θ knowing a word w of a test document and a given topic z .<sep> A feature vector Vz[d] of the topic representation of d is then obtained.<sep> The k[th] feature Vz[d][[] [k][]] (where 1 ≤ k ≤ n ) is the probability of the topic zk knowing the dialogue d :<sep> 3.2. SVM classification<sep> During this stage, the classifiers are trained from the vectorial representation of words to automatically assign the most relevant theme to each conversation.<sep> The classification process requires a multi-class classifier.<sep> For this multi-theme problem, T denotes the number of themes and ti, i = 1 , … , T denotes the T themes.<sep> A binary classifier is used with a linear kernel for every pair of distinct themes. As a result, all binary classifiers T ( T − 1) / 2 are constructed together.<sep> The binary classifier Ci,j is trained from example data where ti is a positive class and tj a negative class ( i ̸ = j ).<sep> Once the vote of all the classifiers is completed, the theme having the highest number of votes is finally assigned to the dialogue d.<sep> 4. Experiments<sep> 4.1. Experimental protocol<sep> In order to perform experiments on the conversation theme identification, the corpus of the DECODA project was used (Bechet et al., 2012).<sep> This corpus is composed of 1,067 telephone conversations split into a train set (740 dialogues) and a test set (327 dialogues), and manually annotated with 8 conversation themes: problems of itinerary , lost and found , time schedules , transportation cards , state of the traffic , fares , infractions and special offers .<sep> The training set is used to define a subset of discriminative words (section 3.1.).<sep> This set allows to elaborate a semantic space for each conversation of the test corpus with the basic TF-IDF-Gini method.<sep> In the experiments, the number of discriminative words has been varied from 800 to the total number of words contained in the training corpus (7,920 words).<sep> The test corpus contains 3,806 words (70.8% occur in the train corpus).<sep> In the same way, a topic vector is calculated by mapping each dialogue of the test corpus with each topic space.<sep> A set of 25 topic spaces with a different topic number ( { 5 , … , 600 } ) is elaborated by using a LDA model in the train corpus (example: test = TRS → LDA train corpus = TRS) . The topic spaces are made with the Mallet Java implementation (McCallum, 2002) of LDA.<sep> Then, a SVM classifier is learned with the LIBSVM library (Chang and Lin, 2011) for both configurations.<sep> The parameters are optimized by cross validation on the learning corpus.<sep> The LIA-Speeral ASR system is used for the experiments (Linarès et al., 2007).<sep> The acoustic models parameters (230,000 Gaussians/triphone modeling) are estimated by maximum a-posteriori (MAP) adaptation from 150 hours of speech (telephone conditions).<sep> A tri-gram language model was obtained by adapting a basic language model with the transcriptions of the DECODA learning corpus.<sep> The vocabulary contains 5,782 words.<sep> The initial Word Error Rate (WER) is 45.8% on the training set and 58.0% on the test set.<sep> These high error rates are mainly due to speech disfluencies and to adverse acoustic environments, when, for example, users call from stations with a mobile phone.<sep> A "stop list" of 126 words[2] was used, which results in a TEM of 33.8% (learning) and 49.5% (test).<sep> Experiments are conducted with the two unsupervised methods (TF-IDF-Gini / LDA) on the manual (TRS) and the automatic transcriptions only (ASR).<sep> We also propose to study the combination of both manual and automatic transcriptions (TRS+ASR) in order to see if ASR errors can be compensated by the correct reference words.<sep> FIGURE 2 – Performance of the theme classification as a function of the number of discriminating words (a) and the number of theme spaces (b).<sep> FIGURE 3 – Word error rate of the n discriminant words extracted with TF-IDF-Gini (a) and LDA (b).<sep> 4.2 Performance of theme identification<sep> Figure 2 presents the theme classification accuracy obtained by the TF-IDF-Gini and the LDA approaches on the test corpus for all transcription configurations (MAN/RAP) when varying the word extraction conditions (number of discriminative words and number of topics).<sep> We can see that the LDA-based method outperforms all the results obtained by the TF-IDF-Gini approach (see table 1).<sep> As expected, the MAN → MAN configuration gives the best classification results with a gain of 6.9 points with the LDA method.<sep> When comparing the training corpus types, we can also note that best performance on the ASR test is obtained with the ASR training data.<sep> A gain of 10.9 points is noted with the LDA method compared to the TF-IDF-Gini approach on the automatic transcriptions of conversations.<sep> It seems clear that using comparable training and testing configurations allows to achieve the best classification performance, whether it be on manual or on automatic transcriptions.<sep> We can finally note that the LDA approach performance has a tendency to fluctuate when varying the number of topics.<sep> This could be explained by the high Word Error Rate (WER) of the targeted corpus: indeed, the words chosen as discriminative in particular topic number conditions could be wrongly transcribed in a high proportion.<sep> We can support this remark by analyzing the results obtained with 90 topics (see figure 2).<sep> An important performance drop is observed for the RAP training condition (RAP → RAP and MAN → RAP) while a smaller performance drop is seen when including the reference transcriptions during the training process (RAP+MAN → RAP and MAN → MAN).<sep> 4.3. Transcription accuracy of discriminative words<sep> While the performance with the TF-IDF-Gini approach is clearly better on manual transcriptions (table 1), the performance is almost identical on manual and on automatic transcriptions with the LDA method (respectively 86.6% and 81.4% of classification accuracy).<sep> We think that the LDA-based approach can better manage the errors contained in the automatic transcriptions by choosing discriminative words with the lowest transcription error rate.<sep> Figure 3 compares the Word Error Rates (WER) of the n most discriminative words using TF-IDF-Gini and LDA approaches on all the configurations (TRS/ASR).<sep> The score s ( w ) used to find the most relevant words for the LDA approach is computed with: where [−→] V[w] is the vector representation of a word w in all topics z of the topic space m , [−−→] V[m] is the vector representation of all the topics z in m and ⟨·, ·⟩ is the inner product.<sep> The WER is then classically computed on the n most discriminative words (weight of 1 for each word).<sep> If we firstly compare the different configurations (TRS/ASR), we can note that the higher the theme classification accuracy is (table 1), the lower the WER is.<sep> This can be observed on both methods.<sep> Moreover, we can see that the TEM obtained with the LDA approach is slightly lower than the one obtained with the TF-IDF-Gini method, no matter the configuration considered.<sep> This means that a better transcription accuracy is associated to the discriminative words extracted with the LDA approach in comparison to the one obtained with the TF-IDF-Gini method, which could explain the higher classification performance reached by the LDA-based configuration.<sep> 5. Conclusions<sep> In this paper, we presented an architecture to identify conversation themes from highly imperfect transcriptions.<sep> Two unsupervised methods of conversation representation (TF-IDF-Gini and LDA) were compared.<sep> We have shown that the topic representation obtained with the LDA method outperforms the classification results obtained with the classical TF-IDF-Gini approach.<sep> The classification accuracy reaches 86.6% on manual transcriptions and 81.4% on automatic transcriptions with a respective gain of 6.9 and 10.9 points.<sep> We also discussed the possible link between classification performance and transcription accuracy.<sep> The proposed analysis showed that the best classification results are obtained on configurations which extract the discriminative words having a lower Word Error Rate.<sep> The promising results will lead to a more detailed qualitative study in future work.<sep> Indeed, this preliminary study could be greatly extended with new analysis by taking into account, for example, the discriminative word weights in the transcription accuracy evaluation.<sep> A general perspective would be to propose a solution to estimate the classification performance depending on the transcription accuracy.<sep> In the context of evaluation metrics, it would also be interesting to find another way to estimate the accuracy of automatic transcriptions in the context of a specific task since the classical WER is not a good indicator of transcription quality in an applicative context.<sep> This work was funded by the SUMACC and DECODA projects supported by the French National Research Agency (ANR) under contract ANR-10-CORD-007 and ANR-09-CORD-005.<sep> The term discriminant is associated with a word if it allows one class to be chosen over another.<sep> 2. http://code.google.com/p/stop-words/
Automatic speech recognition using ant colonies<sep> ABSTRACT<sep> This article presents an original approach that allows the decoding of graphs from an Automatic Speech Recognition System (ASR) using a constructive algorithm: ant colonies.<sep> Applying a higher order language model to a graph requires its extension in order to build histories corresponding to each new n-gram observed.<sep> This extension can quickly generate heavy calculations and significant memory consumption.<sep> We propose an alternative where ant colonies explore the graph with a new language model without the necessity of expanding it.<sep> We first present encouraging results based on the TED English corpus where 2-grams are re-evaluated as 4-grams.<sep> Finally, we discuss the advantages of this approach which allows for massively parallelizable decoding for the same graph as well as strict controls of computation time and memory.<sep> 1. Introduction<sep> In this article, we introduce a new paradigm for the exploration of graphs resulting from an automatic speech recognition system (ASR).<sep> A problem that arises during this exploration of word graphs is when higher-order language models are applied to them.<sep> Indeed, the number of paths grows with the language model order.<sep> For example, the size of a simple word graph decoded with a 2-gram model and expanded to a 4-gram model is tenfold.<sep> Several techniques have been successfully applied to approach (compact-expansion) or perform cuts in the search (beam-search).<sep> Here, we present an alternative method based on a constructive version of an algorithm that is widely used in operational research: an ant colony algorithm.<sep> Such algorithms have been successfully applied to the travelling salesman problem or lexical disambiguation for example.<sep> The paper is structured as follows: In the 2 [nd] section, we briefly review decoding techniques for ASR system with large vocabularies and then ant colony algorithms in general.<sep> Section 3 presents the overall system that was used to carry out our work.<sep> Then, we present all the experiments we conducted in section 6 with their analysis, followed by a discussion in the 7 [th] section.<sep> Finally we conclude by proposing some interesting perspectives related to the use of this algorithm.<sep> 2. State of the art<sep> 2.1. Classical approaches<sep> The principle of ASR systems is to find in a graph the hypothesis that will maximize the probabilities of the acoustic and language models.<sep> Generally, heuristics are applied to limit the size of the search space.<sep> We can find several approaches to dynamically generate hypotheses in the literature:<sep> - synchronous graph algorithms that generate a virtual copy of the graph for all hypotheses ending at a fixed time t .<sep> The next word is shared but is associated to several timelines.<sep> In this approach, the dynamic alignment algorithm is applied for each new word without any conservation of their timelines.<sep> The implementation of this algorithm is rare (Ortmanns et Ney, 2000).<sep> - reentrant graph algorithms, where a virtual copy of the graph is explored for every linguistic context.<sep> The information pertaining to each context is recorded for each path and combined with a new virtual root depending on the history relative to the language model (Ney et al., 1992).<sep> These algorithms are very widespread and the most common implementation is a Viterbi beam-search [5, 6].<sep> Their design is similar to dynamic programming.<sep> - stack asynchronous algorithms [7] where the principle is to do a deep exploration and prioritize promising hypotheses.<sep> This is achieved by expanding the selected hypothesis word by word.<sep> The implementation of this type of algorithm is based on priority stacks that order the hypotheses to explore.<sep> The most commonly used implementation is the A[∗] algorithm (Paul, 1991; Nocera et al., 2002).<sep> The documents (Aubert, 2002; Lecouteux, 2008) present in detail the main decoding techniques for large vocabulary speech recognition systems.<sep> 2.2 Ant colony algorithm<sep> Ant-based algorithms are part of the constructive approaches.<sep> In these approaches, new configurations are generated by iteratively adding solution elements to the configurations under construction.<sep> The idea of ant colony algorithms comes from biology and from the observation of ant social behavior.<sep> Indeed, ants have the ability to collectively find the shortest path between their nest and a source of energy.<sep> It has been demonstrated that cooperation inside an ant colony is self-organized and emerges from interactions between autonomous individuals.<sep> These interactions, often very simple, allow the colony to solve complex problems.<sep> This phenomenon is called swarm intelligence (Bonabeau and Théraulaz, 2000).<sep> In 1989, Jean-Louis Deneubourg studied the behaviour of biological ants in order to understand the method with which they choose the shortest path and find it again in case of obstacle.<sep> He thus developed the stochastic model known as Deneubourg's model (Deneubourg et al., 1989), which is consistent with what is statistically observed in real ants in terms of their sharing of paths.<sep> This stochastic model is the origin of the work on ant algorithms. The main concept of swarm intelligence is stigmergy, that is, the interaction between agents by modifying the environment.<sep> One of the first methods that can be compared to ant algorithms is the ecoresolution which showed the power of a collective resolution heuristic based on local perception, avoiding any explicit path of the state graph (Drogoul, 1993).<sep> In 1992, Marco Dorigo and Luca Maria Gambardella designed the first algorithm based on this paradigm for the famous combinatorial Traveling Salesman Problem (Dorigo and Gambardella, 1997).<sep> In these algorithms, the environment is usually represented by a graph, in which virtual ants use pheromone trails deposited by others, or pseudo-randomly explore the graph. Ant colony algorithms are a good alternative for the resolution of problems modeled by graphs. They allow a fast and efficient exploration that exhibits performance close to other search methods.<sep> Readers can refer to (Dorigo and Stützle, 2004) or (Monmarche et al., 2009) for a state of the art.<sep> Such algorithms have already been applied for natural language processing tasks successfully including Word Sense Disambiguation [21].<sep> The work presented here aims at expanding this paradigm to automatic speech recognition.<sep> 3. ASR system<sep> The ASR system we implement is based on the KALDI toolkit [22].<sep> KALDI offers state of the art tools for automatic speech recognition.<sep> The acoustic model and phonetization of our system have been trained with the corpora provided by LIUM [23] (118 hours of annotated data).<sep> The enrichment of the parameters by the delta and delta-delta coefficients, as well as several transformations such as LDA and MLLT [24] are applied.<sep> Finally, speaker adaptive training is applied on the acoustic models and combined with fMLLR space type parameter adaptation [25] at the speaker level.<sep> TABLE 1 – Perplexity of the different language models used by our system, as well as the word error rates (WER) obtained by our reference system.<sep> The language model is trained on all the data provided for the IWSLT 2012 campaign as well as the training corpus provided by LIUM.<sep> A language model was trained for each subcorpus and all models were interpolated by minimizing the perplexity on the development set, without applying any data selection or pruning.<sep> The final perplexity obtained on the dev is 159 for the trigram model and 150 for the quadgram.<sep> The amounts of n-grams and the perplexity of the different models used in our experiments are shown in Table 1.<sep> All experiments were performed on a corpus made available to the community for the IWSLT 2010 campaign: the TED corpus that corresponds to a set of conference talks recorded in English [26].<sep> Details and baseline results are shown in Table 1.<sep> 4.1. Graph conversion<sep> It is important to note that KALDI is designed around a finite state machine based modeling. Initially, our experiments were conducted on more classical graphs using the HTK formalism.<sep> We have thus converted the entirety of the graphs from KALDI by removing the epsilon-transitions in order to work with a HTK representation.<sep> 4. Proposed approaches<sep> As a first step, we want to validate the approach by simplifying the decoding stages.<sep> For this reason, all the work presented is performed on word graphs extracted from the KALDI ASR.<sep> We have deliberately used an initial bi-gram language model so as not to introduce additional linguistic information. We therefore use the ant colony algorithm to expand the graph to higher n-gram orders.<sep> Our general implementation of the algorithm is as follows:<sep> Each link of the graph is associated with a pheromone variable (a counter) initialized at 1 at the beginning of each epoch.<sep> Our ants are launched from the first node of the graph and in order to leave a node, ants will have to choose a link.<sep> This choice is performed with a random selection based on the quantity of pheromone on each arc (and possibly local factors).<sep> With the arrival of an ant at the endpoint, if a solution is found (i.e. the product of the acoustic and linguistic probabilities of the path travelled: f inChemin ∏ Pn ( Wp | wp − n .. wp −1). P ( X p ) – is p = debutChemin better than the previous best solution found;<sep> So pheromones are laid down on the path.<sep> In the literature, it was shown that with such a simple version of the ant colony, ants tended to converge on a path that does not necessarily represent the optimal solution.<sep> It is therefore necessary to use local or global heuristics to avoid this phenomenon.<sep> The next section presents some local heuristics that bias the choice of ants.<sep> 5.1 Anamorphic ants<sep> We propose different types of ants, as proposed in [19], which use heuristic exploration biased by the information already present in the initial graph.<sep> Posteriors probabilities p(a|G) are computed on the bigram graph for each link a, given the current word graph G.<sep> This probability corresponds to the ratio between all the probabilities of all the paths passing through link a and the set of all paths in the graph G: p(a|G) = C∈G,a⊃C p(C|G) C∈G p(C|G)<sep> Where C ∈ G denotes a full path C in the graph G and a ⊃ C a link that belongs to the path.<sep> This posterior probability is conventionally estimated by using a forward-backward algorithm as shown in (Wessel et al. , 2000).<sep> We propose different types of ants that are tested independently:<sep> - Listening ants (1): these are influenced by the a posteriori acoustic probability of the following node, without taking into account the linguistic aspect.<sep> 2. Talkative ants: unlike previous ants, these ants are only influenced by the linguistic posterior probability of the next node.<sep> 3. Oracles ants, a hybrid model that combines the previous two and that represents the classical posterior probability of the next node.<sep> The various posterior probabilities are calculated by running Viterbi on the bi-gram graph. For models (1) and (2) we respectively remove the acoustic model or language models and for model (3) we keep the initial score.<sep> The different types of ants are used to guide exploration based on acoustic or linguistic information.<sep> In the next section, we present their performance.<sep> Finally, we propose to combine the exploration of the different ants by merging their deposited pheromones.<sep> To do this, we have each type of ant work on a copy of the graph.<sep> Once the graphs are explored, they are merged into one where the quantities of pheromones are added.<sep> A few ants are then sent back onto this new graph and influenced by all the pheromones deposited.<sep> For all of the presented experiments, the number of epochs is set to 30 and the number of ants is 2000, which corresponds to 60000 paths explored for each graph.<sep> The average duration of the decoding with these parameters is approximately 5 seconds per graph (on an Intel Xeon 2.5 Ghz, using a single core).<sep> When using multiple ants, we ran 10 periods with each ant before merging their graphs.<sep> The detailed algorithm is presented below.<sep> Algorithm 1: Ant colony algorithm applied to the decoding of RAP graphs<sep> TABLE 2 – Results, in terms of MET, of decoding with the algorithm of the ants, the decoding with the ants presents oscillations of + / − 0.2 point from one execution to another.<sep> 5. Preliminary experiments and results<sep> Table 2 shows the results (in terms of MET) obtained with the algorithm presented previously.<sep> The experiment confirms that orienting starting ants on optimal paths strongly influences the final result.<sep> Ants launched on paths that privilege acoustic (model 1) or linguistic information (model 2) perform poorly, but the merged model with more heterogeneous ants (full posterior, model 3) provides meaningful information.<sep> These experiments show that ant colony algorithms are able to expand the graph, but do not reach the performance of baseline results.<sep> However, from a computational time point of view, the ant colony algorithm is nearly 15 times faster than a conventional expansion method: the configuration shown in the table is the one that reaches the maximum scores;<sep> If more iterations are added, the colonies still converge on the same path.<sep> The mixed results are normal given the simplicity of the algorithm currently used.<sep> In the literature, it has been shown that heuristics that influence the initial distribution of pheromone on the nodes had a significant bearing on the evolution of the anthill.<sep> Furthermore (Dorigo and Gambardella, 1997) shows that one of the major concerns with this type of algorithm is its convergence towards local optima.<sep> One way to avoid such phenomena is to use several dimensions that can be combined a posteriori , as shown in [19].<sep> The fusion of the three types of ants introduced this heuristic and showed its effectiveness.<sep> 6. Discussion on the ant colony algorithm<sep> 7.1 Benefits<sep> Parallelization of the ant colony algorithm is trivial.<sep> In fact, ants can evolve independently of each other in the search for new paths.<sep> Parallelization is also possible at a higher level: that of ant colonies.<sep> Different colonies operate on copies of a graph and exchange information by merging copies (i.e. by summing the amount of pheromone present on each node).<sep> Another important factor is the amount of memory needed, which is bounded by the space required to store the graph in memory.<sep> As there are no physical extensions, memory usage is constant.<sep> In our experiments, the algorithm uses on average about 100MB against several GBs for a conventional expansion.<sep> The evaluation of the solution is performed when an ant arrives at the final node of the graph.<sep> The number of evaluations is relatively low (2000 per graph in our case), so it is possible to add extra information to refine the solution (semantic, language model based on neural network etc.).<sep> Finally, the calculation time can be perfectly controlled: the number of evaluations is known in advance and its time depends only on the depth of the graph.<sep> 6.2 Disadvantages<sep> Unless the random seed is memorized, the results of the algorithm are not deterministic.<sep> During our experiments, we observed differences of 0.2 points between different explorations.<sep> Nothing guarantees the optimality of the algorithm and the latter can tend to be trapped by local optima.<sep> However, the literature proposes solutions to overcome these problems.<sep> 6.3 Envisaged developments<sep> The work presented here is preliminary.<sep> We wish to explore and analyze this ant colony paradigm more in depth when applied to SRAP.<sep> Future developments will result in the parallel use of ants with different behaviors.<sep> Thus, a selection of well performing individuals will be made as the exploration progresses.<sep> It would also be interesting to analyze in detail how the graphs are explored: this aspect will allow to optimize exploration strategies further.<sep> Finally, in the longer term, we would like to apply ant colony algorithms throughout the ASR process: from the phoneme lattice to the language model expansion.<sep> 7. Conclusion<sep> In this article, we presented a new paradigm to expand word graphs in automatic speech recognition systems.<sep> This paradigm, based on ant colonies, makes it possible to explore the graph in order to find an optimal path without having to build it dynamically according to the histories.<sep> Currently, our method does not achieve the results of our benchmark system where graphs were extended with classical methods.<sep> However, we show that the paradigm works: the application of a higher-order language model systematically improves the initial decoding.<sep> The implementation presented is very basic, we want to refine the exploration heuristics in the short term in order to obtain an approach that is competitive with existing ones.
ORDINAL REGRESSION FOR INTERACTION QUALITY PREDICTION<sep> ABSTRACT<sep> The automatic prediction of the quality of a dialogue is useful to keep track of a spoken dialogue system’s performance and, if necessary, adapt its behaviour.<sep> The prediction model is learnt from a corpus of dialogues evaluated by users or experts.<sep> In this paper, we propose to model this task as an ordinal regression problem.<sep> We apply support vector machines for ordinal regression on a corpus of dialogues where each system-user exchange was given a rating on a scale of 1 to 5 by expert annotators after each system-user exchange.<sep> Compared to previous models proposed in the literature, the ordinal regression predictor has significantly better results according to the following evaluation metrics: Cohen’s agreement rate with experts ratings, Spearman’s rank correlation coefficient, and Euclidean and Manhattan errors.<sep> 1. INTRODUCTION<sep> A Dialogue System (SD) is a human-machine interface that combines different modules: speech recognition, semantic analysis, dialogue management, automatic text generation and speech synthesis.<sep> To be exhaustive, the evaluation of such a system must be double.<sep> Indeed, the technical evaluation of the different modules must be carried out as well as a global evaluation of the usability of the system (Dybkjaer et al., 2004). Möller (Möller, 2000) defines usability as the ability of a system or service to meet the requirements of users.<sep> Classically, two kinds of usability evaluation campaigns are carried out.<sep> The first kind asks the user to give a numerical rating and/or fill in a questionnaire about the dialogue after its end [2, 3, 4].<sep> The second one involves experts (Evanini et al., 2008; Schmitt et al., 2011).<sep> This approach makes it possible to avoid the subjective bias associated with certain aspects of dialogue management that are independent of the voice of the speech synthesis (Möller, 2000; Schmitt et al., 2011).<sep> However, this does imply that experts are trained to avoid too much variability in the annotations.<sep> In the following, we will refer to user evaluations as User Satisfaction (US) and expert scores as Quality of Interaction (QI) (Schmitt et al., 2011).<sep> In order to limit the costs incurred for these evaluation campaigns, it has been proposed to use the collected corpora to learn an automatic predictor of the system's performance.<sep> The predicted scores can then be used to monitor the system's efficiency online and to learn an optimal behaviour for the system with techniques such as reinforcement learning (Levin et al., 1997; Pietquin et al., 2011; Daubigney et al., 2011).<sep> This problem has been considered both as a regression [11] and a classification [12] issue.<sep> This paper proposes to unify these two views by modelling it as an ordinal regression problem.<sep> Ordinal regression returns discrete labels but takes into account the ordering of the labels.<sep> Ordinal Regression with Support Vector machines (SVOR) is compared to several regression and classification models on the LEGO corpus [13] which contains 200 annotated dialogues collected with the Let’s Go system of Carnegie Mellon University [14].<sep> Each system-user exchange was given an Interaction Quality (IQ) rating on a scale of 1 to 5 by three experts.<sep> We show on this corpus that SVOR predictions are significantly better according to four metrics measuring distance and correlation.<sep> Section 2 reviews models previously proposed for users or experts ratings prediction.<sep> Section 3 explains the metrics used to compare these different models and SVOR.<sep> Section 4 then gives an overview of the LEGO corpus. Section 5 describes the models compared on LEGO and Section 6 presents the results of the test of the models.<sep> 2. Previous work<sep> Automatically predicting US or IQ is useful to keep track of a spoken dialogue system’s performance and, if necessary, adapt its behaviour.<sep> Witt [18] proposed to make this adaptation using a calculation rule that estimates the Caller Experience Metric (CEM, equation 1), a score on a scale of 1 to 5 given by an expert.<sep> In this equation, the events are ASR rejection, user time out, user intention misunderstood, user contradicting the system and user asking to be transferred.<sep> d is a discounting factor to reduce the importance of the furthest events in time.<sep> The adaptation of the behaviour of an SD can also be done by applying a datadriven statistical method such as reinforcement learning.<sep> An RL agent compares different strategies on the basis of a numerical reward function.<sep> In the case of SD, this function should evaluate the quality of each dialogue, it is therefore natural to infer this function from US or IQ scores (Walker et al. , 1998; El Asri et al. , 2012).<sep> Finally, another possibility is to ask experts to give an IQ rating for each system-user exchange and then train a model to predict this rating at a dialogue turn level.<sep> The system can then adapt its behaviour during a dialogue if its estimation of IQ degrades.<sep> In such a case, the SDS might prompt contextual help messages, change its current dialogue strategy or even transfer the call to a human operator.<sep> To predict US or IQ on a dialogue or dialogue turn level, regression and classification models were proposed.<sep> Walker et al (Walker et al. , 1997) applied Multiple Linear Regression (MLR) to this problem, modelling the SU as the realisation of the task while minimising the costs of dialogue such as duration or the number of rejections of the voice recognition.<sep> Evanini et. al [5] built a decision tree to predict IQ.<sep> Engelbrecht et. al [10] used Hidden Markov Models (HMM) to represent the evolution of US throughout a dialogue.<sep> Hara et al (Hara et al. , 2010), on the other hand, built an N-gram model based on dialogue acts.<sep> Higashinaka et al compared Hidden Markov Models and Conditional Random Fields to estimate turn-level IQ.<sep> For the same problem, Schmitt et. al [6] proposed Support Vector Machines (SVM).<sep> Modelling IQ prediction as a pure classification issue does not enable to take into account the natural ordering of the scores.<sep> In this paper, we propose SVOR for turn-level IQ prediction [27, 28].<sep> Ordinal regression bridges the gap between classification and regression.<sep> It takes as input a set of labelled examples with naturally ordered labels and then builds a predictor in order to minimise the absolute deviation from the true labels while taking into account the ordering of the labels.<sep> 3 Metrics<sep> For RL-based systems, correctly ordering the system’s dialogue strategies is important.<sep> Indeed, if turnlevel IQ predictions are used as rewards for the system, they must maintain the ordering of system actions that was induced by the actual experts ratings.<sep> To measure models performance on this aspect, we use Spearman’s rank correlation coefficient [30]. This coefficient measures the correlation between two rankings.<sep> Let y = {y 1 , …, yn} and y ˆ = {y ˆ1 , …, ˆ yn} be respectively the IQ ratings and estimations on a set of n system-user exchanges.<sep> Let r ( y ) = {r ( y 1) , …, r ( yn ) } and r (ˆ y ) = {r (ˆ y 1) , …, r (ˆ yn ) } be their corresponding rankings.<sep> For instance, if y = { 1 , 15 , 3 , 12 , 27 } than r ( y ) = { 1 , 4 , 2 , 3 , 5 } .<sep> Equation 2 recalls the calculation of ρ.<sep> We also compare models on the basis of the Euclidean and absolute value errors, recalled in Equations 3 and 4.<sep> The agreement with the experts is measured with Cohen’s κ coefficient [31].<sep> This coefficient computes the probability of agreement between y and y ˆ.<sep> In Equation 5, P ( a ) is the probability of agreement and P ( ca ) the probability of agreement by chance.<sep> 4. THE LEGO CORPUS<sep> The Let’s Go system provides local information on bus schedules in the city of Pittsburgh [14].<sep> Schmitt et al (Schmitt et al. , 2012) had 200 dialogues with Let's Go evaluated by three experts.<sep> These experts were asked to give an IQ rating on a scale of 1 to 5 after each system-user exchange.<sep> In total, 5282 system-user exchanges were rated.<sep> Following Schmitt et al (Schmitt et al. , 2011), we used the median value of the three ratings provided by the experts for our test.<sep> In the LEGO corpus, each system-user exchange is described as a set of characteristic variables that were automatically or manually obtained.<sep> These variables depend on automatic speech recognition (confidence score, rejection,…), semantic analysis (user dialogue act, semantic parse,…) and dialogue management (system dialogue act).<sep> Following Schmitt et al (Schmitt et al. , 2011), we used quantifiable features on three levels: the value for the last system-user exchange, the mean value over the last three exchanges and the mean value since the beginning of the dialogue.<sep> A complete list of the features of the corpus can be found in (Schmitt et al., 2012).<sep> We only kept automatically computable features in order to handle the case where one wants to track the performance of the SD online without having to resort to new annotations.<sep> Two of the variables selected were qualitative: User Dialogue Act (UDA) and System Dialogue Act (SDA).<sep> For example, the UDA could take values such as UDA_CONFIRM_DEPARTURE, UDA_INFORMATION_LINE, etc.<sep> In these cases, noting na the number of possible labels, we split the variable into na − 1 boolean variables.<sep> ADS was split into 27 variables and ADU into 21.<sep> In total, each system-user exchange is made up of 67 variables, all centered and normalized.<sep> The generalisability of the methods described in the following section was assessed with 10-fold cross validation.<sep> 5 Models<sep> 5.1 Multiple Linear Regression and Adaptive Spline Multivariate Regression<sep> The predictors were selected one by one.<sep> We computed the single regression coefficient for each feature and then we kept the feature with the highest coefficient in absolute value[1] .<sep> We then used the error IQ − βiϕi as objective value and we computed single regression coefficients for the remaining features.<sep> We repeated this process until the error was minimised.<sep> 5.2. Multivariate Adaptive Regression Splines MARS was introduced by Friedman [32]. It models IQ as a linear function of hinge functions of the form: Bi ( x ) = max (0 , x − s ) or Bi ( x ) = max (0 , s − x ) where s is a training sample.<sep> We used the ARES toolbox for Matlab[2] .<sep> The algorithm requires two parameters, the maximum number of hinge functions maxFuncs and cubic , which indicates whether cubic splines should be used to smooth the edges where the model function is not derivable.<sep> Different combinations of these parameters were tried but no significant impact on the evaluation metrics was noticed.<sep> Hence, the default parameters were kept (recommended in [32]), maxFuncs was set to 21 and cubic splines were not used.<sep> 5.2 Gaussian Processes<sep> A Gaussian Process (GP) is a set of random variables which joint distribution is a Gaussian [33].<sep> To perform GP regression, y is modelled as: y = y ˆ + ∆ˆ y with ∆ˆ y a centered Gaussian noise vector and y ˆ is a GP which mean and variance are to be determined.<sep> One advantage in using GP over other regression methods is that it returns an entire distribution over the possible values instead of a point-based decision rule.<sep> Another advantage is that it enables a Bayesian treatment of the data, inferring a posterior distribution from a prior belief and observations.<sep> Following Rasmussen and Williams [33], we defined a centered prior GP (0 , k ( x, x )) where k is the covariance function.<sep> We calculated the posterior distribution by performing exact inference from the training samples.<sep> We used the GPML Matlab library by Rasmussen and Nickisch[3] .<sep> Three covariance functions were tested: linear, rational quadratic and squared exponential. Their expressions are recalled in Table 1. The parameters Λ, σ and α were all learnt by automatic relevance determination [34].<sep> Since this computation is very costly ( O ( n[3] ) with n the number of training samples), we only kept in memory a dictionary of points as proposed by Engel [35].<sep> This reduced computational load to O ( m[2] n ) with m the dictionary size.<sep> Section 6 only presents the best results which are those obtained with the exponential covariance: exp(−[1] 2[(] [x][−][x][′][)] [T][Λ][−][2][(] [x][−][x][′][))][.]<sep> 5.3 Support Vector Machines<sep> Originally, SVM (Vapnik, 1998) were meant for 2-class classification.<sep> They take a set of labelled examples { ( xi, yi ) } where yi ∈{− 1 , 1 } and then they look for a hyperplane in a feature space that separates the two classes so that the minimal margin between the samples is maximised.<sep> The decision function returned is given in Equation 6 where ϕ ( x ) is the projection of x into the high dimensional feature space.<sep> SVM for Classification (SVMClass), Support Vector Machines for Regression (SVR) and SVOR solve a quadratic programming problem to find the weight vector ω and the constant b .<sep> The difference between the three approaches lies in the constraints of the problem and the form of the decision function.<sep> These three approaches are detailed in the following sections.<sep> 5.4.1. Support Vector Machines for Classification<sep> To perform 5-class classification with SVM, a one-versus-one approach was applied.<sep> 10 classifiers were learnt, each deciding between two classes.<sep> For each new example, we assign the class that was the most voted for.<sep> In case of a tie, we have always favoured the lowest label as predicting a low IQ instead of a higher one is more critical than the other way round.<sep> The decision function is the one of Equation 6.<sep> We used the LIBSVM software [37].<sep> We tested SVMClass with two kernel functions: a linear and an exponential function.<sep> We only present the best results which are those obtained with the exponential kernel of expression: exp(−γ ( x − x[′] ) [T] ( x − x[′] )).<sep> 5.3.2 Support Vector Machines for Regression<sep> In the context of SVR (Drucker et al., 1996), the weights ω are defined so that the absolute value error on each data is less than a parameter ε.<sep> The prediction for a new example x is f ( x ) = ω[T] ϕ ( x ) + b .<sep> LIBSVM was used once again with an exponential kernel.<sep> The parameter ϵ was set to 0.1.<sep> TABLE 1 – Results of the 10-fold cross-validation on the LEGO corpus.<sep> We calculate 95% confidence intervals for each metric.<sep> 5.3.3 Support Vector Machines for Ordinal Regression<sep> Ordinal regression or ranking learning aims to build a model to predict ordinal ranks.<sep> SVOR [28] adds constraints to the formulation of SVMs so that the ordering between the labels is taken into account.<sep> The idea is to find an optimal weight vector ω as in SVMClass but also r − 1 thresholds bj defining parallel discriminant hyperplanes for the r labels.<sep> For each data xi[j] (the exponent j means that x[j] i belongs to the j-th category), noting b j the threshold separating the j and j + 1 categories, we impose on the function of value ω[T] ϕ ( xi[j]) to be lower than the lower margin ( bj − 1) and we impose on each example xi[j][+][1] to be associated with a value ω[T] ϕ ( xi[j][+][1] ) higher than the upper margin ( bj +1).<sep> A new example x is given the label argmin i{i | ω[T] ϕ ( x ) < bi} .<sep> We computed SVOR with a Gaussian kernel using the C program available at http://www.gatsby.ucl.ac.uk/chuwei/svor.htm.<sep> 6. RESULTS<sep> The results of the test are given in Table 1.<sep> For the regression techniques, Cohen’s κ coefficient was computed on the rounded predictions made by the models.<sep> Surprisingly, the results of the MLR on the corpus are quite good.<sep> Schmitt et. al applied MLR to the same corpus and after rounding the returned values, they obtained a κ of 0.35 and a ρ of only 0.46.<sep> We obtained a ρ of 0.83.<sep> This difference of results should be explained by the fact that different sets of explanatory variables were used and that we made the choice to separate the qualitative variables into boolean variables.<sep> GP performed better than MLR and MARS except concerning the Euclidean error.<sep> MLR and MARS minimise the Euclidean distance, so this result could be anticipated.<sep> SVR, on the other hand, performed better than the previously mentioned techniques on all metrics. A significant improvement can be observed in particular concerning the Euclidean and Manhattan errors.<sep> SVOR outperforms all these methods on all metrics.<sep> A significant improvement is observed on the absolute value errors and Cohen’s κ .<sep> The absolute value error is improved by 0.1 points compared to SVR.<sep> Cohen’s κ is improved of 0.06 point compared to SVMClass.<sep> The lowest ranking correlation coefficient was obtained with SVMClass.<sep> This supports the fact that classification techniques are not the most appropriate for IQ prediction because they ignore the order of the labels.<sep> Nevertheless, as expected SVMClass has the second highest κ coefficient behind SVOR.<sep> The classification performances of SVMClass and SVOR can be further compared thanks to their confusion matrices (Table 4).<sep> The results predicted by SVOR deviated less from the real values than the ones predicted by SVMClass.<sep> For instance, a true 1 was predicted as a 3, a 4 or a 5 88 times with SVOR against 236 times with SVMClass.<sep> The recall and precision for critical values 1 and 2 are significantly better with SVOR.<sep> TABLE 2 – Confusion matrices for SVOR and SVMClass.<sep> T i means that i is the true label and P i means i is the predicted label.<sep> 7. CONCLUSION<sep> This paper proposes to model the prediction of interaction quality with a dialogue system as an ordinal regression problem.<sep> We compared different classification and regression models to ordinal regression on a corpus of evaluated dialogues and showed that ordinal regression provided the best results in terms of Euclidean and absolute error, Spearman's rank correlation coefficient and Cohen's κ .<sep> These good results are explained by the fact that ordinal regression takes into account the natural ordering of the discrete labels assigned to each dialogue.<sep> We will use ordinal regression to infer a reward function for a reinforcement learning based dialogue system.<sep> 1. we recall that values were previously centered and normalized<sep> 2 Jekabsons G., ARESLab: Adaptive Regression Splines toolbox for Matlab/Octave, 2011, available at http://www.cs.rtu.lv/jekabsons/<sep> 3 http://wwww.gaussianprocesses.org/gpml
Semi-automatic enrichment of crowdsourced semantic lexicons: The WISIGOTH system applied to Wiktionary<sep> SUMMARY<sep> Although many TAL applications rely on semantic lexical resources, these are rarely simultaneously of satisfactory quality and freely available.<sep> Starting from the confrontation between traditional methods and emerging trends in the construction and evaluation of lexical resources, we present in this article a new method based on Wiktionary, a free, online, collaboratively built multilingual dictionary, and we propose a semi-automatic enrichment of its synonymy network using endogenous and exogenous data, using a validation "by the crowds".<sep> Finally, we describe an implementation of this system called WISIGOTH.<sep> ABSTRACT.<sep> Semantic lexical resources are a mainstay of various Natural Language Processing applications.<sep> However, comprehensive and reliable resources are rare and not often freely available.<sep> We discuss in this paper the context of lexical resources building and the problems of evaluation.<sep> We present Wiktionary, a freely available and collaboratively built multilingual dictionary and we propose a semi-automatic approach based on random walks for enriching its synonymy network, which uses endogenous and exogenous data.<sep> We then propose a validation “by crowds”.<sep> Finally, we present an implementation of this system called WISIGOTH.<sep> KEYWORDS: synonymy networks, semantic relatedness, collaboratively constructed resources, Wiktionary, semi-automatic enrichment, random walks, hierarchical small worlds.<sep> 1 Introduction<sep> It is a commonplace to underline the importance of lexical resources for Natural Language Processing (NLP) applications. It is also common to complain about their unreliable quality or their prohibitive cost.<sep> While the processing of English is equipped with WordNet (hereafter WN), from Princeton University (Fellbaum, 1998), a resource that has been proven for many years, several languages such as French do not yet benefit from any satisfactory quality resource.<sep> “We desperately need linguistic resources!” is claimed by Sekine (2010), who argues that it is not realistic to assume that large-scale resources can all be developed by a single institute or a small group of people. Sekine concludes that a collaborative effort is needed, and that sharing resources is crucial.<sep> The first difficulty in building such resources is the development process and the resulting cost/quality trade-off.<sep> Relying on experts to manually build resources often comes with a prohibitive cost.<sep> We cannot prejudge the quality of the resources built automatically (and therefore noisy), which should be validated by experts, which brings us back to the initial problem.<sep> Finally, in the event that the use of validation by experts is considered, the implementation of a measure of agreement between these experts is problematic.<sep> After describing in Section 2 the previous attempts to build resources and inventorying the different methods of extracting lexical-semantic relations, we will focus particularly on synonymy and the difficulties linked to its modelling and evaluation. In Section 3, we present new trends based on collaborative editing, which is an interesting avenue for building resources.<sep> In this context, Wiktionary, a free online dictionary, seems to be a key to simultaneously solve the problem of development cost and, to some extent, that of evaluation. We present in Section 4 a semi-automatic enrichment process aiming to densify the synonymy networks extracted from this resource.<sep> We measure the impact of the use of different data sources on this process in Section 5.<sep> Finally, we present an implementation of our system, named WISIGOTH, that any internet user can use to contribute to its enrichment.<sep> 2. Lexical Resources Building: Context<sep> WN is probably the only project of building a semantic lexical resource to be so successful and widely used.<sep> Other projects such as EuroWordNet (Vossen, 1998) and BalkaNet (Tufis, 2000), motivated by the success of WN, have followed in the same vein while aiming for less ambitious coverage.<sep> Moreover, the resources produced were frozen at the end of their initial development while WordNet kept on evolving.<sep> Jacquin et al. (2007) pointed out the weaknesses of the French part of EuroWordNet and proposed automatic methods to add missing relations.<sep> These methods, like those we list in section 2.1, although interesting, would require manual validation by experts (and therefore be costly) to produce a reliable resource.<sep> Time and cost of development, as well as availability of resources, are more and more taken into account: in corpus linguistics, an AGILE-like method borrowed from computer science has been proposed by Voormann and Gut (2008) to simultaneously maximize the size of a corpus and its annotations while reducing the time and cost of its development.<sep> Brunello (2009) tackled the availability issue and proposed a method to build free corpora by using the web and metadata to identify web pages under free licenses.<sep> Before showing, in section 3, how collaborative editing could be an asset to overcome recurrent obstacles in the domain of lexical resources building, we will first describe the background of classical methods.<sep> 2.1 Methods of extracting relationships<sep> Initially proposed by Hearst (1992) to identify hyperonymy relations in a corpus, the approaches based on lexico-syntactic patterns were refined by Pantel and Pennacchiotti (2006) to reduce the manual intervention required.<sep> Such patterns are not always easy to develop and are specific to the language studied. Methods of mutual enrichment of resources by interlingual links consist in projecting semantic relations by following translation links.<sep> Sagot and Fišer (2008) built WOLF, a free French WordNet, using several existing resources to start with a French and English concept base (based on synonymy) and to build an inter-language index from which the projections were made. Similarly, Soria et al. (2009) used translation links to perform an "automatic mutual fertilization" of two lexicons, Italian and Chinese, having a structure similar to that of WN.<sep> These experiments have the merit of proving the feasibility of the method, but do not allow the production of reliable resources in the absence of manual validation.<sep> Many works have finally focused on the development of semantic similarity calculations: different properties are associated with lexemes and the propensity to share common properties is interpreted as a sign of semantic proximity.<sep> Most of these methods are based on vector models: lexemes are represented by vectors, each coordinate of which represents a property of the lexeme, and the semantic similarity of lexemes is given by a similarity calculation between these vectors.<sep> The methods then differ by the properties that constitute the vectors and the similarity calculation algorithms.<sep> A lexeme can be represented, for example, by a vector containing its co-occurrents in a corpus or its syntactic contexts.<sep> Heylen et al. (2008) utilisent la similarité entre vecteurs pour extraire des relations de synonymie et comparent les résultats obtenus en utilisant des sacs de mots et des contextes syntaxiques. Ils étudient également l’impact de certaines propriétés linguistiques (fréquence, spécificité et classes sémantiques) sur la similarité ainsi calculée : les contextes syntaxiques s’avèrent plus efficaces que les sacs de mots et de meilleurs résultats sont obtenus avec les termes de haute fréquence et ceux appartenant à des classes sémantiques abstraites.<sep> The effect of semantic specificity is not conclusive. They also show that vectors that are close according to their method and that do not relate to synonymy often reflect other semantic relations (cohyponymy and hyperonymy/hyponymy).<sep> Comparisons of different measures and weightings of syntactic contexts are given in (Curran and Moens, 2002).<sep> Van der Plas and Bouma (2005) studied which particular syntactic contexts lead to the best results, for example observing that better accuracy is obtained with the object relation than with the modifier relation. These methods can also be used with non-linguistic properties: some take advantage of specific architectures such as Wikipedia or Wiktionary.<sep> Ollivier and Senellart (2007) and Weale et al. (2009) use the hypertext structure of these resources as the object of their similarity calculation.<sep> These methods can give good results on certain tasks (78 to 93% on TOEFL-type tests) but are of course not reproducible outside of these specific architectures (e.g. classical networks of type WordNet under construction).<sep> Finally, random walks are efficient methods for calculating the similarity between vertices in a graph.<sep> Les graphes peuvent être construits à partir de différentes sources de données et modéliser, par exemple, des réseaux lexicaux dans lesquels un sommet représente un lexème et un arc, une relation sémantique [1] . Nous présentons, en section 4, une approche par marches aléatoires appliquées à des graphes bipartis contenant des données endogènes (liens de synonymie et de traduction, gloses de Wiktionary) et exogènes (contextes syntaxiques extraits de larges corpus).<sep> 2.2. Meaning and synonymy<sep> 2.2.1. Choice of modelling<sep> If hyperonymy is at the heart of ontologies, many TAL applications exploit resources based on the relationship of synonymy, on which concepts are based.<sep> Many works have been carried out by philosophers and linguists on the questions of meaning and synonymy.<sep> From the point of view of TAL, it can be interesting, without trying to define what synonymy is, to ask what synonymy is relevant in an applicative context: where the linguist distinguishes, for example, absolute, cognitive and quasi-synonyms[2], a given task may require other partitions.<sep> Furthermore, faced with the difficulty of developing resources, it could be tempting to try to develop a resource that is ideally generic.<sep> Kilgarriff (1997) écrit, à propos de la désambiguïsation lexicale (ci-après WSD), qu'il n'y a aucune raison de penser qu'un même ensemble de sens soit approprié pour plusieurs applications de TAL : différents buts et différents corpus conduisent à différentes représentations.<sep> For example, Edmonds and Hirst (2002) address the problem of lexical choice in machine translation systems which need to access subtle differences of meaning, which requires the use of subtle nuances of meaning beyond traditional synsets.<sep> To overcome this issue, they propose a model based on a coarse-grained ontology into which clusters of near-synonyms represent core meanings.<sep> At a fine level, different types of contrasts classified into a finite list of variations (denotational, stylistic, structural, etc.) demarcate the near-synonyms of a given cluster.<sep> The central role given to the granularity of representation by this model is extremely interesting, however, building a comprehensive resource of this type is a huge work.<sep> Other authors rely on mathematical tools to model synonymy.<sep> For example, Victorri and Fuchs (1996) and Ploux and Victorri (1998) use maximal cliques to detect word senses in lexical networks.<sep> To quote Habert et al (1996): “We argue that the various cliques in which a word appears represent different axes of similarity and help to identify the different senses of that word.”<sep> However, there is a large discrepancy between lexical resources (see Section 2.2.2) and the notion of maximal clique is too sensitive: the addition or removal of a few links leads to significant differences in the modeling of senses.<sep> To address this issue, relying on robust methods, such as the approach proposed by Gaume (2004), seems necessary.<sep> 2.2.2. Properties of synonymy networks<sep> In order to better understand the diversity that characterizes lexical resources, we constructed graphs modeling the synonymy networks of seven reference French dictionaries[3].<sep> We present below the structural properties of these graphs (see table 1) and then compare them to each other.<sep> Common properties: most lexical networks are Hierarchical Small World (HSW) networks sharing similar properties (Watts and Strogatz, 1998; Albert and Barabasi, 2002; Newman, 2003; Gaume et al., 2008; Gaume et al., 2010): low density (few arcs), short paths (the average path length L between two vertices is short), high clustering C (these graphs are locally dense, although globally sparse) and their degree distribution follows a power law (a more complete description can be found in (Gaume, 2004)).<sep> In Table 1, n and m respectively denote the number of vertices and arcs, the average degree of the vertices and λ the coefficient of the power law that approximates the distribution of the degrees of incidence with a correlation coefficient of r[2].<sep> nlcc and Llcc are the number of vertices and the average path length, respectively, calculated on the largest connected component.<sep> If n and ⟨k⟩ vary according to the dictionaries, Llcc is low, C is always high, and the distribution of the degrees remains close to a power law (r[2] > 0.9) with λ between –3.6 and –2.2.<sep> These properties show that these networks are HMMs, just like those extracted from Wiktionary – see (Navarro et al., 2009).<sep> Table 1. Structural properties of synonymy graphs<sep> Divergences: although all these graphs are PMH, table 1 shows that the lexical coverage (n) and the number of synonymy links (m) vary significantly from one graph to another.<sep> Given G 1 = ( V 1 , E 1) and G 2 = ( V 2 , E 2) two of the seven graphs extracted from the dictionaries, we calculate the recall, the precision and the F-measure of the lexical coverage of G 1 with respect to that of G 2 (left column of Table 2).<sep> Note that R• ( G 1 , G 2) = P• ( G 2 , G 1) and F• ( G 1 , G 2) = F• ( G 2 , G 1).<sep> These measures provide information on the relative lexical coverage of G1 and G2 and not on their agreement in terms of synonymy.<sep> To measure this agreement, we project the synonymy networks onto their common vertex set V 1 ∩ V 2 and then construct the subgraph G 1 ⟨V 1 ∩V 2 ⟩ of G 1: G 1 ⟨V 1 ∩V 2 ⟩ = ( V 1 ⟨V 1 ∩V 2 ⟩ , E 1 ⟨V 1 ∩V 2 ⟩ ) with V 1 ⟨V 1 ∩V 2 ⟩ = V 1 ∩ V 2 and E 1 ⟨V 1 ∩V 2 ⟩ = E 1 ∩ (( V 1 ∩ V 2) × ( V 1 ∩ V 2)).<sep> We construct G 2 ⟨V 1 ∩V 2 ⟩ in the same way.<sep> Finally, we calculate the recall, precision and F-measure of the arcs of G 1 ⟨V 1 ∩V 2 ⟩ compared to those of G 2 ⟨V 1 ∩V 2 ⟩ (right column of Table 2).<sep> Table 3 shows the value of these measures for each pair of graphs.<sep> The comparison of lexical coverage is given in the columns (•) and the agreement on restricted synonymy networks on common summits in the columns (↕).<sep> Ranging from 0.27 to 0.69, and with an average score of 0.46, the F-measure (in bold) varies significantly according to the pairs of dictionaries considered.<sep> These results show that there is a significant divergence between the reference synonymy networks constructed by lexicographers.<sep> Apart from the subjectivity of the experts, this is also due to editorial choices (e.g. target audience, size constraints in the printed version, etc.).<sep> Following these observations, we compiled the seven dictionaries into a single resource, which we then divided according to syntactic categories[4] to obtain three resources: DicoSyn.Noms, DicoSyn.Verbes and DicoSyn.Adjs.<sep> This set will serve as a benchmark for evaluating Wiktionary and our enrichment method (see sections 3.2 and 4).<sep> 2.3 The Unresolved Problem of Evaluation<sep> Table 2.<sep> Comparison of lexical coverage and synonymy between standards<sep> Table 3.<sep> Dictionary pair agreement: recall (R), precision (P) and F-measure (F) (for the row dictionary compared to the column dictionary)<sep> Despite numerous attempts, providing a relevant evaluation for automatically constructed resources remains an open question.<sep> A usual approach is to compare a resource against a gold standard.<sep> Assuming the existence and availability of such a resource, it has its limits and therefore the evaluation that results from it also has its limits. The standard chosen may have been designed for a specific purpose (as is the case for dictionaries) and may only reflect one aspect of reality. It is therefore not necessarily generic or appropriate for any evaluation.<sep> Therefore, gold standards have to be themselves evaluated or at least characterized before being used for evaluation.<sep> It is shown in Section 2.2.2 that there is not a perfect agreement between gold standards.<sep> So, choosing a given gold standard or another may lead to significant differences in evaluation and, therefore, comparing a resource against any gold standard will not permit to draw definitive conclusions. Indeed, whenever a system proposes a pair of synonyms that are not synonymous in the gold standard, either the system is wrong or the gold standard is not comprehensive enough.<sep> Moreover, in (Navarro et al, 2009), we explained how we had to adapt our experimental material to comply with gold standards (symmetrizing the edges to evaluate against WordNet and flattening word senses to evaluate against DicoSyn, presented below), which may introduce some bias in the evaluation.<sep> A manual evaluation can also consist of extracting a sample of relations and labeling them manually as correct or incorrect.<sep> However, such a judgment is tainted by the subjectivity linked in particular to a different representation of the world for each annotator and often leads to poor inter-judge agreement (ITA).<sep> If there is a satisfactory agreement, it is frequently used as the only criterion for quality, even though there is no guarantee that the judgments made are good.<sep> Murray and Green (2004) analyzed the factors correlated with the low agreement rates on a lexical disambiguation task and showed that high scores are correlated with the annotators' comparable (not high) level of lexical knowledge.<sep> Two non-expert judges may obtain the same level of agreement as two experts ; adding an expert to a group of non-experts tends to decrease this level.<sep> They conclude that agreement alone cannot be taken as a confident measure of correctness but must be combined with some other measure of task ability.<sep> Finally, several resources can be compared via task-based evaluation by measuring the performance of a system using the different resources to perform a given task.<sep> Semantic lexical resources can be evaluated, for example, in tasks of information retrieval, automatic translation, WSD, etc.<sep> To evaluate the system performances, the evaluation process has to determine, for a given input, what output the system should provide.<sep> This problem then requires the construction of a gold standard and raises the same problems as those mentioned above.<sep> For example, Kilgarriff (1998) has shown the difficulties of preparing a gold standard for the SENSEVAL competition.<sep> In Section 2.2.1, we have mentioned the central role of granularity in synonymy modeling.<sep> This notion also plays a crucial role in the evaluation process.<sep> In a WSD task evaluation, Palmer et al (2007) have shown that grouping the senses of the machine readable dictionary used can reconcile subtle disagreements between annotators.<sep> In general, the agreement rose between 10% and 20% when measured against the system's annotation using a larger granularity.<sep> However, they note that extremely high ITA with highly polysemous words is an unrealistic goal.<sep> They also note that increasing this agreement is only relevant if it has no or little impact on the resulting quality of TAL applications.<sep> 3. Collaborative editing "by the crowds"<sep> Since the creation of Wikipedia, the accuracy of collaborative resources built "by the crowds" has been questioned.<sep> At the time, Wikipedia was the only resource of this type and the question of its validity led to a controversy: Giles (2005) claimed that the online encyclopedia was as accurate as the Britannica encyclopedia, which in turn refuted the evaluation criteria used.<sep> Since then, wikis have proliferated.<sep> More moderate than Giles, Zesch and Gurevych (2010) showed, through a semantic similarity measurement task, that resources based on "the wisdom of the crowds" are not better than those based on linguists, but are seriously competitive. They even surpass resources built by experts in some cases, especially in terms of coverage.<sep> 3.1. Plusieurs modèles. Le problème de la qualité du contenu s’ajoute à celui de la participation « des foules ». En effet, les approches collaboratives n’impliquent pas la seule participation de collègues et d’étudiants mais doivent mobiliser une population plus large ne partageant pas nécessairement les motivations des chercheurs.<sep> Several recent trends are reshaping the field of resource creation.<sep> Among them, some researchers have developed online games designed to attract "ordinary" Internet users who play for fun, regardless of the primary purpose of the game.<sep> This is the case of JeuDeMots, developed by Lafourcade (2007), which has managed to collect a large number of semantic relations (essentially untyped, but also relations such as hyperonymy and meronymy). However, creating a game that is sufficiently entertaining is a difficult task in itself and it is likely that some attempts will fail if they do not produce games that are sufficiently attractive.<sep> The "Mechanical Turk" system, created by Amazon (AMT), consists of defining micro-tasks that workers (turkers) complete in exchange for a minimal remuneration.<sep> These tasks, or HITs (human intelligence tasks), allow to do what a computer system is incapable of: label an image, express a preference for a color, etc.<sep> Generally used in e-commerce, this system has also been used to judge the quality of Wikipedia articles by collecting the appreciation of a group of users. Researchers have also used this model to set up evaluation systems.<sep> Snow et al. (2008), par exemple, ont évalué les performances d’annotateurs naïfs utilisés comme turkers dans des tâches telles que désambiguisation lexicale, jugement de similarité sémantique, annotation de sentiments dans les documents textuels, etc.<sep> They obtained, in five out of seven tasks, the counterintuitive result that a system trained on the annotations of turkers surpasses that trained by a single expert.<sep> They explain this result by the fact that the judgment of several naive people allows to correct the bias introduced by the uniqueness of an annotator, even if he is an expert. The Amazon model has shown that it can be appropriate for annotation tasks.<sep> However, this statement must be taken with a grain of salt and it must be kept in mind that AMT was designed to perform short tasks and should only be used for such tasks.<sep> Otherwise, unscrupulous turkers may be tempted to abuse the system by spending a minimum of time on each task and giving random answers.<sep> Moreover, even with "honest turkers", it may be necessary to verify the competence of an annotator for a given task (see section 2.3).<sep> The implementation of sophisticated and expensive infrastructures in the perspective of a "crowd-sourced" edition presents the risk of resulting in empty shells waiting indefinitely to be filled.<sep> Indeed, in the current context of competition to attract Internet users, platforms devoid of content, however promising they may be, attract no one.<sep> Any solution that underestimates the constraint of attractiveness is doomed to fail. Only a few collaborative initiatives and social networks have managed to survive and concentrate the majority of Internet users.<sep> The mere fact of leaning on one of these "success stories" of the Web leaves hope for a multitude of visitors.<sep> Wikipedia and Wiktionary are certainly among the best examples of success and the TAL community can bring its skills and tools to their users, benefiting in return from a large number of contributors.<sep> Des jalons ont été mis en place dans une approche que nous avons nommée « piggybacking » (Sajous et al. , 2010) et que nous poursuivons ici : nous appuyant sur l'architecture de Wiktionary et son contenu déjà existant, nous proposons aux contributeurs des synonymes calculés automatiquement afin qu'ils les valident. Nous espérons ainsi aider ces contributeurs à accélérer l'enrichissement du dictionnaire tout en profitant de son infrastructure pour mettre au point des méthodes également applicables à d'autres types de ressources.<sep> 3.2. Wiktionary<sep> Wiktionary, the lexical companion to Wikipedia, is a free multilingual dictionary available online.<sep> As the other satellites of the Wikimedia Foundation, it is a collaborative project: any user can contribute and its changes are published immediately.<sep> Each article may include information on etymology, contain glosses, examples, translations and semantic relations (see (Navarro et al., 2009; Sajous et al., 2010) for a more detailed description).<sep> From the point of view of NLP, Wiktionary may seem like an ideal playground and the apparent lexical coverage reinforces this impression.<sep> We present below a more in-depth review that nuances often (too?) enthusiastic statements.<sep> 3.2.1. Encoding and structuring of data<sep> Wikicode The Wikimedia Foundation’s projects come with a content management system called MediaWiki.<sep> A language such as HTML has been judged too difficult to edit for a random contributor and articles’ contents are encoded into a language called wikicode.<sep> Unfortunately, no formal syntax has been defined to specify MediaWiki’s wikicode and deviations from the—tacitly agreed?—language are often encountered.<sep> We manually analyzed the users’ editions and noticed that a non-negligible number of problems in the articles are due to the wiki-syntax misunderstanding or non-compliance.<sep> Our intuition is that a significant proportion of users will not become contributors because the wikicode is not so easy to handle.<sep> A typical article contains potentially several language sections. The first one is the language of the Wiktionary’s edition of the article.<sep> A language section may contain several sections related to a given syntax category.<sep> In these sections, we can find glosses and examples, divided into several senses.<sep> Then come translations and semantic links.<sep> However, there is a lot of variation between the prototypical case and the reality.<sep> First, each language has its own conventions. In a given language, the written conventions are not always respected.<sep> The notion of flexibility is even proclaimed as an intrinsic characteristic of the Wikimedia Foundation projects. The automatic analysis of the content of Wiktionary is not an easy task.<sep> It is even less so when analysing the historical files that trace the chronology of the articles (i.e. containing all their dated versions), when both syntax and conventions evolve over time.<sep> The implications of questionable choices on the extracted resources are given in (Navarro et al, 2009).<sep> The debate, for example, on the relevance of the representation of the sub-senses of words in TAL will not take place here: their too loose encoding format prevents their use.<sep> 3.2.2. Lexemes and semantic relations: two-speed growth<sep> In order to study how evolves a collaborative resource such as Wiktionary, we analyzed the “history dump” provided by the Wikimedia Foundation. [6]<sep> These files contain the full versions of all articles after each edition.<sep> As can be seen in Figure 1, the growth of the English Wiktionary is steady while we notice two jumps in the French edition: the first one (early 2006) is due to an automated import from a public-domain dictionary, the Dictionnaire de l’Académie Fran¸caise (DAF).<sep> Other imports have been done gradually, from a second dictionary (Littré).<sep> The number of automatic imports for English is not significant.<sep> The second jump observed for French (mid-2008), more massive, is due to automated imports of demonyms taken from a specialized web site. This explains why verbs did not undergo this jump. However, one may wonder why Pétrocorien (inhabitant of the town Périgueux ), together with 76 347 other demonyms, has been included as a standard noun of the dictionary.<sep> No automated import was made to add semantic relations.<sep> The growth of the semantic relations has been slower than the lexical coverage: Contributors are more prone to add new words than semantic information.<sep> Among them are mostly synonyms and a few antonyms.<sep> Figure 2 shows the evolution of the number of semantic links and translation links in English and French.<sep> No automated import of translations is explicitly mentioned in Wiktionary.<sep> Nevertheless, we noticed in the French edition a massive addition of translations (in early 2006) operated by a bot without any explanation.<sep> After examination, we found a very brief note in the discussion page of the bot's author mentioning the import from an online site whose content and license were not clarified.<sep> Finally, despite a significant increase in the number of semantic and translation links, the gap with respect to the growth of the number of lexemes continues to widen (see Table 4). These links are essential to TAL applications.<sep> Fig. 1. Evolution of the number of lexemes and automated imports in Wiktionary<sep> Figure 2.<sep> Wiktionary: evolution of semantic relations and translation links<sep> Table 4. Growth of French and English Wiktionaries from 2007 to 2010<sep> 5.3 Size of Headword List and Lexical Coverage<sep> The English Wiktionary has "2,038,436 entries with English definitions from over 400 languages" and the French version has "1,821,097 articles [which] describe in French the words of more than 700 languages".<sep> These impressive figures should be qualified, however: meta-articles (help pages, discussion pages, etc.) are counted as entries, and many foreign words (in the language of the Wiktionary in question) are curiously included in the nomenclature (e.g. lexicon appears as an English entry in the French Wiktionary).<sep> Inflected forms are the subject of articles when they could be expected in articles devoted to their citation form.<sep> While in the French edition, the phrasal verbs are categorized as such, the English edition classifies them under the category of their head (or another category), which artificially inflates the number of lexemes announced (e.g. “caught on the hop” appears as a standard verb).<sep> Despite the surprising categorisations and massive automated imports (half of the names are demonyms, see section 3.2.2), the number of lexemes contained in the French and English editions of Wiktionary remains high.<sep> We then thought it was relevant to evaluate its effective lexical coverage.<sep> We compared the nomenclature to that of the Trésor de la Langue Française informatisé (TLFi) and examined the coverage between the names, verbs and adjectives (canonical forms) of the collaborative dictionary compared to those present in Morphalou.<sep> Table 4 shows that Wiktionary contains three quarters of the TLFi’s nouns, almost all its verbs and two thirds of its adjectives.<sep> In order to evaluate the proportion covered by each dictionary of the vocabulary of the three following corpora: 30 million words from 515 novels of the 20th century from the Frantext base, 200 million words from the articles of the daily newspaper Le Monde (period 1991 to 2000) and 260 million words extracted from the Wikipedia encyclopedia (version 06/2008),<sep> We lemmatized and categorized these corpora with TreeTagger[7] , then kept for each the categorized lemmas with a frequency greater than or equal to 5.<sep> We observe that the two lexicons follow the same trend: the vocabulary of Frantext is better covered than that of Le Monde, which is better covered than that of Wikipedia.<sep> The low coverage on Wikipedia may be due to the wide range of contributors and topics, as well as tokenization problems and a significant number of words from different languages.<sep> The low percentage of nouns covered may be explained by the fact that the articles in the encyclopaedia contain many isolated words unknown to TreeTagger, which it often tags as common nouns.<sep> We observe on the three corpora that Wiktionary covers more nouns and verbs (2% to 7%) and that Morphalou covers better the adjectives (1% to 4%).<sep> Building the union of the two nomenclatures (referred to as T∪W) leads to a rise of coverage for nouns (5%) and adjectives (10%).<sep> These observations lead us to conclude that, despite its noisy nature and lack of formality, Wiktionary, due to its coverage and availability, is worth considering as an interesting lexical resource for TAL.<sep> Furthermore, the results presented in Table 5 confirm the observations made by Zesch (2010): resources created by experts and those built collaboratively by crowds do not overlap exactly but contain complementary knowledge.<sep> Indeed, if it is true that the Wiktionary contains neologisms that are not in the TLFi, particularly those related to the Internet such as googler and wikifier, or regional (dracher) and national (diplomation, hommerie) diatopic variations, the Wiktionary also contains specialized terms such as clitic and métier (e.g. an application métier) and others that have become part of common usage such as sinogramme, homophobie, sociétal, fractal, ergonomique, médicaliser, étanchéifier, décélérer, paramétrer, etc.<sep> Table 5. Lexical coverage of Wiktionary (2011) and Morphalou (1.0)<sep> 4. Semi-automatic enrichment<sep> To fill the gap between the number of lexemes and the number of semantic relations (see section 3.2.2), we propose to develop a system of enrichment of semantic networks, starting with the relations of synonymy. In a previous experiment (Navarro et al., 2009), we developed an automatic system of densification of synonymy networks, which we applied to the French and English Wiktionary and evaluated using DicoSyn and WN.<sep> The results obtained were predictable: adding a small amount of links increases the recall and decreases the precision slightly; adding a large amount of links significantly increases the recall and decreases the precision.<sep> This evaluation method suffered from the bias of using a gold standard, as discussed in Section 3.2.<sep> Furthermore, the question of the appropriate number of synonyms to be added for a given lexeme arose.<sep> This number could be a function of the degree of incidence (number of neighbors) of the lexeme, but in a resource under construction such as Wiktionary, one cannot judge whether the current number of synonyms of a lexeme reflects its polysemy or the degree of completion of the corresponding entry. Manual validation would make it possible to judge not only the relevance of the proposals, but also to decide on the number of additions to be made.<sep> We describe below a method of enriching resources already initiated by calculating candidate synonym relations in a "crowds-based" validation perspective and study the impact of the different data sources used.<sep> 6.1 Weighted Bipartite Graphs Model<sep> In the following experiments, we rely on symmetric and weighted bipartite graphs.<sep> In order to homogenize the presentation, all the data sources we will use will be modeled by a graph G = ( V, V[′] , E, w ) consisting of two subsets of vertices. V will always refer to the set of lexemes of Wiktionary for the language and the syntax category considered.<sep> V[′] will designate a second subset of peaks whose content will be made up of different data sources.<sep> The set of edges (E) is such that E ⊆ (V × V[′] ) and models the relations between the lexemes of V and V[′].<sep> Moreover, a weight is given to each edge by the function w : E → R[+].<sep> - Translation graph GW t = (V, VW t, EW t, wW t) Here, V[′] = VW t is the set of the lexemes in all languages but the one of interest.<sep> EW t is the set of translation links: There is an edge between v ∈ V and t ∈ VW t if t is a translation of v in Wiktionary.<sep> All links have the same weight: ∀e ∈ E, wW t(e) = 1.<sep> Synonyms graph GW s = (V, VW s, EW s, wW s) Here, V[′] = VW s is simply a copy of V .<sep> There is an edge between v ∈ V and u ∈ VW s when v = u or u (or v) is indicated as synonym in v entry (or u entry).<sep> The arcs also all have the same weight here: ∀e ∈ E, wW s(e) = 1.<sep> Glosses graph GW g = (V, VW g, EW g, wW g) - Here, V[′] = VW g corresponds to the set of all lemmatized lexemes found in the glosses of all entries.<sep> There is an edge between v ∈ V and g ∈ VW g if g is used in one of the definitions of v.<sep> For a given lexeme, glosses have been concatenated, lemmatized, tagged with TreeTagger, and stopwords have been removed.<sep> Various weights may be used here but we simply used frequency. The weight of the edge between u ∈ V and g ∈ VW g is the number of occurrences of g in u’s gloss.<sep> We plan in a future experiment to use the position of the term in the gloss.<sep> Graph of Wikipedia’s syntactic contexts GW pc = (V, VW pc, EW pc, wW pc)<sep> - We extracted a 260 million words corpus from the French Wikipedia and analyzed it with Syntex, a syntactic parser for French (Bourigault, 2007).<sep> This parser produces dependency relations that we used to construct a list of syntactic cooccurrents by building up a frequency table of <lexeme,context> pairs, the context consisting of another lexeme and a syntactic relation linking both lexemes.<sep> VW pc is the set of all these contexts and an arc e = (v, c) ∈ EW pc means that a lexeme v appears in the context c.<sep> We used pointwise mutual information to weight these edges:<sep> where f (v, c) is the frequency of the lexeme v in the context c, f (v, ∗), f (∗, x) and f (∗, ∗) are respectively the total frequency of v (within any context), the total frequency of c (with any lexeme) and the total frequency of any pair.<sep> The sizes of the graphs thus constructed and of the graphs combining the different data sources are summarised in Table 6.<sep> For example, “s + t + g” is the graph resulting from the agglomeration of the vertices and arcs of the synonymy, translation and glosses graphs:<sep> G = ( V, V[′] = VW s ∪ VW t ∪ VW g, E = EW t ∪ EW t ∪ EW g, w ).<sep> Two vertices from different "V[′]" (for example one in VW t and one in VW g) are always considered as dissimilar even if they correspond to the same lexeme.<sep> We weight the edges of the combined graph by multiplying the initial edges’ weights by a coefficient depending on the type of edge.<sep> The graph denoted “αs.s + αt.t + αg.g” will have the following weighting function:<sep> Other ways of aggregating data and weighting the arcs can of course be considered.<sep> At this stage, the configurations we propose already make it possible to significantly increase the number of relevant candidates proposed (see Section 5.3).<sep> Table 6. Order and size of the bipartite graphs used to compute similarity.<sep> n and n[′] are the number of vertices, respectively in V and V[′] , which count at least one neighbor.<sep> m is the number of arcs.<sep> s, t, g and s: synonymy graphs, translations, glosses and syntactic contexts.<sep> 6.2 Random Walks-Based Similarity Computation<sep> We calculate for each vertex if its similarity with the set of other vertices is high enough to propose as candidate synonyms the vertices with the highest similarity scores with si.<sep> This similarity is calculated by performing random walks in the graphs presented in section 4.1.<sep> Such approaches are introduced in (Gaume et al, 2005; Gaume and Mathieu, 2008) for measuring topological resemblance in graphs. This kind of methods has also been applied to lexical networks in (Hughes and Ramage, 2007) to compute semantic relatedness. This approach is indeed adapted here: we have seen in section 2.2.2 that the synonymy networks, although globally sparse, are locally dense, most of the edges of a synonymy network being located in these dense areas.<sep> We can hypothesize that most of the links still missing from a network under construction are missing between pairs of vertices in the same dense area.<sep> However, a random walker entering a dense region is captured by this region (it stays there for a long time before leaving).<sep> A walker starting out on a summit thus has a high probability of passing at the beginning of his walk on the summits of the dense areas to which he belongs (Gaume et al., 2010).<sep> We consider a walker wandering at random along the edges of the weighted undirected bipartite graph G = (V ∪ V[′] , E, w) and starting from a given vertex v.<sep> At each step, the probability for the walker to move from nodes i to j is given by the cell (i, j) of the transition matrix P , defined as follow:<sep> where N (i) is the set of neighbors of the vertex i: N (i) = {j/(i, j) ∈ E}.<sep> Thus, starting from v, the walker’s position after t steps is given by the distribution of probabilities Xt(v) = δvP[t] , where δv is a row vector of dimension |V ∪ V[′] | with 0 anywhere except 1 for the column corresponding to vertex v.<sep> We note Xt(v, u) the value of the coordinate u of this vector, which represents the probability of the walker reaching u after t steps, starting from v.<sep> Several measures of similarity based on this probability were tested in (Sajous et al. , 2010) and give equivalent results.<sep> We will carry out the following experiments with X 2(v, u), which corresponds to a random walk of length 2.<sep> 5. Evaluation<sep> 5.1. Relevance of the proposed candidates: In view of a semi-automatic enrichment in which contributors validate or invalidate the proposed candidates, we consider that a (short) list of suggestions is acceptable if it contains at least one relevant candidate.<sep> Thus, our evaluation will broadly consist in counting for how many lexemes the system produces an acceptable list.<sep> We also examine how many lexemes are proposed with lists containing 2, 3 or more relevant candidates.<sep> Let GGS = (VGS, EGS) be a gold standard synonymy network, where VGS is a set of lexemes, and EGS ⊆ VGS × VGS a set of synonymy links.<sep> We evaluate below the pertinence of the suggested relations to enrich the deficient resource in relation to the gold standard’s relations.<sep> We perform this evaluation for the lexemes common to the resource to be enriched and the standard.<sep> We remove from the list of candidates those who are not in the gold standard and limit this list to k ≤ 5 candidates.<sep> For each lexeme v ∈ V ∩ VGS, we note Γk(v) the “evaluable” suggested list of candidates:<sep> Γk(v) contains a maximum of k candidates (but it may be smaller or even empty).<sep> Note also that Γk(v) depends on the gold standard.<sep> We note Γk[+][(][v][)] the set of correct candidates within Γk(v): Γk[+][(][v][)][=] { c[+] ∈ Γk(v) / (v, c[+] ) ∈ EGS }.<sep> We define the set Nk of lexemes having k candidates being proposed and the subset Nk[+][p] of lexemes for which at least p correct candidates are proposed: [14]<sep> To measure the impact of the data used on the calculation of the candidates, we measure Rk, the ratio between the number of suggested lists and the number of evaluable lexemes, and Pk, the ratio between the acceptable suggested lists (i.e. lists counting at least one good candidate) and the lexemes for which suggestions are made:<sep> We use WN and DicoSyn as the standard resources for English and French respectively.<sep> For details on the extraction of synonymy networks from these resources, we refer to (Navarro et al, 2009).<sep> 5.2. Qualification of the proposed relationships<sep> In order to better understand the type of relationships captured by our measure of similarity, we studied the nature of the candidate synonyms rejected by the chosen standard. Using WN, we classified the English candidates from the lists Γ k ( v ) presented above ( k ≤ 5) according to the relationships of synonymy, hyperonymy, hyponymy, cohyponymy for nouns and synonymy, hyperonymy, troponymy, cotroponymy for verbs [10] .<sep> We have kept the granularity fineness of WN while respecting its strict definitions: two lexemes are synonymous if they appear in the same synset, and we only consider strict hyperonymy/hyponymy/cohyponymy relations (e.g. w 1 is in hyperonymy relation with w 2 if w 2 appears in a synset that is a direct child of a synset in which w 1 appears).<sep> 5.3. Results<sep> Table 7. Impact of different data sources on the calculation of similarity.<sep> Table 7 shows the results obtained from the different data sources.<sep> The translation graph provides better precision than synonymy graph.<sep> This result was expected since in Wiktionary, lexemes have more translation links than synonyms.<sep> Moreover, these links are distributed over a large number of languages, which makes the information relatively reliable.<sep> The best recall and the least precision are obtained with glosses and syntactic contexts.<sep> This result was also expected, the information conveyed by these data being less specific. However, it allows for the proposal of candidates for almost all lexemes.<sep> Note that using the lexemes’ frequency to weight the graphs of glosses slightly improves the results. A more fine weighting (for example, by favoring the lexemes occurring at initial positions in the glosses) may perform even better.<sep> Curiously, syntactic co-occurrents lead to a quite poor result in terms of precision, which is opposite to the results found in the literature (e.g. van der Plas and Bouma, 2005).<sep> Filtering low frequency contexts would probably improve this score: indeed, a lexeme appearing with a single syntactic context tends to have a high mutual information with it without the association with another lexeme appearing with the same context being really significant.<sep> For English, combining synonyms and translations graphs improves recall without significant loss of precision.<sep> In French resources, it leads to a loss of precision compared to the “translations only” graph.<sep> As soon as glosses are used, candidates may be proposed for almost all lexemes.<sep> The best results are obtained by combining the graphs of synonymy, translation and glosses for English (graph 10.s + 10.t + g) and that of synonymy, translation and syntactic contexts for French (graph 10[3] .s +10[3] .t +10[2] .g + c).<sep> Using these graphs enables us to propose a list of 5 candidates for almost all lexemes and between 35% and 60% of these lists count at least one candidate validated by a gold standard.<sep> Let us remember that these lists are proposed on the basis of a resource that is still very incomplete.<sep> It can be thought that the prediction of missing links will improve with the densification of the resource.<sep> D'autre part, l'objectif n'est pas de suggérer des candidats pour un nombre restreint de lexèmes avec un score de confiance élevé (nous atteignons dans ce cas 80 à 90 % de listes pertinentes en ne recourant qu'aux graphes de traduction pour le français, mais pour seulement 6 à 20 % des lexèmes), mais d'effectuer les suggestions les plus pertinentes pour un nombre maximal de lexèmes.<sep> Notez que l'utilisation des gloses et des contextes syntaxiques dans les graphes combinés, tout en permettant de traiter l'ensemble des lexèmes, fait chuter la précision seulement au niveau global : au niveau local, les lexèmes pour lesquels les liens de synonymie et de traduction conduisaient à proposer des candidats pertinents ne sont pas nécessairement affectés par cette baisse (la proportion P 5 baisse mais pas le cardinal Nk[+] [i][[).]] k[[).]]<sep> The results are better for French than for English.<sep> This could be explained by the unequal density of the initial networks, but the difference is mainly due to the standards used: DicoSyn, being a compilation of seven dictionaries, is denser than WN.<sep> Drawing definitive conclusions about the overall quality of the method is difficult: a qualitative analysis shows that some candidates proposed and rejected by the gold standards do not seem unreasonable (e.g. <force, poigne> , <salade, bobard> , <drogue, psychotrope> , etc.).<sep> Conversely, some candidates validated as synonyms by the gold standards could be discussed (e.g. <rongeur, mulot> , <sens, toucher> seem to be good candidates for hyperonymy).<sep> The gold standards are still useful for selecting the data sources to be used.<sep> Figure 3 shows the type of relationships calculated by our method.<sep> For all the nouns and verbs common to Wiktionary and WN, we considered lists of 1 to 5 candidates, then removed those that were absent from WN.<sep> We can see that a part of the candidates not relevant for synonymy covers another semantic reality. Without the results being directly comparable (enrichment endogenous vs. extraction in corpus, WN vs. Dutch WordNet), we can note that the similarity of Heylen et al. (2008) produces as many cohyponymes as synonyms while our random walks produce twice as many synonyms as cohyponymes.<sep> Figure 3.<sep> Examples and proportions of relations captured by random walks<sep> 6. Implementation and application to Wiktionary: the WISIGOTH system<sep> To implement the enrichment and its validation system described above, we implemented the WISIGOTH system (WIktionarieS Improvement by Graph-Oriented meTHods), consisting of a processing chain that, from the Wiktionary dumps, extracts its network of synonymy and calculates the new candidate relations, and a Firefox extension.<sep> When a user installs this extension and visits a French or English Wiktionary page, our server is queried and returns an ordered list of candidates for the lexeme(s) being consulted.<sep> These candidates are then presented to the user (see figure 4).<sep> If they are validated (button ‘+’), the extension supports the addition of the synonym in Wiktionary and the editing of the corresponding wiki code.<sep> A free text area also allows a contributor to suggest a new synonym that has not been suggested.<sep> Regardless of our enrichment method, WISIGOTH thus enables non-wiki code familiar internet users to contribute.<sep> To remain close to the wiki principle, we have not implemented a cross-validation system and additions are published immediately.<sep> Nevertheless, while facilitating the addition of synonyms, we must also facilitate their removal: a ‘-’ button is added to each synonym for this purpose.<sep> Finally, a blacklist system allows a contributor to report a suggestion that they consider irrelevant (button '×').<sep> This suggestion will no longer be made and will allow other candidates to move up the list. Beyond a threshold (currently set arbitrarily at 3) of individual blacklistings, the proposal is added to a global blacklist so that it is no longer proposed to any user.<sep> Figure 4. Architecture of the WISIGOTH system<sep> 7. Conclusion and perspectives<sep> In this work, we pointed out the obstacles that oppose the creation of semantic lexical resources and in particular the problems related to their cost, availability and evaluation.<sep> In light of those observations, we proposed a system of enrichment for the resources already started, based on manual validation.<sep> We provide an implementation to apply this method to Wiktionary, whose content is already significant and we rely on crowd validation.<sep> This bet could solve the problems of cost, availability, sustainability and updating of such a resource.<sep> Furthermore, based on graphs and the use of endogenous data, our method is independent of the language considered and can be applied to other types of lexical networks.<sep> It may help, for example, building wordnets that are under construction, such as the Mandarin Chinese one (Huang et al, 2005).<sep> Nevertheless, we do not refrain to use exogenous data when available.<sep> Although we pointed out the limitations of using gold standards, we still proceeded to evaluate the candidates proposed by our system based on gold standards.<sep> These have allowed us to show the viability of our method for the intended application and also to observe the impact of the data sources used.<sep> A more relevant evaluation will be possible after one or two years of using this application.<sep> We will then be able to judge whether our system has helped to accelerate the growth of the synonymy network of Wiktionary. These initial results suggest several extensions. Automatic learning would allow us to obtain a better weighting of the arcs of the graphs used.<sep> In the short term, a modification of the interface will allow, for a candidate judged not to be a synonym, to add it as a target of other relations.<sep> We plan to adapt the similarity calculation to produce these relations on demand (e.g. hyperonymy, translations). It would finally be interesting to disambiguate to produce relations between lexemes (and not between forms).<sep> The work in this direction by Meyer and Gurevych (2010) takes advantage of a better structuring of the German Wiktionary (systematic presence of the number of the source lexeme of the relations), but for the moment it is only moderately successful.<sep> We are finally open to any collaboration to bring WISIGOTH to other languages and other lexical networks.<sep> In addition, we can integrate candidates produced by other teams: by hosting them or by having an additional web service interrogated by our interface.<sep> Resources: the resources presented or mentioned in this article (WISIGOTH extension, dumps converted to XML format, Wikipedia corpus) are available online on the REDAC site: http://redac.univ-tlse2.fr/<sep> Thanks<sep> We thank Yannick Chudy, for his work on the development of WISIGOTH and his contribution to all of our work.<sep> We have also benefited since the beginning of this project from the valuable collaboration of Laurent Prévot.<sep> 1. The summits can also correspond to vectors such as those presented above, the arcs being weighted by the distances calculated between these vectors.<sep> 2. Cruse (1986) uses the term plesionym.<sep> 3. The synonym relationships were extracted from each dictionary by INALF (now ATILF) and then corrected by CRISCO.<sep> 4. This automatic categorisation and manual validation work was carried out at CLLEERSS with the help of Lydia-Mai Ho-Dac.<sep> 5. These dumps are available at: http://download.wikipedia.org/<sep> 6. Lexicon distributed by ATILF from the nomenclature of TLFi, available at: http://www.cnrtl.fr/lexiques/morphalou/<sep> 7. http://www.ims.uni-stuttgart.de/projekte/corplex/TreeTagger/<sep> 8. It may be a neologism or a domain-specific word, less often it may be a misspelling or a poorly-covered entry in the standard.<sep> 9. i.e. the number of lexemes for which at least 1 candidate is proposed.<sep> 10. We also considered, and then discarded, the relationships of antonymy, holonymy/meronymy and causality, which concerned between 1‰ and 0.1‰ of cases.
Finding Salient Dates for Building Thematic Timelines<sep> ABSTRACT<sep> We present an approach for detecting salient (important) dates in texts in order to automatically build event timelines from a search query ( e.g. the name of an event or person, etc.).<sep> This work was carried out on a corpus of newswire texts in English provided by the Agence France Presse (AFP).<sep> In order to extract salient dates that warrant inclusion in an event timeline, we first recognize and normalize temporal expressions in texts and then use a machine-learning approach to extract salient dates that relate to a particular topic.<sep> We focused only on extracting the dates and not the events to which they are related.<sep> 1 Introduction<sep> A thematic event timeline is a list of descriptions of specific events, associated with their date of occurrence, and considered important from the point of view of a particular theme (for example, "the Arab Spring", "Michael Jackson", "the attacks in Baghdad").<sep> Our final goal is to build thematic event timelines from a user query using a corpus of news in French and English provided by the Agence France Presse (AFP).<sep> This task, which involves the extraction of important events, is related to the tasks of Retrospective Event Detection (Yang et al., 1998), or New Event Detection , as defined for example in Topic Detection and Tracking (TDT) campaigns (Allan, 2002).<sep> The majority of systems designed to tackle this task make use of textual information in a bag-ofwords manner. They use little temporal information, generally only using document metadata, such as the document creation time (DCT).<sep> The few systems that do make use of temporal information only extract absolute dates (those that can be placed on the time axis without any context, such as "14 July 1789", as opposed to "14 July").<sep> In the corpus of journalistic dispatches that we use and that we present in Section 3.1, we found that only 7% of extracted temporal expressions are absolute dates.<sep> Our work is distinguished from that of previous researchers in that the extraction of important events is guided by temporal processing. Indeed, we consider that important events, those that we wish to find in the chronologies, occur on dates that we can also judge as important - from the point of view of the theme imposed by the user's query.<sep> On the other hand, the expression of these events in texts will often be accompanied by a temporal expression, and repeated several times if the event is of a certain importance - from a journalistic point of view. We therefore want to show that it is relevant to look for these dates first, in order to then associate one or more events with each of them - this last part not being the subject of this article. For this, we rely essentially on a linguistic temporal processing of texts.<sep> Other types of content (textual for example) are used for initial thematic document retrieval.<sep> To extract these important dates, the first step is to collect as much temporal information as possible in the texts.<sep> Then we create the notion of a salient date, defined using essentially statistical criteria, with the aim of coming closer to the dates presented in the reference chronologies.<sep> We propose several definitions of the prominence of a date, starting with the simple redundancy of this date – which can take different lexical forms – in texts concerning the query, up to a modeling automatically learned from a certain number of finer characteristics.<sep> Furthermore, we use simple linguistic elements such as reported speech, modality or verb tense to refine this process by filtering out sentences that could introduce noise into the chain.<sep> As we have said above, to the extent that the dates appearing in the texts anchor the linguistic expression of events in time, if a date is considered to be significant for a given theme, then we assume that the events to which these dates are linked are certainly important from an informational point of view for this theme.<sep> They will therefore be good candidates for the construction of event chronologies.<sep> Output is a list of dates, ranked from most important to least important with respect to the given topic.<sep> Each date is presented with a set of relevant sentences for the given theme (see figure 5 below).<sep> The evaluation of such a system consists in verifying to what extent the dates returned are indeed those of the events that can be found in reference event chronologies - constructed independently by AFP journalists.<sep> In what follows, we first review some of the related work in Section 2.<sep> Section 3 presents the resources used and the system.<sep> The temporal analysis of texts is detailed in Section 4. Finally, the approaches chosen for indexing and extracting salient dates, as well as the results obtained, are presented in Section 5.<sep> 2 State of the art<sep> 2.1. Importance of the temporal component in TAL tasks. The ISO-TimeML language (Pustejovsky et al., 2010) is a specification language for manual annotation of temporal information in texts, but, to the best of our knowledge, it has not yet actually been used in information retrieval systems.<sep> Nevertheless, (Alonso et al., 2007; Alonso, 2008; Kanhabua, 2009) and (Mestl et al., 2009), among others, have highlighted that the analysis of temporal information is often an essential component in text understanding and is useful in a wide range of information retrieval applications.<sep> Thus, Harabagiu and Bejan (2005) and Saquete et al. (2009) highlight the importance of processing temporal expressions in Question Answering systems.<sep> For example, in the TREC-10 QA evaluation campaign, more than 10% of questions required an element of temporal processing in order to be correctly processed (Li et al., 2005a).<sep> In multidocument summarization, temporal processing enables a system to detect redundant excerpts from various texts on the same topic and to present results in a relevant chronological order (Barzilay and Elhadad, 2002). Furthermore, large knowledge bases automatically or semi-automatically constructed by extracting information from texts and which can be used as an encyclopedic source of information for TAL tasks are now enriched with a temporal component (Wang et al., 2010).<sep> Finally, temporal analysis is also useful for applications such as medical decision-making.<sep> (Kim and Choi, 2011) present work on the extraction of temporal information in clinical narrative texts.<sep> Similarly, (Jung et al., 2011) present an end-to-end system that processes clinical records, detects events and constructs timelines of patients’ medical histories.<sep> The importance of this temporal component has led to the development of systems for annotating temporal information, the majority of which are for English.<sep> Several of these systems are presented and evaluated in the TempEval campaigns (Verhagen et al., 2007; Verhagen et al., 2010).<sep> They are in most cases based on learning from corpora annotated according to the ISO-TimeML standard.<sep> While in (Verhagen et al., 2007) the main annotation tasks were focused on the determination of temporal relations between events and/or pre-annotated temporal expressions, in (Verhagen et al., 2010) two tasks consist in the automatic recognition and typing of temporal expressions and events without prior annotation.<sep> The community’s efforts are thus directed towards a task of temporal annotation, starting from the raw text and going as far as a fine analysis of the temporal structure of a document.<sep> The work of Uzzaman and Allen (2011) is an illustration of this concern.<sep> It presents a system combining deep syntactic analysis and classifiers to annotate and normalize events and temporal expressions from any text.<sep> Most of the existing systems that have participated in the competitions mentioned above deal with texts in English.<sep> For French, we can cite the work of Parent et al. (2008) and Battistelli et al. (2008).<sep> The first annotator detects events and uses finite state automata to recognize and annotate temporal location expressions automatically.<sep> The annotation here consists in typing these expressions according to their reference.<sep> The second annotator identifies and normalizes a subset of temporal location expressions (calendar expressions).<sep> Standardisation is done in terms of operations carried out on a calendar basis.<sep> We have developed an annotation and normalization tool for English and French for the extraction of salient dates.<sep> As in (Uzzaman and Allen, 2011), it benefits from a fine syntactic-semantic analysis.<sep> We will, however, only be interested in a subset of the temporal expressions considered in the cited work.<sep> 2.3. Event detection<sep> The analysis of time is closely linked to that of events, and this is generally the case but also, more particularly, in the field of the press. The various editions of the TDT task have given rise to the development of different systems that detect novelty in news streams (Allan, 2002; Kumaran and Allen, 2004; Fung et al., 2005).<sep> Most of these systems are based on statistical bag-of-words models that use similarity measures to determine proximity between documents (Li et al., 2005b; Brants et al., 2003).<sep> (Smith, 2002) used spatio-temporal information from texts to detect events from a digital library.<sep> His method is based on place/time collocations and ranks events according to statistical measures.<sep> Some efforts have been made for automatically building textual and graphical timelines.<sep> For example, (Allan et al., 2001) present a system that uses measures of pertinence and novelty to construct timelines that consist of one sentence per date.<sep> (Chieu and Lee, 2004) propose a similar system that extracts events relevant to a query from a collection of documents.<sep> Important events are those reported in a large number of news articles and each event is constructed according to one single query and represented by a set of sentences.<sep> (Swan and Allen, 2000) present an approach to generating graphical timelines that involves extracting clusters of noun phrases and named entities.<sep> More recently, Yan et al. (2011b; Yan et al., 2011a) used a summarization-based approach to automatically generate timelines, taking into account the evolutionary characteristics of news. Furthermore, developers of graphical interfaces have recently become interested in the temporal dimension, as shown by Time Explorer[1], Dipity[2] or Time-Surfer (Llorens et al., 2011). However, most of these applications only deal with absolute temporal expressions in texts.<sep> 3. Description of resources and system<sep> 3.1 AFP Corpus<sep> For this work, we used a corpus of newswire texts provided by the AFP French news agency for the period 2004-2011.<sep> The English AFP corpus is composed of 1.3 million documents (511 documents/day on average and 426 million words). Each document is an XML file containing a title, a date of creation (DCT), set of keywords, and textual content split into paragraphs. The French AFP corpus is composed of 1 million documents (499 documents/day on average and 390 million words).<sep> 3.2 AFP Chronologies<sep> Among the AFP dispatches in our corpus, there is a specific type of articles: these are textual event timelines written by AFP journalists in order to contextualize current events.<sep> They are in the form of a list of dates (usually between 10 and 20) associated with a text describing the event that took place on that date.<sep> Figure 1 shows an example of such a chronology produced by AFP.<sep> Further examples are given in Figure 2.<sep> Since our goal is to automatically produce such timelines, we chose to use AFP timelines for the learning and evaluation of our system.<sep> For this, we selected a certain number of chronologies satisfying the following constraints:<sep> - All dates in the chronologies are between 2004 and 2011 to be sure that the related events are described in the corpus.<sep> For example, a chronology of the Vietnam War was excluded because its corresponding dates do not appear in the content of the articles.<sep> For example, the chronology “Space in 2005: A calendar” , published in January 2005 and listing scheduled events, was not selected (because almost no rocket launches finally happened on the expected day).<sep> - The temporal granularity of the chronology is the day.<sep> We are not interested in timelines relating events hour by hour, for example. We are working at this level of granularity in the development of our system.<sep> There are 91 of these chronologies in English and 94 in French. In the following, we will call them "manual chronologies".<sep> These chronologies are in a very heterogeneous format, with unmarked dates in particular.<sep> To ensure easy use for learning and evaluation of our system, each chronology is therefore converted to a more precise and homogeneous XML format.<sep> On the other hand, we manually associate keywords with it, representing the user's search query, by which the user wants to obtain the thematic chronology. The usefulness of this query will be explained later.<sep> Figure 1.<sep> Example of AFP manual timeline<sep> Figure 2.<sep> Examples of AFP manual timeline topics<sep> Figure 3.<sep> 3.3 System Overview<sep> Figure 3 shows the general architecture of the system.<sep> First, pre-processing of the AFP corpus tags and normalizes temporal expressions in each of the articles (step x in the Figure).<sep> The corpus thus enriched is indexed by the Lucene search engine[2] (step y).<sep> All the extracted temporal information is thus associated with the textual content during the indexing process.<sep> Given a query, a number of documents are retrieved by Lucene (z).<sep> These documents can be filtered ({), and dates are extracted from the remaining documents.<sep> Each date is thus accompanied by a set of sentences relevant to the given query.<sep> These dates are then ranked in order to show the most important ones to the user (|), together with the sentences that contain them. All these steps are detailed in the following sections.<sep> 4. Temporal analysis of texts<sep> In this section, we describe the linguistic and temporal information extracted during the pre-processing phase and how the extraction is carried out.<sep> We rely on the XIP analyzer (A¨ıtMokhtar et al., 2002), that we adapted for our purposes.<sep> 4.1. Introduction to XIP<sep> The XIP analyzer performs a deep syntactic analysis of texts.<sep> It takes as input XML files and analyzes the textual content enclosed in the various XML tags in different ways that are specified in an XML guide (a file providing instructions to the parser, see (Roux, 2004) for details).<sep> XIP performs complete linguistic processing ranging from tokenization to deep grammatical dependency analysis.<sep> It also performs named entity recognition (NER) of the most usual named entity categories and recognizes temporal expressions.<sep> Linguistic units manipulated by the parser are either terminal categories or chunks.<sep> Each of these units is associated with an attribute-value matrix that contains the unit’s relevant morphological, syntactic and semantic information.<sep> Linguistic constituents are linked by oriented and labelled n-ary relations denoting syntactic or semantic properties of the input text.<sep> A Java API is provided with the parser so that all linguistic structures and relations can be easily manipulated by Java code.<sep> In the following subsections, we give details of the linguistic information that is used for the detection of salient dates.<sep> 4.2 Named Entity Recognition<sep> Named Entity (NE) Recognition is one of the outputs provided by XIP.<sep> The named entities are represented as unary relations in the parser output.<sep> We use the existing recognition modules for French and English which tag the following types: location names , person names and organization names .<sep> The ambiguity that may exist between certain types (between the location or organization type for country names for example) is preserved in the annotation.<sep> 4.3. Recognition of temporal expressions<sep> A previous module for temporal analysis was developed and integrated into the English grammar (Hagège and Tannier, 2008), and evaluated during TempEval campaign (Verhagen et al., 2007).<sep> The goal of this analyzer was to establish temporal relations between dates and events. For the work presented in this article, we wanted to prioritize precision for the normalization and recognition of a subset of the temporal expressions considered in TimeML. We also developed a normalization module that is common to both languages (French and English).<sep> Finally, the annotation guide that we adopted in this work differs from TimeML in several points (Bittar et al., 2012). The goal of temporal analysis is to be able to recognize, annotate and normalize[5] a subset of temporal expressions that we consider to be relevant for our task.<sep> This subset of expressions is described in the following sections.<sep> As a first approximation, given that we have a large corpus in which redundancy exists, we estimated that we must at all costs prioritize precision over recall.<sep> Indeed, we believe that introducing noise into the detection of salient dates would be more detrimental than omitting some dates.<sep> We have thus deliberately ignored difficult cases such as those that would require the resolution of anaphora between possibilities, and we have therefore considered the dates that are not recurrent, complete (absolute) or relative to the moment of the utterance which is given as a metadata and corresponds to the date of creation of the news item.<sep> 4.3.1 Absolute Dates<sep> Absolute dates are dates that can be normalized without external or contextual knowledge.<sep> This is the case, for instance, of “On January 5th 2003” .<sep> In these expressions, all information needed for normalization is contained in the linguistic expression.<sep> However, absolute dates are relatively infrequent in our corpus (7% of all dates extracted in English, 12% in French). It is therefore essential to consider relative dates, which are far more frequent, in order to broaden the coverage for the detection of salient dates.<sep> 4.3.2 DCT-relative Dates<sep> DCT-relative temporal expressions are those which are relative to the creation date of the document. This class represents 40% of dates extracted from the AFP corpus in English and French.<sep> Unlike absolute dates, their consideration alone does not allow them to be standardised.<sep> Other information, in particular the date which corresponds to the moment of utterance, is required.<sep> In news articles, this date corresponds to the DCT.<sep> Two sub-classes of relative TEs can be distinguished. The first sub-class only requires knowledge of the DCT value to perform the normalization.<sep> This is the case of expressions like next Friday , which correspond to the calendar date of the first Friday following the DCT. The second sub-class requires further contextual knowledge for normalization.<sep> For example, on Friday will correspond either to last Friday or to next Friday depending on the context where this expression appears ( e.g. He is expected to come on Friday corresponds to next Friday while He arrived on Friday corresponds to last Friday ).<sep> In such cases, the tense of the verb that governs the TE is essential for normalization.<sep> This information is provided by XIP.<sep> 4.4. Mood, future and reported speech<sep> In the context of automatic creation of event timelines, we are interested in proven events, leaving aside those of a hypothetical or uncertain nature, or those that do not take place. For our task, we then decided to ignore the dates associated with such events in the texts.<sep> A certain number of linguistic properties can indicate that an event is unproven, including negation, modality and certain tenses and verb modes. Similarly, an event described in reported speech may not necessarily be proven.<sep> We have integrated some of this linguistic information into our processing. Rather than relying on a particular theoretical basis, we have implemented a set of heuristics to be able to filter out dates associated with unverified events.<sep> In this section we present our treatment of modality, the future tense, and reported speech.<sep> The modality associated with timestamped events in text is an important issue that can affect the detection of salient dates.<sep> Intuitively, a date associated with an unconfirmed event should not be considered in the same way as a date associated with an event described as certain by the author of the dispatch, insofar as the salient dates will correspond to dates of confirmed facts and not to dates of hypothetical facts. For example, in the sentences "The meeting took place on Friday", "The meeting should take place on Friday" and "The meeting will take place on Friday, Mr. Hong said", the dates do not have the same salient status.<sep> The time-stamped event meeting takes place is factual in the first example and can be taken as granted.<sep> In the second and third examples, however, the event does not necessarily occur.<sep> This is expressed by the modality (should in the second example), or by the use of the future tense or reported speech (third example). We wanted to take these elements into account for the extraction of salient dates.<sep> However, it did not seem necessary to us in this context to assign specific values of modality, but simply to mark the fact that a temporal expression that we consider for the extraction of salient dates modifies a predicate that has a modal value.<sep> We did the same for temporal expressions referring to future predicates.<sep> In both cases, the intuition is the following: in the case of a non-factual or future eventuality, there is uncertainty as to the actual realisation of this eventuality.<sep> The date associated with such an event will therefore have a special status that will allow subsequent filtering for the detection of significant dates.<sep> In the same way, we also wanted to mark the possibilities corresponding to reported speech or introduced by a reported speech verb.<sep> XIP thus considers the following features for the annotation of temporal expressions.<sep> – Verbs mentioned in the future: if a time-stamped event modifies a verb in the future tense or a noun governed by a verb in the future tense, we add the FUTURE attribute with the value + to the corresponding TE annotation.<sep> – Verbs described with a modal verb: if a timestamped event is introduced by a modal verb (for example, should or would for English, pouvoir or devoir for French), then the MODALITY attribute of the corresponding TE annotation has the value MODAL.<sep> Reported speech verbs: Reported speech verbs introduce indirect or reported speech.<sep> In the case of time-stamped events governed by a reported speech verb, or otherwise appearing in reported speech, XIP marks the reported speech verbs and segments complex sentences.<sep> If a temporal expression modifies a reported speech verb, the annotation of this TE contains a specific attribute, DECLARATION=”YES”.<sep> "A senior U.S. disarmament official will hold talks with the British government on how to verify Libya's pledges to abandon its weapons of mass destruction programs, the State Department said Wednesday."<sep> If the relevant TE modifies a verb that appears in a clause introduced by a reported speech verb then the annotation contains the attribute REPORTED=”YES”. For example, in the following sentence from the same corpus, the annotation of the TE in 2004 contains the attribute REPORTED=”YES” because it is part of the reported speech introduced by the verb demander.<sep> "In his New Year's message, Prime Minister John Howard has called for no let-up in 2004 [...].<sep> Note that the different annotations can be combined ( e.g. modality and reported speech can occur for a same time-stamped event).<sep> For example, the TE Friday in “The meeting should take place on Friday, Mr. Hong said” is annotated with both modality and reported speech attributes.<sep> 4.5 Corpus-dependent Special Cases<sep> While we developed the linguistic and temporal annotators, we took into account some specificities of our corpus.<sep> We decided that the temporal expressions today and now for English, aujourd'hui for French, were not relevant for the detection of salient dates.<sep> In the AFP news corpus, these expressions are mostly synonymous with nowadays and do not really date an event with respect to the DCT.<sep> Another specificity of the corpus is the fact that if the DCT corresponds to a Monday, and if an event in a past tense is described with the associated TE on Monday or Monday , it means that this event occurs on the DCT day itself, and not on the Monday before.<sep> We adapted the date normalization to take into account these special cases.<sep> 4.6 Implementation and Example<sep> As said previously, a NER module is integrated into the XIP parser.<sep> The TE tagger and normalizer was adapted from (Hagège and Tannier, 2008).<sep> We used the Java API provided with the parser to perform the annotation and normalization of TEs.<sep> The outputs are XML files where only the desired information is kept (structural information distinguishing headlines from news content, DCT), and enriched with the linguistic annotations described before.<sep> Figure 4 shows an example of an analysis of an excerpt of a news article in English.<sep> In this news excerpt, only one TE ( Wednesday ) is normalized as both The year 2004 and in a decade are not considered to be relevant.<sep> This grammatical dependency is calculated by XIP.<sep> The second expression is not standardised as it is of a granularity superior to a year.<sep> The annotation of Wednesday has the attribute DECLARATION indicating that this expression time-stamps an event realized by a reported speech verb.<sep> The normalized value of the expression corresponds to the 5th of January 2005, which is a Wednesday.<sep> The named entities are also annotated.<sep> In the entire AFP corpus in English, 11.5 million temporal expressions were detected, among which 845,000 absolute dates (7%) and 4.6 million normalized relative dates (40%).<sep> Figure 4. Example of an XIP output for a dispatch.<sep> TYPE is the type of the expression, SUBTYPE is the subtype of a date (absolute or relative), REF is the reference of this date, relative to the moment of utterance (ST) or relative to a reference moment (RT).<sep> 4.7. Evaluation of the time annotation<sep> We wanted to evaluate the performance of our annotation tools by comparing them to the TimeBank corpora of French and English.<sep> We remind you that this assessment concerns absolute dates and dates relative to the DCT.<sep> The reference corpus used for annotation thus corresponds to the TimeBank resources in which all annotated temporal expressions that do not correspond to an absolute date or a date relative to the time of utterance are ignored.<sep> We evaluate the following three points: - 1) the recognition of the expression; - 2) the typing of the annotated expression; - 3) the normalization of the annotated expression.<sep> In the case where a system annotation does not have exactly the same delimitation as that present in the reference corpus or in the case where we have a total absence of normalization for an expression whose extent is correctly delimited, we consider an error for the annotator.<sep> To evaluate the typing and normalization of expressions, we only consider the annotations of expressions that are correctly recognized and delimited<sep> This measure is more rigorous than a measure that would take into account normalization and detection separately, but we chose to proceed in this way because the detection of salient dates cannot be done, according to our method, without a normalization of the dates identified. 4.7.1. For French For French, we compared the outputs of the annotator with the TimeBank of French (Bittar et al., 2011) adapted by filtering the temporal expressions that we do not consider in our work.<sep> After this filtering, the corpus contained 299 temporal expressions annotated with the < TIMEX3 > tag (out of 608 in the original corpus).<sep> We measured recall, precision and F-measure, standard measures in the evaluation of information extraction systems, as well as agreement (Kappa coefficient (Cohen, 1960)).<sep> Unlike other measures used, the calculation of Kappa takes into account the notion of chance agreement between two annotations.<sep> The results are shown in Table 1.<sep> For the detection of temporal expressions, the performance is acceptable, but can still be improved.<sep> A closer analysis of the results shows that the main errors are due to gaps in the coverage of the grammar, which is still under development.<sep> Furthermore, for this experiment, we used the general grammar of French and did not make any adaptations based on the corpus.<sep> For the evaluation of typing and normalization, we considered the subset of 239 expressions that were correctly recognized and delimited.<sep> No errors were made in the typing of the expressions (absolute dates and dates relative to the DCT).<sep> Very good results have been achieved for the standardization of expressions.<sep> The main source of errors in normalisation comes from cases where a relative date expression with respect to the DCT appears in a context where it is not syntactically related (directly or indirectly) to a verbal predicate.<sep> Indeed, for some of these expressions, the time of the associated verb is necessary to correctly proceed with the normalization.<sep> In some cases, the absence of the syntactic link between temporal expression and verbal predicate is due to an error in the syntax analyzer.<sep> In other cases, however, they are expressions that appear in sentences that do not contain verbs.<sep> Table 1. Performance of the annotation system for French over the entire evaluation corpus<sep> 4.7.2. For English<sep> We did a similar thing to evaluate the annotations in English.<sep> As for French, we performed a filtering on the English TimeBank 1.2 to remove expressions that did not fit within the scope of this work.<sep> Furthermore, we chose to carry out the evaluation on a subset of the total corpus, taking one document in three.<sep> This choice was motivated by two factors.<sep> Firstly, we wanted to use a corpus of similar size to the one used for French in terms of the number of temporal expressions, in order to facilitate the comparison of the results for the two languages.<sep> Secondly, since the analysis of the errors had to be done partly manually, we thought it would be a good idea to reduce the size of the corpus in order to facilitate and speed up this part of the task.<sep> The evaluation corpus we used contains 320 temporal expressions annotated with the < TIMEX3 > tag (out of 1,414 in the original corpus).<sep> The results are presented in Table 2.<sep> As for French, we evaluated the typing and normalization on the subset of expressions that were correctly recognized and delimited (a total of 198 for English).<sep> No errors were made in the typing of the expressions.<sep> The results for the standardization of expressions are also quite good, even if slightly lower than those obtained for French.<sep> The recall obtained for the identification of temporal expressions is well below what we hoped to obtain for the type of expressions we are dealing with here.<sep> As with French, the English grammar was not developed with the perspective of treating a particular corpus and, consequently, certain types of temporal expressions, which are recurrent in the English TimeBank, are not yet treated by the grammar, for example, numerical dates such as « 19980108 » and « 11/02/89 » and dates in full « the year two thousand » and « in nineteen seventy-nine ».<sep> In the first case, the patterns that would be used to detect these dates (out of context) might also recognize other types of numbers.<sep> Because the grammar was developed with a general purpose in mind, these expressions are not recognized, which has generated silence.<sep> For the second type of expressions, while it is relatively more common to write these types of dates in numerical format (“the year 2000” and “in 1979”), these expressions deserve to be included in the grammar.<sep> As with French, a number of errors come from an upstream parsing error.<sep> So we find expressions such as "Friday" and "November" that are not detected, or are detected but not normalized, which is an error in our measurement.<sep> Table 2. Performance of the annotation system for English over the entire evaluation corpus<sep> In conclusion, the results of these two evaluations show that improvements are possible and have highlighted a series of errors that can be corrected.<sep> The measures used for this evaluation only take into account the expressions correctly identified and normalized.<sep> In our future work, we plan to extend this evaluation to all expressions identified by the system.<sep> We also want to extend the standardization to take into account expressions other than absolute and relative dates at the time of utterance.<sep> 5. Experiments on peak dates and results<sep> In Section 5.1, we propose two baseline approaches in order to give a good idea of the difficulty of the task (Section 5.4 also discusses this point).<sep> In Section 5.2, we present our experiments using simple filtering and statistics on dates calculated by Lucene.<sep> Finally, Section 5.2.2 details our experiments with a learning approach.<sep> In all these experiments, we used three different values to rank dates: - occ ( d ) is the number of textual units (documents or sentences) containing the date d . Lucene provides ranked documents associated with their relevance score.<sep> luc ( d ) is the sum of Lucene scores for textual units containing the date d .<sep> - An adaptation of tf.idf for dates:<sep> where N is the number of indexed paragraphs and df ( d ) is the number of paragraphs containing date d . The tf.idf are summed to give the score of the date.<sep> In all cases, as explained above, the output of the system is a list of dates, ordered from the most prominent to the least prominent, accompanied by phrases associated with these dates and the theme of the search.<sep> A simplified extract of such an output is presented in figure 5.<sep> To evaluate our results, we compared them to the manual chronologies of AFP (see Section 3.2) using Mean Average Precision (MAP), which is a widely accepted metric for ranked lists.<sep> MAP gives a higher weight to higher ranked elements than lower ranked elements.<sep> This is to calculate the precision at each position of the ordered list of results (here, dates) and to sum them up as long as all dates have not been found.<sep> For a query, the average precision (AP) is therefore:<sep> where k is the rank of the date in the list, n the number of returned dates, r the number of dates in the reference chronology, P (k) the precision at this rank and rel (k) the relevance value (0 or 1) of this date.<sep> The MAP is the mean of the average precisions over all queries. The statistical significance of the results is indicated by the p-value, which is the result of the Student’s t-test ( t (90) = 1.9867).<sep> 5.1 Baseline Runs<sep> We implemented the two following approaches which serve as a baseline. For these, as well as for the following experiments, the chosen textual unit is the paragraph. Each date is thus associated with a part of the text and not with the entire dispatch, which can relate to other events without a direct relationship with the specified date.<sep> Figure 5.<sep> Example of output (simplified) of the system of selection of salient dates<sep> - BLabs . Indexing and search were done at sentence level by the Lucene search engine (document title and keywords are added to each sentence).<sep> Given a query, the top 10,000 documents are returned.<sep> Only absolute dates in these sentences were considered.<sep> Dates are ranked according to one of three values described earlier (occ, luc, or tf.idf).<sep> We thus obtained runs BL[occ] abs[,] [ BL] abs[luc][and] [ BL][tfidf] abs[.]<sep> - Chieuburst. We have implemented and adapted to our task the system described in (Chieu and Lee, 2004) which extracts from a collection of documents the events relevant to a query, and classifies them according to a combination of measures called Burstiness and Interest.<sep> The first step of the algorithm is to associate each of the sentences returned by the system to a date, either an absolute date if it exists in the sentence, or the DCT. Then, the sentences are classified according to the Burstiness measure: each sentence/date pair is compared to the query with the Interest measure. This consists of calculating the cosine between each lexical vector, taking into account a period of k days around the date associated with s in order to filter out the sentences with a date too far from the initial date.<sep> This allows the contingency table (see Table 3) to be completed as defined in 1, 2, 3, 4:<sep> Table 3. Contingency table for the Burstiness measure.<sep> Line K represents documents that are temporally close (∥date (s[′]) − date (s) ∥ < = k), line K[¯] represents documents that are temporally distant (∥date (s[′]) − date (s) ∥ > k).<sep> The column s measures the similarity, the column ¯ s the dissimilarity (see the formulas for a, b, c, d below).<sep> The final score of the Burstiness measure for a sentence/date pair s is obtained by summing the log-likelihood ratio with k ranging from 1 to n as defined in 5.<sep> where LL (s) = log likelihood ratio from the 3x2 contingency table.<sep> The Interest measure is then reused to remove duplicate sentences, taking into account the previously obtained ranking.<sep> The system described by Chieu and Lee (2004) is intended to produce events (text), not dates.<sep> To adapt it to our problem, we choose to order the dates according to the Burstiness value of the corresponding event.<sep> Table 4. MAP scores for the two baseline systems<sep> In the preliminary tests, we varied k between 1 and 20.<sep> The best results for MAP were obtained with k variant from 1 to 10 (n = 10). However, the system remains extremely slow when the number of sentences returned for the query is important despite the optimization of the Interest measure described in the article.<sep> Table 4 shows results for these two systems.<sep> The baseline that uses only absolute dates presents extremely low results whatever the type of classification. The Chieu system presents interesting results with a MAP score around 0.5.<sep> 5.2 Extraction of salient dates 5.2.1 With simple filtering<sep> In these experiments, the Lucene index was built as follows: each paragraph containing a date normalized by XIP was considered to be a document.<sep> The title and keywords of the AFP article are added to each paragraph of the document during indexing.<sep> Given a query, the top 10,000 documents are returned.<sep> Different combinations of filtering were implemented to not take into account dates associated with a reported speech verb (R), a declarative verb (D), a modal verb (M) or a future verb (F).<sep> All these filtering operations were intended to remove references to events that were not certain, thereby minimizing noise in results.<sep> Table 5. MAP scores obtained by combining salient date extraction with XIP and simple filtering.<sep> The statistical significance of the filtered results compared to the unfiltered results is indicated by the Student t-test (∗: p < 0.05 (significant); ∗∗: p < 0.01 (highly significant)).<sep> The use of tf.idf (d) compared to occ (d) also shows a very significant progression in both languages.<sep> These processing runs are named SD runs, with different indices depending on the type of filtering used.<sep> For example, a run obtained by filtering modal and future verbs is called SDM,F .<sep> For all these combinations, the dates obtained were ranked by the sum of Lucene scores for the associated paragraphs or by tf.idf[8] .<sep> Table 2 presents the results for this series of experiments.<sep> MAP values are much higher than for baselines.<sep> Using tf.idf ( d ) is only very slightly better than luc .<sep> The different filtering operations bring significant improvement but the benefits of these different techniques have to be further investigated in order to refine the results.<sep> 5.2.2. With learning<sep> We used our set of manually-written chronologies as a training corpus to perform machine learning experiments.<sep> We used IcsiBoost[5] , a free version of the BoosTexter classifier, based on Ada-Boost (Freund and Schapire, 1997), an algorithm of boosting of simple classifiers (decision trees with 1 level of depth).<sep> Regarding the parameter defining the number of iterations of the algorithm, experiments have shown that an optimum is reached around 1,000 turns.<sep> In our approach, we consider two classes: salient dates are dates that have an entry in the manual chronologies, while non-salient dates are all other dates.<sep> This approach, however, represents an important bias.<sep> The choices of journalists are indeed very subjective, and chronologies must not exceed a certain length, which means that relevant dates can be thrown away.<sep> These issues will be discussed in Section 5.4.<sep> We chose not to represent each paragraph as an instance of the classifier but rather to group all paragraphs corresponding to the same date before the learning phase.<sep> Therefore, each instance corresponded to a single date, and features were figures concerning the set of sentences containing this date.<sep> The features used in this series of runs are as follows:<sep> 1. Features representing the fact that the more a date is mentioned, the more important it is likely to be:<sep> - sum of the Lucene scores for all paragraphs containing the date,<sep> - number of paragraphs containing the date,<sep> - Ratio between the Lucene scores of this date and the Lucene scores of all dates,<sep> 4) Ratio between the frequency of the date and frequency of all returned dates;<sep> 2. Features representing the fact that an important event is still mentioned long after it has occurred:<sep> 1) Distance in number of days between the date and the most recent mention of this date (the latest in the corpus),<sep> 2) Distance in number of days between this date and the DCT;<sep> 3. Other features:<sep> - Lucene’s best ranking of the date,<sep> - Number of times where the date is absolute in the paragraphs (i.e. Number of paragraphs returned, in which the date was an absolute date, normalized without recourse to external or contextual knowledge, as opposed to relative dates),<sep> 4) Total number of query keywords in the title, sentence and named entities of retrieved documents, - number of times the date is relative and normalised in paragraphs,<sep> - Number of times where the date is extracted from a reported speech verb or is in the future.<sep> We did not aim to classify dates, but rather to rank them.<sep> For this reason, we used the predicted probability P ( d ) returned by the classifier, combined with the Lucene score of paragraphs or the tf.idf of the date d : score ( d ) = P ( d ) × val ( d ) where val ( d ) is either luc ( d ) or tf.idf ( d ). Given the bias reported above, and especially the small amount of learning data, the approaches commonly called Learning to Rank, which aim to learn a ranking model from partially ordered lists and a set of traits, do not seem suitable for our problem.<sep> Indeed, these methods require a large volume of learning data, which we do not have in our case.<sep> We evaluated this approach with a classical cross-validation on four partitions of the learning corpus.<sep> Each manual timeline is thus randomly distributed in one of the partitions.<sep> We use three sub-corpora as learning data (two are used for learning while the last one is used to calibrate the classifier) and the fourth corpus is reserved for testing: four rotating test sets are thus created.<sep> The final score of a test is then calculated by averaging all the scores obtained on each of the four test corpora.<sep> Table 3: MAP results for learning.<sep> ML[luc] base used Lucene scores and only the first set of features described above.<sep> ML[luc] and ML[tf.idf] used the three sets of features.<sep> We thus observe an increase in the MAP score of around 0.08 points on the English corpus and 0.02 on the French corpus.<sep> 5.2.3. Error analysis<sep> A more detailed analysis of the errors shows that they can be of several types.<sep> A lack of precision in manually defined queries can lead the system to suggest invalid dates for the theme.<sep> Thus, the query "Niger" used to trace the various events of the crisis in Niger in 2009, leads the system to propose the dates of the matches of the Niger Cup which took place during the summer of 2009.<sep> Similarly, the search term "Georges Tron", associated with the timeline of the sexual assault allegations, does not make it possible to distinguish between the dates of the interventions of the Secretary of State and those of the case itself.<sep> Table 6.<sep> MAP scores obtained for the extraction of salient dates with learning. The results on English show a very significant improvement (p ≈ 6 . 10 [−][4] ) compared to SD[luc] and SD[tf.idf] .<sep> On the other hand, even if the query seems correct, less relevant documents selected by the search engine can introduce noise in the results.<sep> For example, for the chronology of events that occurred during the crisis in the world of Formula 1 in 2009, all the dates of events associated with this crisis are found, but the order of these events is disrupted by the dates of Grand Prix races, which also have a significant frequency in the corpus.<sep> Similarly, the timeline of all the crimes committed in Marseille in 2009, with the search term “Marseille crime”, has a very poor average precision (0.02).<sep> A search of the corpus shows that all the news reports on these events generally refer to more specific locations (such as the northern districts, the Cité des Bleuets or the Timone hospital).<sep> These relevant documents are therefore not returned by Lucene, which gives priority to other documents relating to crimes that took place during this period, without any connection to the city of Marseille.<sep> In this case, the size of the chosen textual unit is at fault. Moreover, some events chosen by journalists to be included in the manual chronologies have no direct link with the theme.<sep> Thus, the date of 21 February 2011 in the chronology "Decline and fall of Hosni Mubarak" is associated with the violence in Libya, a bordering country.<sep> This last example shows the difficulty of evaluating the results of our system in relation to reference chronologies constructed manually in a subjective manner (see section 5.3).<sep> Finally, we can see that the performance is much better for English than for French.<sep> A more detailed analysis of the results shows that for English, only 0.6% of the dates in the reference chronologies are not found at all by the system, while this is 3.6% for French.<sep> We have noticed that the corpus of French news reports sometimes contains no (or very few) references to certain events described in the chronologies, as well as some inconsistencies between the date in the chronology and the date provided in the corpus.<sep> The larger number of dates not found in French may explain in part the lower performance of the system for French. Table 7. Average accuracy for four themes, compared to the original chronology (APC, automatic evaluation) and with the expert's opinion (APE, manual evaluation)<sep> 5.3. What is a good result?<sep> Existing chronologies, hand-written by AFP journalists, are a very useful resource for an objective evaluation of our system, as they are completely dissociated from our research and are an exact representation of the output we aim to obtain.<sep> However, assembling such a chronology is a very subjective task, and no clear method for estimating the agreement between two journalists writing the same chronology is immediately apparent.<sep> Only experts in a field can build such chronologies, and calculating this agreement would require at least two experts from each domain, which are hard to come by. We propose two specific experiments for this delicate point.<sep> 5.3.1. Manual evaluation<sep> In the first experiment, we chose four topics in English, concerning the Arab Spring[10] and we proposed the chronology produced by our system for each of these topics to an AFP expert.<sep> We asked him to assess the first 30 dates of the chronology.<sep> Table 4 presents results for this evaluation, comparing average precision values obtained 1) against the original, manual chronologies ( APC ), and 2) against the expert assessment ( APE ).<sep> These values show that, for 3 runs out of 4, many dates returned by the system are considered as valid by the expert, even if not presented in the original chronology. Despite the low number of subjects concerned, this shows that our system can be an effective aid for the journalist, since he considers most of the dates proposed as relevant.<sep> Table 8.<sep> Agreement between the French and English chronologies on the same theme (same day of publication)<sep> 5.3.2. Inter-annotator agreement on two languages<sep> In order to estimate an inter-annotator agreement between two journalists writing the same chronology, we extracted from our collection of manual chronologies pairs of chronologies that meet the following constraints: - one is written in French, the other in English; - the theme of the two chronologies given by the title is the same; - the two chronologies were written on the same day; - the authors of the two chronologies are different. Six pairs of chronologies meet these criteria.<sep> We arbitrarily considered the English chronologies as the reference and give the precision, recall and F-measure scores obtained by the corresponding French chronology[11] . We see in Table 8 that the agreement between two journalists creating a chronology on the same theme is therefore relatively low.<sep> For a given task, a system does not necessarily have the mission of approaching 100% of results in common with the reference, but rather to approach it with an agreement comparable to the agreement possible between two humans.<sep> This result therefore allows us to put the MAP values obtained by our system and given above into perspective.<sep> 6 Conclusion and Future Work<sep> This article presents a system of extraction of salient dates from a user's query, and shows the importance of taking temporal information into consideration and how with relatively simple temporal processing, we were able to indirectly point to important events using the temporal information associated with these events. Our system obtains satisfactory results as it is close to the chronologies produced manually by journalists.<sep> Thus, for English, our system produces 52.8% of chronologies with an average precision score greater than 0.8 compared to the reference chronologies, while it only produces 6.6% of chronologies with a score less than 0.5.<sep> For French, on the other hand, the system only proposes 34% of timelines with an average accuracy of more than 0.8, and 22.4% of timelines with a score of less than 0.5.<sep> As we noted, this difference seems to be explained by the absence of many events in the French corpus, as well as less important redundancy of information.<sep> The final goal of the project and the logical continuation of our work is to identify events corresponding to these important dates. This therefore involves taking into account the textual content of documents and passages associated with dates.<sep> The existing work on the similarity scores between sentences and thematic "centrality" should provide good indications on the most representative sentences of an event among those associated with a date.<sep> Another interesting direction in which we soon aim to work is to use categorisation techniques to determine if textual excerpts associated with a date really correspond to the same event. This should help to refine the detection of salient dates. As for the extraction of salient dates themselves, it could benefit from hybrid approaches using both efficient temporal analysis described in this article, and content-based techniques, closer to the field of multidocument automatic summarisation.<sep> Finally, as we have presented separate results for English and French, it will be interesting to study the possibility of combining information from the corpora of both languages for a multilingual extraction of salient dates.<sep> Acknowledgements<sep> This work has been partially funded by French National Research Agency (ANR) under project Chronolines (ANR-10-CORD-010).<sep> We would like to thank the French News Agency (AFP) for providing us with the corpus and their help in the evaluation.<sep> 2. www.dipity.com 3. http://lucene.apache.org<sep> 4. We call the core syntagm the non-recursive syntagm whose last constituent is the syntactic head of the syntagm.<sep> They correspond to the chunks of Abney (1991).<sep> 5. We call normalization the operation of turning a temporal expression into a formated, fully specified representation. 6. This figure was defined empirically.<sep> 7. For Salient Dates in English 8. We do not present runs where dates are ranked by the number of times they appear in retrieved sentences (occ), as we did for baselines, since results are systematically lower.<sep> 9. http://code.google.com/p/icsiboost/<sep> 10. “Arab revolt timeline for Morocco” , “Kyrgyzstan unrest timeline” , “Lebanon’s new government: a timeline” , “Libya timeline” . 11. MAP has no meaning here since the dates of the timelines are not ordered.
Unsupervised morphological analysis for Information Retrieval in the biomedical domain<sep> ABSTRACT<sep> In the biomedical field, using specialized terms is essential to access information.<sep> However, in many languages, these terms are complex morphological structures that complicate access to information.<sep> In this article, we are interested in identifying the morphological components of these terms and their use for an information retrieval task (IR).<sep> We propose different approaches based on an automatic alignment with a specific pivot language, Japanese, and on an analogical learning that allows an accurate morphological analysis of terms in a given language.<sep> These morphological analyses are then used to improve the indexing of biomedical documents.<sep> The experiments reported in this paper show the validity of this approach with a 10% improvement in MAP over a standard IR system.<sep> Keywords: Morphology, biomedical terminology, alignment, analogical learning, morphosemantic indexing, biomedical information retrieval.<sep> 1 Introduction<sep> In the biomedical domain, terminologies and their multiple uses are at the heart of many applications.<sep> They are used for structuring the knowledge as well as retrieving and formalizing information contained in domain documents.<sep> The most well-known example is probably the MeSH® (Medical Subject Headings) terminology (www.nlm.nih.gov/mesh) which was developed to index the articles of specialised journals in the PubMED®/MEDLINE® databases (www.pubmed.gov).<sep> The terms listed in these terminologies have very particular characteristics. In most Indo-European languages, biomedical terms are complex compositions of several constituents, often of Latin or Greek origin.<sep> This morphological complexity is an important point to take into account for basic operations like handling, understanding, translating or building semantic relationships between these terms, and furthermore for higher level applications like machine translation or, as we demonstrate in this paper, Information Retrieval (IR).<sep> In this paper, we investigate the development of morphological analysis techniques for biomedical terms and show how a biomedical Information Retrieval task can benefit from such resources.<sep> More precisely, we present several techniques aiming at breaking up a term into its morphological components, namely morphs[1] , while labeling these morphs with some semantic information.<sep> Unlike existing studies (Deléger et al., 2008; Markó et al., 2005a, for example) which are chiefly based on human expertise, our techniques use unsupervised approaches.<sep> The original idea at the heart of our approach is to use the multilingualism of existing terminological databases.<sep> We use Japanese as a pivot language, or more precisely terms written in Kanjis, to help decompose the terms of other languages into morphs and associate them with the corresponding Kanjis, in a fully automatic way.<sep> Thus, Kanjis play the role of a semantic representation for morphs.<sep> The main advantage of Kanjis in this respect is that Japanese terms can be seen as a concatenation of elementary independent words that may even be found in general language dictionaries.<sep> For example, the term photochemotherapy can be translated in Japanese by 光化学法; splitting and aligning these two terms gives: photo ↔ 光 (’light’), chemo ↔ 化学 (’chemistry’, ’medicine’), therapy ↔ 法 (’therapy’).<sep> As it is shown here, each morph is associated with Kanjis that may be used as descriptors more convenient to index a document than the term itself.<sep> In this article[2], we present an automatic technique to decompose and assign the Kanjis corresponding to these biomedical terms.<sep> This technique does not require any human intervention but relies on the availability of bilingual terminologies such as those contained in the UMLS.<sep> The morphological analysis, and the document indexing that it allows, thus relies on an alignment step between morphs and Kanjis.<sep> This alignment is performed with an original technique, suited to the biomedical domain and based on a Forward-Backward algorithm and on analogy learning.<sep> We then show that these correspondences between morphemes and kanji, once obtained automatically, can be exploited in different ways to improve the results of an IR system.<sep> The paper is structured as follows.<sep> After a review of the related studies in Section 2, we present the alignment technique and its results in Sections 3 and 4.<sep> Then, in Section 6, the use of the obtained morphological decompositions in an IR framework is explained.<sep> Before concluding, we detail in Section 6 the evaluations conducted on a biomedical IR test collection. 2. Scientific context<sep> 2.1 Related work<sep> Many studies have used morphology for terminological analysis.<sep> This is more particularly the case in the biomedical domain where terminologies are central to many applications and where terms are constructed by neo-classical composition. For example, we have terms like magnetoencephalography which can be decomposed into three morphemes: magneto/encephalo/graphy.<sep> The nature of the constituents involved (Iacobini, 1999; Dal and Amiot, 2008) and the rules governing these compositions (Dal and Amiot, 2008; Fradin, 2005) make them objects of particular study in linguistics.<sep> It is also the productive (many neologisms are thus constructed) and regular (the same rules and constituents are used in these neologisms) nature of this type of composition that makes it an important phenomenon to treat from an applicative point of view.<sep> There are a few computer databases containing morphological information (for example, for French the Biotop dictionary[3], and for English the Dorland’s dictionary[4]).<sep> However, their coverage is far from exhaustive, and the process of morphological analysis of a term from such lists remains a problem, even assuming the existence of more complete databases.<sep> The approach presented in this article is an original response to these two pitfalls.<sep> However, various morphological analyses can be compared to ours.<sep> One can distinguish two views of the use of morphology as a tool for term (or word) analysis.<sep> In the lexematic view, the form of the terms is exploited to build or discover the relations they maintain between them, but without necessarily resorting to their decomposition into morphs (Grabar and Zweigenbaum, 2002; Claveau and L’Homme, 2005; Hathout, 2009, for example).<sep> In contrast to this implicit use of morphology, the morphemic view chiefly relies on splitting the term into morphs as a first step.<sep> Many studies fall under this framework and can be distinguished according to their need for expertise.<sep> On the one hand, there are automatic techniques, which usually try to find recurrent letter patterns in word lists as morph-candidates (Creutz and Lagus, 2005; Kurimo et al., 2010, inter alia).<sep> However, such techniques cannot associate any semantic knowledge with the morphs discovered.<sep> There are also expert approaches, such as the work already mentioned by Namer (2007), Deléger et al. (2008) or Markó et al. (2005a), in which the morphs, their semantic information and their composition rules are provided either by an expert or by heuristics, which are also provided manually (Baud et al., 1999).<sep> Depending on their applicative purpose, these latter techniques are distinguished by their level of analysis, ranging from segmentation and labelling with interlingual identifiers (Markó et al., 2005a) to hierarchical decomposition and interpretation of the compound (Namer, 2007).<sep> To our knowledge, our approach is the first to make the most of an automatic approach while providing analysis elements that can be qualified as morphosemantic thanks to the information associated with each morpheme.<sep> The construction of terminological links from morphological analysis elements, as we propose in section 5, is also an area explored by several authors.<sep> These methods are distinguished by the use and type of expertise used.<sep> Thus, the relations between morphs can be directly defined by the expert (Namer and Zweigenbaum, 2004) and even typed;<sep> Namer (2007) defines for example relations of synonymy, hyponymy, meronymy and approximation based on the lexical relations defined in terminologies. However, the development cost and coverage of these approaches are rarely discussed and evaluated.<sep> Other approaches, based on supposedly lighter expertise, consist of using heuristic rules (Jacquemin, 1997; Daille, 2003).<sep> Learning approaches, including those based on formal analogies (see section 3.2), have made it possible to delegate this need for expertise to a selection of interesting examples (Krovetz, 1993; Grabar, 2004; Claveau and L’Homme, 2005), or even to do without it (Gaussier, 1999; Moreau et al., 2007; Hathout, 2009).<sep> From a more technical point of view, the use of a bilingual terminology also evokes studies in transliteration, particularly of Arabic or Katakana (Tsuji et al., 2002; Knight and Graehl, 1998, for example), or in translation.<sep> In this framework, Morin and Daille (2010) propose to map complex terms written in Kanjis with French ones, by using morphological rules.<sep> Yet, here again, these rules are to be given by an expert, and this study only concerns a special case of derivation.<sep> Moreover such an approach is not suitable for neo-classical compounds.<sep> In other studies, translation methods for biomedical terms have been proposed (Claveau, 2009; Harastani et al., 2012, inter alia).<sep> Even if the goal is different here, these approaches share similarities with ours: they consider the terms as sequences of letters and require alignments.<sep> In most cases, this is performed with 1-1 alignment algorithms (one character, possibly empty, of the source language word is aligned with one another character of the target language word), but in recent work about phonetization (Jiampojamarn et al., 2007), authors have shown that the interest of many-to-many alignment.<sep> Concerning the applicative aspect of this article, namely the use of morphological analysis in an information retrieval context, the literature is more abundant (Moreau and Sébillot, 2005, for a panorama).<sep> Although the results depend on numerous factors (language, morphological tool, size of collection, domain…), there is a broad consensus about the benefit of simple processes like stemming (or, rarer in IR, lemmatization): such tools are available in many languages, conceptually simple, and they usually improve the results of IR systems.<sep> It is noteworthy that the only morphological phenomena addressed by these tools are inflection and derivation.<sep> As they only perform simple operations on the prefix and suffix of the words, morphological composition remains out of their scope.<sep> Yet, many authors have noted the importance of tokenisation, i.e. the delimitation of indexing terms, in the biomedical field (Jiang and Zhai, 2007; Trieschnigg et al., 2007), highlighting the interest of considering morpheme-based tokenisation, but without proposing effective solutions.<sep> Recently, advanced morphological tools developed in the framework of MorphoChallenge have been applied to IR problems (Kurimo et al., 2009).<sep> Here again, the authors have observed an improvement for some languages, such as Finnish which is highly compositional, but results on English were significantly lower than when using a simple stemmer.<sep> In that respect, the good results presented in the next sections confirm the interest of our approach.<sep> 2.2. Motivations<sep> As it was previously explained in section 2.1, a large part of the work in automatic morphological processing is now done by looking for regularities in the structure of word forms, whether in context or not. When automatic approaches, that is, approaches not based on human expertise, are used, these words must then be in sufficient quantity for the detection of regularities to be statistically possible.<sep> These pragmatic approaches may seem far from morphological description theories, but they have the advantage of being resolutely based on data.<sep> They ensure, in particular, a compromise between the criteria of minimalism of the morphs (the decomposition is as fine as possible) and minimalism of the description (the collection of morphs used is as small as possible).<sep> This compromise being an instantiation of Occam’s razor or Minimum Description Length (MDL), the use of learning techniques (Mitchell, 1997) or compression is obvious.<sep> Of course, this same data-driven approach guides our work, but applied jointly to two languages.<sep> Since the decomposition of terms is possible in each of the languages considered, it is natural to try to match these decompositions.<sep> Furthermore, each of the languages offers a context to the other to guide its decomposition.<sep> Alignment appears to be a simple solution for carrying out this joint decomposition by exploiting this last point.<sep> Finally, our approach is therefore in the same logic as the automatic decomposition work from a list of words, but by extending the reasoning to pairs of words, with, in this case, one of the words serving as a pivot.<sep> The alignment described in the following section seeks to produce decompositions into morphs and kanji with the same aims of minimality of decompositions and descriptions.<sep> It is also important to note that the choice of Kanjis as pivot is not fortuitous.<sep> Kanji is one of three sets of characters used in Japanese.<sep> They are borrowed from Chinese – they are also called sinograms – and are particularly used in scientific fields.<sep> Unlike hiragana and katakana, the other two character sets of Japanese, kanji do not form a syllabary but a so-called semantic writing system, hence their very large number: around 2,000 kanji, called official, are learned in the Japanese school curriculum, but many others among the 50,000 to 60,000 existing sinograms are used, particularly in specialized fields.<sep> Kanjis can be pictograms, associating a concept with an image (schematic and sometimes difficult to interpret) for example 血 (blood), representing a sacrificial chalice receiving blood[5].<sep> They can also be ideograms, more complex characters composed of several elements, for example 炎 (flame, inflammation), composed of two times 火 (fire).<sep> They can also be phono-semantic compounds, with one component taking a kanji from a phonologically close word (even of a different meaning) and the other component specifying its meaning here.<sep> However, in our work, kanji, even if they are etymologically composed, are considered as a single unit.<sep> Using Japanese terms as pivots offers several advantages for our problem.<sep> In the medical field, these terms are often written in kanji and consist of the juxtaposition of several kanji.<sep> Their form is invariable whatever their position in the term and whatever their neighboring kanjis.<sep> It should be noted, however, that the minimum unit of interpretation is not necessarily composed of a single kanji, some words are composed of several kanjis that cannot be interpreted independently, as in 茉莉 (jasmine).<sep> Kanjis are independent of the Greek and Latin roots used in most European languages.<sep> In our alignment process presented below, this prevents the detection of fortuitous regularities based on common etymology.<sep> Furthermore, a segment of a Kanji term is most of the time a valid Kanji term by itself (to the contrary of morphs).<sep> It is thus possible in theory to use dictionaries to access their meaning.<sep> Finally, Japanese terms have few kanji (a term is typically composed of one to six kanji) compared to the letters of terms in the Latin alphabet (many terms exceed twenty characters).<sep> It is therefore necessary to test only a few combinations during their segmentation, which reduces the computational cost of the alignment (see next section).<sep> These different reasons make Kanji-based Japanese a very good pivot when compared to other languages available in the multilingual terminologies we use.<sep> On the other hand, the implementation of our approach makes a strong assumption of parallelism: the term in kanjis must be constructed in an order identical to that of the constituents of the terms in the studied language.<sep> This hypothesis may seem unrealistic, but the results presented in the following sections show that it is reasonable in our data.<sep> Some explanations are provided in the discussion of the results (section 4.2).<sep> Assuming this hypothesis, the use of an alignment technique without distortion (which does not manage a change in the order of the elements to be aligned) such as the one presented in the following section is sufficient.<sep> It should be noted that other alignment techniques that manage distortion, for example those derived from statistical translation, would still allow the same morphological analysis approach to be used if this hypothesis were not validated, but at the cost of a higher computational cost, and certainly lower quality.<sep> 3. Alignment and analogy for alignment<sep> As we explained earlier, our morphological decomposition technique is based on aligning the terms with their translation in the pivot language (Japanese in kanjis).<sep> All that is provided is a list of terms with their translation in kanjis, without any other pre-processing, and it is the result of the alignment algorithm that will provide both the segmentation into morphemes and the assignment of kanjis to the corresponding morphemes.<sep> Our alignment technique is mainly based on an Expectation-Maximization (EM) algorithm that we briefly present in the next sub-section (Jiampojamarn et al., 2007, for more details and examples of its use).<sep> The second sub-section explains the modification made to this standard algorithm so that it can naturally and automatically handle morphological variation, which is a phenomenon inherent to our morph splitting problem.<sep> 3.1 EM Alignment<sep> The alignment algorithm at the heart of our approach is standard: it is a Baum-Welch algorithm, extended to map symbol sub-sequences and not only 1-1 alignments.<sep> In our case, it takes as input French terms (or English or other) and their Kanji translations, taken from a multilingual terminology for instance.<sep> The principle of this iterative algorithm is to alternate between two operations: the first one calculates a score table indicating the weight of each possible alignment, based on the probability of this alignment in each pair considered (see example below), and the second one estimates the alignment probabilities based on the score table.<sep> More formally, these two steps are detailed in Algorithm 1: for each term pair ( x[T] , y[V] ) to be aligned (T and V being the lengths of the terms in kanjis and letters), the EM algorithm alternates between the two previous steps.<sep> In the Expectation step, it first counts the number of occurrences of all possible alignments between sub-sequences of Kanjis and letters (the maximum lengths of the sub-sequences of letters and Kanjis considered for the alignment are respectively set by maxX and maxY).<sep> These counts are stored in table γ , and are then used to estimate the alignment probabilities in table δ ( Maximization step).<sep> The Expectation step relies on a forward-backward approach (Algorithm 2): it computes the forward probabilities α and backward probabilities β .<sep> Its principle is illustrated in figure 1: it consists of estimating the weight of each possible alignment (here 学療 /himiot) according to its probability (δ) but also the probability in the pair of arriving at this alignment (by all possible cuts) – this is α –, and the probability of starting from this alignment – this is β.<sep> This weight is then used to update the γ accounts for this particular alignment and will be used in the next iteration.<sep> More precisely, for each position t, v in the terms, αt,v is the sum of the probabilities of all the possible alignments of ( x[t] 1 [, y] 1 [v]), that is, from the beginning of the terms to the current position, according to the current alignment probabilities in δ (cf. Algorithm 4).<sep> βt,v is computed in a similar way by considering ( x[T] t[, y] v[V] ).<sep> These probabilities are then used to re-estimate the counts in [γ] .<sep> In this version of the EM algorithm, the Maximization (Algorithm 3) simply consists in computing the δ alignment probabilities by normalizing the counts in γ .<sep> Illustration of the forward-backward step for the alignment 学療 /himiot<sep> Algorithm 1 EM<sep> Algorithm 2 Expectation<sep> Algorithm 2 Forward-many2many<sep> The EM process is repeated until the probabilities δ are stable.<sep> When the convergence is reached (Gupta and Chen, 2010, for a discussion on the convergence properties of algorithms of this type), the alignment simply consists in finding, for each pair, the correspondences that maximize αT,V (see figure 2).<sep> In addition to this resulting alignment, we also store the final alignment probabilities δ , which are used to split unseen terms (cf. Section 6.2).<sep> This technique is not fundamentally different from the ones widely used in statistical translation.<sep> Yet, some particularities are worth noting: this approach allows us to handle fertility , that is the capacity to align from or to empty substrings (for lack of space, it does not appear in the above simplified version); conversely, distortion , that is reordering of morphs, cannot be handled easily without major changes in this algorithm.<sep> 3.2 Automatic morphological normalisation<sep> As we have seen, the maximization step is used to calculate the translation probability of a Kanji sequence into a letter sequence.<sep> For example, for the Kanji 菌 (’ bacteria ’), there may exist one entry in δ associating it with bactérie, one with bactério (as in bactério/lyse) and another one with bactéri (in myco/bactéri/ose), each with a certain probability.<sep> This dispersion of probabilities, which is of course harmful for the algorithm, is caused by morphemic variation: bactério, bactérie, and bactéri are 3 morphs of the same morpheme, and we would like their probabilities to reinforce each other.<sep> The adaptation we propose aims at solving this problem by allowing the maximization phase to automatically group the different morphs belonging to a same morpheme.<sep> To achieve this goal, we use a simple but well suited technique relying on formal analogical calculus.<sep> 3.2.1. Analogy between morphs<sep> An analogy is a relation between 4 elements that we note: a : b :: c : d which can be read a is for b what c is for d (Lepage, 2000, for more details about analogies).<sep> Analogies have been used in many NLP studies, especially for translation of sentences (Lepage, 2000) or terms (Langlais and Patry, 2007; Langlais et al., 2008).<sep> Analogies are also a key component in the previously mentioned work on terminology structuring (Claveau and L’Homme, 2005) or (Hathout, 2009), from which we draw inspiration to formalize our problem. The original idea we wish to implement is to apply this standard tool of morphology not at the word-form level, as in lexical morphology, but at the morph level.<sep> In our framework, one possible analogy may be: dermato : dermo :: hémato : hémo.<sep> Knowing that dermato and dermo belong to a same morpheme, one can infer that this is the case for hémato and hémo.<sep> Such an analogy, build on the graphemic representation of words, is said a formal analogy.<sep> According to Stroppa and Yvon (2005), formal analogies can be defined in terms of factorizations.<sep> Let us note [←−] ⊕ the (non-commutative) concatenation operator at the right ( abc[←−] ⊕ d = abcd ), and [←−] ⊖ its associated string subtraction operator ( abc[←−] ⊕ d[←−] ⊖ d = abc[←−] ⊖ c[←−] ⊕ c = abc ), and similarly for [−→] ⊕ and [−→] ⊖ operating at the left of the first argument.<sep> Let a be a string (a term in our case) over an alphabet Σ, a factorization of a , noted fa , is a sequence of n factors fa = ( fa[1] [, …, f] a[ n]), such that a = [ f] a[ 1] ←−⊕ fa[2] ←−⊕ …[←−] ⊕ fa[n].<sep> An analogy<sep> Definition 1 ∀ ( a, b, c, d ) ∈ Σ , [ a : b :: c : d ] there exist factorizations ( fa, fb, fc, fd ) ∈ (Σ [∗][n] )[4] of ( a, b, c, d ) such that, ∀i ∈ [1 , n ] , ( fb[i][, f] c[ i][)] [ ∈] {( fa[i][, f] d[ i][)] [,] [ (] [f] d[ i][, f] a[ i][)] }.<sep> The smallest n for which this definition holds is called the degree of the analogy.<sep> For most Indo-European languages, such as French and English, the interactions between the morphemes that make up a term are mostly likely to modify the prefixes and suffixes.<sep> Thus, we are looking for formal analogies of degree at most 3 (ie, 3 factors: prefix ⊕ base ⊕ suffix).<sep> In practice, to check if four morphemes are in analogy, we construct a rule of rewriting between one of the two pairs of morphemes (for example dermatodermo) and check if it applies to the other pair (hémato-hémo). This rule involves three factors;<sep> The base is considered as the longest common sub-string (lcss) between the 2 words.<sep> So, to go from dermato to dermo, you have to remove the ato base and add o.<sep> The rule is therefore: r = lcss(morph1,morph2) [←−] ⊖ ato [←−] ⊕ o.<sep> This rule makes it possible to rewrite dermato into dermo and hémato into hémo; thus, hémato,hémo is in analogy with dermato,dermo.<sep> 3.2.2 Normalization by analogy<sep> In practice, for our problem, we need examples (like dermato and dermo previously) to use analogies to group the morphs into morphemes.<sep> To get around this problem, we use a simple bootstrapping technique: if two morphs are stored in γ as possible translations of the same Kanji sequence, and if these two morphs share a sub-string longer than a certain threshold, then we assume that they both belong to the same morpheme.<sep> For example, it is observed that among the morphs aligned at the pharyngo and pharynx share a long common sub-chain;<sep> We assume that these are two morphs of the same morpheme. From these bootstrap pairs, we build the prefixation and suffixation rules allowing us to group other pairs of morphs.<sep> The more a rule is found, the more certain it will be.<sep> Therefore, we keep all the analogical rules generated at each iteration along with their number of occurrence, and we only apply the most frequently found ones. (Unlike the beginnings, these rules can then be applied to very short morphemes).<sep> The whole process is thus completely automatic.<sep> This new Maximization step, including this morphemic normalization, is summarized in Algorithm 5.<sep> It ensures that all the morphs supposed to belong to the same morpheme have equal and reinforced alignment probabilities.<sep> Algorithm 5 Maximization with morphemic normalization<sep> 4. Validation expérimentale<sep> 5.1 Evaluation Data<sep> The data used in the experiments presented below come from the UMLS MetaThesaurus (Tuttle et al., 1990).<sep> The MetaThesaurus groups several terminologies for several languages and associates to each term a concept identifier (CUI).<sep> The CUI are language independent and thus make it easy to build lists of terms in the studied language associated with their Japanese equivalents.<sep> In this paper, we present results for two languages, English and French.<sep> In both cases, we only considered Japanese terms composed of Kanjis, and only simple (one-word) French or English terms.<sep> About 14,000 English-Kanjis pairs and 8,000 French-Kanjis ones are formed this way.<sep> An ending mark (’;’) is added to each French or English term.<sep> We randomly selected about 1,000 pairs for French and 500 for English in order to evaluate the performance of our alignment technique.<sep> These pairs have been aligned manually (by the author with the help of Japanese speakers) and serve as a gold standard.<sep> The different versions of the alignment algorithm were therefore launched on the training pairs.<sep> At convergence, the algorithm produces the most probable alignment between each term and its translation in kanjis, accompanied by the probability (extract in English in figure 2).<sep> We also retrieve the probability table δ (extracted in figure 3) and the analogical rewrite rules of the last iteration.<sep> Figure 2.<sep> From alignments produced for English by the EM algorithm with morphemic normalization<sep> Figure 3.<sep> From the probability table δ produced for English at the last iteration of the EM algorithm with morphemic normalization<sep> 5.2 Alignment results<sep> In the experiments presented below, the performance is evaluated in terms of precision: an alignment is counted as correct only if all the components of the pair are correctly aligned (thus, it is equivalent to the sentence error rate in standard machine translation).<sep> For each pair, the EM algorithm indicates the probability of the proposed alignment.<sep> Therefore, it is possible to only consider alignments having a probability greater than a given threshold.<sep> By varying this threshold, we can compute a precision according to the number of terms aligned.<sep> Figures 4 and 5 respectively present the results obtained for French and English.<sep> We indicate the performance of the EM algorithm with and without morphemic normalization.<sep> For comparison purposes, we also report the results of GIZA++ (Och and Ney, 2003), a reference alignment tool in the field of machine translation.<sep> The different IBM models and sets of parameters available in giza++ were tested; the results reported are the best ones (obtained with IBM model 4 without distortion).<sep> As expected, the interest of the morphemic normalization appears clearly in these two experiments; in the worst case (that is, when all the terms are kept for alignment), it yields a 70% precision for French and 80% for English.<sep> This corresponds to a 10% improvement whatever the number of aligned pairs considered.<sep> It should be noted that normalization also has another interest in terms of complexity since it reduces the number of iterations needed to reach the convergence of the EM algorithm.<sep> Figure 5. Precision of English-Kanji alignment according to the number of test pairs aligned Figure 6. Precision of French alignment according to the number of examples<sep> To study the impact of the size of the learning set of our approach, we present in figure 6 the precision as a function of the number of pairs used for French.<sep> The rapid increase in performance illustrates the importance of examples to cover most of the morphs used.<sep> The subsequent, slower but continuous increase is also due to the addition of new components, but also to the importance of the redundancy of the morphs and kanjis, even those already encountered, so that the algorithm can estimate their alignment probability as accurately as possible.<sep> 4.3. Comparison with other approaches<sep> In addition to the previous experiments, we are interested in this subsection in comparing our approach with two emblematic tools in the field: Morfessor[7] (Creutz and Lagus, 2005) and DeriF[8] (Namer, 2007).<sep> This comparison is based solely on the segmentation capabilities of these tools, i.e. the morphological segmentation.<sep> Indeed, this task is the only one performed by Morfessor, and the comparison of the semantic information of DeriF with that provided by our kanjis is difficult to evaluate.<sep> We therefore measure the accuracy of these tools on this segmentation task using the ground truth of the previous experiment.<sep> Morfessor is a tool that belongs to the class of tools based on the MDL principle for detecting letter sequences that can form morphological components within a list of words.<sep> The size of the list provided can be an important parameter for the quality of the results;<sep> We therefore vary it to observe the evolution of the tool’s performance (from a list of 13,000 simple French terms collected in the UMLS).<sep> DeriF, on the other hand, relies on human expertise, and the segmentations evaluated are those directly produced by the tool in its current version.<sep> These hierarchical segmentations are flattened here for comparison.<sep> We also perform some normalization operations in order not to penalize it because of certain choices concerning the suffixes (DeriF proposes a suffix ie in acr/odyn/ie) different from those induced by our approach (odynie is considered as a realization of the morpheme odyn- if it does not induce a different sense attested by a difference in kanjis).<sep> Figure 7 shows the accuracy of the three systems, according to the number of words (for Morfessor) and the number of word pairs (for our system).<sep> There is no surprise in the same learning curve shape for our approach as before, with a quite high accuracy from the beginning, and a maximum accuracy of 80.5%.<sep> Of course, these results are directly correlated to those of alignment.<sep> Morfessor results are, on the other hand, relatively constant with respect to the number of examples.<sep> An examination of the errors explains this a priori surprising result and reveals a tendency to over-segment on the basis of a few fortuitous similarities between words.<sep> Our approach, with the same number of examples, offers much better results, but it has more information through the translations in kanjis.<sep> The DeriF system gives results close to ours on this segmentation task.<sep> Its errors are mainly due to a lack of segmentation, which may be explained by the presence of unknown morphes (e.g. ameloblastoma, athetosis, micrognathism, sparganosis, serositis are not segmented), or particular morph configurations (argyria, cholangitis, angiocholitis).<sep> In rarer cases, it is a matter of segmentation errors (incorrectly recognised morpheme; e.g. ré/tinoblastome).<sep> The absence of segmentation or partial segmentation are also the main errors of our approach, caused by rare morphs and kanjis.<sep> However, the importance of these errors decreases as the training data increases.<sep> Overall, DeriF and our approach agree on 70.5% of the segmentations, and more than 80% of the correct segmentations of one are found by the other.<sep> Figure 7: Precision of French segmentation according to the number of examples. The comparison of the semantic representations between DeriF and our approach is difficult to measure quantitatively.<sep> On the one hand, DeriF offers a hierarchical segmentation that our system is not capable of producing.<sep> On the other hand, the semantic information provided by DeriF is quite general and sometimes missing, while the information provided by kanjis is specific to the term.<sep> This shows the potential complementarity of the systems: our approach could provide DeriF with more appropriate semantic information in certain cases and reinforce its coverage, while benefiting from DeriF’s hierarchical segmentation, as shown in Table 1.<sep> 4.4. Discussion of results and return on hypotheses<sep> A manual examination of the results shows that most of the errors are caused by the falsification of our hypothesis: some French-Japanese pairs or English-Japanese pairs cannot be decomposed in a similar way.<sep> For example, the French term anxiolytiques (anxiolytics) is translated by a sequence of Kanjis meaning literally ’drugs for depression’.<sep> Among these errors, some pairs imply terms that are not compounds in French, Japanese or both (eg. méninges (meninges) is translated by 脳膜 which literally means ’brain membrane’).<sep> These problems then lead to decompositions that are not minimal (two morphs are not separated) or even completely wrong.<sep> Other errors are caused by a lack of training data: some morphs or sequences only appear once, or only combined with another morph, which mislead the segmentation.<sep> Examples of analyses produced by DeriF that can benefit from our approach<sep> But beyond these few errors, it is interesting to note that the hypothesis of parallelism in the construction of terms is mostly confirmed.<sep> If the principle of detecting regularities corresponding in both languages is not in doubt (see Section 2.2), the fact that the order of the morphemes and kanji is identical may seem more surprising.<sep> This can nevertheless be explained by two elements.<sep> On the one hand, although the order of words in Japanese grammar is often described as partly free (the roles of words can be marked by means of particles that are attached to them), a basic principle is to indicate the attributes of an object before the object, the actants before the predicate that marks the action, and, in general, the regent element before its regent (Nakamura-Delloye, 2007, for a didactic and well-supported presentation).<sep> Such an order is reflected in the structure of many Japanese biomedical terms (Dal and Amiot, 2008; Namer, 2007), for which this order is indeed a mark of neoclassical composition[9]. On the other hand, a more pragmatic explanation may lie in the way Japanese terminologies used in the UMLS were constructed.<sep> For example, the Japanese Medical Abstracts Society (JAMAS, www.jamas.gr.jp) states that it has built the Thesaurus for Medical and Health Related Terms, used in the UMLS, based on the English MeSH.<sep> Its developers indicate that they only used terms appearing in articles published in Japanese (Onogi et al., 2004), but it is not impossible that the search for an equivalent introduced a bias in the choice of Japanese terms, favouring those with structures close to English terms.<sep> It is also interesting to observe the behaviour of the method on terms whose composition does not involve only non-autonomous constituents (in the syntactic sense) with a referential meaning of Greek or Latin origin.<sep> This Greek-Latin origin of the components, combined with the fact that they exist autonomously or not, is a controversial condition for defining neoclassical composition (Dal and Amiot, 2008, for a full discussion).<sep> Of course, these considerations have no impact on our approach, the origin and the status of syntactic autonomy not being criteria intervening in the decomposition.<sep> Thus, dietotherapy, an example of compounds whose status is discussed, is regularly aligned with 食事 ’meal, diet’ and 療法 ’therapy’.<sep> Furthermore, some terms are also based on other morphological operations such as derivation.<sep> For example, the prefixation by re- in the English term reintubation is not a neoclassical compound.<sep> Again, this distinction has no bearing on the approach.<sep> Indeed, these constituents will be considered as the others and possibly aligned with the corresponding kanjis (re- is thus aligned most often with 再 'again, repeated'). Moreover, these alignments make it possible to highlight the contextual meaning of these constituents (Corbin, 2001).<sep> Thus, the English term dehydration is translated as 脱水 ’to remove’ ’water’, while de- in dehumanization is translated as 非 ’not’ (humanized), in deceleration it is translated as 減 ’less’ (speed), in decerebration it is translated as 除 ’to eliminate’ (the brain)…<sep> Even if these considerations are beyond the scope of this article, the parallel drawn with Japanese could, once again, guide a linguistic analysis of these phenomena based on real data.<sep> Note also that certain suffixes specific to medical vocabulary (e.g. -ite, -ose in French) are naturally considered in the same way as the other components and regularly aligned with the kanji corresponding to the meaning conveyed (inflammation, disease, etc.).<sep> This is in line with Namer’s analysis (2007), which seeks to integrate them into what she calls training elements under an exceptional status.<sep> In contrast, in the UMLS, inflectional and some derivational variations are classified under the same concept identifier. Therefore, it is not possible to show differences in analysis for conversion cases, such as between reintubation and reintubate, both translated as 再挿管.<sep> Other cases of derivation, leading to conceptual differences that are sufficiently important to be referenced in the UMLS under different CUIs, are nevertheless observable.<sep> Again, for our approach, these cases are treated as for neoclassical composition and the aligned kanjis provide the necessary information for segmentation and interpretation.<sep> We have thus dent/ 歯 , dentition/ 歯列 (’dent’ ’rangée’), dentiste/ 歯科医師 (’dent’ ’spécialiste’), and also odontologie/ 歯学 (’dent’ ’science’).<sep> 4.5. Translation and segmentation of unknown terms. Our alignment technique can be used as a first step to translate an unknown term (absent from the data used to train the alignment algorithm), based on its potentially known morphological components. The translation of terms has already been the subject of several works, mainly to remedy the so-called out-of-vocabulary errors during the tasks of artificial text translation.<sep> Many of these works seek translations in textual resources: parallel or comparable corpora (Chiao and Zweigenbaum, 2002; Fung and Yee, 1998), the Web (Lu et al., 2005).<sep> Some authors have looked at the same problem but without any other data than the pairs of terms, relying on the similarities (cognates) from one language to another (Schulz et al., 2004, for example), or on the similarities of the operations that allow to move from one language to another (Langlais and Patry, 2008; Claveau, 2009; Harastani et al., 2012). Of course, it is in the context of these latter works that we are situated. In the experiment reported here, we translate French terms into Japanese.<sep> In practice, we use the probabilities δ to generate a translation.<sep> The implementation we use here is very simple: the translation probabilities of the morphs in δ are exploited in a Viterbi-like algorithm;<sep> We do not use a language model. This translation process has another very interesting advantage: it produces the alignment of the term of the source language with its translation.<sep> The term is therefore segmented into morphemes, and the morphemes are labelled with the corresponding kanji.<sep> This produces a morphosemantic decomposition of the unknown term.<sep> For the purposes of this experiment, 128 terms and their kanji translations were randomly selected to make up our test set (they have of course been removed from the data feeding our alignment algorithm).<sep> These French terms are then translated using the alignment probabilities δ and compared to the reference.<sep> Table 2: Results (percentage accuracy) of the translation of unknown terms according to a strict reference (UMLS) and a broad reference (Web)<sep> The results of this small experiment are presented in Table 2.<sep> Of 128 terms, 58 were translated (and segmented) correctly, which is an accuracy of 45%.<sep> There are two types of errors: 34 terms have been given a wrong translation, and for the remaining 36, no decomposed translation was found.<sep> Looking at these, it is not surprising to find terms that are not scientific compounds, or compounds where one or more of the constituents do not appear in the training data.<sep> The accuracy measured on the translated terms alone is therefore 63%, which seems very encouraging given the simplicity of our implementation.<sep> Another interesting point is that a manual review of the results shows that for some cases marked as errors, the first translations proposed are often correct paraphrases, not attested in the UMLS but attested on the Web in Japanese institutional sites (government, universities, etc.) or hosted documents (PDF) in the biomedical field.<sep> With this broader reference, controlled by a Japanese speaker, the translation accuracy (and breakdown) reaches 89%.<sep> 5. Morpho-semantic analysis for Information Retrieval<sep> As it was previously said, biomedical Information Retrieval (IR) has some important characteristics due to the use of specialized terms.<sep> In that respect, taking into account rich morphological information has already been proved useful, but only with hand-crafted resources (Markó et al., 2005b).<sep> In addition to the intrinsic evaluations of our approach presented in the previous section, we evaluate its interest in a task of information retrieval on a large collection of biomedical documents in English.<sep> More specifically, we show how to take advantage of all the information produced by alignment and in what form it can then be exploited to index documents.<sep> 6.1 Morpho-semantic graphs<sep> Once all the terms are aligned, one can study the recurrent correspondences between English morphs and Kanjis.<sep> The more a morph is aligned with a sequence of Kanjis, the more they are ’semantically’ related.<sep> All these links can be represented as a graph: the vertices represent Kanjis and morphemes (i.e a set of morphs grouped during the analogical step of the alignment), and the edges are weighted according to the number of times that a particular morpheme is aligned with a Kanji sequence among the 14,000 training pairs from the umls.<sep> Figure 3 shows a toy example of such a graph.<sep> The thickness of the arches is proportional to the associated weight.<sep> This representation allows us to shed light on types of semantic relations between the morphemes.<sep> To do this, we explore the neighborhood of each morpheme by following the arcs and taking into account the weights associated with these links (in a similar way to the Folk-Fulkerson algorithm (Heineman et al., 2008); this amounts to giving each node a certain amount of energy which it distributes to its neighbors proportionally to the strength of the link that unites them, which in turn distribute it, etc.).<sep> Figure 9 presents the kanjis (manually translated), in the form of a word cloud (the size and color represent the energy reaching this node) for the morpheme represented by ome; (suffix for 'tumor'). Figure 8. Morphosemantic graph morpheme-kanji<sep> Figure 9. Kanji cloud for ome;<sep> Figure 10 shows the morphemes found in the vicinity of the same morpheme ome;. The reached nodes are considered to be conceptually close and are expected to highlight synonym or quasi-synonym morphemes of the suffix ome.<sep> It is interesting to note that other related suffixes are found, but also morphemes more commonly used as prefixes like onco.<sep> The alignment and the segmentation produced by our algorithm also make it possible to study the co-occurrences of morphemes.<sep> One can study first-order affinities (which morphemes are frequently associated with other morphemes) and, more interestingly, second order affinities (morphemes sharing the same co-occurring morphemes).<sep> These second-order affinities must allow us to group morphemes sharing a certain semantic proximity.<sep> We hope to capture relationships such as those defined manually by Namer and Baud (2007): synonymy or quasi-synonymy, cohyponymy, and proximity (physical, functional or procedural).<sep> For instance, the tag cloud in Figure 11 groups morphemes close to gastro (morpheme for stomach) according to this second order affinity.<sep> Most of these neighbours designate organs, and it is even interesting to note that the organs anatomically closest are the most related.<sep> Figure 10. First-order affinity cloud of the French morpheme ome;<sep> Figure 11. Second-order affinity cloud of the French morpheme gastro<sep> This information of different natures makes it possible to identify relationships between terms, or build synonyms, or explore the termbase using these morphological elements.<sep> However, to our knowledge, no comparable and sufficiently complete morpho-semantic resources are available to allow a direct evaluation of our results.<sep> In the remaining of this paper, we propose an indirect evaluation through an information retrieval task in which we try to exploit these morphological information as much as possible.<sep> 6.2 Morphemic representation for Information Retrieval<sep> In order to integrate the morphological information in an IR system, we adopt a simple indexing representation: the documents are considered as bags-of-words and morphemes.<sep> The morphemes are those obtained by decomposing biomedical terms, and for some systems those associated to the former ones as second order affinities.<sep> The goal of these experiments is of course to use morphological information to be able to return a document containing gastrodynia to a query containing stomachalgia.<sep> During the indexing phase, terms are decomposed.<sep> Two cases may occur: the term is either known as it appears in the alignment pairs, or it is unknown.<sep> In the first case, we simply use the decomposition produced by the alignment algorithm.<sep> In the second case, we try to decompose it according to the principle explained in section 4.5.<sep> In these two cases, another alignment product is also used: the analogical rewriting rules collected at the last alignment iteration.<sep> They allow us to detect the morphs belonging to a same morpheme.<sep> Such information makes it possible to match a query containing hemo with a document containing haemo, hemato or even emia;.<sep> A baseline system and four indexing systems using the morphological information are proposed.<sep> They all rely on a standard IR approach, namely a vector space model with an Okapi BM25 weighting scheme (Robertson et al., 1998, for details, see) and a tokenizer similar to Terrier’s one (Ounis et al., 2006); the standard values of the BM25 parameters b , k 1, k 3 have been kept.<sep> This system was used in particular in the context of the filtering task for which we use the data (see below where it gave the best results (Robertson and Hull, 2000).<sep> The baseline system performs a standard indexing of the documents with a Porter stemming (Porter, 1980).<sep> The other systems are as follows.<sep> 1 – The first system using morphological information that we propose is based on morphemes.<sep> It simply considers the morphemes produced by the decomposition of the words in the documents (and queries) as words to index (the original terms are no longer used for indexing, only its morphemes).<sep> The morpheme weights take the decomposition probability into account; it is defined as the product of this probability and the BM-25 weight.<sep> 2 – The second system is Kanji-based.<sep> Here again, the terms of the documents are decomposed, and the closest Kanjis are used as indexing words.<sep> These Kanjis are those identified in the neighborhood of the morphs produced when decomposing the terms (see Section 6.1).<sep> 3 – The third system adopts the same morpheme-based representation as the first system, but expands the queries with first-order affinities of its morphemes.<sep> The morphemes used as expansion are weighted according to their proximity in the graph and the weight of the morphemes that they expand.<sep> 4 – The last system is similar to the third one but uses the second-order affinities to expand the queries.<sep> 6. Biomedical IR experiments<sep> This section presents the experimental context and the results obtained by the systems described in the previous section.<sep> The aim of these experiments is to characterize the gain that can be expected from such a morphological component for an IR system dedicated to the biomedical field.<sep> 7.1 Experimental setting<sep> For the following experiments, we use the dataset built for the filtering track of the TREC-9 conference.<sep> This game is itself based on the OHSUMED collection, which is composed of about 350,000 medline abstracts.<sep> In addition to this, about 4,000 queries and the corresponding relevance judgments were developed for TREC-9.<sep> The queries are composed of several fields: the subject, which a MeSH term, and a definition of this term.<sep> We use this collection as a standard IR collection, and only consider the subject field as the query.<sep> 6.2 Results<sep> Figure 12 summarises the results of all the systems in terms of mean average precision (MAP).<sep> For comparison purposes, we also indicate the results obtained by our reference system (see section 5.2) and by three biomedical IR systems proposed by Dinh and Tamine (2010): their own reference system also based on Okapi (but without stemming), noted Dinh 0, and two systems implementing strategies for disambiguating medical concepts (Dinh 1 and Dinh 2).<sep> These results were obtained under the same experimental conditions as ours, but on a subset of 48 queries.<sep> Figure 12. Mean precision of different IR systems on the OHSUMED/TREC-9 collection<sep> Table 3. Performance of morpheme-based and kanji-based systems on the OHSUMED collection, with TREC queries<sep> Table 3 presents the results of the baseline IR system and the two systems based on morphological decomposition (systems 1 and 2, see section 5.2).<sep> In addition to the MAP, the performance is evaluated using the standard IR evaluation measures: we compute precision on top 5, 10… 1,000 documents (P@x), mean average precision (MAP), interpolated average precision (IAP) and the R-precision (R-prec).<sep> In order to assess if the between the two systems are statistically significant, we run a Wilcoxon test ( p = 0 . 05) (Hull, 1993); those differences with the baseline that are not judged statistically significant are italicized.<sep> The morpheme-based system, only relying on decomposing term and grouping its morph into morpheme, yields very good results with a 13% MAP gain.<sep> As expected, decomposing the terms improves more specifically the performance at the end of the retrieved document list (P@100 and higher), since it makes it possible to retrieve relevant documents even though they do not contain the exact terms of the queries.<sep> The Kanji-based system yields very similar results, which confirms the equivalence in terms of the semantic representation of morphemes and Kanji.<sep> This result, a little disappointing, can be explained by two points.<sep> In practice, in some queries, the Kanjis are too generic to capture the specific meaning expected or bring no additional information compared with the original morphemes.<sep> Moreover, no selection is performed on the morpheme to be translated into Kanjis, and some Kanjis have properties (document frequencies) that highly differ from the source morpheme since they can be associated with other morphemes.<sep> A more in-depth study of this phenomenon that would lead to a weighting scheme adapted to these cases is an important avenue to explore for using this indexing based on kanjis.<sep> Table 4. Performance of systems with query expansion on the OHSUMED collection, with TREC queries<sep> Table 4 presents the results of the two last systems, based on query expansion (systems 3 and 4, see section 5.2).<sep> The two systems have very contrasted results.<sep> Indeed, the extension with first-order affinities gives good results, much better than the reference. The precision is slightly lower than system 1, but its recall is significantly better thanks to the documents brought back by the morphemes extending the query.<sep> On the other hand, second-order affinities clearly degrade the performance.<sep> The affinities added to the query, most of the time, break the specificity of the information asked initially, which makes the system retrieve documents on related subjects but not sufficiently pertinent to the query.<sep> This negative result of extension with more distant links is nevertheless important.<sep> Their importance in biomedical IR has indeed been the subject of several unproven assumptions: Namer (2007) indicates that cohyponymy and comernymy links are useful in IR, but Namer and Baud (2007) assume the opposite.<sep> It should also be noted that this finding is similar to those reported for general language (Voorhees, 1998).<sep> 7. Conclusion and perspectives<sep> In this work, the original idea of making the most of the multilingual aspect of biomedical terminologies, and in particular of Japanese as a pivot language, allows for a fine morphological analysis of terms. This analysis opens up many opportunities for intelligent manipulation of terms based on their morphological components.<sep> To do this, we have shown that a simple sequence alignment technique is sufficient, but that it can benefit from several more fine-tuned adaptations to the task at hand. We have shown, on the one hand, the interest of taking into account morphemic variation during the alignment process, thanks to analogy learning.<sep> The high quality results obtained allow us to address IR problems caused by the morphological complexity of the biomedical terminology that could not be addressed with usual IR tools like stemmers.<sep> In this respect, our concerns about the role of morphology to access information are similar to existing studies (Markó et al., 2005a; Deléger et al., 2008), but to our knowledge, we are the first to propose an automatic process, directly available for many languages.<sep> Of course, our approach chiefly relies on the existence of the UMLS, a group of multilingual terminologies containing kanji terms.<sep> Many perspectives are opened by this work, whether it is direct improvements or works in the long term.<sep> First, from a technical point of view, it would be interesting to consider more complex segmentations than the linear ones we implemented.<sep> Indeed, the syntactic properties of the Kanjis (some of them expect an agent or object), could help to better structure the different morphemes.<sep> Morphosemantic analysis, as we perform it in section 5.1, could also be based on the semantic relations between Kanjis that can be found in general Japanese dictionaries.<sep> Concerning the aspects discussed in the last sections, many possibilities are also open.<sep> For example, our current approach does not allow us to type the links between morphs; but simple heuristics (such as string inclusion used by Grabar and Zweigenbaum (2002)) or techniques used in distributional analysis could provide useful additional information to better characterize these relationships.<sep> Of course, the problem of evaluating this type of work arises, especially the ground truth construction, since such resources do not exist.<sep> The indirect evaluation by a task such as the IR that we use in this article could be used again, possibly with other biomedical collections such as those of the TREC Genomics task (Hersch and Voorhees, 2009).<sep> Finally, an adaptation of these principles for complex terms is under study.<sep> The main difficulty is that the parallelism hypothesis is no longer realistic for certain languages such as French since the order of words is generally different from the neoclassical one;<sep> The main difficulty in this case is to manage the reordering of the words composing these terms, which corresponds to the distortion phenomenon in the alignment.<sep> This perspective is essential, especially in IR, since these complex terms are extremely common but appear in many variants, preventing the matching of queries and documents with different variants of the same term (Nenadic et al., 2005).<sep> This problem of distortion would also arise for the morphological analysis of words of the general language (for which bilingual dictionaries could easily provide the data) which would not be part of the neoclassical order of composition.<sep> However, more complex alignment solutions that manage these phenomena exist and their adaptation seems promising.<sep> Acknowledgments<sep> This work was partly funded by OSEO, the French innovation agency, in the framework of the Quæro project.<sep> 1. In this article, following Mel’čuk (2006), we distinguish between morphs, elementary linguistic signs (segments), and morphemes, abstract units seen in this work as a class of equivalence of morphs sharing an identical signified and a close signifier, that is, semantically equivalent and formally close realizations (Anderson, 2013, for an exhaustive and historical view of the different schools of linguistic definitions of the morpheme).<sep> 2. Some of the work presented in this article has been published in conferences: decomposition by alignment (Claveau and Kijak, 2010; Claveau and Kijak, 2011), application to information retrieval (Claveau and Kijak, 2012; Claveau, 2012).<sep> 3. georges.dolisi.free.fr/<sep> 4. www.dorlands.com/wsearch.jsp<sep> 5. en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E8%A1%80#Etymology<sep> Here, prefix and suffix are used in the computer sense of the term: strings of characters that appear at the beginning or end of sequences, regardless of their linguistic relevance.<sep> 7. www.cis.hut.fi/projects/morpho<sep> 8. www.cnrtl.fr/outils/DeriF/requete.php<sep> Dal and Amiot (2008) note: “In Romance languages, the order of constituents is […] different, depending on whether it is neoclassical composition or ordinary composition: in the first case, the semantically governing constituent is on the right, in the second, it is on the left.”
Identifying implicit discourse relations by combining natural and artificial data<sep> ABSTRACT<sep> This paper presents the first experiments on identifying implicit discourse relations (i.e., relations lacking an overt discourse connective) in French.<sep> Our systems use annotated implicit examples, as well as artificial implicit examples obtained from explicit examples by connector removal, a method introduced by Marcu and Echihabi (2002).<sep> Previous studies on English show that the use of artificial data in training largely degrades performance on natural data, which reflects important differences in terms of distribution.<sep> This observation, which also applies to French, led us to consider different methods, inspired by domain adaptation, aimed at combining the data more effectively.<sep> We evaluate these methods on the corpus_ANNODIS: our best system achieves an accuracy of 41 . 7%, corresponding to a 4 . 4% significant gain over a system solely trained on manually labeled data.<sep> 1 Introduction<sep> The goal of discourse analysis is to account for the coherence of a text, which is based on the fact that the propositions are not interpreted in isolation from each other, but are linked to each other by discursive or rhetorical relations (such as explanation, contrast, etc.) in order to form a global structure covering the entire document.<sep> Thus, in example 1[1] the propositions forming the first sentence are linked by a contrast relation, and the whole sentence is itself linked to the next sentence by a continuation relation.<sep> - (1) { { [La hulotte est un rapace nocturne]1 [mais elle peut vivre le jour.]2 }contraste [La hulotte mesure une quarantaine de centimètres.]3 }continuation (ANNODIS - document WK_-_hulotte)<sep> Different theoretical frameworks and formalism have been developed for discourse analysis, including Rhetorical Structure Theory (RST) (Mann and Thompson, 1988), Segmented Discourse Representation Theory (SDRT) (Asher and Lascarides, 2003) and the formalism of Discourse Lexicalized Tree Adjoining Grammars (D-LTAG) (Webber, 2004).<sep> These frameworks all define a different set of relationships, with some commonalities (Roze, 2013).<sep> Relations can link elementary discourse units (EDUs), which are usually clauses (like segments 1, 2 and 3 in example 1).<sep> They can also be established between so-called complex segments, i.e. pairs of segments, elementary or complex, themselves linked by a relation (like the pair of segments (1, 2) linked by the contrast relation in example 1).<sep> Finally, the final structures obtained are different: RST trees and SDRT graphs. These frameworks and formalism have made it possible to annotate corpora. For the English language, we can cite the RST Discourse TreeBank (RST DT) following the RST (Carlson et al., 2001) and the Penn Discourse TreeBank (PDTB) following the D- LTAG formalism (Prasad et al., 2008).<sep> For the French language, the ANNODIS corpus (Afantenos et al., 2012) was developed as part of the SDRT. The frameworks that underpin these corpora involve differences in the structures annotated and the sets of relations. Concerning the sets of relations: the RST DT has 78 relations grouped into 16 classes, ANNODIS 17 relations and the PDTB proposes a hierarchical organization with 4 classes, 16 types and 23 subtypes.<sep> The PDTB has another characteristic: an explicit distinction is established in the annotation between different types of relations.<sep> This corpus is based on the D-LTAG formalism, the idea being that certain specific lexical elements, belonging to a closed list, have the function of triggering a discursive relationship: the connectors [2] or discursive markers (but, because, for...)<sep> The annotation starts from a pre-established list of connectors that are identified and distinguished from the forms in non-discursive use (such as for marking an attribution).<sep> Their arguments, seen as EDUs, and the relations they trigger are then annotated.<sep> So in example 2a, to trigger a goal between segments 1 and 2.<sep> We speak of an explicit relation because it is explicitly marked by a discursive connector. In contrast, when no connector is present, we speak of an implicit or unmarked relation, as in the example of the relation of explanation between segments 1 and 2 in example 2b[3].<sep> - (2) a. { [At first the Nancy president invited Pablo to stop his career]1 [to join the technical staff.]2 }but<sep> - b. { [Yesterday late afternoon, Pablo signed a new two-year contract,]1 [finally accepting the proposals of Jacques Rousselot.]2 }explanation (ANNODIS - document Extr_estrep-025_PabloCorrea)<sep> These corpora have made it possible to develop complete automatic analysis systems or systems limited to the various sub-tasks.<sep> Although variable depending on the underlying theoretical framework, the steps of complete systems generally include a segmentation step corresponding to the identification of EDUs, an attachment step allowing to decide on the presence or absence of a relationship between two segments, a step of identification of the relationship linking two EDUs and finally a process of construction of the complete structure.<sep> The complete systems still obtain modest performances, so Sagae (2009) and Hernault et al. (2010) obtain respectively 44.5% and 47.3% of F-measure on the RST DT and Lin et al. (2010) report a score of 33.0% of F-measure on the PDTB.<sep> In these complete systems, the step of identifying a relationship is crucial, because a relationship can constrain the structure (via the constraint of the right boundary in SDRT for example) or the triggering of other relationships (Roze, 2013). Moreover, a system automatically identifying relationships could be useful to other systems.<sep> For temporal analysis, identifying an explanatory relationship in example 3 between segments 1 and 2 allows us to infer the correct temporal order between the events, “push” before “fall”.<sep> For an automatic summary system, identifying a relationship between two segments can make it possible to determine whether one of the segments can be deleted, by the principle of hierarchy between the segments defined, for example, in SDRT under the term coordinating or subordinating relationships.<sep> - (3) { [ Paul fell.]1 [ Mary pushed him.]2 }explanation (Constructed example)<sep> Different studies have sought in recent years to improve performance on this particular task of identifying a relationship between two text segments.<sep> On the RST DT, Hernault et al. (2010) report 66.8% accuracy.<sep> In the French ANNODIS, Muller et al. (2012) report 44.8% accuracy.<sep> The PDTB studies broke the problem down into two subtasks: identifying examples of explicit relations and non-explicit relations.<sep> These studies have shown that identifying a relationship in the explicit case is much easier, with systems achieving performance of around 94% accuracy for the 4 main classes of relationships in the PDTB (Pitler and Nenkova, 2009) and 86% for the 16 level 2 relationships (Lin et al., 2010), even when only taking the connector as a feature.<sep> In contrast, for the non-explicit case, the best performances for the 4 classes are of the order of 65 , 54 % (Pitler et al. , 2009) when only manually annotated data are used for learning, and of 72 , 2 % (Wang et al. , 2012) when explicit data are added.<sep> For 11 level-2 relations, Lin et al. (2009) report 40.2% accuracy on manually annotated data.<sep> Performance is therefore still modest when a relationship is not explicitly marked, which corresponds to about half of the PDTB data.<sep> In this case, the features are complex, and the low performance is likely due to a lack of annotated data.<sep> To deal with the lack of data, Marcu and Echihabi (2002) proposed a simple method to automatically create new examples of implicit relations from raw data. This method is based on the detection of segments and the automatic identification of connectors, ideally unambiguous (or disambiguated) in use and in relation: these connectors are then removed[4] and used as annotation of the identified relation.<sep> In addition to its simplicity, this approach also has the advantage of allowing the creation of a large number of examples, since it operates on raw data. However, this method may potentially suffer from errors made during segmentation and the detection of connectors. It also makes several important assumptions.<sep> On the one hand, it postulates that the connector is redundant with its context: there must indeed be enough information left, once the connector is removed, for the relationship to still be identifiable.<sep> Furthermore, it assumes that automatically (or artificially) constructed data follows the same distribution as manually annotated (or natural) data.<sep> We will see in detail in the following sections that these assumptions are not always verified.<sep> Moreover, previous studies based on this approach have not often led to an improvement in performance when these new data are used as the only training data. The observed performance decrease, for example in (Sporleder and Lascarides, 2008), shows that the new data do not allow for good generalization to the examples of implicit relations manually annotated.<sep> In their study, Wang et al. (2012) set up a selection principle among the examples of originally explicit relations, from the PDTB, in order to select the examples resembling the natural examples of implicit relations used for evaluation.<sep> This method allows them to manage differences in terms of distribution and improve performance, particularly in terms of micro-accuracy in multiclass, compared to a system using only manually annotated data.<sep> Unlike them, we do not have a corpus in which the connectors have been explicitly annotated.<sep> Furthermore, as we have less natural data, the use of raw data allows us to acquire a very large number of artificial data, which could potentially compensate for the low volume of manually annotated data, which is even more crucial in French (252 examples used here against more than 14,000 for the PDTB) but which introduces noise that was absent from their study.<sep> Finally, their methodology requires manual rules for the example selection phase and excludes natural examples from the training data which could limit the strategy.<sep> Building a model on underlying distribution data that is different from the data on which it will be used goes against the assumptions generally required by a learning system and risks resulting in poor performance.<sep> This configuration is similar to that studied in the context of domain adaptation where the problem is to adapt a classifier to so-called out-of-domain data from a different domain than that of the manually annotated data available, the in-domain data [5]. We therefore have a similar basic problem, which led us to implement strategies inspired by this framework, combining data or models.<sep> Thanks to simple methods, we have obtained significant improvements compared to a simple training on the available natural data.<sep> In this article, we first present previous studies in which data was automatically annotated from connectors (section 2).<sep> We then examine the problems posed by this method (section 3) before presenting the strategy envisaged to address these problems (section 4).<sep> Finally, we present the data (section 5) and the experiments carried out and the results obtained (section 6). Finally, we present the future prospects (section 7).<sep> 2. Previous studies<sep> We present in this section previous studies that have used a corpus of data annotated automatically from explicit examples.<sep> It should be noted that a direct comparison between these studies is not possible, firstly because the manually annotated corpus differs, RST DT or PDTB, and secondly because, even when using the same corpus, the configurations also differ. For example, the RST DT corpus does not explicitly separate explicit and implicit data, and studies on this corpus, without generally specifying how the data was separated, report different quantities and therefore use different evaluation corpora.<sep> For example, for contrast[6] , Marcu and Echihabi (2002) report 177 implicit examples.<sep> On the other hand, Wang et al. (2012) only consider the occurrences of interphrastic relations and count 889 of them (including 311 tests). Finally, Sporleder and Lascarides (2008) select a random sample and use 238 examples for evaluation.<sep> If the PDTB should lead to more consensus, the authors use different training and evaluation sets.<sep> The first reason is due to the definition of "implicit": while Wang et al. (2012) restrict their study to examples annotated as implicit in the PDTB, Pitler et al. (2009) and Park et Cardie (2012) include examples annotated as Entity and AltLex, forming a set of non-explicit examples. Furthermore, a pair of segments can be annotated with several relations in the PDTB.<sep> Some authors take them all into account in their systems by duplicating the examples for each annotation (Pitler et al., 2009). In contrast, Wang et al. (2012) only take into account the first annotated relation.<sep> Finally, the training corpora also differ due to random down-sampling performed for binary classifiers, and possibly optimization of these corpora (Park and Cardie, 2012). Marcu and Echihabi (2002) were the first to propose using explicit examples for the construction of a system for identifying implicit relations.<sep> As connectors are not ambiguous, they generally trigger only one relation, it is relatively easy to extract explicit examples of raw data and assign them the correct relation. These authors used two English raw corpora (nearly 48 million sentences) and defined patterns based on the position of the connector and punctuation to extract examples of 4 relations (contrast, cause-explanationevidence, condition, elaboration). Thus, they extract examples of contrast from but<sep> if the connector starts a sentence, the arguments are the sentence containing but and the previous sentence.<sep> If but appears in the middle of a sentence, the arguments are the segments delimited by the connector. The authors also extract examples that potentially correspond to an absence of relation based on distant phrases (within the same document or between documents). The data is represented by the Cartesian product of the words on the arguments, the idea being to identify pairs of words whose link would correspond to a relationship, such as an opposition "embargo/legally" for contrasts.<sep> The authors test on artificial examples naive Bayesian binary classifiers: these all exceed 50% accuracy.<sep> They also test on the same data a naive Bayesian multiclass classifier (4 discursive relations and 2 classes marking the absence of inter or intradocument relation) whose accuracy is also around 50%. It is important to note that Marcu and Echihabi (2002) did not really test their approach on natural implicit data, their natural evaluation set also contains explicit and moreover they keep the connector in the data extracted from the raw corpora.<sep> They estimate the potential results of their system on natural implicit relation examples in a very informal way. That said, the performances obtained on artificial data are largely superior to chance, which supports the hypothesis of redundancy of the connector: for at least a part of this data, the relation remains identifiable once the connector is removed.<sep> Following Marcu and Echihabi (2002), several authors have taken up the principle of automatically annotated data and tested this method in various ways. Blair-Goldensohn et al. (2007) tested the method both on a raw corpus and on the PDTB corpus with 2 relations (contrast, cause-explanation-evidence) and a class representing the absence of relation (intradocument) and binary classifiers. They sought to limit the noise in the data, notably through pre-processing.<sep> Their results are difficult to compare as the data and setup are different.<sep> Above all, they evaluated themselves on artificial data (5,000 examples per relation) and on natural implicit data from the PDTB (by randomly selecting 280 examples per relation) but did not compare themselves to training on natural data.<sep> Their experiments are not sufficient to know if artificial data leads to an improvement in the identification of examples of natural implicit relations, but only that these synthetic data allow to achieve performances superior to chance on natural data, for the relations considered and in binary classification. Moreover, the pre-treatments used do not improve the performance in terms of accuracy on the natural test set. Pitler et al. (2009) build a standard system on the PDTB, with training and testing on manually annotated data with traits taken from previous studies.<sep> They use the 4 first level relations (temporal, contingency, comparison, expansion) for which they build binary classifiers. Their use of artificial data (corpus of (Blair-Goldensohn et al., 2007) or explicit data from the PDTB) is limited to the extraction in these data of pairs of words (product cartesian on the arguments), taking up the basic idea of Marcu and Echihabi (2002) which they seek to test the validity.<sep> Interestingly, Blair-Goldensohn et al. (2007) showed that the use of these word pairs generally degrades performance, at least the use of these traits leads to the worst systems, but the authors do not present a system combining these traits with others. Moreover, the authors show that the word pairs with the highest information gain are not semantically related, but functional word pairs. However, the study also shows a potentially effective combination between natural and artificial data: if only the word pairs extracted from artificial data corresponding to a non-zero information gain on implicit data are kept, the best system for comparison and the second best system for contingency are obtained.<sep> However, these systems have since been surpassed by Park and Cardie (2012) with simpler models that do not use Sporleder and Lascarides (2008) conducted an in-depth study of the very principle of this strategy and built a system using linguistically motivated features.<sep> They test this strategy on data from the RST DT corpus by selecting 5 relations from the SDRT (by establishing a correspondence between the relations).<sep> They conclude that it is impossible to use this data directly for training and ask various questions that call into question the very principle of this strategy.<sep> We take up these issues in the next section.<sep> These authors showed that training on a small set of manually annotated data resulted in significantly better performance (1,051 examples, accuracy of 40.3%) than training on a large set of data automatically annotated from explicit examples (72,000 examples, accuracy of 25.8%).<sep> This drop in performance reflects the difference in distribution between the two data sets, but the results obtained are still above chance (set at 20%).<sep> Wang et al. (2012) used a principle of selection of training examples based on an unsupervised algorithm.<sep> The system is tested on the 4 classes of the PDTB (temporal, contingency, comparison, expansion) and on the RST DT (temporal, contrast, cause, background).<sep> Manual rules allow to identify a small "seed" set of examples that are considered "typical" of a relation among the training examples. For example, for comparison and contingency, a pair of words of opposite polarity must be identified in the arguments.<sep> For temporal, one of the arguments must contain the words "including, following, last, first, second."<sep> A clustering algorithm then extends the “seed” set and a supervised algorithm is used on the resulting training set.<sep> For the RST DT, the authors have about 2,400 artificial examples and 3,900 natural implicit ones.<sep> For the PDTB, the artificial corpus corresponds to the explicit examples of the corpus.<sep> The data is represented by binary attributes taken from previous studies (lexical and semantic features).<sep> In multiclass, the authors report 51.3% accuracy with the naive Bayes (NB) classifier and 53.5% with decision trees (DT) when all natural implicit data is used.<sep> When the artificial data is used alone, performance falls to 34.1% (NB) and 42.6% (DT).<sep> The combination of data improves these performances: 42.3% (NB) and 51.4% (DT).<sep> Finally, the method of selecting examples introduced allows for a significant improvement: 68.3% (NB) and 72.2% (DT).<sep> In this configuration, the number of artificial and natural examples is similar (6,753 and 7,816, respectively).<sep> However, it should be noted that the binary classifiers on the PDTB obtained lower F-measure scores than those reported in the study by Park and Cardie (2012) that did not use artificial data but different pre-processing and feature combinations, however, as noted in the introduction, a direct comparison between these studies is not possible.<sep> A strict comparison of these two strategies and an estimation of their cost would make it possible to determine the most effective one.<sep> Finally, Wang et al. (2012) note that the examples correctly identified by their system correspond generally to "typical" examples, so it is not clear that this system can lead to even higher performance, although a study on the representation of data and its influence on the typicality of examples remains to be conducted.<sep> 3. Problematic<sep> The use of artificial examples for learning implicit relations is based on different assumptions that most previous studies have often not clearly explained. As we have already mentioned, this method first assumes a certain redundancy of the connector with its context: there must be enough information left, once the connector is removed, to be able to identify the relationship. Then, the artificial examples must also follow a distribution that is close enough (especially in terms of labels or the association between pairs of segments and labels) to that of the natural examples to be able to hope that the generalizations obtained by the classification system can be applied to the natural examples and lead to reduced error rates on these data.<sep> The remainder of this section discusses these two assumptions in detail.<sep> 3.1. Connector Redundancy<sep> As a reminder, the automatic annotation method is based on raw examples identified as explicit: the connector is removed and the relationship that the lexical connector was lexicalizing is annotated.<sep> To illustrate, consider the contrast example 4 formed of the segments 1 and 2 containing the connector namely: the example of an associated synthetic implicature is an example of the contrast formed of the segments 1 and 2 ['] .<sep> - (4) { [She was very comic, very funny.]1 [( That said ) [, the drama was never far away.]2 [′] }contrast<sep> - ( Est Républicain - Artificial example)<sep> In order to better evaluate the hypothesis of redundancy, we consider the different discursive effects of the suppression of a connector.<sep> In a schematic way, we identify three possible cases: – the removal of the connector has little or no effect: the relation remains inferable in its absence, the connector is redundant with its context;<sep> – the deletion of the connective makes the discourse incoherent: the discourse becomes unacceptable and not simply because of syntactic effects; – the deletion of the connective modifies the inferred relation: the relation lexicalised by the connective is no longer inferable but another relation is inferred.<sep> 3.1.1. Redundant connector<sep> According to Moeschler (2002), a connector "gives instructions on how to link [units] together" and "imposes the drawing of conclusions from the discourse connection that would not be drawn in its absence".<sep> However, how can we explain that the same link, temporal in 5a or causal in 5b, is inferred in the presence or absence of the connectors (respectively and and because )?<sep> This possibility seems to depend essentially on the content of the linked segments and on preferences about the relationships that are not hierarchical in the absence of explicit markings.<sep> - (5) a. { [The plane landed] [(and) the passengers got off.] }narration<sep> - b. { [ Paul fell, ] [( because ) Mary pushed him. ] }explanation ((Moeschler, 2002) - constructed example)<sep> In their study, Soria and Ferrari (1998) asked subjects to identify a relation (among additive, consequential and contrastive) in examples where the connective is or is not deleted (the example remaining grammatical).<sep> The study shows that identification is indeed more difficult without a connector (we go from 72.6-88.9% to 42.7-64.3% of correct identification by relation), but the status of the relations differs: the additive relation seems to be predicted by default (because it is the one that is predicted by error most often), and the consequential relation, on the other hand, remains well predicted, reflecting a preference of speakers for this type of relations.<sep> These conclusions correspond to those of Sanders (2005): readers try to infer the most informative relationship, a causal link, and then, if the content of the segments does not allow for inferring a more specific relationship, a simple link of temporal continuity is inferred.<sep> These conclusions are found in a study conducted on the PDTB by Asr and Demberg (2012): examples involving a non-linear temporal sequence are more often marked than others and causal relationships are more easily implicit.<sep> This does not mean that only temporal and causal relations remain identifiable in the absence of a connector, but their inference is preferred.<sep> It should also be noted that training and evaluating a model on artificial data results in performances that are superior to chance for the relationships considered, which are therefore identifiable in a portion of the data.<sep> 3.1.2.<sep> Coherence of the speech<sep> In some cases, however, the connector is necessary: its removal can make the discourse incoherent, an effect noted by Asher and Lascarides (2003) in the case of expectation violation contrasts.<sep> Thus, in the example given by these authors and reproduced in 6a, the removal of the but connector leads to a bizarre discourse judged to be incoherent.<sep> However, in formal contrasts, where there is no logical relationship between the truth conditions of the arguments but rather a contrast due to a difference in content, the marker is not necessary: in example 6b, the removal of the connector results in a loss of information but the discourse remains acceptable.<sep> - (6) a. { [John likes sports.] [( But ) he hates football.] } violation of expectation<sep> - b. { [John has green eyes.] [( But ) Mary has blue eyes.] } formal contrast<sep> - ((Asher and Lascarides, 2003) - constructed example)<sep> 3.1.3. Modification of the inferred relationship<sep> Finally, deleting the connector can change the inferred relationship type between two segments.<sep> This effect joins the question of examples of implicit interpretation relations of indeterminate in (Moeschler, 2002). Regarding this effect, Sporleder and Lascarides (2008) proposed the example 7 attested having served to produce an artificial example: the suppression of the connector although marking a contrast cancels the inference of this relation but the discourse remains coherent, we identify a relation of type continuation.<sep> Here both relations were present originally, but the removal of the connector no longer allows the inference of the implicit continuation relation.<sep> - (7) { [( Although ) the electronics industry has changed greatly,] [possibly the greatest change is that very little component level manufacture is done in this country.] }contrast, continuation ((Sporleder et Lascarides, 2008) - Artificial example)<sep> The authors did not observe this effect for the result and explanation types of relationships.<sep> However, the removal of the connector since in example 8 seems to modify the inferred relationship.<sep> The connector marked the fact that the second proposition is an explanation for what is stated in the first which implies that the event of migration occurs before the fact of becoming adversaries.<sep> Without the connector, the order of events seems reversed and follows the order of the text.<sep> Moreover, a relationship of result seems to be inferable, the first segment explaining the second.<sep> Here, it is not an already present implicit relation that is inferred by removing the connector, but a new relation.<sep> This modification can be explained by the hypothesis of an inference of a default linear continuity linked to a lack of knowledge in the field, a continuity linked to a causal interpretation because the content of the arguments allows it. It should be noted that the temporal localizer "then" is modified by the deletion of the connector: with the connector it seems to refer to the whole sentence, without it, it refers more to the second proposition.<sep> - (8) { [The Amorites become serious adversaries of the kings of Ur in the following period,] [(since they then begin to migrate in large numbers to Mesopotamia.)] }<sep> - (ANNODIS - Document WK_-_amorrites)<sep> 3.1.4. Effects on a classification system<sep> We would like to be able to define criteria that would allow us to choose the artificial examples that are most likely to help identify examples of implicit relations, for example in terms of connectors or relations.<sep> Based on the preceding considerations, one might think that we should not take into account violation of expectation contrasts, since they are never implicit.<sep> However, the indices they use, such as lexical oppositions (love/hate), can appear in examples of formal contrast.<sep> The more troublesome cases for a classification system are those where the inferrable relation is changed, since we might have examples of similar natural and artificial implicit relations but annotated with different relations.<sep> However, changing the relationship strongly depends on the content of the related segments, which is a difficult criterion to encode.<sep> As these cases are rare (1 case out of 28 examples of explanation considered), we hope that the example selection strategy as well as the combination methods will make it possible to manage this problem.<sep> 3.2 Distribution Differences<sep> In statistical learning, it is generally assumed that the data from training and test samples are independently and identically distributed (i.i.d.). This means, informally, that the data follow the same probability law (usually unknown) and that their sampling was done randomly. It is clear, by its design, that the method of automatic creation of implicit examples proposed by Marcu and Echihabi (2002) is likely to undermine this important assumption.<sep> There is indeed no guarantee that our artificial examples should follow a distribution similar to that of the natural examples.<sep> This in turn poses the problem of learning in a context where the data is not i.i.d.<sep> In this particular context, we have two sets of data that are similar (same set of labels, the instances are text segments), but are distributed differently, and this for several reasons. On the one hand, the artificial data are by definition obtained from examples of explicit relations: there is no guarantee that these data are distributed like the examples of implicit relations that are attested. The difference is in the distribution of labels (the relations) and the association between labels and inputs (the pairs of segments) to be classified.<sep> Also, deleting the connector changes the examples, which can have an impact as noted in the previous section.<sep> Finally, automatic annotation is based on heuristics that allow the identification of connectors and their arguments.<sep> These heuristics introduce additional noise, which is not found in natural data.<sep> For example, we may have made a mistake in identifying a connector: the form was not in discursive use, we have no relationship at all or a different relationship than the one annotated.<sep> We may also have made errors in the identification of the arguments. We describe the differences in distribution in the following section, using the categories described in the domain adaptation, for example in (Moreno-Torres et al., 2012) and (Jiang, 2008).<sep> 3.2.1. Class imbalance (class imbalance or prior probability drift)<sep> In this case, the difference is in the marginal distribution of the classes. This is already different between explicit and natural implicit data, and our heuristic produces a new one.<sep> The exact figures are given in section 5. The class underrepresented in the natural data, contrast, becomes overrepresented in the artificial data.<sep> For this class, the form mais , still in discursive use, allowed 75% of the data to be extracted.<sep> On the other hand, the continuation relation becomes underrepresented in the artificial data.<sep> The connectors of this relation, like and , are more ambiguous in use and we had to define stricter patterns to avoid retrieving bad examples.<sep> This problem can be easily handled by resampling artificial data according to the distribution of natural implicit data.<sep> 3.2.2. Distribution of the pairs of segments (covariate shift or population drift) Here the difference is in the marginal distribution of the inputs, the pairs of spans of text.<sep> The use of explicit examples induces a difference, because one can think that without the connective the indices used are different.<sep> Moreover, the removal of the connective can result in ungrammatical examples.<sep> Segmentation also leads to differences.<sep> On the one hand, there are potentially segmentation errors in the artificial data.<sep> On the other hand, the segmentation of artificial data corresponds to simplifying assumptions: an argument covers at most one sentence and there are at most two arguments per sentence.<sep> Segmentation of natural data does not follow these assumptions: arguments can be multi-phrastic or separate a sentence into more than two segments. Finally, there is a potential gender bias: artificial examples are all constructed from L'Est Républicain but natural data also comes from Wikipedia (see data description in section 5).<sep> 3.2.3. Association between labels and segment pairs (concept drift or functional relation change) In this case, the difference is in the joint distribution of classes and segment pairs.<sep> One can get a sense of the difference in distribution across the label-example association by considering some characteristics of the data.<sep> For example, we can look at the distribution between occurrences of inter- and intra-phrastic relations (the relation is established between two sentences or two segments within a sentence), see table 1.<sep> The proportion of inter-sentential examples in natural and artificial datasets is the same for contrast (57 . 1%), it is similar for result (resp. 45 . 7% and 39 . 8%), but very different for continuation (resp. 70% and 96 . 5%) and for explanation (resp. 21 . 4% and 53 . 0%). We also observe that the proportion of inter-sentential relations in artificial data does not reflect that of explicit data, this being due to our heuristic.<sep> Table 1.<sep> Distribution of occurrences of implicit (natural), explicit and artificial interphrastic relations for all available examples, (X %) for the examples used in our experiments in the case of implicit ones<sep> The automatic annotation strategy can lead to errors in labelling. We may identify a form as a discourse connective when it is not in fact in use: either there is no relationship between the arguments, or another relationship is present.<sep> Furthermore, removing the connector can have the effect of changing the identifiable relationship as seen in the previous section.<sep> In these cases, our natural implicit data may contain examples that resemble these artificial examples but annotated with the relation that we identify without taking into account the connector.<sep> In previous studies, training on artificial data alone resulted in lower results than training on natural data (which are, however, much less numerous).<sep> This is due to the differences in the distribution between the two datasets described in the previous section.<sep> In this section, we describe different methods to leverage the new artificial data, not alone, but in combination with the existing natural data.<sep> 4.1. Classic supervised classification framework<sep> The classification task corresponds to the assignment of an example to a class from a predefined set.<sep> In supervised learning, the classification function is learned from a set of data that is labeled with its class, the training data.<sep> In our experiments, we use a maximum entropy model, or logistic regression (Berger et al., 1996), which gives good performance for different TAL problems.<sep> It is a probabilistic model, we obtain a probability distribution on the classes for each example, and a discriminant model, we directly model the conditional probability of the classes given the data. This type of model also has the advantage of allowing the addition of many potentially redundant descriptors without making independence assumptions. To formally describe this model, we note X the set of input data and Y the possible outputs.<sep> We have a set of labeled data S = { ( x 1 , y 1) , … , ( xi, yi ) , … , ( xn, yn ) } ⊂X × Y .<sep> We want to learn a hypothesis function h: X →Y .<sep> The prediction is based on a representation of the data in the form of feature vectors, Φ( xi, yi ) ∈ R [d] (d the number of dimensions or features), and a weight vector w ∈ R [d] , the parameters of the model.<sep> Each trait φi is associated with a weight wi.<sep> The parameter vector is learned in training from a labeled dataset Strain ⊂ S . In a maximum entropy model, the class is predicted according to formula [1], for an instance x ∈X .<sep> The learning process must determine the “best” vector of parameters ˆw, understood here as the one that maximizes the log-likelihood of the training data and, in order to avoid too much attachment to the data, a regularization term is added that will penalize weights that are too large.<sep> We arrive at the formula [2], where λ is the regularization parameter of the model, more precisely, it is the precision of the Gaussian prior on the weights.<sep> Différents algorithmes peuvent être utilisés pour estimer ces paramètres, on utilise ici une méthode d’optimisation dite à mémoire limitée (limited memory BFGS) implémentée dans MegaM[7] .<sep> 4.2. Domain adaptation framework<sep> The problem of distribution differences between the two types of data led us to study the methods used in domain adaptation. Indeed, domain adaptation refers to learning situations where we have data sets following different distributions.<sep> For example, we have data annotated in morphosyntactic categories in the field of journalism and we want to annotate data from computer manuals.<sep> If we simply use a model built on the first data, we observe a degradation in performance: the difference in terms of domain leads to a drop in performance, the model does not achieve a good generalization from the first domain to the second.<sep> More formally, we have a set of annotated data called source data Ds, generally in large quantity, and a set of target data Dt.<sep> It is usually assumed that a small part of the target data is also annotated (but there are also techniques that do not make this assumption, see (Daumé III et al., 2010)).<sep> The source data follows an underlying distribution Ds unknown, and the target data an underlying distribution Dt unknown. The methods developed in the context of domain adaptation have been interested in different cases, according to the distributional differences at stake presented in the previous section.<sep> The problem of class imbalance is well defined and managed by methods of resampling (up- or down-sampling) or weighting of the examples. The other two cases, covariate shift and change of functional relation are less clearly separated (Sogaard, 2013).<sep> Domain adaptation problems have been addressed in many studies and various solutions have been proposed. Daumé III (2007) describes a system that is based on data representation, dividing it into three spaces, one for each domain and one common one corresponding to the shared characteristics.<sep> So on the morphosyntactic tagging task, the will have the category determiner whatever the domain while monitor will be more of a verb in news articles and more of a noun in computer manuals.<sep> He compares this strategy to a set of so-called baseline systems, some of which are considered difficult to beat.<sep> These are the models we test and describe below.<sep> Another approach was proposed by Chelba and Acero (2006): these authors build a model on the source data and then use it as regularization for a model built on the target data.<sep> This gives the model a priori information on the data and manages a constraint of proximity between the two models through a regularization parameter.<sep> Other methods have been proposed, including Jiang (2008) who describes strategies based either on an estimation of the difference between the marginal probabilities of the data or on a form of filtering of the source examples that lead the model into error, those that are too different in terms of conditional probability.<sep> We are not exactly in a domain adaptation framework, in the sense that we are not particularly interested in the gender difference between our data (Wikipedia or journalistic articles), but mainly because we are not trying to build a good model on artificial data and on natural data, only the latter interest us.<sep> However, this framework corresponds to a learning situation from data drawn from a different distribution than the evaluation data. In this sense, the automatically annotated data constitute our source data, and the manually annotated data, on which we want to improve performance, our target data.<sep> 4.3. Models tested<sep> As a first step, we decided to investigate the simplest domain adaptation methods proposed by Daumé III (2007), methods described as relatively competitive and simple to implement.<sep> The different combination methods we propose differ according to whether the combination is done directly at the level of the data sets or at the level of the models trained on them.<sep> We added a principle of automatic selection of automatically annotated examples based on the confidence of the model trained on these data concerning its prediction in order to manage a part of the noise, and therefore to select the most reliable examples.<sep> The performance of all these systems will be compared to the base systems trained on both sets of data in section 6.4.1. Base systems.<sep> The first basic system (NATONLY) is the one where you train and evaluate yourself on natural data.<sep> This system gives us the performance to beat and corresponds to a classical learning framework where all data is assumed to be drawn identically from the same unknown underlying distribution.<sep> The second basic system (ARTONLY) is one where you train on automatically (or artificially) annotated data and evaluate on natural data.<sep> This is the system proposed in the studies of Blair-Goldensohn et al. (2007) and Sporleder and Lascarides (2008) and we should normally observe, as in these studies, a significant decrease in performance.<sep> These baseline systems serve as a comparison to the other systems tested, systems where data or models are combined.<sep> 4.3.2. Combination of data<sep> The first combination strategy we are studying (UNION) is of the first type: it consists of creating a training corpus that contains the union of the two data sets.<sep> This method does not allow us to control the importance of the two sets of data nor to evaluate their influence on the system.<sep> We thus refine it in two other strategies that we describe below.<sep> A first derived strategy (ARTSUB) consists of taking, not the entirety of the artificial data, but random subsets of this data, in addition to the natural data.<sep> This method is a bit more subtle in that the proportion of artificial examples to natural examples can be varied.<sep> However, we do not take into account the entirety of the artificial data, so we lose information. Finally, the third method of the first type, derived from the first, (NATW) keeps this time all the artificial data but reweights (or duplicates) the natural examples in order to avoid too great an imbalance in favor of the artificial data.<sep> 4.3.3. Combination of models<sep> In the second type of method, we first have a method (ADDPRED) that consists of using the predictions of a model trained on artificial data (i.e. the "source" data) as a descriptor in the model trained on natural data (i.e. the "target" data).<sep> The parameter associated to the attribute therefore measures the importance to be given to the predictions made by the model trained on artificial data.<sep> This method is the best baseline and the third best model in (Daumé III and Marcu, 2006).<sep> A variation of this method (ADDPROB) also uses the confidence score (here the probability) of the artificial model as an additional descriptor in the model built on natural data.<sep> The intuition behind these methods is that even if the classifier is wrong, it could still be consistent in its errors, which can be a useful source of information for the model.<sep> A third method (ARTINIT) aims to initialize the parameters of the trained model on natural data with those of the model using artificial data.<sep> This method allows to give an initial information to the trained model on natural data, rather than a random initialization.<sep> Finally, the last method (LININT) is based on a linear interpolation of two models previously trained on each of the data sets.<sep> The parameters of the linear interpolation allow you to vary the importance of each of the models.<sep> 4.3.4. Automatic selection of examples: We also tested all the strategies by adding a step of automatic selection of artificial examples. The method used is naive since it is based simply on the probability of the predicted label: we test different thresholds on these probabilities by adding each time only the examples predicted with a probability higher than the threshold, and by rebalancing the entire data set.<sep> This selection aims to eliminate noisy data, by finally exploring one of the paths proposed by Marcu and Echihabi (2002) and developed in a different way by Blair-Goldensohn et al. (2007), namely improving the quality of the artificial corpus.<sep> This method also makes it possible to some extent to select the data for which the hypothesis of connector redundancy is verified: the more confident the model is in its prediction, the more likely it is that it has found good indicators for its prediction.<sep> 4.4. Stroke set<sep> Our set of strokes is based on existing work with some notable adaptations for French.<sep> These features exploit surface information, as well as other information from deeper linguistic processing.<sep> In comparison, Marcu and Echihabi (2002) only rely on the co-occurrence of lemmas in segments.<sep> Sporleder and Lascarides (2007) show that taking into account different types of linguistically motivated features improves performance.<sep> Sporleder and Lascarides (2008) use various features including bigram of lemmas but without syntactic features.<sep> We tested lexicosyntactic features used in previous studies on this task.<sep> We were not able to recover the semantic features such as the semantic classes of the heads of the arguments (determined by the dependency analysis) because the necessary resources do not exist for French.<sep> Features with discrete or categorical values have been binarized.<sep> Some features are calculated for each argument: – index of syntactic complexity: number of nominal, verbal, prepositional, adjectival, adverbial syntagms (continuous);<sep> – information on the head of an argument: - negative elements lemma depending on the head, of the type "not, no... " (boolean), - temporal/aspectual information: number of times a head-dependent auxiliary function lemma appears (continuous), time, person, number of the auxiliary (boolean), - information on the dependents of the head: presence of a head, subject or object dependent depending on its type in the dependency analysis (object, "by" object, modifier or prepositional dependent) (boolean);<sep> Morphosyntactic category of modifiers and prepositional dependents of the head, subject or object (boolean), - morphological information: tense and person of the verbal head, gender of the non-verbal head, number of the head, precise morphosyntactic category (e.g. “VPP”) and simplified category (respectively “V”) (boolean).<sep> Other features are about the pair of arguments: – position feature: whether the relation is between two sentences (interphrastic) or between two clauses within a sentence (intraphrastic) (boolean);<sep> – thematic continuity index: overlap in lemmas and in open category lemmas (continuous);<sep> - information about the heads of the arguments: - pair formed by the verbal tenses of the heads (boolean), - pair formed by the numbers of the heads (boolean).<sep> Finally, note that our goal is primarily to combine data, so we did not try to optimize this set of features, which would have introduced an additional parameter in our model.<sep> 5. Data<sep> 5.1. Choice of relations: We have chosen to restrict ourselves to 4 relations: contrast , result , continuation and explanation . These relations are annotated in the French corpus used and correspond to examples of implicit and explicit relations.<sep> These are 4 of the 5 relations (summary/résumé is not annotated in ANNODIS) used in (Sporleder and Lascarides, 2008), which allows for a comparison, however not direct since the language is different. Finally, these are relations that can be expressed implicitly (unlike, for example, the condition type relation which requires lexicalization by a connector), but also explicitly, which is necessary to build the artificial corpus (unlike, for example, the encadrement relation for which we do not have a lexicon of connectors).<sep> In our natural data, we merged the meta-relations (or pragmatic relations, which are established between speech acts) with the corresponding relations (non-pragmatic, which are established between facts) with the hypothesis that they involve the same kind of clues and constructions. Natural data allow us to obtain examples of manually annotated implicit relations.<sep> The automatically generated data are explicit examples extracted by heuristics from raw data in which the connector is removed, and we then have artificial implicit data.<sep> 5.2 Manually Annotated Data: ANNODIS<sep> The ANNODIS project (Afantenos et al., 2012) aims to build an annotated corpus of discourse for French at two levels: on the one hand, relations of discourse between EDU and complex segments are annotated according to the SDRT framework (microstructure), on the other hand, high-level discursive structures concerning the functional organization of the document are annotated (macrostructure). Here, we are only interested in the microstructure level.<sep> The version of the corpus used (as of 15/11/2012) contains 86 documents from L'Est Républicain and Wikipedia.<sep> In total, 3,339 examples have been annotated using 17 rhetorical relations.<sep> It should be noted that the lack of manually annotated data is even more significant for French than for English, since when only the English corpus of the PDTB is taken into account (around 40,000 examples), there are around 12 times fewer manually annotated examples.<sep> Documents are segmented in Elementary Discourse Units (EDUs) which can be clauses, prepositionnal phrases and some adverbials and parentheticals if the segment contains the description of an eventuality.<sep> The relations are annotated between EDUs or complex segments, adjacent or not.<sep> The connectives are not annotated.<sep> The corpus has been pre-processed using the MELt tagger (Denis and Sagot, 2009) for POS-tagging, lemmatization and morphological markings.<sep> The MSTParser (Candito et al., 2010) provides a dependency analysis.<sep> In order to restrict our study to implicit relations, we used the LexConn, a lexicon of discursive connectives in French developed by Roze et al. (2012) and extended in 2012 to connectives introducing nominal phrases.<sep> We use a simple method: we project the lexicon (except for the form deemed too ambiguous) onto the data, which allows us to identify any token corresponding to a connector.<sep> We did not add constraints on the connective position, as we wanted to be sure to identify all connectors and thus only recover implicit relationship examples, but this method carries the risk of losing some of them.<sep> Out of 1,108 examples available for the 4 relations, we have 494 examples of implicit relations; the distribution of examples by relation is summarized in table 2. Table 2. Corpus ANNODIS: number of examples of explicit and implicit relations by relation<sep> 5.3. Automatically Annotated Data<sep> We use LexConn to automatically extract examples of one of the 4 discursive relations considered in the corpus composed of articles from Est Républicain (9M sentences), with the same pre-processings as ANNODIS.<sep> LexConn contains 329 connectives, among them, 131 are unambiguous for our 4 relations.<sep> Ambiguous connectors in terms of the triggered relation could also be interesting but they would bring noise in the automatic annotation since we do not have a model to disambiguate them. We merged the corresponding relations and meta-relations, assuming they involve the same kind of predictors. We also grouped the 3 contrastive relations, as they were done in the manually annotated corpus.<sep> We did not take into account 3 connectives that are not associated with any morphosyntactic category in the lexicon (unknown morphosyntactic category, like d'où que ).<sep> After an initial evaluation, we chose to delete 6 particularly ambiguous connectives that were difficult to define between discursive and non-discursive readings (such as "maintenant" ("now")).<sep> We finally have 122 connectives, only 100 were actually useful, the other 22 were not found in the corpus or were not found in a configuration defined as discursive.<sep> The heuristic used to automatically annotate the examples has two main steps.<sep> First, we identify forms used in discourse readings using patterns (see table 3) that were manually defined for each connective based on its position, its part-of-speech and the punctuation around it. These patterns are based on the position of the form (initial, medial or final), its morphosyntactic category (POS) and the punctuation around the form, and using the indications of LexConn.<sep> We then identify the arguments of a connective, which can be seen as a simplification of the segmentation problem.<sep> We make the same simplifying assumptions as in the previous studies: an argument covers at most one sentence, and we have at most 2 EDUs within a sentence.<sep> We also use the position of the connector, its morphosyntactic category and punctuation for this identification.<sep> Table 3. The defined motifs and some corresponding examples. "A1" corresponds to the first argument, "A2" to the second and "C" to the connector; "beg" and "end" correspond respectively to the beginning and the end of an argument;<sep> "(x)" indique le caractère facultatif de "x", selon la forme des connecteurs mis en jeu. Certains motifs ne sont applicables que pour certaines catégories morphosyntaxiques de connecteur ("POS") entre conjonction de subordination (CS), préposition (Prep.) et adverbe (Adv.).<sep> This simple method allows to quickly generate a large amount of data. In total, we extracted 392 , 260 examples (see table 2).<sep> When two connectors are present in a segment, one may modify the other or there may be a double connector (for example, "but because he is...").<sep> In this case, we risk getting the same arguments for two forms triggering different relations which is problematic for a classification system.<sep> When 2 connectors are identified in 1 sentence, we generate 2 examples provided that the arguments are different: 1 example must correspond to 1 relation established between 2 sentences and the other to 1 relation established between 2 propositions within 1 sentence.<sep> We balanced the corpus in relations by keeping the maximum number of available examples in a training corpus (80% of the data), a development corpus (10%) and a test corpus (10%).<sep> Note that there are some important differences in the label distributions between natural and artificial data. The most represented continuation in the natural data becomes the least represented in the artificial data.<sep> This is because the connectives that trigger this relation are highly ambiguous which forced us to define strict patterns for the extraction of examples.<sep> Finally, this method generates some noise: out of 250 random examples, we found 37 errors in span boundaries and 18 cases in which the connective form does not have a discourse reading.<sep> 6. Experiments<sep> Our main objective is to assess whether one can use the artificial data to improve the performance of a system solely based on data manually annotated only available in small amount. We therefore test the methods described in section 3.<sep> Experiments are performed with the maximum entropy algorithm implementation provided in the MegaM library, in multiclass classification, with a maximum of 100 iterations.<sep> We did not try to optimize the regularization coefficient, its value is then equal to 1.<sep> We use a balanced corpus of natural data with a maximum of 70 examples per relation.<sep> Experiments that preserve the natural, highly skewed data distribution will need to be considered, but for now we are focusing on the data combination aspect.<sep> Given the low volume of manually annotated data available, it is not possible to cut them into distinct sets for training and validation.<sep> Thus, we use a nested cross-validation.<sep> This methodology ensures that the optimization of hyperparameters (described in section 6.2) is done on data that is different from the one on which we evaluate ourselves. It has been shown that this method provides an estimate of the error that is very close to that one could obtain on an independent evaluation set (Scheffer, 1999; Varma and Simon, 2006).<sep> As its name suggests, the nested cross-validation has two loops: an inner loop of cross-validation that is used to optimize the hyper-parameters, and an outer loop of cross-validation that is used to measure the performance obtained, and to estimate its error.<sep> The outer loop goes through the N subsets of the first random split.<sep> The subset k (with 1 ≤ k ≤ N ) is considered as the current evaluation set. The N − 1 other subsets are used as training data and split into M subsets used for model fitting.<sep> The classifier is finally trained with the N-1 subsets of the outer loop and evaluated on the subset k using the best values for the hyperparameters.<sep> We used two 5-fold cross-validations in order to select and evaluate the best models for the systems described in section 4.3.<sep> We have no guarantee to select the best models at each test step, but this procedure allows to evaluate the stability of the system with respect to the hyper-parameters (i.e. the chosen values should not be too scattered), the overfitting (i.e. inner and outer estimations should be close) and the stability of the models (i.e. variance in the predictive capacity, between the results on the outer folds).<sep> As in the previous studies, we report performance using micro-averaged accuracy and F1 score per relation.<sep> In the case of very small samples (here N = 5), it is difficult to calculate the significance of the observed performance gaps. (de Winter, 2013) shows that the paired Student test can be used in this case, provided that the effect size (calculated using the Cohen coefficient) and the correlation between the samples are sufficiently important. (de Winter, 2013) indicates that, on the contrary, the Wilcoxon signed rank test can lead to overestimated p -values with such small samples. We therefore choose to give the results using the Student test (with a p -value < 0 . 05).<sep> 6.1 Basic Models<sep> First, we build two separate models, one from natural data only (NATONLY, 252 examples), the other from artificial data only (ARTONLY, 93,636 training examples).<sep> The overall accuracy of the NATONLY model is 37 . 3 with F1 score ranging from 15 . 0 for contrast to 47 . 9 for explanation (see table 5).<sep> The contrast relation is therefore very poorly identified, perhaps because it is under-represented, with only 42 examples compared to 70 for the other relations. The lack of data probably plays an important role here.<sep> The overall accuracy of the ARTONLY model is 47 . 8 when evaluated on the same type of data, that is, artificial ones (11 , 704 test examples), but only 23 . 0 when evaluated on natural data.<sep> This significant drop in performance is comparable to that observed in the previous studies on English.<sep> It can be attributed to the distribution differences described in section 3.2.<sep> In general, we observe a degradation compared to NATONLY for the identification of result and explanation (see table 5). On the other hand, the identification of contrast is improved, obtaining 23.2% of F1 with 11 correctly identified examples compared to 6 previously. Table 5. Basic models, system accuracy and F1 by relation<sep> 6.2 Models with Combinations of Data<sep> In this section, we present the results for the systems using both natural and artificial data.<sep> We either directly combine the data or use the data to build separate models that are then combined.<sep> Some of these models use hyper-parameters.<sep> When weighting the natural examples, we test weights c ∈ [0 , 5 , 1 , 5] and c ∈ [10 ; 2 000] with an increment of 10 until 100, of 50 until 1000 and of 500 until 2000.<sep> When adding random subsets of artificial data, we add each time k times the number of natural examples artificial examples with k ∈ [0 . 1; 600] with an increment of 0 . 1 until 1, of 10 until 100 and of 50 until 600.<sep> Finally, when taking a linear interpolation of the models, we build a new model by weighting the artificial model by α ∈ [0 . 1; 0 . 9] with increments of 0 . 1. (In the new model, we will weight the model built on the natural data by a coefficient of 1 − α.)<sep> The scores of the systems are shown in Table 6.<sep> Table 6. Models without sample selection, system accuracy and F1 by relation<sep> In general, we observe that most of the systems lead to similar or higher accuracy than NATONLY, but none of the improvements is statistically significant.<sep> The best system is ARTINIT (accuracy 40 . 1, p -value of 0 . 18 and a small effect size, 0 . 39).<sep> Two other systems get an accuracy score better than 39%, that is ADDPRED and LININT, with results still not significant.<sep> The system ADDPROB, similar to ADDPRED, leads to lower accuracy, showing that adding the probabilities decrease the performance.<sep> For these systems, the scores on each of the outer folds are very close[8] , especially for ADDPRED, revealing a high model stability.<sep> The other systems allow us to evaluate the impact of the artificial data on the final results.<sep> The only method leading to lower results is when training on the union of the data sets (UNION), the accuracy (22 . 6) is similar to ARTONLY.<sep> These results are not surprising: the natural data are about 372 times less numerous than the artificial ones, they are thus "drowned" in the artificial data.<sep> The experiments of combining data, adding random subsets of artificial data (ARTSUB, accuracy 34 . 5) or by weighting the natural examples (NATW, accuracy 38 . 9), show the influence of the relative importance between the two types of data on the accuracy of the systems.<sep> We can observe this effect by looking at the scores obtained in the inner loop of optimization: for these two systems, natural data must have a weight around 2.5 times higher than artificial data to obtain the best accuracy scores.<sep> The variance between the chosen hyperparameters values is very high for ARTSUB, this is probably due to the randomness of the choice of the subsets which can lead to important differences.<sep> It is a little less strong for NATW, showing that this method is more robust, but the a priori choice of a value for the hyperparameter remains wide (1,020 to more or less 272).<sep> The linear interpolation (LININT) of the two models allows us to observe the same effect. The best models are obtained with an average coefficient α equal to 0.3, so again an influence more than twice as strong.<sep> The standard deviation is relatively high but it seems reasonable to choose a priori for a future model a value corresponding to the average. The combination methods lead to systems of similar or higher accuracy than NATONLY. At the level of scores by relation, we observed during the optimization phase that a strong influence of artificial data tended to improve the identification of contrast and continuation.<sep> Thus the F1 average increases with the increase of the coefficient α and the linear interpolation of the models.<sep> On the contrary, a strong weight of artificial data leads to a strong degradation of the identification of results and explanation.<sep> The contrast relation may benefit from less noisy artificial data: the majority of examples (more than 75%) are constructed from mais , a form that is still in discursive use and whose arguments are in the canonical order, argument1 + connector + argument2.<sep> Differences in performance between classes can come from distributions that are more or less close between the two types of data.<sep> Looking at the distribution in terms of traits (850 traits in total), we see a gap of more than 30% for 2 and 5 traits for result and explanation but none for contrast and continuation, the relations for which the direct contribution of artificial data is positive.<sep> 6.3 Models with Automatic Selection of Examples<sep> Previous experiments showed that adding artificial data mostly improves the performance but still not significantly.<sep> Our hypothesis is that a lot of artificial data is noisy, which could hurt the model.<sep> Ideally, we would like to be able to select the most informative artificial examples that best complement the natural data.<sep> The method of selection of examples that we propose aims at eliminating potentially noisy examples.<sep> The artificial model is used on the training set, and we keep the examples that are predicted with a probability higher than a threshold s ∈ [0 . 3; 0 . 85] with an increment of 0 . 1 until 0 . 5 and of 0 . 05 until 0 . 85.<sep> If the model is confident enough about its prediction, the example might not correspond to noise, that is, a word form that does not have a discourse readings and/or a segmentation error.<sep> We also check whether the connective is redundant.<sep> For each threshold, we rebalance the data based on the least represented relation (system + SELEC). The scores of the systems are shown in Table 7.<sep> Table 7. Models with example selection, system accuracy, and F1 by relation; *signifies a result significantly better than NATONLY<sep> The automatic selection of examples allows to improve most of the previous results, showing the interest of this additional step.<sep> In particular, the system corresponding to the addition of predictive traits (ADDPRED + SELEC) corresponds to a clear tendency toward significant improvement in terms of accuracy compared to training on natural data only (p-value of 0.033 with a large effect size of 0.756 and a strong correlation of 0.842).<sep> The F1 scores for all classes are improved : 20 . 8 for contrast , 51 . 0 for result , 31 . 2 for continuation and 53 . 9 for explanation .<sep> Two other systems get an accuracy over 40: NATW+SELEC (accuracy 41 . 3, with a trend toward significance[8] ) and UNION+SELEC (no significantly higher than NATONLY).<sep> We note that ADDPRED corresponds to the best baseline in (Daumé III and Marcu, 2006), which shows the relevance of dealing with the distributions differences in our data through domain adaptation methods.<sep> In general, the selection phase allows a stronger weight on the information provided by the artificial data.<sep> For LININT+SELEC, the best results are obtained with an almost equal influence of the two models.<sep> In the same way, the mean of the chosen values for the coefficient for NATW+SELEC is much lower, and it increases a lot for ARTSUB+SELEC allowing for larger subsamples, however with a strong dispersion of the values.<sep> These considerations still support the hypothesis that the selection improves the quality of the artificial corpus.<sep> At the chosen thresholds, the mean over all the systems is around 0.7, with a variable standard deviation but always greater than 0.1.<sep> This deviation is pretty high, this hyper-parameter seems to be relatively poorly estimated by our internal cross-validation and would require future experiments, where we can reduce the search space.<sep> The selection of examples improves the identification of relations and leads to a system significantly improving the accuracy of NATONLY showing that the artificial data, when rightly integrated, can improve the identification of implicit relations, especially when their influence is low, the model being guided towards the good distribution.<sep> When creating the corpus with selection, we observed that with the growth of the threshold, we kept more and more examples for the result.<sep> From threshold 0, 4, we have about 3,900 more examples for this relation, while contrast becomes under-represented. This observation shows that noise is probably not the only way to explain the results since the relation improved by artificial data is the one for which the artificial model is the least confident while the relation whose results are the most degraded is the one for which the model is the most confident.<sep> 7. Conclusion and perspectives<sep> We have developed the first series of systems that identify implicit discourse relations for French.<sep> This kind of relation is difficult to identify because of the lack of strong indicators.<sep> In the previous studies on English, the performance on this task are fairly low despite the use of complex features, probably because of a lack of manually annotated data.<sep> To deal with this issue, even more crucial for French, we used automatically annotated data in relation to explicit examples.<sep> Although it seems that the strategy is relevant, in the sense that a connector can be redundant with its context, these new data do not allow a generalization that is suitable for natural implicit data, because they are of different distributions.<sep> We thus tested methods inspired by domain adaptation to combine natural and artificial data. We added an automatic selection of examples among the artificial data to deal with noise generated by the method of automatic annotation. This strategy allowed us to achieve significant improvements compared to the model using only natural data.<sep> The best systems use example selection, the best one relies on adding predictive features (41.7% accuracy), the second best one corresponds to manual data weighting (41.3%).<sep> First, these methods would need to be applied to English data in order to validate this first approach by comparison and to check whether it is possible to obtain results of the same order for another language.<sep> Then, as the simple combination and selection methods used here achieve encouraging results, we can hope that more sophisticated methods could lead to more significant improvements. We plan to test other methods used in domain adaptation, such as the regularization approach proposed by Chelba and Acero (2006), or the one based on a modification of the representation space of Daumé III (2007). Finally, a study of explicit data would allow us to increase the size of the artificial corpus.<sep> This could also lead to improving its quality by selecting connectors for which this method is more or less effective. It would also be necessary to identify the relations for which this method is not possible, either because these relations never appear without a connector (like violation of expectation contrasts) or, on the contrary, because they never appear with a connector (like the framing relation in ANNODIS). This study would also probably make it possible to find the most informative traits in terms of combining data.<sep> An example of a relation is a pair of text segments (or arguments) associated with a relation (or relation type, such as explanation, result, etc.).<sep> In the examples cited, the following convention is adopted: connectors are included in the argument formed by the clause of which they are syntactically dependent.<sep> Brackets delimit the elementary segments and brackets delimit the complex segments.<sep> 2. The definition of connectors used in this document corresponds to the lexicon described in section 5.<sep> 3. Here, "finally" can be seen as a connector, but according to our lexicon, it does not trigger the explanation relation.<sep> The presence of the present participle "accepting" can be seen as an ambiguous mark of the explanatory relation.<sep> Here, we consider as implicit the cases where no connective of our lexicon is present to lexicalize the annotated relation.<sep> 4. Details on this method are given in section 3. 5. The notion of "domain" is to be understood in a broad sense.<sep> It usually distinguishes texts on different themes (economic vs. Sport) or from the same source but covering different time periods (for newspaper articles, for example).<sep> More formally, to say that one has data in a field is to say that one has data following a certain distribution.<sep> Les données « out-of-domain » sont donc des données suivant une autre distribution (Daumé III et Marcu, 2006). 6. Lorsque nous faisons référence à de précédentes études, nous conservons les notations utilisées dans ces études pour le nom des relations car, selon le cadre théorique sous-jacent, un même nom ne recouvre pas nécessairement la même définition.<sep> 7. http://www.umiacs.umd.edu/~hal/megam/version0_3/<sep> 8. Standard deviation of 0.074 for ARTINIT for an average of 40.1 and 0.037 for ADDPRED and 0.061 for ADDPROB for an average of about 39.<sep> 9 p -value = 0 . 077, large effect size, 0 . 68 and high correlation, 0 . 67
Web search for the collection of Named Entities<sep> Abstract<sep> This study focuses on the acquisition of Named Entities (NEs) from the Web.<sep> The presented application consists of a page harvester and three surface analyzers dedicated to specific structures. Two evaluations are proposed: an evaluation of the productivity of the engines according to the types of NEs and a measure of the precision.<sep> 1 Overview<sep> Lexical acquisition from electronic corpora is now considered as a classic technique for enriching dictionaries (Boguraev and Pustejovsky, 1996).<sep> We are interested here in a particular type of lexical unit, the Named Entities (NE), a generic term for proper names designating people, places or organizations.<sep> While traditional electronic corpora such as journal articles or corpus resources (BNC, SUSANNE, Brown corpus) are satisfactory for classical lexical acquisition, Web corpora are another source of knowledge (Crimmins et al., 1999) that can be used to acquire NEs because of the constant updating of online data.<sep> As Hearst (1998) and Morin & Jacquemin (1999) use enumerative contexts for the detection of hyponym/hyperonym links, it relies on the beginnings of EN lists to detect ENs.<sep> Our approach differs from the approaches traditionally used in corpus linguistics in that it exploits information on the structure of documents to acquire data.<sep> It is similar to studies on wrappers, tools for analyzing semi-structured data (Kushmerick et al., 1997).<sep> The technique of acquiring NEs described here combines a harvester (associated with a web search engine) and surface analyzers of HTML pages whose grammars use lexical-syntactic information and formatting instructions within the same formalism.<sep> 2. Using Definitory Contexts<sep> - The acquisition of EN from the web poses two new problems in lexical acquisition:<sep> 1. While traditional text corpora can be accessed directly and entirely, web pages are only seen through the keyhole of search engines.<sep> In order to spot ENs, we must focus on linguistic cues that can be used to access pages containing typed NEs with high precision.<sep> 2. While Web pages are full of NEs, only a small proportion of them are relevant for the acquisition of public, fresh and wellknown NEs (the name of someone’s cat is not relevant to our purpose).<sep> In addition, automatically acquired ENs can only be included in electronic lexical databases if they are associated with types such as PERSON, LOCATION or ORGANISATION, or even finer types.<sep> The need for selective linguistic cues (wrt to the current facilities offered by search engines) and for informative and typifying contexts has led us to focus on collections, a specific type of definitory contexts (Péry-Woodley, 1998). Because they contain specific linguistic triggers such as following or such as, definitory contexts can be accessed through phrase queries to a search engine.<sep> In addition, these contexts use the classical scheme genus/differentia to define NEs, and thus provide, through the genus, a hypernym of the NEs they define.<sep> Our study extends the work of (Hearst, 1998; Morin & Jacquemin, 1999) to Web-based corpora with rich material formatting.<sep> 3 Architecture and Principles<sep> To acquire NEs from the Web, we have developed a system that consists of three sequential modules (see Figure 1):<sep> 1. A harvester that downloads the pages retrieved by a search engine from the four following query strings - (1.a) following (NE) (1.c) (NE) such as (1.b) list of (NE) (1.d) such (NE) as in which (NE) stands for a typifying hypernym of NEs such as Universities, politicians, or car makers (see list in 4).<sep> The full list of channels represented by EN is given in section 4.<sep> 2. Three surface analyzers Ae, Al and Aa which extract candidate named entities respectively from enumerations, lists and tables and anchors. 3. Coordinates in EN units.<sep> Web Corpus Harvesting<sep> The four strings (1.a-d) given above are used to query a search engine. They consist of an hypernym and a discourse marker.<sep> Figure 2 shows five prototypical examples of collections encountered in HTML pages retrieved through one of the previous queries.<sep> FIG. 1: Architecture of the acquisition of the EN<sep> The first collection is an enumeration and consists of a coordination of three ENs.<sep> The second collection is a list organized into two sublists.<sep> Each sublist is introduced by a hypernym.<sep> The third structure is also a list marked by bullets.<sep> Such lists can be constructed through an HTML table (this example), or by using enumeration marks (<ul> or <ol>).<sep> The fourth list is also built by using a table structure but is richer than the previous one because each item is accompanied by an image and preceded by a title.<sep> In the fifth example, the list is not present in the document, but is accessible by means of a hyperlink whose anchor contains the start.<sep> The corpus of HTML pages is collected through two search engines with different capabilities: AltaVista (AV) and Northern Light (NL).<sep> [3] AV offers an advanced search mode for strings while NL only searches for a "bag of words".<sep> In return, the number of documents accessible by NL is potentially unlimited[4] while AV only gives access to the 200 first documents.<sep> The choice of these two search engines is intended to evaluate whether a poorer query mode can be compensated by accessing more documents.<sep> Acquisition of Candidate NEs<sep> Three parallel shallow parsers Ae, Al and Aa are used to extract NEs from the corpora collected by the harvester.<sep> The grammars of these parsers are regular expressions built on the query strings (1.a-d) and on the HTML tags that signal the physical formatting of a collection.<sep> The following three types of spatio-syntactic structures are searched for: enumerations (parser Pc, first example in Figure 2), lists (parser Pl, the next three examples in Figure 2), and anchors to a page containing a collection of EN (parser Pa, bottom example in Figure 2).<sep> FIG. 2: Five different types of formatting of EN collections.<sep> These three parsers combine string matching (the initial lexical cue), syntactic analysis (enumerations in Pe), analysis of formatting instructions (lists and tables in Pl), and access to linked documents (in Pa).<sep> The results presented in this paper only concern the first two parsers. Since anchors raise specific problems in linguistic analysis (Amitay, 1999), they will be analyzed in another publication.<sep> A preliminary manual analysis of 100 anchors shows that 37% of them refer to a page containing a collection of expected EN and 9% of them point to a directory page containing one or more links to pages with such collections.<sep> The failed cases are made up of 40% of links to inaccessible URLs and 14% of links to pages that do not contain an EN collection and do not point to a page with an EN collection.<sep> The Enumeration Parser Ae<sep> An enumeration is expected to occur as a coordinated structure following the query string within the same sentence.<sep> Ae thus searches for the EN of patterns described by (3) within enumerations described by (4).<sep> The List Parser Al<sep> The lists are expected to occur no further than four lines after the sentence containing the query string.<sep> They are extracted using one of the following three patterns, which correspond to the three main ways of describing vertically aligned lists in HTML.<sep> The selected string is the shortest acceptable underlined pattern (case is not taken into account):<sep> After the removal of the HTML mark-up tags, only the longest subpart of the string accepted by (3) is provided to the final post-filtering module.<sep> These patterns do not cover the lists formatted with pre-formatted text (mark 3,kl`Kij8 ) or with line breaks by paragraphs (mark ( 3,km8 ).<sep> These modes of construction are ignored because they would produce too inaccurate results because they are not typical enough of lists.<sep> After stripping HTML tags, only the longest subparts of the strings accepted by (3) are provided to the final post-filtering module.<sep> These styles do not cover lists formatted using preformatted text (mark 3,kl`Kij8) or using line breaks to create paragraphs (mark ( 3,km8).<sep> These construction modes are ignored<sep> Post-filtering module<sep> The pre-candidate NEs produced by the parsers are filtered before being proposed as candidate NEs.<sep> The filters used are not very selective, which explains the good productivity of the search engines and their low precision.<sep> The roles of the filters are (in this order): - removal of trailing lower-case words, - deletion of the determiner the and the coordinating conjunctions and and or and the words which follow them, - rejection of pre-candidates that contain the characters @, {, # , ", $, ! or ?. - suppression of item marks such as 1., — * or a), - transformation of words in upper-case letters into words with only the first letter capitalised in the EN candidates that are not organisations (in the hypothesis where only the names of organisations contain acronyms in upper-case letters).<sep> Postfiltering is completed by discarding single-word candidates, that are described as common words in the CELEX 4 database, and multi-word candidates that contain more than 5 words.<sep> TABLE 1: Sizes of the HTML document corpora (in Mb) collected on the 4 patterns (1.a-d).<sep> 4. Experiments and Evaluations<sep> The acquisition of NEs is performed on 34 types of NEs chosen arbitrarily among three subtypes of the MUC typology: ORGANIZATION (American companies, international organizations, universities, political organizations, international agencies, car makers, terrorist groups, financial institutions, museums, international companies, holdings, sects, and realtors), PERSON (politicians, VIPs, actors, managers, celebrities, actresses, athletes, authors, film directors, top models, musicians, singers, and journalists), and LOCATION (countries, regions, states, lakes, cities, rivers, mountains, and islands).<sep> Each of these 34 types is combined with the four discourse markers given in (1.a-d), yielding 136 queries for the two search engines.<sep> Each of the 272 HTML corpora collected through the harvester is made of at most 200 documents on AV in the chain search mode and at most 2,000 documents on NL in the standard search mode.<sep> These documents are processed by enumeration and list parsers.<sep> The total corpus collected is 2,958 Mb (368 Mb are extracted by AV and 2,590 Mb by NL);<sep> It is subdivided as shown in Table 1.<sep> The documents recovered by NL for the pattern list of EN represent more than a half of the documents extracted by NL (1,307 Mb).<sep> The most productive pattern for AV is EN such as through which 41% of the AV collection is obtained (150 Mb).<sep> Quantitative measures<sep> In all, 44,624 EN candidates are produced: 17,116 from AV corpus and 34,978 from NL corpus.<sep> The use of larger corpora with NL compensates for its lower accuracy than AV since the production from the NL corpora is greater than that from the AV corpora.<sep> However, the cost (calculation and network access) is higher for candidates from NL than from AV since more textual data must be collected and analyzed to produce the same volume of terms.<sep> In addition to the number of candidates produced for each of the search engines and for each of the four families of chains, Table 2 provides four measures for which the highest values are in bold and the lowest values are in italics.<sep> Productivity. The productivity is the average number of candidates produced for a collection of 100kb.<sep> The productivity is 3.5 times higher for AV (46.7) than for NL (13.5), which means that the use of a search engine allowing more precise queries requires 3.5 times less data to reach the same number of candidates.<sep> The ratio of enumerations to lists measures the ratio of the number of EN enumerations encountered in the documents analyzed by Ae to the number of EN lists in the documents analyzed by Al.<sep> As expected, there are 11 times more enumerations than lists after EN such as and 18 times more after such EN as . The output is more balanced with list of EN : there are only 1.66 times more lists than enumerations.<sep> The large number of enumerations produced from this pattern certainly relies on the combination of linguistic information and formatting cues in the construction of meaning.<sep> In order to satisfy Grice's maxim of quantity (1975), the writer avoids using the word list when the text is followed by a (physical) list.<sep> Table 2: Size of the number of candidate NEs acquired from the web-based corpora described in Table 1.<sep> Redundancy in acquisition of EN is the rate of candidates acquired more than once for a search engine. Redundancy comes from the fact that the same EN can be acquired from several distinct lists or enumerations within the same corpus.<sep> On average, redundancy is 2.09: each candidate is acquired slightly more than two times.<sep> In addition, the same result can be obtained independently by the two search engines.<sep> The recovery is the ratio of the number of candidates acquired jointly by AV and NL to the total number of candidates. Due to the different search modes on the two search engines, different indexing areas on the web and the types of indexes built, the recovery is only 15%.<sep> In such a context, the two search engines seem to be complementary rather than competitive because they retrieve different sets of documents.<sep> Precision of Acquisition<sep> Among the 44,624 EN produced by the module, a set of 339 candidates is chosen for testing.<sep> For each candidate, an advanced query is formulated on AV composed of the string of the NE and the topmost 20 pages retrieved by the search engine are noted. These pages are manually analysed to verify that the candidate NE unambiguously designates a person, a place or an organisation of the expected type.<sep> The manual inspection of the candidate ENs gives a precision of 55% with errors distributed as follows: 25% incorrect, 24% incomplete, 8% over-complete and 43% diverse.<sep> The analysis of the near context sometimes provides an incorrect typing of EN.<sep> For instance, Ashley Judd (an actress) is incorrectly reported as an athlete from the occurrence His clientele includes stars and athletes such as Ashley Judd and Mats Sundin.<sep> His clientele includes stars and athletes such as Ashley Judd and Mats Sundin.<sep> The error is due to an incorrect analysis of the initializer: only athletes is seen as the hypernym while stars is also part of it.<sep> Other wrong types are due to polysemy. For instance, actors has a metaphorical meaning in computer science.<sep> Incomplete extraction of candidates is mainly due to the partial expression of EN in lists or enumerations where they appear.<sep> For example, the author's name Goffman is drawn from the work of such authors as Laing, Szasz, Goffman, Sartre, Bateson, and Freud.<sep> Readings are drawn from the work of such authors as Laing, Szasz, Goffman, Sartre, Bateson, and Freud.<sep> Since this enumeration does not contain the first names of the authors, it is not appropriate for an unambiguous acquisition of the authors' names.<sep> In addition, some proper names, even if complete, are ambiguous and are also counted as errors because they lead to incorrect recognitions of EN. For example, Lucero is a software company, a Mexican singer and actress, the name of a sculptor, a magazine, etc.<sep> Excessive extractions are due to parsing errors or to collections that contain independent words that are incorrectly collected together with the name.<sep> For instance, O. Shtrichman Next is extracted from a list of author names where the name O. Shtrichman is followed by a hyperlink Next.<sep> Other types of errors are due to an incorrect analysis of the web page and cannot be classified due to a lack of clear connection between the candidate and the entity they designate.<sep> 5. Refinement of the Types of NEs<sep> The typing of the candidate NEs described so far is based on the hypernym of the NE given in the sequences (1.a-d).<sep> However, the initializer preceding the collection of NEs to be extracted can contain more information on the type of the following NEs.<sep> More precisely, the initializer fulfills four distinct functions: 1. introduces the presence and the proximity of the enumeration, e.g. Here is (Voici) ;<sep> 2. describes the structure of the enumeration, e.g. a list of<sep> 3. describes the hyperonym, i.e. the category of the items of the enumeration, e.g. universities ;<sep> 4. specifies the particular characteristics of each item. e.g. universities in Vietnam<sep> The cues used by the harvester are elements which either introduce the collection (e.g. the .following) or describe the structure (e.g. list of).<sep> In general, in an initializer, these two functions need not be expressed explicitly by lexical means, as the layout itself indicates the presence and type of the collection.<sep> Readers exploit the visual properties of written text to aid the construction of meaning (P6ry-Woodley, 1998).<sep> However it is necessary to be explicit when defining the items of the collection as this information is not available to the reader via structural properties.<sep> The initializers generally contain additional characteristics of the items which provide the differentia (underlined here):<sep> This is a list off American companies with business interests in Latvia.<sep> (Here is a list of American companies with business interests in Latvia)<sep> This sequence is the most explicit form of an initializer, containing four lexical elements, each of which corresponds to one of the functions outlined above.<sep> It is fairly simple to extract the details of the items from the collection, as the hypernym is modified by a relative clause, a prepositional phrase or an adjectival phrase.<sep> Figure 3[7] shows a detailed grammar of this form of initializer.<sep> Before being analysed, the tags are labelled by the TreeTagger (Schmid, 1999).<sep> The elements which express the differentia are extracted by means of pattern matching: they are always the modifiers of the plural noun in the string, which is the hypernym of the items of the collection.<sep> Initializers containing the search string such as behave somewhat differently.<sep> They are not saturated on the syntactic level and the missing constituent is provided by each item of the collection (Virbel et al., 1999).<sep> The structure of these phrases can take many forms and complex syntactic analysis is required to extract the properties of the hypernym.<sep> We will not discuss these in more detail here.<sep> One type of error in the analysis of the leads is due to paragraphs that contain the search string followed by a list that is not related to it.<sep> For example the harvester recognizes Ask the long list of American companies who have unsuccessfully marketed products in Japan.<sep> (Ask the long list of American companies that have unsuccessfully launched products in the Japanese market) as a starter, although it is not related to any collection.<sep> If this sequence was followed on the page by a collection of any type, the system would collect its items with an incorrect class, the one provided by the defining list.<sep> The cue list of is commonly used in discursive texts, so some filtering is required to identify collections which are not employed as initializers and to reduce the collection of erroneous items.<sep> This allows us to reduce the errors in the classification of entities.<sep> Analyzing the syntactic forms has allowed us to construct a set of regular expressions which are used to eliminate noninitializers and disregard any items collected following them.<sep> We have extracted 1813 potential initializers from the corpus of HTML pages collected via AV & NL for the query string list of EN.<sep> A surface analyzer filters and analyzes the sequences using lexico-syntactic patterns in order to identify correct initializers.<sep> This parser consists of 14 modules, 4 of which carry out pre-filtering to prepare and tag the corpus, and 10 of which carry out a fine-grained syntactic analysis, removing collections that do not function as initializers.<sep> After filtering, the corpus contains 520 sequences.<sep> The process has a precision of 78% and a recall of 90%.<sep> 6 Conclusion<sep> This study is another application that demonstrates the usability of the WWW as a resource for NLP (see, for instance, (Grefenstette, 1999) for an application of using WWW frequencies in selecting translations).<sep> The precision for the acquisition of NE is only 55%, requiring human filtering that can be done from the web as was done for validation.<sep> It should be noted, however, that the value of the precision was established under very demanding conditions (rejection of partial forms and ambiguous ENs).<sep> Accepting such forms and rejecting only incorrect EN candidates gives an accuracy of 81%.<sep> The accuracy of the primer analysis is 78% and therefore defines a precise typing of the EN.<sep> 1 For example, the BNC (http://info.ox.ac.uk/bnc/) for English or the CLEF corpus (http ://www.biomath.jussieu.fr/CLEF/) for French.<sep> 2 In the examples of figure 2, EN is the international organizations string;<sep> The typographical highlights were added by us.<sep> 3 The harvester that retrieves Web pages is a combination of wget available from ftp://sunsite.auc.dk/pub/infosystems/wget/ and Perl scripts.<sep> 4 For reasons of computation time and corpus sizes, we limited ourselves to the first 2000 documents on NL.<sep> 5 The actual patterns are more complicated to accept diacriticized letters and abbreviations.<sep> 6 The CELEX lexical database for English is distributed by the Consortium for Lexical Resources at the URL www.ldc.upenn.edu/readme_files/celex.readme.html.<sep> 7 SP = prepositional phrase, N = noun (singular), N pl = noun (plural), adj = adjective, V = verb in present tense, rel.cl. = relative clause.
Segment and structure texts thematically by using collocations and lexical recurrence<sep> Abstract<sep> We present in this paper a method for achieving in an integrated way two tasks of topic analysis: segmentation and link detection.<sep> This method combines word repetition and the lexical cohesion stated by a collocation network to compensate for the respective weaknesses of the two approaches.<sep> We report an evaluation of our method for segmentation on two corpora, one in French and one in English, and we propose an evaluation measure that specifically suits that kind of systems.<sep> Keywords: Discourse analysis, topic analysis, topic segmentation, link detection.<sep> 1 Introduction<sep> Topic analysis, which aims at identifying the topics of a text, delimiting their extend and finding the relations between the resulting segments, has recently raised an important interest.<sep> Most of them are dedicated to thematic segmentation or are part of the TDT (Topic Detection and Tracking) evaluation. The latter addresses the three axes mentioned above but from a domain-dependent viewpoint and not necessarily in an integrated way.<sep> Systems that implement this work can be categorized according to what kind of knowledge they use.<sep> Most of those dedicated to thematic segmentation, that is to say the division of texts into thematically homogeneous segments, rely solely on the intrinsic characteristics of texts such as the distribution of words (Hearst, 1997), (Choi, 2000) and (Utiyama and Isahara, 2001), or linguistic cues (Passonneau and Litman, 1997).<sep> They can be applied without restriction about domains but have low results when a text doesn’t characterize its topical structure by surface clues.<sep> A second type of system uses knowledge characterising the notion of lexical cohesion. This knowledge, which is not linked to a domain, takes the form of a network of words constructed from a dictionary (Kozima, 1993; Morris, Hirst, 1991) or a large set of collocations collected from a corpus (Ferret, 1998; Kaufmann, 1999; Choi, 2001). Thanks to the relationships between words that they contain (synonymy, hyperonymy, etc.), these knowledge bases make it possible to discard false topical shifts defined on the basis of ruptures existing at the level of the recurrence of words.<sep> The last main type of systems relies on knowledge directly related to the topics appearing in the texts they process.<sep> In the case of TDT for example, this knowledge is automatically built from a set of reference texts characterising each theme considered.<sep> The work of Bigi et al. (1998) stands in the same perspective but focuses on much larger topics than TDT.<sep> These systems have a limited scope due to their topic representations but they are more precise for the same reason.<sep> The thematic analysis method we propose in this article differs from the works we have just discussed on two main points.<sep> Firstly, it simultaneously achieves topic segmentation and link detection, i.e. determining whether two segments discuss the same topic. This is the first step towards the thematic structuring of texts.<sep> Then, it implements a hybrid approach: it is based on a resource that accounts for lexical cohesion, in this case a network of collocations, but it exploits it in conjunction with lexical recurrence in texts.<sep> We detail in this paper the implementation of this method by the TOPICOLL system, we report evaluations of its capabilities concerning segmentation for two languages, French and English, and finally, we propose an evaluation measure that integrates both segmentation and link detection.<sep> 2 Overview of TOPICOLL<sep> In accordance with much work about discourse analysis, TOPICOLL processes texts linearly: it detects topic shifts and finds links between segments without delaying its decision, i.e. , by only taking into account the part of text that has been already analyzed.<sep> A window that delimits the current focus of the analysis is moved over the entire text to be processed.<sep> This window contains the lemmatized content words of the text, resulting from its pre-processing.<sep> A topic context is associated to this focus window.<sep> It is made up of both the words of the window and the words that are selected from a collocation network[1] as strongly linked to the words of the window.<sep> The current segment is also given a topic context.<sep> This context results from the fusion of the contexts associated to the focus window when this window was in the segment space.<sep> A change of topic is detected when the context of the focus window and the context of the current segment are not similar any more for several successive positions of the focus window.<sep> The detection of thematic links is performed by comparing the thematic context of each new segment to that of the previously defined segments.<sep> TOPICOLL thus takes up the general principle of analysis of the SEGAPSITH system (Ferret, Grau, 2000) by introducing, at the level of thematic contexts, the characterisation of lexical cohesion developed within the framework of the SEGCOHLEX system (Ferret, 1998).<sep> The use of a collocation network permits TOPICOLL to find relations beyond word recurrence and to associate a richer topical representation to segments, which facilitates tasks such as link detection or topic identification.<sep> However, work such as (Kozima, 1993), (Ferret, 1998) or (Kaufmann, 1999) showed that using a domain-independent source of knowledge for text segmentation doesn’t necessarily lead to get better results than work that is only based on word distribution in texts.<sep> The methods used do not control the type of relations they select precisely enough and do not take into account the incompleteness of their knowledge.<sep> Hence, while they discard some incorrect topic shifts found by methods based on word recurrence, they also find incorrect shifts when the relevant relations are not present in their knowledge or don’t find some correct shifts because of the selection of non relevant relations from a topical viewpoint.<sep> By combining word recurrence and relations selected from a collocation network, TOPICOLL aims at exploiting a domain-independent source of knowledge in a more accurate way.<sep> 3 Collocation networks<sep> TOPICOLL depends on a collocation network that is specific to each language it processes.<sep> The one for French was built from 24 months of the Le Monde newspaper selected between 1990 and 1994, respecting a balance between years and between months; the one for English was built from two years of the Los Angeles Times newspaper, part of the TREC corpus.<sep> In both cases, the corpus contains around 40 million words.<sep> For each network, the initial corpus was first pre-processed in order to characterize texts by their most thematically significant words, that is, nouns, verbs and adjectives, given in lemmatized form.<sep> The ambiguities of lemmatization were resolved thanks to a morphosyntactic tagger.<sep> Collocations were then extracted using a sliding window according to the method described in (Church and Hanks, 1990).<sep> The parameters of this extraction were set to favour the capture of topical relations: the window was rather large, 20 words wide, and took into account the boundaries of texts; moreover, collocations were indifferent to word order.<sep> We also adopted an evaluation of mutual information as a cohesion measure of each collocation. This measure was normalized according to the maximal mutual information relative to the considered corpus.<sep> After filtering the less significant collocations (collocations with less than 10 occurrences and cohesion lower than 0.1), we got a network with approximately 23,000 words and 5.2 million collocations for French, 30,000 words and 4.8 million collocations for English.<sep> 4 Description of TOPICOLL<sep> TOPICOLL is based on the creation, the update and the use of a topical representation of the segments it defines and the content of its focus window at each position of a text.<sep> These topical representations are called topic contexts .<sep> 4.1 Topic contexts<sep> A topic context characterizes the topical dimension of the entity it is associated to by two vectors: the text vector and the collocation vector.<sep> Each of their coordinates represents a word and its value corresponds to a weight expressing the relative importance of this word compared to the other words of the vector. The text vector is composed of words coming from the text that is analyzed while the collocation vector contains words selected from a collocation network and strongly linked to the words of the processed text. For both vectors, the weight of a word expresses its importance with regard to the other words of the vector.<sep> 4.1.1 Topic context of the focus window<sep> The text vector of the context associated to the focus window is made up of the content words of the window.<sep> The weight given by (1) combines the importance of w in the part of text delimited by the window and its general significance. This significance is defined as in (Kozima, 1993) as its normalized information in a reference corpus[2] :<sep> Figure 1: Selection and weighting of the words in the collocation network<sep> The building of the collocation vector for the window’s context comes from the procedure presented in (Ferret, 1998) for evaluating the lexical cohesion of a text.<sep> It consists in selecting words of the collocation network that are topically close to those in the window.<sep> We assume that this closeness is related to the number of links that exist between a word of the network and the words of the window.<sep> Thus, a word of the network is selected if it is linked to at least a minimum number - 3 in our experiments - of words of the window.<sep> Each selected word from the network is then assigned a weight. This weight is equal to the sum of the contributions of the window words to which it is linked to. The contribution of a word of the window to the weight of a selected word is equal to its weight in the window, given by (1), modulated by the cohesion measure between these two words in the network (see Figure 1).<sep> We therefore obtain for a position t of the window:<sep> where coh(m,mi) is the measure of the cohesion between m and mi in the collocation network.<sep> 4.1.2 Topic context of a segment<sep> The topic context of a segment results from the fusion of the contexts associated to the focus window when it was inside the segment.<sep> This fusion is achieved as the segment is extended: the context associated to each new position of the segment is combined with the current context of the segment.<sep> This combination, which is done separately for text and collocation vectors, consists in merging two lists of weighted words. First, the words of the window context that are not in the segment context are added to it.<sep> Then, the weight of each word of the resulting list is computed according to its weight in the window context and its previous weight in the segment context:<sep> with Cf , the context of the window, Cs , the context of the segment and wghtx(m, C{s,f},t) , the weight of the word m in the vector x (txt or coll) of the context C{s,f} for the position t and signif(m) , the degree of specificity of m outside the context (see 4.1.1).<sep> For the words from the window context that are not part of the segment context, wghtx(w,Cs,t-1) is equal to 0.<sep> For those of Cs, the revaluation of the weight given by (2) represents a compromise concerning the speed of evolution of the segment contexts: it allows to free oneself from the micro-variations in the way a theme is expressed within a segment while following the thematic evolution of the context of the window close enough not to miss a change of theme.<sep> 4.1.3 Similarity between thematic contexts<sep> In order to determine if the content of the focus window is topically coherent or not with the current segment, the topic context of the window is compared to the topic context of the segment.<sep> This comparison is performed in two stages: first, a similarity measure is computed between the vectors of the two contexts; then, the resulting values are exploited by a decision procedure that states if the two contexts are similar.<sep> As (Choi, 2000) or (Kaufmann, 1999), we use the cosine measure for evaluating the similarity between a vector of the context window ( Vw ) and the equivalent vector in the segment context ( Vs ):<sep> where wgx(mi,C{s,f}, t) is the weight of the word mi in the vector x (txt or coll) of the context C{s,f} .<sep> In order to minimize noise in the vectors, this measure only takes into account the most recurrent words of the segment contexts, the importance of a word in a context being supposed to be correlated with its recurrence within it. This recurrence is defined as the proportion, among the focusing window contexts that have made it possible to constitute the segment context, of those containing the word considered.<sep> This score must be above a set threshold for the word to be kept.<sep> This threshold is higher for text vectors than for collocation vectors, due to the greater heterogeneity of words coming from texts.<sep> The decision stage takes root in work about combining results of several systems that achieve the same task.<sep> In our case, the evaluation of the similarity between Cs and Cw at each position is based on a vote that synthesizes the viewpoint of the text vector and the viewpoint of the collocation vector.<sep> First, the value of the similarity measure for each vector is compared to a fixed threshold and a positive vote in favor of the similarity of the two contexts is decided if the value exceeds this threshold.<sep> Finally, the global similarity of the two contexts is rejected only if the votes for the two vectors are negative.<sep> 4.2 Topic segmentation<sep> The algorithm for detecting topic shifts is taken from (Ferret and Grau, 2000) and basically relies on the following principle: at each text position, if the similarity between the topic context of the focus window and the topic context of the current segment is rejected (see 4.1.3), a topic shift is assumed and a new segment is opened.<sep> Otherwise, the active segment is extended up to the current position.<sep> This basic algorithm assumes that the transition between two segments is punctual and unambiguous.<sep> In reality, the similarity between contexts can be locally fluctuating due to the surface form of the texts.<sep> It is therefore preferable to introduce a delay before deciding whether the active segment really ends or whether a new segment is opening.<sep> To take this uncertainty into account, the segmentation algorithm takes the form of an automaton (see Figure 2) whose transitions are controlled by the following three parameters: - the current state of TOPICOLL;<sep> - the similarity between the context of the focus window and the context of the current segment: Sim or no Sim ;<sep> – the number of successive positions of the focus window for which the current state doesn’t change: confirmNb.<sep> It must exceed the Tconfirm threshold (equal to 3 in our experiments) for leaving the NewTopicDetection or the EndTopicDetection state.<sep> Figure 2: The theme change detection agent<sep> At the beginning of a new text or after the end of a segment has been detected, TOPICOLL is in the ChangementThème state.<sep> As soon as the thematic context of the focus window remains stable from one position to another with respect to (3), it enters the DetectNewTheme state.<sep> It can then only reach the state ThemeDevelopment if this stability is maintained for the next nbConfirm - 1 positions.<sep> Otherwise, it assumes that it is a false alarm and returns to the ChangingTheme state.<sep> The detection of the end of a segment is the symmetrical of the detection of its beginning.<sep> TOPICOLL enters the DetectionChangeTheme state as soon as the context of the focusing window changes significantly between two successive positions.<sep> The transition to the ChangeTheme state is only carried out, however, if this change is confirmed for the next nbConfirm - 1 positions.<sep> 4.3 Detection of thematic links<sep> The algorithm of TOPICOLL for detecting identity links between segments is closely associated to its algorithm for delimiting segments.<sep> Before entering the DevelopmentTheme state, TOPICOLL checks whether the context of the new segment is similar to the context of one of the segments already defined.<sep> In this case, the similarity between contexts only relies on the application of (3) between the collocation vectors of the contexts and the comparison with a specific threshold.<sep> If the similarity value exceeds this threshold, the new segment is linked to the corresponding segment and takes the context of this one as its own context.<sep> In this way, TOPICOLL assumes that the new segment continues to develop a previous topic.<sep> When several segments are possible, TOPICOLL selects the one with the strongest context similarity.<sep> 5 Experiments<sep> 5.1 Topic segmentation<sep> To evaluate the thematic segmentation capabilities of TOPICOLL, we applied it to the classical task of rediscovering the boundaries of a set of concatenated texts.<sep> For the measurement of performance, we used the probabilistic error metric Pk proposed in (Beeferman et al., 1999) and now widely used[3] .<sep> Recall and precision was computed for the Le Monde corpus to compare TOPICOLL with older systems[5] .<sep> 5.1.1 Evaluation of segmentation for French: Le Monde corpus<sep> The evaluation corpus for French was made up of 49 texts, 133 words long on average, from the Le Monde newspaper (1995) covering 11 themes.<sep> The results in Table 1 are average values computed from 10 different sequences of these texts.<sep> The baseline procedure consisted in randomly choosing a fixed number of sentence ends as boundaries.<sep> Its results in Table 1 are average values from 1,000 draws.<sep> TOPICOLL1 is the system described in section 4.<sep> TOPICOLL2 is the same system but without its link detection part.<sep> The results of these two variants show that the search for links between segments doesn’t significantly degrade TOPICOLL’s capabilities for segmentation.<sep> TextTiling is our implementation of Hearst’s algorithm with its standard parameters.<sep> Table 1 shows clearly that TOPICOLL gets better results than a system that only relies on a collocation network such as SEGCOHLEX.<sep> This advantage also exists in comparison to systems such as TextTiling that are based on lexical recurrence and work like TOPICOLL with a local context.<sep> These elements seem to indicate that the joint use of collocations and lexical recurrence is an interesting approach.<sep> Moreover, TOPICOLL is more accurate than a system such as SEGAPSITH that depends on topic representations.<sep> Its performance is also slightly higher than the one reported in (Bigi et al., 1998) for a system that uses topic representations in a probabilistic way: 0.75 as precision, 0.80 as recall and 0.77 as f1-measure on a corpus made of Le Monde ’s articles too.<sep> Table 1: Precision/Recall and Pk for the Monde corpus[4]<sep> 5.1.2 Evaluation of segmentation for English: Choi corpus<sep> Table 2: Pk for the Choi corpus<sep> For English, we used the artificial corpus built by Choi (Choi, 2000) for comparing several segmentation systems.<sep> This corpus is made up of 700 artificial texts, each consisting of 10 segments, each segment being formed of the first n sentences of documents from the Brown corpus.<sep> The first seven lines of Table 2 result from Choi’s experiments (Choi, 2001).<sep> The basic procedure systematically partitions each document into 10 segments of equal length.<sep> Table 2 confirms that the detection of thematic links does not alter the segmentation capabilities of TOPICOLL.<sep> It also shows that TOPICOLL’s results on this corpus are significantly lower than its results on the Le Monde corpus.<sep> This is partially due to our collocation network for English: its density, i.e. the ratio between the size of its vocabulary and its number of collocations, is 30% lower than the density of the network for French, which has certainly a significant effect.<sep> Table 3 also shows that TOPICOLL, which only uses a local context, has worse results than systems such as CWM, U00, C99 or DOTPLOT, which process the whole text they are submitted to.<sep> This global view improves accuracy but results in greater algorithmic complexity.<sep> Moreover, the detection of thematic links made possible by the thematic contexts makes TOPICOLL functionally richer.<sep> 5.2 Global evaluation<sep> The global evaluation of a system such as TOPICOLL faces a problem: a reference for link detection is necessarily linked to a reference for segmentation.<sep> Hence, mapping it onto the segments defined by the system to evaluate is not a straightforward operation.<sep> To bypass this problem, we chose an approach close to the one adopted in TDT for the link detection task: we evaluated the probability of an error in classifying each couple of positions in a text as being part of the same topic ( Cpsame ) or belonging to different topics ( Cpdiff ).<sep> A false negative is detected if a couple is found about different topics while they are about the same topic and a false alarm corresponds to the complementary case.<sep> Table 3: Overall measures for the Le Monde corpus<sep> As the number of Cpdiff couples is generally much larger than the number of Cpsame couples, we randomly selected a number of Cpdiff couples equal to the number of Cpsame couples in order to have a large range of possible values.<sep> Table 3 shows the results of TOPICOLL for this measure and compares them to a baseline procedure randomly selecting a fixed number of segment boundaries and thematic identity links between segments.<sep> This measure is a first proposition that should certainly be improved, especially for balancing more soundly misses and false alarms.<sep> 6 Conclusion<sep> We have proposed a method for achieving both topic segmentation and link detection by using collocations together with word recurrence in texts.<sep> Its evaluation showed the soundness of this approach for working with a local context.<sep> In order to extend its validation, we plan to apply it to methods that rely on a global understanding of texts.<sep> We also aim at extending the evaluation part of this work by improving the global measure we have proposed and by comparing our results to human judgments.<sep> 1 We define the theme here as a configuration of semantic units of inter-textual nature, that is, observable between several texts and several authors. 2 The nodes of this network are constituted by words and the edges, by collocations between these words.<sep> 3 Pk evaluates the probability that a randomly chosen pair of words, separated by k words, is wrongly classified, i.e. they are found in the same segment by TOPICOLL while they are actually in different ones (miss of a document break) or they are found in different segments by TOPICOLL while they are actually in the same one (false alarm).<sep> k is equal to half the average segment size at the level of the reference corpus.<sep> 4 Precision is defined by Nc / Nb and recall by Nc / D , where Nb is the number of document breaks found by TOPICOLL, Nc is the number of correct document breaks, i.e. corresponding to text boundaries in a range of 9 full words around this boundary, and D the total number of text boundaries.
Evaluating semi-automatic acquisition of semantic classes<sep> Abstract<sep> This paper aims to evaluate two different approaches for the constitution of semantic classes.<sep> An endogenous approach (corpus-based learning) is contrasted with an exogenous one (through a rich semantic network).<sep> The article presents a fine evaluation of these two techniques.<sep> Keywords: Semantic classes, Evaluation, Resources, Semantic network<sep> 1 Introduction: general resources vs. specific resources<sep> This paper aims to evaluate two approaches for the constitution of semantic classes.<sep> We are in the perspective of an application of information extraction, for which the notion of semantic class is primordial[1] .<sep> In this introduction we consider the two main approaches that are commonly used: direct access to general resources and the dynamic development of resources from the working corpus.<sep> The utility of general resources has been strongly criticized in the last few years.<sep> The main objections are enumerated in D. Dutoit’s thesis (Dutoit, 2000):<sep> - General linguistic resources (especially large semantic networks) are rarely usable in context since they encode abstract data but not the main linguistic features specific of the domain to be addressed.<sep> - Even if relevant information has been encoded, this information is lost among a large set of irrelevant information. Finding and using the good information is then a difficult task.<sep> - The information that has to be encoded is so large that the task is potentially infinite and, so, is doomed to failure (Victorri, 1998).<sep> The usability of a linguistic resource is largely dependent of the way it is structured.<sep> From this point of view, it should be noted that most of the above criticisms concerned the Princeton version of Wordnet (Fellbaum, 1998), which certainly suffers from a lack of structuring to be optimally used in an applicative context.<sep> On a more theoretical level, understanding is a process implying different kind of knowledge and the use of a semantic network, even if it is incomplete, lead to a more realistic situation compared to the sole use of the corpus as a reservoir of knowledge.<sep> No understanding mechanism can be satisfied with a purely endogenous analysis, where all knowledge comes from the immediate context.<sep> However, several researchers refused these arguments and have investigated some automatic procedure to automatically derived semantic classes from a representative corpus (Hirschmann et al , 1975) (Grishman et Sterling, 1994).<sep> The acquisition methods based on corpora are mostly based on a "distributionalist hypothesis" (Harris, 1951): in a sublanguage, regular syntactic structures allow to highlight word families occurring in common contexts.<sep> These distributional word families are a basis for the elaboration of semantic classes.<sep> This approach is attractive but the results are nuanced. The question of the size of the corpus, its nature and its variability is indeed crucial.<sep> This aspect is relatively little addressed in the reports of experiments, which often deal with regular or technical corpora (for example, Nazarenko et al. (1997) propose an experiment on the medical field, Faure (2000) on cooking recipes).<sep> Moreover, most of the studies mention that the classes obtained automatically are not completely satisfactory (Nazarenko et al. , 2001): they cannot be directly injected in an operational application.<sep> Several well-known reasons can be given for this state of affairs:<sep> - Even in a sublanguage, a syntactic schema can be ambiguous ; - Words appearing in different contexts are linked by various kinds of relations. These relations can be specific to a given context.<sep> - Some words that are very frequent and very general induce semantically irrelevant classes.<sep> It is therefore necessary to inject knowledge into the acquisition system to improve the results and make it usable.<sep> The learning process is then supervised, like in the experiment from Nazarenko et al. (2001) who propose to adapt the medical nomenclature SNOMED to the MENELAS corpus.<sep> The authors project the categories of SNOMED on the results of the distributional analysis, which contributes to a refinement of the semantic classes that were otherwise automatically obtained from the corpus.<sep> Morin and Jacquemin (1999) use a similar technique to specialize a thesaurus (AGROVOC) in relation with a technical corpus.<sep> The debate is therefore less clear than it might seem at first between general resources and specialised resources.<sep> We propose to re-investigate this question in this paper from an applicative point of view, by comparing two approaches for the semi-automatic acquisition of semantic classes.<sep> We firstly evaluate the ASIUM system that proposes an automatic acquisition from a corpus and then an interactive validation phase (section 3).<sep> We will then do the same experiment with the semantic network from MEMODATA (Dutoit, 2000), which is currently, as far as we know, the richest semantic network for French (section 4).<sep> We will then present conclusions on the evaluation process itself (section 5).<sep> 2 Experiment protocol<sep> The experiments that are described here have been performed on a financial corpus.<sep> 300 news stories reporting company transactions in French have been selected (this constitutes the FIRSTINVEST corpus).<sep> The set of news stories is divided in two parts: 57 stories for the test corpus, 243 for the training corpus.<sep> An information extraction system on that domain has been developed.<sep> The manually elaborated resources included semantic classes that have been considered as a reference for the further experiments we have done in this domain.<sep> 3 An interactive symbolic machine learning approach for the automatic acquisition of semantic classes<sep> We have evaluated the contribution of a machine learning system to acquire knowledge from texts and elaborate the resources dedicated to an Information Extraction system.<sep> We gave below a brief description of the ASIUM system that we used (for a more detailed description, please refer to (Faure et Nédellec, 1998), (Faure, 2000)).<sep> 3.1 The ASIUM acquisition system<sep> The ASIUM system provides knowledge acquired from unstructured texts that have previously been syntactically analyzed.<sep> ASIUM aims at helping the user to create a set of semantic classes relevant to the task and to formalise them into ontologies.<sep> These ontologies must make it possible to clearly show the existing relationships between classes.<sep> The originality of the method lies essentially in the interactive validation phase.<sep> The approach is based on a distributional analysis that allows to generate classes of words appearing in similar contexts (the base classes).<sep> The similarity measure implemented in ASIUM gives a score for the coverage of a class compared to another one. The system then proposes to group together classes that have a similarity measure above a certain threshold (this threshold is empirically fixed by the expert).<sep> The base classes are progressively aggregated following a cooperative bottom-up method.<sep> This classification process is not limited to lists of words appearing in similar contexts but it also extends these lists by induction.<sep> Indeed, the combination of two basic classes (C1 and C2) found in two different contexts CTXT1 and CTXT2 allows for the authorization of non-attested sequences like CTXT1 C2 or CTXT2 C1.<sep> For example, imagine that acquisition and fusion belong to the same base class.<sep> If procéder à une acquisition is present in the corpus, the system will infer that procéder à une fusion is also a valid sequence, even if it is not present in the corpus.<sep> The result is then a generalization of the knowledge found in the corpus.<sep> ASIUM requires that a domain expert intervene to validate the results. This validation is done by examining each class, one by one, until the threshold is reached. Classes under the threshold are supposed to be non relevant and are automatically rejected by the system.<sep> 3.2 Supervised or unsupervised learning?<sep> The basic classes provided by ASIUM require a lot of validation work.<sep> Given the small amount of data available, the threshold that we retained to merge the base classes was low. The consequence is that the propositions from the system concerned classes having very few elements in common.<sep> Two experiments were carried out.<sep> In the first one, ASIUM is used as it.<sep> The comparisons between base classes are made in an unsupervised mode[5]: they are solely based on the score obtained between the two classes.<sep> This strategy requires validating or rejecting a large number of classes that have common elements but are not relevant to the domain.<sep> A second experiment then used a new function of ASIUM allowing to focus the search on the sole classes containing elements of the domain, defined by a set of words placed in a file that acts as a filter.<sep> For example, to find the semantic class purchase_operations ( Opération d’achat ), the filter contained the following set of words: achat , fusion, scission and for the class Company ( Entreprise ), the words: entreprise , société , filiale .<sep> This strategy leads to a supervised learning type[6], which significantly improves the relevance of the result, provided that a set of relevant words is defined each time.<sep> Depending on the semantic class that the analyst wants to model, this set of words is not the same.<sep> There is here a subjectivity factor in our evaluation: elaborating a filter is, by definition, a subjective task that influences the quality of the results.<sep> 3.3 Criteria for the elaboration of semantic classes<sep> Class modeling necessitates an important part of manual work.<sep> Even with a file of words used as a filter, the number of base classes is important, varying from 41 to 576 in function of the total number of words contained in the filter.<sep> Most of the time, the nearest base class defined contained less than 30% of the desired elements.<sep> On the other hand, it is very rare to see more than 30% of a base class validated by the analyst.<sep> The amount of work to clean and aggregate the different classes is then relatively high.<sep> It is not infrequent to find semantic classes split into 20 base classes, requiring as many aggregations.<sep> This point can be problematic when implementing the system: the analyst must accept to spend some time to validate classes that are initially of very poor quality.<sep> 3.4 Measuring the contribution of learning to the acquisition of resources<sep> The aim of the experiment is to try to identify semi-automatically, thanks to ASIUM, the semantic classes that are useful for extraction.<sep> In the framework of the experiment on the FirstInvest corpus, the evaluation was based on a comparison of the items in the class previously defined by the expert with those obtained by learning.<sep> The analysis of ASIUM takes into account the frequency of the elements: in fact, almost all the elements that have a major influence on the result have been found.<sep> There are a few missing elements but they have a limited influence on the overall results, like échange , émission , transaction .<sep> We must however note that some elements like reprise or vente have not been found, even if they are common in our corpus.<sep> Lastly, the distributional analysis makes it possible to find some elements that have not previously been retained by the expert working manually ( désengagement , regroupement , scission ).<sep> Of course, any elements that do not appear in the training corpus cannot be found in the classes proposed by ASIUM.<sep> Once they have been refined and validated, the semi-automatically defined semantic classes obtain good overall results.<sep> The corpus is very homogeneous: even if its size is reduced (243 texts, 45,334 words), the training corpus allows to obtain very good performances over the test corpus (80% precision and 60% recall on average depending on the targeted semantic classes).<sep> In this context, using ASIUM together with an important validation phase allows to accurately cover the training corpus.<sep> The tool allows to establish jointly lists of nouns and associated verbs.<sep> It therefore offers a time saving compared to reading the corpus.<sep> The evaluator estimates that about 10 hours have been spent to defined semantic classes with ASIUM, to be compared with the 50 hours spent to read the corpus and manually elaborate the resources.<sep> Filtering according to a set of initial keywords allows to obtain relevant classes from the beginning of the validation, which is a great advantage compared to the experiment of Faure and Poibeau (2000) which was based on an unsupervised learning phase.<sep> 4 Using general linguistic resource: the semantic network from Memodata<sep> In order to contrast the experience done with ASIUM, we decided to proceed with the same manipulation starting from a semantic network of the general language.<sep> We used the network from Memodata, which has developed since more than 10 years a very complete tool, the INTEGRAL DICTIONARY, together with a set of functionalities accessible via a programming interface (API) (Dutoit, 2000).<sep> 4.1 The semantic network: THE INTEGRAL DICTIONARY and associated tools<sep> THE INTEGRAL DICTIONARY is the name of the semantic network developed by the French company Memodata.<sep> This network is based on the notion of sense words, that is, the different senses associated with a word (a string of characters).<sep> The network is made of 186,000 word senses. From this point of view, the coverage of the network is comparable with that of Wordnet (Fellbaum, 1998). However, THE INTEGRAL DICTIONARY is very different when one observes its overall structure.<sep> Indeed, the decomposition is not only based on an "is-a" relationship and on psychological assumptions, but also on a decomposition of meaningful words into sèmes (component analysis) structured by typed links.<sep> The network is structured thanks to an important set of links between elements of different syntactic category, like in EUROWORDNET (Vossen, 1998).<sep> This aspect is especially important for the task we are interested in, given that we must find both the noun achat and the verb acheter to reflect the notion of acquisition.<sep> The coverage of the INTEGRAL DICTIONARY is larger than the French EUROWORDNET. By the way, a part of the information contained inside the French EUROWORDNET has been automatically derived from MEMODATA’s resources (the rest of the French EUROWORDNET network has been produced by the University of Avignon, that was responsible of the French part of the project).<sep> 4.2 Criteria for the elaboration of semantic classes<sep> To elaborate semantic classes from a semantic network like the one from MEMODATA, the end-user must choose a keyword from the domain he is interested in as a starting point.<sep> A semantic class then progressively emerges when following the different links between elements in the semantic net.<sep> In our experiment, we took into account all the words that were linked to the original keyword with one of the following typed links: generic , specific or synonym .<sep> The lexical class we obtain is then refined, so that we finally obtain a relatively homogeneous and relevant semantic class (essentially, the analyst must delete terms that are not relevant for the task or the domain).<sep> For example, in French, if the entry point (the initial keyword) is achat ( purchase ), the system will propose the following list of terms: abonnement, accaparement, acheter, acquérir, acquisition, appropriation, commande, prise de contrôle, prise de participation, préemption, téléachat …<sep> In the context of company purchasing other companies, the words abonnement and téléachat are irrelevant.<sep> These words have to be manually discarded.<sep> Unlike the experience with ASIUM, the end-user has no information about the representativeness of a word: the number of occurrences in the training corpus cannot be accessed.<sep> Going back to the corpus manually is a heavy and tedious task.<sep> We will see in the next section that the representativeness of the results is affected.<sep> The process stops when the analysed links no longer yield any relevant words.<sep> The most distant words retained are generally separated by only 2 to 3 nodes from the initial keyword.<sep> The network is homogeneous: the specifics of the synonyms of the initial keyword often cover almost perfectly the specifics of the initial keyword[8].<sep> In fact, the links that are followed by the analyst rapidly provide a set of already found terms or some set of irrelevant terms.<sep> The acquisition process then stops.<sep> 4.3 Measuring the gain brought by general resources for the acquisition of semantic classes<sep> The evaluation of the INTEGRAL DICTIONARY for the definition of the semantic classes of the domain is partially close to the one that was implemented to evaluate ASIUM.<sep> We will compare the result of the acquisition process using the tool from MEMODATA with the semantic classes that have been manually defined.<sep> However, we see a certain number of differences. The tool of Memodata does not necessitate any modeling task nor any training corpus.<sep> Several subjectivity factors also appeared blatantly during the evaluation.<sep> The MEMODATA tool is interrogated using a word or a set of keywords.<sep> The starting point (the initial keyword chosen by the analyst) has a major effect on the quality of the overall results: one word can be more or less accurately linked with other words. The semantic network can be more detailed in one part than in some other parts, etc.<sep> We noticed that, by interrogating the INTEGRAL DICTIONARY with only 3 to 5 words, it is possible to integrally reconstruct any of the semantic classes on which the evaluation has been made.<sep> The difficulty consists, of course, in choosing the good initial set of keywords (like achat in the example of the previous paragraph), which are crucial for the quality of the results.<sep> Here we find the same subjective factor as the one that presides over the development of ASIUM filters.<sep> However, the small number of initial elements of the INTEGRAL DICTIONARY that must be activated in order to reconstruct the semantic classes shows the homogeneity of the semantic classes defined by MEMODATA.<sep> To avoid the subjectivity that comes with choosing a combination of keywords, we wanted to evaluate the system by only taking one word as a starting point, namely the word "achat" (purchase).<sep> The semantic class we obtained by activating the direct links of "achat" and then by validating these results, showed that more than 75% of the original class is found in this way (but we don’t take into account the total number of occurrences in the test corpus of the words composing the class).<sep> 60% of the elements proposed by the Integral dictionary have been positively validated.<sep> A large part of the class we obtained was not present in the class defined manually (there are on average 40% of new elements in the classes obtained from the INTEGRAL DICTIONARY, compared to the classes defined manually).<sep> In other words, the semantic network from MEMODATA provides lots of relevant elements that the analyst would not have thought of spontaneously.<sep> However, these results are misleading and are very different if we reason in terms of the number of people.<sep> Some key elements of the target semantic class have not been found.<sep> The figures taking into account the number of elements reveal that the class obtained with the INTEGRAL DICTIONARY only covers 45% of the target class, and the new elements proposed only contribute 7% to the improvement of the coverage.<sep> In other words, a lot of potentially relevant words are proposed that could be interesting, but these words are rarely present in the test corpus.<sep> The conclusion for this part of the study is that the semantic classes proposed by the INTEGRAL DICTIONARY are of better quality than those of ASIUM. They cover a larger spectrum of elements since they are not limited to the training corpus.<sep> Unfortunately, some key elements are forgotten (30% of undiscovered elements correspond in fact to 55% of the occurrences of the corpus).<sep> Some of these elements are very frequent ones and they contribute to a lower recall.<sep> 5 Resource acquisition tools, a difficult evaluation<sep> Information extraction (IE) systems offer clear evaluation methods: a reference can generally be manually established and the results of automatic IE systems are compared with the reference.<sep> Things are very different when it comes to resource acquisition.<sep> Manually defined resources define a relative reference, which is known to be largely imperfect.<sep> The evaluation is then not based on an objective and indisputable basis.<sep> These difficulties are increased again when we think to the fact that resource acquisition cannot constitutes an isolated and abstract task.<sep> Indeed, the linguistic modeling task requires a large knowledge of the domain and of the corpus.<sep> This knowledge allows the user to guide the machine learning process in defining good filters and good keywords.<sep> But, like all human knowledge, it is difficult to model, contains a part of unvoiced feeling and of implicitness.<sep> This part of subjectivity is inherent to the task and should not be hidden during the evaluation.<sep> We obtain results that are less readable and less clear than when we strictly follow a black box evaluation protocol.<sep> This lack of clarity is often compensated by the intuition of the expert who develops his own strategies of analysis and use of the tools at his disposal.<sep> It is therefore necessary to propose guides when implementing such tools: guides to functionalities, but also and especially methodological guides explaining the analysis strategies possible according to the size of the corpus, its homogeneity, its representativeness and the domain considered.<sep> 6 Conclusion<sep> In this paper, we evaluated two knowledge sources for acquiring semantic classes: the corpus itself and a general semantic network.<sep> The results obtained are contrasted and we have shown that the two sources of knowledge do not allow the same results to be obtained.<sep> Acquisition from the corpus is more precise, while using a semantic network makes it possible to cover a wider area.<sep> The complementarity of these two sources of data now remains to be better exploited within a cooperative system.<sep> 1 Here we will detail the evaluation of the semantic classes themselves, taking into account their degree of overlap in particular.<sep> For lack of space, we cannot here present an evaluation and discussion of their influence on the extraction process itself.<sep> On this subject, see [Poibeau, 2002].<sep> 2 Since then, a more complex WORDNET model has been developed to improve some of the weaknesses of the initial model: this is EUROWORDNET, which was designed during the creation of multilingual semantic networks for several European languages (Vossen, 1998).<sep> 3 In a corpus of cooking, the verb conserver (au) can be followed by frais, froid, réfrigérateur, sec, etc [Faure, 2000].<sep> Even for the expert, the segmentation is not obvious: should we consider that, in the corpus, froid is synonymous with refrigerator?<sep> The groupings then depend on the degree of fineness sought and can hardly be determined automatically.<sep> 4 Firstinvest.com is a financial website on the Internet.<sep> The provision of this corpus by FirstInvest made this work possible. 5 At this stage, the user is not in the loop: he intervenes just to validate the proposals made by the system. 6 This strategy follows the use of Asium in experiments of resource acquisition for extraction.<sep> Similarly, Riloff and Jones (1999) propose an approach based on a set of initial seed words to initiate the learning of semantic classes.<sep> These experiments showed that it was necessary to develop a way of supervising learning, as opposed to what is sought in the acquisition of ontologies, which generally concerns all text.<sep> As a reminder, extraction only concerns a tiny part of the text.<sep> 7 Although they are frequent, these words are not retained by the analysis because they are found in contexts different from the words supporting the notion of purchase.<sep> 8 This is less obvious than it seems: the links of synonymy in the networks are rarely reciprocal (a link of synonymy can exist from A to B, but not from B to A), contrary to a common idea.
Discovering word senses from a network of lexical cooccurrences<sep> Abstract<sep> Lexico-semantic networks such as WordNet have been criticized about the nature of the senses they distinguish as well as on the way they define these senses.<sep> This article presents a possible solution to overcome these limits by defining the sense of words from the way they are used.<sep> More precisely, it proposes to differentiate the senses of a word from a network of lexical cooccurrences built from a large corpus.<sep> This method was tested both for French and English and was evaluated for English by comparing its results with WordNet.<sep> Keywords: Lexical semantics, word sense discovery, lexico-semantic networks<sep> 1 Introduction<sep> The use of semantic resources in information retrieval or information extraction has been shown to be useful for some time now through works ranging from query expansion (de Loupy, El-Bèze, 2002) to question/answer systems (Pasca, Harabagiu, 2001).<sep> This work has also shown that such use must be surrounded by precautions: an improvement of performance is only observed if the disambiguation of the meaning of words is performed with a very good reliability.<sep> These findings highlight one of the primary roles of the concept of a semantic resource: defining for each of its words an inventory of its possible meanings and a characterization of each of them.<sep> The main semantic resources with a wide coverage that can be exploited by computers are lexico-semantic networks such as WordNet (Miller, 1995).<sep> Because of the way they were built, mainly by hand, these networks are not fundamentally different from traditional dictionaries.<sep> They are based primarily on the formalisation and systematisation of existing lexicographic practices.<sep> Hence, it is not very surprising that they were criticized, as in (Harabagiu et al. , 1999), for not being suitable for Natural Language Processing.<sep> These criticisms are about the nature of the senses they distinguish and the way they characterize them.<sep> Their senses are considered as too fine-grained but also incomplete.<sep> Moreover, they are generally defined through their relations with synonyms, hyponyms and hyperonyms but not by elements that describe the contexts in which they occur.<sep> Two major solutions have been explored to remedy this situation.<sep> The first of these is to automatically enrich WordNet-type networks with the information needed to respond to the criticisms made.<sep> Various works, including recently (Agirre, Lopez de Lacalle, 2003), have thus aimed to group WordNet senses to obtain a multi-level sense granularity, and therefore adaptable to the task in question.<sep> Other work, particularly in the context of the eXtended WordNet project (Mihalcea, Moldovan, 2001), has focused on extracting more diverse semantic relations from the definitions (the “glosses”) associated with WordNet synsets, which makes it possible to characterize the context of use of each of them more fully.<sep> The second solution consists in automatically discovering the senses of words from corpora, without using existing dictionaries.<sep> Each sense is defined by a list of words that is not restricted to synonyms or hyperonyms.<sep> The work already done in this area can be divided into three main trends.<sep> The first one, represented by (Pantel and Lin, 2002), is not focused on the problem of discovering word senses: its main objective is to build classes of equivalent words from a distributionalist viewpoint, hence to gather words that are mainly synonyms.<sep> The discovery of word senses is an indirect consequence: the classification method used, Clustering by Committee, allows a word to belong to several classes, each of them becomes de facto a sense of this word.<sep> The second main trend, found in (Schütze, 1998), (Pedersen and Bruce, 1997) and (Purandare, 2003), characterises each instance of a target word by a set of features that occur in its neighbourhood and applies an unsupervised clustering algorithm to all its instances.<sep> The different classes formed constitute as many meanings of the word.<sep> The last trend, explored by (Véronis, 2003), (Dorow and Widdows, 2003) and (Rapp, 2003), starts from the cooccurrents of a word recorded from a corpus and builds its senses by gathering its cooccurrents according to their similarity or their dissimilarity.<sep> It is in this last perspective that the work we describe in this article takes place.<sep> 2 Principles<sep> The starting point of the method we present in this article is a network of lexical cooccurrences, that is a graph whose vertices are the significant words of a corpus and edges represent the cooccurrences between these words in the corpus.<sep> The discovering of word senses is performed word by word and the processing of a word only relies on the subgraph that contains its cooccurrents.<sep> The first step of the method consists in building a matrix of similarity between these cooccurrents by exploiting their relations in the subgraph.<sep> An unsupervised clustering algorithm is then applied for grouping these cooccurrents and forming the different senses of the considered word.<sep> The underlying hypothesis of this method, which it shares with the works of the third trend identified in the previous section, is of course that the connectivity within the subgraph of the cooccurrents forming the meaning of a word is more important than their connectivity with the cooccurrents defining the other meanings of this word.<sep> The clustering algorithm that we use is an adaptation of the Shared Nearest Neighbors (SNN) algorithm presented in (Ertöz et al. , 2001).<sep> This method has the advantage of automatically determining the number of classes, in our case the number of senses, and leaving aside the elements that are less representative of the classes formed.<sep> This last point is especially important for our application as there is a lot of “noise” among the cooccurrents of a word.<sep> 3 Networks of lexical cooccurrences<sep> In the course of this work, we tested our method of discovering word senses both for French and English.<sep> Hence, two networks of lexical cooccurrences were built: one for French, from the Le Monde newspaper (24 months between 1990 and 1994), and one for English, from the L.A. Times newspaper (2 years, part of the TREC corpus).<sep> In each case, the size of the corpus was around 40 million words.<sep> The building process was the same for the two networks. First, the initial corpus was preprocessed in order to characterize texts by their topically significant words. Thus, we retained only the lemmatized form of plain words, that is, nouns, verbs and adjectives.<sep> Cooccurrences were then extracted using a sliding window according to the method described in (Church, Hanks, 1990).<sep> The parameters of this extraction were set in order to capture semantic and topical relations: the window was rather large (20 words), respected the end of texts and the order of cooccurrences was not preserved.<sep> As (Church and Hanks, 1990), we adopted an evaluation of mutual information as a cohesion measure of each cooccurrence. This measure was normalized according to the maximal mutual information relative to the considered corpus.<sep> After filtering the less significant cooccurrences (cooccurrences with less than 10 occurrences and cohesion lower than 0.1), we got a network with approximately 23,000 words and 5.2 million cooccurrences for French, 30,000 words and 4.8 million cooccurrences for English.<sep> 4 Word sense discovery algorithm<sep> 4.1 Building of the similarity matrix between cooccurrents<sep> The number and the extent of the clusters built by a clustering algorithm generally depend on a set of parameters that can be tuned in one way or another.<sep> But this possibility is implicitly limited by the similarity measure used for comparing the elements to cluster, hence its importance.<sep> In our case, the elements to cluster are the cooccurrents in the network of lexical cooccurrences of the word whose senses have to be discriminated.<sep> While keeping the same general framework, we tested two measures for evaluating the similarity between cooccurrents in order to get word senses with different levels of granularity.<sep> The first measure simply corresponds to the cohesion value existing in the cooccurrence network between the considered cooccurrents.<sep> If there is no relation between two words in the network, the similarity is equal to zero.<sep> This measure has the advantage of being simple and efficient from an algorithmic viewpoint but some semantic relations are difficult to catch only from cooccurrences in texts.<sep> We experimentally noticed that there are few synonyms of a word among its cooccurrents[1] .<sep> Hence, we can expect that some senses that are discriminated by the algorithm actually refer to one sense.<sep> To prevent this risk, we tested a measure of similarity between co-occurrents based not only on a first level co-occurrence relationship but also on a second level co-occurrence relationship, the latter being considered more stable (Schütze, 1998).<sep> This measure is implemented as follows: a vector of size equal to the number of cooccurrents of the considered word is associated with each of its cooccurrents. This vector contains the cohesion values between this cooccurrent and the others.<sep> As for the first measure, a null value is taken when there is no relation between two words in the cooccurrence network.<sep> The similarity matrix between cooccurrents is simply built by applying the cosine measure between the vectors of each couple of cooccurrents.<sep> With this second measure of similarity, two cooccurrents no longer necessarily need to maintain a direct cooccurrence relationship to be considered close: they can just share a set of words with which they maintain such a relationship.<sep> 4.2 The Shared Nearest Neighbors (SNN) algorithm<sep> The SNN algorithm (Ertöz et al., 2001) is representative of the algorithms that perform clustering by detecting the high-density areas of a similarity graph.<sep> In such a graph, each vertex represents an element to cluster and an edge links two vertices whose similarity is not null.<sep> When the similarity matrix is symmetric, as is the case here, the resulting graph is not directed. It should be noted that in the case of discovering the senses of a word, the problem is fundamentally a problem of detecting high-density components, the senses, within the graph of cooccurrents of this word. It is preserved as is with the first similarity measure but transposed into a more general problem of classification with the second.<sep> In its general principle, the SNN algorithm can be split up into two main steps: the first one aims at finding the elements that are the most representative of their neighborhood by masking the less important relations in the similarity graph.<sep> These elements are the seeds of the final clusters that are built in the second step by aggregating the remaining elements to those selected by the first step.<sep> The SNN algorithm, considered in the context of the discovery of meaning, is more precisely broken down as follows:<sep> 1. "sparsification" of the similarity graph: for each cooccurrent of the target word, only the links towards the k (k=15 in our experiments) most similar other cooccurrents are kept.<sep> 2. construction of the shared nearest neighbor graph: this step consists in replacing, in the sparsified graph, the value of each edge by the number of direct neighbors shared by the two cooccurrents linked by this edge.<sep> 3. computation of the distribution of strong links among cooccurrents: as for the first step, this one is a kind of clarification.<sep> Its aim is to help finding the cooccurrents around which a set of other cooccurrents are organized, i.e. the seeds of the senses, but also to identify those that are clearly not really connected to the others.<sep> More precisely, two cooccurrents are considered as strongly linked if the number of the neighbors they share is higher than a fixed threshold.<sep> The number of strong links of each cooccurrent is then computed.<sep> 4. identification of the sense seeds and filtering of noise: the sense seeds and the cooccurrents to discard are determined by comparing their number of strong links with a fixed threshold.<sep> 5. construction of senses: this step mainly consists in associating to the sense seeds identified by the previous step the remaining cooccurrents that are the most similar to them. The result is a set of clusters that each represents a sense of the target word.<sep> For associating a cooccurrent to a sense seed, the strength of the link between them must be higher than a given threshold.<sep> If a connection to several seeds is possible, the one that is the most strongly linked to it is chosen.<sep> Moreover, this step is also an opportunity to group several seeds of meaning that are considered too close to each other to form distinct meanings: the grouping of cooccurrents also involves the seeds of meaning.<sep> 6. extension of senses: after the previous steps, a more or less important number of cooccurrents that are not considered as noise are still not associated to a sense.<sep> The size of this set depends on the strictness of the threshold controlling the aggregation of a sense seed but as we are interested in getting homogeneous senses, the value of this threshold cannot be too low.<sep> Nevertheless, it is also interesting that the senses can be described as completely and as precisely as possible.<sep> As senses are defined at this point more precisely than at step 4, the integration into these senses of cooccurrents that are not strongly linked to a sense seed can be performed on a larger basis, hence in a more reliable way.<sep> 4.3 Adaptation and modalities of application of the SNN algorithm<sep> The principles of the SNN algorithm presented in the previous section must be specified more precisely in terms of their implementation. The main point is the way its different thresholds are fixed.<sep> In our case, we chose the same method for all of them: each threshold is set as a certain quantile of these values. In this way, it is adapted to the distribution of these values.<sep> For the identification of the sense seeds (threshold equal to 0.9) and for the definition of the cooccurrents that are noise (threshold equal to 0.2), the thresholds are quantiles of the number of strong links of cooccurrents.<sep> For the threshold defining the strong link (equal to 0.65), the threshold of associating cooccurrents to sense seeds (equal to 0.5) and the threshold of associating cooccurrents to senses (equal to 0.7), the quantile is applied directly to the strength of the links between cooccurrents in the shared nearest neighbor graph.<sep> Beyond the modalities of implementation of the principles, we also introduced adaptations.<sep> The most important one is the addition of a new step between the last two ones.<sep> Indeed, we have observed that despite the possibility, at the level of the construction of the meaning, to merge classes through the association of a sense seed to another one, some senses remain divided into several classes.<sep> This phenomenon is observable even when initially using cooccurrences of the second order and cannot be effectively treated by adjusting the threshold that controls the association of a cooccurrent to a sense seed.<sep> In a significant number of cases, the "split" sense is distributed between one or several classes that only contain 3 or 4 words and a larger class.<sep> In practice, the sense seeds of these "minority" classes could not be associated with the "majority" class while most of the cooccurrents that are linked to them are associated to this seed.<sep> Instead of defining a specific mechanism for grouping these "minority" classes with the most important class, we chose to let the algorithm in its current form do it by destroying these classes (size < 6) and putting their elements back into the set of unclassified cooccurrents.<sep> The last step of the algorithm then aggregates in most of the cases these cooccurrents to the large cluster.<sep> Moreover, this mechanism makes the built senses more stable when the parameters of the algorithm are only slightly modified.<sep> A second adaptation, with a smaller impact, was carried out to ensure that the co-occurrents attached during the last step do not introduce noise.<sep> We have thus imposed that the condition of attachment does not only concern the strength of the relationship between the cooccurrent to be attached and one of the members of the class but on the average strength of the relationships between this cooccurrent and the elements of this class.<sep> 5 Experiments<sep> We applied our method of discovering word senses to the two networks of lexical cooccurrences (LM: French; LAT: English) that we have constructed with the parameter values specified in the previous sections.<sep> For each network, we tested the use of first order cooccurrences (LM-1 and LAT-1) and second order ones (LM-2 and LAT-2).<sep> For English, the use of second order cooccurrences was tested only for the subpart of the words of the network that was selected for the evaluation of Section 6 (LAT-2.no).<sep> Table 1 gives some statistics about the results of the discovered senses for the different cases.<sep> We can notice that a significant percentage of words do not have any sense, even with second order cooccurrences.<sep> These are the words whose cooccurrents are weakly linked and whose meaning is probably poorly represented in their cooccurrence network.<sep> Furthermore, we can note that the use of second order cooccurrence actually leads to a smaller number of senses by word.<sep> Table 1: Statistics concerning the results of the discovery of meaning. As Véronis (2003), we illustrate the results of our algorithm by giving some of the words characterizing the senses found for the word barrage:<sep> - LM-1 1.1 demonstrator, law_enforcement, prefecture, farmer, protest, burn, calm, stone<sep> - 1.2 driver, road, vehicle, heavy goods vehicle, lorry, licence, traffic, block, car, motorway<sep> - 1.3 river, lake, stream, basin, cubic metre, flood, upstream, pollution, tributary, salmon, fish<sep> - 1.4 injured, casque_bleu, soldier, milicien, tir, milice, convoi, evacuer, croate, milicien, combattant<sep> - LM-2 2.1 water, meter, lake, rain, river, basin, river, site, fish, tributary, mountain, flood, valley<sep> - 2.2 driver, traffic, road, roadway, truck, driver, car, truck_driver, heavy_goods_vehicle<sep> - 2.3 casque_bleu, soldier, shooting, convoy, militiaman, armoured vehicle, militia, airport, wounded, incident, croat<sep> In both cases, three of the four senses distinguished in (Véronis, 2003) are found: hydraulic dam (senses 1.3 and 2.1); road dam (senses 1.2 and 2.2); border dam (senses 1.4 and 2.3).<sep> The sense of play-off game ( match de barrage ) is not represented as it is weakly represented in the cooccurrence network and is linked to words, such as division , that are also ambiguous (it refers both to the sport and the military domains).<sep> It should be noted that barrage has only 1,104 occurrences in our corpus while it has 7,000 occurrences in the corpus of (Véronis, 2003).<sep> This example is also a good illustration of the difference of granularity of the senses induced by the use of cooccurrences of order 1 or 2.<sep> The sense 1.1, which is close to the sense 1.2 as the two refers to demonstrations in relation to a category of workers, disappears when the second order cooccurrences are used.<sep> We give below the senses for other words in French and English with first order cooccurrences:<sep> 6 Evaluation<sep> The discovery of word senses, like other tasks dedicated to the building of linguistic resources, comes up against the problem of evaluating its results.<sep> The most direct way of doing it is to compare the resource to evaluate with a similar resource that is acknowledged as a golden standard.<sep> In this case, WordNet-like lexicosemantic networks are the most relevant reference resource.<sep> Using this kind of networks for evaluating the word senses that we find is of course criticizable as our aim is to overcome their insufficiencies.<sep> Nevertheless, as these networks are carefully controlled, such an evaluation provides at least a first judgment about the reliability of the discovered senses.<sep> We chose to take up the evaluation method proposed in (Pantel and Lin, 2002). This method relies on WordNet and shows a rather good agreement between its results and human judgments (88% for Pantel and Lin).<sep> As a consequence, our evaluation was done only for English, and more precisely with WordNet 1.7.1.<sep> This protocol consists of trying to match each discovered sense of a word with one of its synsets in WordNet by applying a specific similarity measure.<sep> Hence, only the precision of the word sense discovering algorithm is evaluated but Pantel and Lin indicate that recall is not very significant in this context: a discovered sense may be correct and not present in WordNet and conversely, some senses in WordNet are very close and should be joined for most of the applications using WordNet.<sep> They define a recall measure but only for ranking the results of a set of systems.<sep> Hence, it cannot be applied to our method alone.<sep> The similarity measure between a sense and a synset used for computing precision relies on the Lin’s similarity measure between two synsets:<sep> where s is the most specific synset that subsumes s1 and s2 in the WordNet hierarchy and P(s) represents the probability of the synset s estimated from a reference corpus, in this case the SemCor corpus.<sep> We used the implementation of this measure provided by the Perl module WordNet ::Similarity v0.06 (Patwardhan and Pedersen, 2003).<sep> The similarity between a sense and a synset is more precisely defined as the average value of the similarity values between the words that characterize the sense, or a subset of them, and the synset.<sep> The similarity between a word and a synset is equal to the highest similarity value among those between the synset and the synsets to which the word belongs to.<sep> A sense is mapped to the synset that is the most similar to it, provided that the similarity between them is higher than a fixed threshold (equal to 0.25 as in (Pantel and Lin, 2002)).<sep> Finally, the precision for a word is given by the proportion of its senses that match one of its synsets.<sep> Table 2: Mean accuracy of senses found for English compared to WordNet<sep> Table 4 gives the results of the evaluation of our algorithm for the words of the English cooccurrence network that are nouns only and for which at least one sense was discovered.<sep> Two measurements are given.<sep> As Pantel and Lin, we only take into account 4 words of each sense for the evaluation.<sep> But, unlike them, we do not have a specific measure of the proximity of the words of a sense to the word that it describes.<sep> We therefore give the average precision obtained by choosing the 4 words of a sense that have the most strong links (the criteria of frequency or cohesion in the co-occurrence network give the same results) and that obtained by choosing the 4 words of a sense that allow to have a maximum score.<sep> A clear difference can be noted between the two variants. With the optimal choice of the four words, we get results that are similar to those of Pantel and Lin: their precision is equal to 60.8 with an average number of words defining a sense equal to 14. On the other hand, Table 4 shows that the words selected on the basis of their number of strong links are not strongly linked in WordNet (according to Lin’s measure) to their target word.<sep> This does not mean that the selected words are not interesting for describing the senses of the target word but more probably that the semantic relations that they share with the target word are different from hyperonymy.<sep> The best results obtained by Pantel and Lin on this point can be explained by the fact that the basis of their method is the clustering of similar words, i.e. words that are likely to be synonyms, and not on the classification of the cooccurrents of a word, which do not contain many synonyms of their source word.<sep> Moreover, their initial corpus is much larger (around 144 millions words) than ours and they make use of more elaborated tools, such as a syntactic analyzer.<sep> As expected, the results obtained with first order cooccurrences (LAT-1.no), which produce a higher number of senses by word, are lower than the results obtained with second order cooccurrences (LAT-2.no).<sep> However, without a recall measure, it is difficult to draw a clear conclusion from this observation: some senses of LAT-1.no probably result from the artificial division of an actual word sense but the fact to have more homogeneous senses in LAT-2.no also facilitates in this case the mapping with WordNet’s synsets.<sep> 7 Discussion<sep> By its nature, our method is most directly compared to (Véronis, 2003) and (Dorow, Widdows, 2003). Despite a general approach proximity with (Rapp, 2003), the distance with the latter is greater because it does not rely on the detection of high-density areas in a network of cooccurrences.<sep> (Véronis, 2003) and (Dorow, Widdows, 2003) do not provide a formal evaluation, so only a qualitative comparison is possible.<sep> Nevertheless, two main differences can be noted with our work.<sep> The first one concerns the direct use they make of the cooccurrence graph.<sep> In our case, we chose a more general approach by working at the level of a similarity graph: when the similarity of two words is given by their relation of cooccurrence, our situation is comparable to the one of (Véronis, 2003) and (Dorow and Widdows, 2003); but in the same framework, we can also take into account other kinds of similarity relations, such as the second order cooccurrences.<sep> The second main difference is the fact they discriminate senses in an iterative way.<sep> This approach consists in selecting at each step the most obvious sense and then, to update the graph of cooccurrences by discarding the words that make up the new sense. The other senses are then easier to discriminate.<sep> We preferred to put emphasis on the ability to gather close or identical senses that are artificially distinguished by the use of surface forms (see Section 4.3).<sep> More generally, the two pointed differences have as their main consequence to lead to finer distinctions of meaning than those we highlight.<sep> Nevertheless, as methods for discovering word senses from a corpus tend to find a too large number of close senses, it was more important from our viewpoint to favour the building of stable senses with a clear definition rather than to discriminate very fine senses.<sep> 8 Conclusion and future work<sep> In this article, we have presented a new method for discriminating and defining the senses of a word from a network of lexical cooccurrences.<sep> This method applies an unsupervised classification algorithm, the SNN algorithm, to the cooccurrents of the word by relying on the relations that these cooccurrents have in the network.<sep> We have achieved a first evaluation based on the methodology defined in (Pantel, Lin, 2002). This evaluation has shown that the relevance of the discriminated senses is comparable to the relevance of Pantel and Lin’s word senses.<sep> However, this assessment needs to be further developed.<sep> It seems particularly necessary to rely on a measure of similarity between synset and formed sense allowing to take into account a wider set of semantic relations such as those implicitly present in the glosses associated with synsets.<sep> Moreover, an evaluation based on the use of the built senses in an application such as query expansion is necessary to determine the actual interest of this kind of resources in comparison with a lexicosemantic network such as WordNet.<sep> 1 This observation comes from the intersection, for each word of the L.A. Times network, of its cooccurrents in the network and its synonyms in WordNet.<sep> 2 That is, without grouping classes corresponding to different senses.
ILIMP: Tool to recognize occurrences<sep> Abstract<sep> We present a tool, called ILIMP, which takes as input a raw text in French and produces as output the same text in which every occurrence of the pronoun il is tagged either with tag [ANAphorique] or [IMPersonnel].<sep> This tool is therefore designed to distinguish between the anaphoric occurrences of il , for which an anaphora resolution system has to look for an antecedent, and the expletive occurrences of this pronoun, for which it does not make sense to look for an antecedent.<sep> The precision rate for ILIMP is 97,5%.<sep> We present a detailed analysis of the errors and briefly describe other potential applications of the method used in ILIMP, as well as the use and positioning of ILIMP in a modular syntactic analysis system.<sep> Keywords: Expletive pronouns, Anaphoric pronouns, Lexicon-Grammar, Automata, Anaphora resolution, Modular syntactic analysis<sep> 1 Introduction<sep> In TAL, the resolution of anaphora is a well-studied research topic because it is a crucial issue for applications such as Information Retrieval or Text Summarization.<sep> Among anaphora, third person pronouns are quite frequent and therefore widely studied.<sep> Among the pronouns, one can distinguish an element (il in French, it in English) with an impersonal use (“expletively”) (il pleut, it rains) which is different from the anaphoric use (il est cher, it is expensive).<sep> A system of resolving anaphora must be able to recognize the occurrences of impersonal pronouns before dealing with anaphoric pronouns and other anaphores.<sep> There exists a number of works on the impersonal use of the English pronoun it , among them (Lapin, Leass, 1994), (Kennedy, Bogurev, 1996) and (Evans 2001).<sep> However, to our knowledge, no similar work has been done on the French pronoun il .<sep> This paper presents a tool, ILIMP, which is designed to mark any occurrence of the impersonal pronoun il in French texts: ILIMP decorates each occurrence of il with the tag [ANAphorique] or [IMPersonnel].<sep> This tool is rule based (as it is the case for Lapin and Leass’ system); it works on raw texts (contrarily to Lapin and Leass’ system which relies on a syntactic analysis).<sep> If ILIMP is an imperative tool for an anaphora resolution system, it is also a tool which can be integrated into a processing chain within a modular approach to syntactic analysis.<sep> Indeed, on the one hand, the [IMP] and [ANA] tags on the pronoun it can be seen as a refinement of the morpho-syntactic tags traditionally used in taggers: the tag “pronoun” would be replaced by two tags, “anaphoric pronoun” and “impersonal pronoun”.<sep> It is known that the richer the tag set is, the better would the syntactic analysis based on tagging be (Nasr, 2004).<sep> Moreover, it will be shown that tools derived from ILIMP can be used for other linguistic annotations.<sep> Section 2 presents our method, which is based, on linguistic grounds, on the lexicon-grammar of the LADL, and on computational grounds, on UNITEX.<sep> Section 3 presents the realization of ILIMP, the difficulties which have been encountered and the choices made to solve them.<sep> Finally, Section 4 presents an evaluation of ILIMP and discusses its positioning within a modular syntactic analysis.<sep> 2 Method<sep> 2.1 Lexicon-Grammar<sep> As for most linguistic phenomena, the impersonal use of il depends on both lexical and syntactic conditions.<sep> For example, the adjective violet can never be the lexical head of an impersonal clause – see (1a); the adjective probable followed by a clausal complement anchors an impersonal clause – see (1b); and the adjective difficile when followed by an infinitival complement introduced by the preposition de (resp. à ) anchors an impersonal (resp. personal) clause – see (1c) and (1d).<sep> (1)a Il est violet (It is purple) b Il est probable que Fred viendra (It is likely that Fred will come) c Il est difficile de résoudre ce problème (It is difficult to solve this problem) d Il est difficile à résoudre, ce problème (It is difficult to solve, this problem)<sep> Therefore, the French lexicon-grammar developed by Maurice Gross and his group (Gross 1994, Leclère 2003) is an appropriate linguistic resource for ILIMP since it describes, for each lexical head of a clause, its syntactic arguments and the possible alternations.<sep> We have therefore extracted (manually) from the lexicon-grammar all the lexical items that can anchor an impersonal clause by recording their syntactic arguments.<sep> Below is a brief overview of the impersonal constructions in French that we have identified.<sep> We can distinguish between constructions that are intrinsically impersonal, which can only have il as their subject, and constructions with an “extrinsic deep subject”.<sep> Among the former ones, I have compiled 45 meteorological verbal phrases (Il neige (It snows), Il fait beau (It is a nice day) ), 21 verbs from Table 17 of (Gross 1975 ) (Il faut que Fred vienne /du pain) and 38 frozen expressions (Il était une fois (once upon a time), quoi qu’il en soit (whatsoever)) .<sep> Among the impersonal constructions with an extraposed deep subject, one has to distinguish those with a phrasal subject from those with a nominal extraposed subject.<sep> Among the former ones, I have compiled 682 adjectives scattered in the tables of (Picabia, 1978) and (Meunier, 1981) (It is probable that Fred will come) , 88 expressions of the form "être Prép X" from tables Z5P and Z5D of (Danlos 1980) (It is standard practice to wear a hat) , 21 verbs from table 5 of (Gross 1975) (It pleases Vanne that Fred will come) , and finally 140 verbs from table 6 and 92 verbs from table 9 of (Gross 1975) constructed in the passive or se-moyen (It has been said/told that Fred will come) .<sep> The impersonal constructions with a nominal extraposed subject have as their lexical head verbs that are scattered in the tables elaborated by (BGL, 1976b).<sep> On can distinguish on one side verbs like manquer or rester whose use in an impersonal construction is quite common (Il manque /reste du pain) , and on the other side "inacusatifs" verbs (Il est venu trois personnes) or verbs constructed in the passive (Il a été mangé trois gâteaux) , whose use in an impersonal construction is a refined level of language.<sep> 2.2 Unitex<sep> Unitex[1] is a tool which allows us to write linguistic patterns (regular expressions or automata) which are located in the input text, with a possible addition of information when an automaton is in fact a transducer.<sep> A raw text, when given as input to Unitex, is first preprocessed: it is segmented into sentences and the sentences are segmented into tokens. Each token is tagged with all the parts of speech and inflexion features recorded in the "full-form" dictionary DELAF (Courtois, 2004).<sep> There is no disambiguation, in other words, the pre-processing in Unitex does not amount to a morphosyntactic tagging.<sep> For ILIMP, the basic idea is to manually write patterns (transducers) such as the one presented in (2) in a simplified linear form.<sep> The [IMP] tag is the addition of information brought about by the transducer aspect of (2).<sep> The elements between chevrons of (2) are defined as follows: <être.V:3s> corresponds to all the forms of the verb être conjugated to the third person singular, corresponds to the masculine singular adjectives that belong to the class Adj1, which groups together adjectives behaving as difficult, corresponds to any verb in the infinitive form.<sep> [IMP] is a tag which is added in the input text to the occurrences of il that appear in clauses which follow the pattern in (2).<sep> The occurrence of il in (1c) is thereby marked with tag [IMP].<sep> The tag [ANA] - an abbreviation for anaphoric - is the default tag: it marks the occurrences of il that have not been tagged with [IMP].<sep> The occurrence of il in (1d) is thereby marked with tag [ANA].<sep> Nevertheless, the matter is slightly more complex, since there is a third tag, [AMB], which is explained in Section 3.2.<sep> After this presentation of the theoretical principles underlying ILIMP, let us examine its practical realization.<sep> 3 Realization of ILIMP<sep> 3.1 Left context of the lexical head<sep> In (1c), the left context of the lexical head - the sequence of tokens on the left of difficile (difficult) - is reduced to Il est (it is) .<sep> However, sentences such as (3a) or (3b), in which the left context of the lexical head is more complex, are frequently found in real texts.<sep> In (3a), the left context includes (from right to left) the adverb très (very) which modifies the adjective, the verb paraître (seem) in the infinitive form which is a “light verb” for adjectives, the pronoun lui (to him) and finally the modal verb peut (may) preceded by il (it ).<sep> In (3b), the left context includes the verb s’avérer which is conjugated in a compound tense (s’est avéré) and negated (ne s’est pas avéré).<sep> (3)a Il peut lui paraître très difficile de résoudre ce problème (It may seem very difficult to him to solve this problem) b Il ne s’est pas avéré difficile de résoudre ce problème (It didn’t turn out to be difficult to solve this problem)<sep> As a consequence, for each type of the lexical heads (adjectival, verbal) that anchors an impersonal clause, all the elements that may occur in the left-context have to be determined and integrated in patterns.<sep> This task does not raise any real difficulties, let's say it is a meticulous and time consuming work[2] .<sep> In contrast, we are faced with real ambiguities with the right context of the lexical head, as we are going to show it.<sep> In the rest of the paper, the left contexts of the lexical heads are presented in a simplified way - as in (2) - for the sake of readability.<sep> 3.2 Right context of the lexical head<sep> 3.2.1 Syntactic ambiguities<sep> There is a number of syntactic ambiguities in the right context since, as is well known, a sequence of parts of speech may receive several syntactic analyses.<sep> As an illustration, consider the pattern in (4a), in which the symbol Ω matches any nonempty sequence of tokens.<sep> This pattern corresponds to two syntactic analyses: (4b) in which il is impersonal and the infinitival phrase de is subcategorized by difficile , and (4c) in which il is anaphoric and the infinitival phrase is part of an NP.<sep> These two analyses are illustrated in (4d) and (4e) respectively - these sentences differ only in the adverb ici/juste .<sep> (4)a Il est difficile pour Ω de b Il[IMP] est difficile pour [Ω]NP de c Il[ANA] est difficile pour [Ω de ]NP d Il est difficile pour [les étudiants qui viennent ici]NP de résoudre ce problème (It is difficult for the students who came here to solve this problem)<sep> To deal with syntactic ambiguities, one solution is to state explicitly that a pattern such as (4a) is ambiguous by means of the tag [AMB] which is to be interpreted as “ILIMP cannot determine whether il is anaphoric or impersonal”.<sep> However this tag is of no use for later processing of an anaphora resolution system or a chain of syntactic processing: it must therefore be used with moderation.<sep> Another solution is to rely upon heuristics based on frequencies.<sep> For example, sentences which follow the pattern in (4a) are more frequently analyzed as (4b) than as (4c). Therefore il in (4a) can be tagged as [IMP] despite some rare errors.<sep> We have adopted this latter solution.<sep> ILIMP is based on a set of heuristics that we have established either based on our linguistic knowledge and intuition and/or on quantitative studies on corpora.<sep> The evaluation of ILIMP will reveal whether our heuristics are sound (Section 4).<sep> 3.2.2 Lexical ambiguities<sep> In a very small number of cases (about ten), a lexical item may anchor both impersonal and personal clauses with the same subcategorization frame, e.g. the adjective certain (certain) with a clausal complement as illustrated in sentence (5a).<sep> Since both readings of (5a) seem equally frequent, il in the pattern (5b) is tagged as [AMB].<sep> (5)a Il est certain que Fred viendra (He/it is certain that Fred will come) b Il[AMB] est certain que S[4]<sep> 3.2.3 Other difficulties<sep> A last type of difficulties is found with impersonal clauses with an extraposed nominal subject. These clauses differ only very subtly from personal clauses.<sep> See the pair in (6a-b) in which the only difference is du/de , whereas (6a) is impersonal and (6b) personal.<sep> See also the pair in (6'a-b) which only differs by the names valise/priorité but where (6'a) is impersonal and (6'b) personal.<sep> We have tried to set up heuristics to distinguish these cases, without, however, venturing, for example, into the (perilous) use of semantic features, such as ± abstract.<sep> (6)a There is no pepper (in this house) b There is no pepper, this roast (6’)a There is the boss’s suitcase (in the car) b There is the boss’s priority (unemployment)<sep> In conclusion, ILIMP relies on a number of heuristics so as to avoid a too frequent use of [AMB].<sep> These heuristics may lead to errors, which are going to be examined in the following section.<sep> 4 Evaluation of ILIMP<sep> Our work corpus has been Le Monde .<sep> More precisely, I have worked on a corpus of 3,782,613 tokens extracted from the corpus Le Monde 1994 .<sep> Unitex segments this corpus into 71.293 sentences.<sep> It contains 13,611 occurrences of the token il on 20,549 occurrences of third person subject pronouns, i.e. il, elle, ils, elles (he, she, it, they) .<sep> So il is the most frequent third person subject pronoun, with a rate of 66%.<sep> From this corpus, 8544 sentences which include at least one occurrence of il have been extracted, and they add up to around 10.000 occurrences of il (a complex sentence with embedded clauses may include several occurrences of il ).<sep> These sentences have been given as input to ILIMP and the results - the tags [IMP], [ANA] and [AMB]- have been manually evaluated by friends, colleagues and students.<sep> The evaluators were asked to rely only on their intuition as speakers: they were not to use their potential expertise as linguists to try to detect virtual ambiguities of occurrences of il.<sep> In these conditions, the assignment of a [IMP] or [ANA] tag is immediate in almost all cases, the [AMB] tag only being used in a negligible number of cases (recall, section 3.2.2, that it is only lexically justified for a dozen lexical heads).<sep> The result of this evaluation is the following: the precision rate is 97,5%.<sep> We are going to examine the errors in detail, leaving aside the [AMB] tag.<sep> 4.1 Errors from morphological ambiguities<sep> Errors coming from morphological ambiguities are (of course) counted as the other errors coming from the realization of ILIMP (which are examined in the next sections).<sep> For the moment, let's examine the errors due to the fact that the pre-processing in Unitex does not include any disambiguation: it is not a tagger (Section 2.2).<sep> Consider the pattern in (7a): let us recall (note 3) that P represents a non-empty sequence of tokens which includes a finite verb; it covers the verbs of Table 6 in the past participle, e.g. choisi .<sep> This pattern aims at targeting impersonal clauses such as (7b).<sep> Nevertheless, it also targets (7c), in which the pronoun il is thus wrongly tagged as [IMP].<sep> This error comes from the fact that the dictionary DELAF rightly includes two entries for the word mètres - finite form of the verb métrer and plural form of the noun mètre - and Unitex does not make any distinction between these two entries.<sep> Therefore, the sequence le béton pour soutenir une toiture de 170 mètres is interpreted as including a finite verb, and hence follows pattern P.<sep> (7)a Il[IMP] <avoir.V:3s> été (ADV) que S b Il a été choisi que les séances se feraient le matin vers 9h (It has been chosen that sessions would take place around 9 am) c Il a été choisi plutôt que le béton pour soutenir une toiture de 170 mètres (It has been chosen rather than concrete to support a 170 meter roof)<sep> Any tagger should tag the word mètres in (7c) as a noun.<sep> If ILIMP worked not on raw text but on the output of a tagger, the error on il in (7c) would be avoided.<sep> This strategy is possible[5], but ILIMP would then be dependent on the errors of a tagger.<sep> More generally, assuming that a syntactic parser relies upon a modular approach in which a set of modules - tagger, named entity recognition module, ILIMP, chunker, etc. – collaborate in a pipeline, the question of the order in which the modules should be chained arises.<sep> But let us leave this question open and come back to the errors of ILIMP working on a raw text.<sep> 4.2 il wrongly tagged as [IMP] instead of [ANA]: 0,3%<sep> Very few errors: 33. This is surprising when considering the frequent appeal to “brutal” heuristics.<sep> As an illustration, we have put the tag [IMP] in the pattern Il y a is systematically tagged as [IMP] with its left context variants.<sep> This heuristic gives rise to only two errors, cited in (8), out of around 1500 phrases that follow this pattern where it is correctly tagged [IMP].<sep> (8)a He had taken refuge in England.<sep> He had known the pianos of... very early on. b He has just returned from Rimini.<sep> Il y a donné la réplique à Madeleine.<sep> 4.3 il wrongly tagged as [ANA] instead of [IMP]: 2%<sep> More errors.<sep> This type of errors comes from the fact that [ANA] is the default value. These errors are thus directly imputable to gaps in the patterns making up ILIMP.<sep> Among these gaps, there are first those coming from my laziness/tiredness/lack of time.<sep> For example, we have introduced quotation marks at some places in patterns but not everywhere. Hence, it is wrongly tagged as [ANA] in (9a) just because of the quotation marks.<sep> Similarly, we wrote some patterns for cases with subject inversion, but we did not take time to write all of them, hence the error in (9b).<sep> (9)a It [ANA] was "even desirable" that it should come "from the opposition".<sep> b Est-il [ANA] inconcevable … (Is it inconceivable that …)<sep> A second type of error comes from lexical gaps in our patterns.<sep> In the current state of ILIMP, there is a lack of adjectives that anchor an impersonal construction, because adjectives have not been studied as systematically as verbs in lexigrammar.<sep> The list of 682 adjectives which anchor an impersonal construction - with an extraposable phrasal subject - can therefore still be completed.<sep> An anonymous proofreader of this article asks the question of whether it is possible to actually list the adjectives that are used in an impersonal construction.<sep> He/She notes that an adjective like myope, which a priori does not anchor an impersonal construction, could in fact allow an impersonal sentence like (10).<sep> (10) It seems quite short-sighted, even blind, to think that the situation cannot get worse<sep> While this sentence is nicely constructed and understandable, it still seems unacceptable to us (even when we try to improve it by adding his part to the model of it was stupid of him to refuse this offer).<sep> We are several linguists to judge (10) as unacceptable as * This action/idea is short-sighted[6] .<sep> Does this mean that it is impossible to find a sentence like (10) in the corpus?<sep> Totally excluded, maybe not, because it presents a nice stylistic effect.<sep> But it seems that we can say that it is highly unlikely.<sep> As a result, myope and aveugle can be excluded from the list of adjectives that anchor an impersonal construction.<sep> More generally, we think that the list of adjectives (or verbs) that anchor an impersonal construction is not open to semantic slippage: it is a closed list, and therefore can be enumerated.<sep> A third type of error comes from syntactic gaps.<sep> In particular, we have considered any extraposed clausal subject as obligatory, whereas there exist cases where such a subject is not realized, for example, in phrases introduced by comme (as) , (10).<sep> We have added some of these expressions, but we have not conducted a linguistic study to know the extent of the phenomenon, so we have syntactical gaps.<sep> (11) As it has been announced / it would be / it often happens / it is well known<sep> Finally, a fourth and last type of error concerns impersonal clauses with a nominal extraposed subject.<sep> On the one hand, as we explained in 3.2.3, these constructions are difficult to identify for common verbs such as manquer or rester.<sep> On the other hand, we have not written any pattern to identify impersonal forms with a passive verb or a refined language level, see section 2.1, hence errors like (12).<sep> (12) A circle of hatred had formed around this abject individual... The first three types of errors can be avoided at low cost, but the same cannot be said for the fourth type.<sep> 4.4 Other errors: 0,2%<sep> Some errors come from the fact that the word il is not used as a subject pronoun but as part of a named entity in a foreign language, see (11)[5] .<sep> There are also typos/spelling errors, (13b) and (13c).<sep> These errors are inexcusable when starting from a raw text.<sep> (13)a It started in the second half of the 18th century, when, in Milan, this enlightenment magazine called Il Caffé was published. b It was 25 years ago. c Then they crossed the obstacles in the woods.<sep> 4.5 Evaluation on corpora of different gender<sep> An evaluation of ILIMP has also been realized on French literary texts written in the XIXth century. It concerns 1858 occurrences of il .<sep> The precision rate falls compared to the journalistic genre: it goes from 97,5% to 96,8%.<sep> This fall comes, on the one hand, from impersonal expressions which are not used anymore, (11), on the other hand, from a high number of sentences with subject inversion, as in (9b) in Section 4.3.<sep> (14) But maybe it was a little bit early to organize a concert, ...<sep> The percentage of impersonal il in literary texts increases compared to Le Monde corpus: it goes from 42% to 49,8%.<sep> In a more general way, we expect important differences on the percentage of il with an impersonal use according to the genre of corpora[8] , but we don't expect significant differences on the rate of good results of ILIMP (especially if the three first types of errors described in Section 4.2 are corrected). This is because the list of lexical heads for impersonal clauses is closed and stable whatever the corpus.<sep> 5 Conclusion and future work<sep> The method used in ILIMP to locate the occurrences of impersonal or anaphoric il, which gives good results, can be used for other languages and for other tasks.<sep> It has already been said (note 2) that a tool derived from ILIMP can be designed to identify the lexical head of a simple sentence.<sep> Another tool can be designed to enhance a module in charge of the computation of syntactic functions, thanks to the notion of “deep extraposed subject”, which is relevant for impersonal clauses.<sep> Furthermore, the method can be used to disambiguate frequent and ambiguous words such as il. Thus, (Jacques, 2005) uses a method similar to ours in the first step of the processing that she proposes to disambiguate the word que: without even using the richness of the lexicon-grammar of the LADL, she increases the precision rate on the labeling of this word by 14% compared to Tree Tagger (passage from 75% of good results to 89%).<sep> We can question the relevance of these "little" tools which are limited to a single word or a very specific feature. They are certainly modest when compared to a system which would produce, for any given input sentence, a (and only one) complete syntax analysis, with a precision rate close to 98%.<sep> However, it has to be acknowledged that such a system does not exist yet.<sep> So we will move forward for the defence of small tools with the famous saying: Many a little makes a mickle .<sep> It remains to channel these streams, i.e. to organize a vast research effort to determine how to order the "little" tools in a processing chain leading to a robust, complete and correct syntactic analysis.<sep> Acknowledgements<sep> I would like to thank Eric Laporte who provided me with all the logistics necessary to carry out this work at the University of Marne-la-Vallée, and Olivier Blanc for the vital technical assistance he provided me. I would also like to thank Sylvain Kahane and Alexis Nasr for their fruitful comments on this article.<sep> 1 Unitex is a GPL open source system, which is similar to Intex (Silberstein 1994).<sep> Documentation and download of Unitex can be found at the following url: http://ladl.univmlv.fr.<sep> 2 This work can be re-used in a tool which aims at identifying the lexical head of a simple sentence, a tool which can be integrated in the processing chain of a modular syntactic analyser.<sep> This work consists of putting the notion of “verbal cluster” (Gerdes, Kahane, 2004) into the form of automata.<sep> 3 P is the symbol for the pattern aiming at representing a sentence.<sep> This pattern is made up of a non-empty sequence of tokens which includes a finite verb.<sep> 4 Namely Isabelle Faugeras, Annie Meunier, Christian Leclère, Laurence Delort, Ane Dybro-Johansen, François Lareau, Alexis Nasr, Céline Raynal, Jacques Steinlin, François Toussenel and Mélodie Soufflard, whom we thank warmly.<sep> 5 She asks that UNITEX be adapted to take into account the results of a tagger, which has been done by Patrick Watrin for Tree Tagger.<sep> 6 One can put forward the hypothesis of a correlation between the possibility for an adjective to anchor an impersonal construction and that of having an abstract subject as an action or idea, see the pair<sep> It is abracadabrantesque to think that Fred will vote no and This idea is abracadabrantesque .<sep> 7 If ILIMP took as input a text in which the named entities are recognized, the error in (13a) would be avoided since the sequence Il Caffè would be recognized as a named entity.<sep> In this article, the word il often belongs to the metalanguage and is not used as a subject pronoun.<sep> The daily newspaper Le Monde contains a number of long articles about the lives and works of famous people.<sep> These articles, when they concern a famous male person, chain together numerous anaphoric il referring to this man.<sep> One can expect the percentage of impersonal il to increase in newspapers dealing only with news or economics.
Improving automatic text segmentation thanks to the knowledge acquired by latent semantic analysis.<sep> Abstract<sep> Choi, Wiemer-Hastings, and Moore (2001) proposed to use Latent Semantic Analysis (LSA) to extract semantic knowledge from corpora in order to improve the accuracy of a text segmentation algorithm.<sep> By comparing the accuracy of the very same algorithm, depending on whether or not it takes into account complementary semantic knowledge, they were able to show the benefit derived from such knowledge.<sep> In their experiments, semantic knowledge was, however, acquired from a corpus containing the texts to be segmented in the test phase.<sep> If this hyper-specificity of the LSA corpus explains the largest part of the benefit, one may wonder if it is possible to use LSA to acquire generic semantic knowledge that can be used to segment new texts.<sep> The two experiments reported here show that the presence of the test materials in the LSA corpus has an important effect, but also that the generic semantic knowledge derived from large corpora clearly improves the segmentation accuracy.<sep> Keywords: Automatic text segmentation, Latent Semantic Analysis (LSA)<sep> 1. Improving Text Segmentation by Using Complementary Semantic Knowledge<sep> For the last ten years, many methods have been proposed for the automatic segmentation of texts in topically related units on the basis of lexical cohesion.<sep> The major distinction between these methods is in the contrast between the approaches based exclusively on the information contained in the text to be segmented, such as lexical repetition (e.g., Choi 2000; Hearst 1997; Heinonen 1998; Kehagias, Pavlina, and Petridis 2003; Utiyama and Isahara 2001), and those approaches that rest on complementary semantic knowledge extracted from dictionaries and thesauruses (e.g., Kozima 1993; Lin et al. 2004; Morris and Hirst 1991), or from collocations collected in large corpora (Bolshakov and Gelbukh 2001; Brants, Chen, and Tsochantaridis 2002; Choi et al. 2001; Ferret 2002; Kaufmann 1999; Ponte and Croft 1997).<sep> According to their authors, methods that use additional knowledge allow for a solution to problems encountered when sentences belonging to a unique topic do not share common words due to the use of hyperonyms or synonyms.<sep> Empirical arguments in favor of these methods have been provided recently by Choi et al. (2001) in a study using Latent Semantic Analysis (Latent Semantic Indexing, Deerwester et al. 1990) to extract a semantic space from a corpus allowing determination of the similarity of meanings of words, sentences, or paragraphs.<sep> By comparing the accuracy of the very same algorithm according to whether or not it takes into account complementary semantic knowledge, Choi et al. (2001) were able to show the benefit derived from such knowledge.<sep> However, implications of Choi et al.’s study for text segmentation and for the use of LSA in natural language processing are unclear due to the methodology employed.<sep> In their experiments, semantic knowledge was acquired from a corpus containing the texts that were segmented in the test phase.<sep> One could speculate whether the largest part of the benefit obtained thanks to the addition of semantic knowledge was not due to this hyper-specificity of the LSA corpus (i.e., the inclusion of the test materials).<sep> If this were the case, it would call into question the possibility of using LSA to acquire generic semantic knowledge that can be used to segment new texts.<sep> A priori, the problem does not seem very important, because Choi et al. used a large number of small test samples to evaluate their algorithm, each sample representing on average only 0.15% of the LSA corpus.<sep> The present study shows, however, that the presence of the test materials in the LSA corpus has an important effect, but also that the generic semantic knowledge derived from large corpora clearly improves the segmentation accuracy.<sep> This conclusion is drawn from two experiments in which the presence or absence of the test materials in the LSA corpus is manipulated.<sep> The first experiment is based on the original materials from Choi et al., which consisted of a small corpus (1,000,000 words).<sep> The second experiment is based on a much larger corpus (25,000,000 words).<sep> Before reporting these experiments, Choi’s algorithm and the use of LSA within this framework are described.<sep> 2. The Two Versions of Choi’s Algorithm<sep> The segmentation algorithm proposed by Choi (2000) is made up of the three steps usually found in any segmentation procedure based on lexical cohesion.<sep> Firstly, the document to be segmented is divided into minimal textual units, usually sentences.<sep> Then, a similarity index between every pair of adjacent units is calculated.<sep> Each raw similarity value is cast on an ordinal scale by taking the proportion of neighboring values that are smaller than it.<sep> Lastly, the document is segmented recursively according to the boundaries between the units that maximize the sum of the average similarities inside the segments thus comprised.<sep> The step of greatest interest here is the one that calculates the inter-sentence similarities.<sep> The procedure initially proposed by Choi (2000), C99, rests exclusively on the information contained in the text to be segmented.<sep> Each sentence is represented by a vector constructed according to the classical vector model (Manning, Schütze, 1999, pp. 539ff) and the similarity between two sentences is calculated by means of the cosine measure between the corresponding vectors.<sep> In a first evaluation based on the procedure described below, Choi showed that its algorithm outperforms several other approaches such as TextTiling (Hearst 1997) and Segmenter (Kan, Klavans, and McKeown 1998).<sep> Choi et al. (2001) proposed to improve the inter-sentence similarity measure by taking into account the semantic proximities between words estimated on the basis of Latent Semantic Analysis (LSA).<sep> Briefly stated, LSA rests on the thesis that analyzing the contexts in which words occur permits an estimation of their similarity in meaning (Deerwester et al. 1990; Landauer and Dumais 1997).<sep> The first step in the analysis is to construct a lexical table containing an information-theoretic weighting of the frequencies of the words occurrence in each document (i.e. sentence, paragraph, or text) included in the corpus.<sep> To extract the semantic dimensions, this lexical table undergoes a decomposition into singular values, a sort of factor analysis that extracts the most important orthogonal dimensions.<sep> After this step, every word is represented by a vector of weights indicating its strength of association with each of the dimensions.<sep> This makes it possible to measure the semantic proximity between any two words by using, for instance, the cosine measure between the corresponding vectors.<sep> Proximity between any two sentences (or any other textual units), even if these sentences were not present in the original corpus, can be estimated by computing a vector for each of these units—which corresponds to the weighted sum of the vectors of the words that compose it—and then by computing the cosine between these vectors (Deerwester et al. 1990).<sep> Choi et al. (2001) have shown that using this procedure to compute the inter-sentence similarities results in the previous version of the algorithm (based solely on word repetition) being outperformed.<sep> 3. Experiment 1<sep> The aim of this experiment is to determine the impact of the presence of the test materials in the LSA corpus on the results obtained by Choi et al. (2001).<sep> Does semantic knowledge acquired from a corpus that does not include the test materials also improve the segmentation accuracy?<sep> 3.1 Method<sep> This experiment was based on the methodology developed by Choi (2000). This methodology was also used by several authors to evaluate the effectiveness of their segmentation system (Brants, Chen, Tsochantaridis, 2002; Ferret, 2002; Kehagias et al. , 2003; Utiyama, Isahara, 2001).<sep> The task consists in finding the boundaries between concatenated texts.<sep> Each test sample is a concatenation of ten text segments.<sep> Each segment consisted in the first n sentences of a randomly selected text from two sub-sections of the Brown corpus.<sep> For the present experiment, I used the most general test materials proposed by Choi (2000), in which the size of the segments within each sample varies randomly from 3 to 11 sentences.<sep> It is composed of 400 samples.<sep> The experiment aims to compare the efficiency of the algorithm when the test material is included in the LSA learning corpus (non-autonomous condition) or when it is not (autonomous condition).<sep> A non-autonomous semantic space, which corresponds to the one used by Choi et al., was built using the entire Brown corpus as the LSA corpus.<sep> Four hundred different autonomous spaces were built, one for each test sample, by each time removing from the Brown corpus only the sentences that make up this sample.<sep> To extract the LSA space and to apply the segmentation algorithm, a series of parameters had to be set.<sep> First of all, paragraphs were used as documents for building the lexical tables because Choi et al. observed that such middle-sized units were more effective than shorter units (i.e., sentences).<sep> The words on Choi’s stoplist were removed, as were those that appeared only once in the whole corpus.<sep> Words were not stemmed, as in Choi et al. (2001).<sep> To build the LSA space, the singular value decomposition was realized using the program SVDPACKC (Berry 1992; Berry et al. 1993), and the first 300 singular vectors were retained.<sep> Concerning the segmentation algorithm, I used the version in which the number of boundaries to be found is imposed, and thus fixed at nine.<sep> An 11 × 11 rank mask was used for the ordinal transformation, as recommended by Choi (2000).<sep> 3.2 Results<sep> The segmentation accuracy was evaluated by means of the index reported by Choi et al. (2001): the Pk measure of segmentation inaccuracy (Beeferman, Berger, and Lafferty 1999), which gives the proportion of sentences that are wrongly predicted to belong to the same segment or wrongly predicted to belong to different segments.<sep> Results are presented in Figure 1.[1]<sep> Compared with the Within condition, the performance in the Without condition is definitely worse, as confirmed by t tests for paired sample (each test sample being used as an observation) that are significant for an alpha smaller than 0.0001.<sep> The C99 algorithm, which does not employ LSA to estimate the similarities between the sentences, produces a Pk of 0.13 (Choi et al. 2001, Table 3, line 3: No stemming).<sep> It appears that although the Without condition is still better than C99, the benefit is very small.<sep> Figure 1: Error rate and variance (in parentheses) for non-autonomous and autonomous conditions.<sep> Before concluding that the presence of the test materials in the LSA corpus strongly modified the semantic space, an alternative explanation must be considered.<sep> The loss of accuracy in the autonomous condition could potentially be due to the fact that there are systematically slightly fewer words indexed in the autonomous semantic spaces than in the non-autonomous space.<sep> Removing each test sample led to the loss—on average— of 23 different words out of the 25,847 words that are indexed in the Within space.<sep> In the autonomous spaces, these words are not available to estimate the similarity of the sentences, whereas they are used in the non-autonomous space.<sep> In order to determine whether this factor can explain the difference in performance, a complementary analysis was carried out on the non-autonomous space in which, for each test sample, only the words present in the corresponding autonomous space were taken into account.<sep> In this manner, only the semantic relations can come into play.<sep> Compared with the complete non-autonomous space, almost no drop in performance was observed: the Pk error rate went from 0.084 to 0.085 in the new analysis.<sep> This result indicates that it is not the words selected for the calculation of the proximities that matter, but the semantic relations in the spaces.<sep> 4. Experiment 2<sep> Experiment 1 was conducted on the Choi et al. (2001) LSA corpus, a 1,000,000-word collection of texts from very different genres and with varied themes.<sep> The smallness of the corpus and diversity of the texts could have affected the results in two ways.<sep> First, the impact of the presence of test material in the corpus is likely to depend on these corpus characteristics.<sep> First, removing a few sentences of a text should have less impact if the corpus contains a lot of texts on similar topics.<sep> Second, a larger corpus would probably also permit the extraction of a more stable and efficient semantic space.<sep> This could produce a greater difference between the LSA version of the algorithm and the version that does not use additional semantic knowledge (C99).<sep> For these reasons, a second experiment was conducted on the basis of a much larger corpus consisting of the articles published during 1997 and 1998 in the Belgian French-speaking newspaper Le Soir (roughly 52,000 articles and 26,000,000 words).<sep> In this corpus, the test materials from each sample account for—on average—0.0066% of the complete corpus.<sep> This second experiment also made it possible to compare the non-autonomous and autonomous conditions with a former condition based on articles published in the same newspaper, but during the years 1995 and 1996 (approximately 50,000 articles and more than 22,000,000 words).<sep> This condition will inform us about the possibility of using LSA to extract more generic semantic knowledge, since the LSA corpus is earlier than the text to segment.<sep> It should be noted, however, that since this information comes from the same journalistic source, to call it independent would be a gross exaggeration.<sep> 4.1 Method<sep> The test materials were extracted from the 1997–1998 corpus following the guidelines given in Choi (2000).<sep> It is composed of 100 samples of ten segments, of which the length varies randomly from 3 to 11 sentences.<sep> Three types of LSA space were built.<sep> The Non-autonomous space is based on the whole 1997–1998 corpus.<sep> One hundred different autonomous spaces were built as described in Experiment 1.<sep> Finally, a Former space was built from the 1995–1996 corpus.<sep> The parameters employed to build the semantic spaces are identical to those used in Experiment 1 with one exception: in order to reduce the size of the lexical tables, articles and not paragraphs were used as documents and the words were lemmatised using TreeTagger (Schmid 1994).<sep> 4.2 Results<sep> Overall, the results are similar to those obtained in the first experiment. As shown in Figure 2, the autonomous spaces lead to lower performances than the non-autonomous space and, as expected, the anterior space leads to even lower performances.<sep> Figure 2: Error rates and variance (in parentheses) for the non-autonomous, autonomous and prior conditions.<sep> However, it is important to note that the C99 algorithm, which is not based on latent semantic analysis, produces a Pk error rate of 0.155, a value definitely worse than those obtained with the autonomous spaces (0.084) and with the former space (0.098).<sep> This confirms the usefulness of semantic knowledge acquired from large corpora in estimating inter-sentence similarities.<sep> Compared to the first experiment, the gap between the non-autonomous and autonomous conditions is much smaller, going from 0.036 for experiment 1 to 0.01 for experiment 2.<sep> This difference remains statistically significant (t(99) = 3.17; p = 0.002).<sep> Although larger, the difference between the post- and pre-conditions (0.014) is statistically just significant (t(99) = 2.04; p = 0.045).<sep> Figure 3 shows that the independent condition outperforms the prior condition in 46 samples, while the opposite occurs in 35 samples, with the remaining 19 samples showing no difference between the two conditions.<sep> Figure 3: Distribution of differences in PK between Autonomous and Antecedent conditions<sep> So we see that the advantage of the autonomous condition over the prior condition is mainly due to a few test samples for which the autonomous condition is much more effective.<sep> It should also be noted that the prior condition leads to much better results than those obtained when segmentation is carried out without the use of additional semantic knowledge.<sep> 5. Conclusion<sep> The two experiments reported here show that the presence of the test materials in the LSA learning corpus increases the segmentation algorithm's efficiency even when a corpus of more than 25,000,000 words is used.<sep> They also showed that the use of independent semantic knowledge improves the segmentation accuracy and that this can be observed even when the semantic knowledge is extracted from former years of the same source.<sep> This observation underlines the possibility of building relatively generic semantic knowledge; that is, knowledge which could be employed to process new linguistic data, as has been recently proposed in a anaphora resolution algorithm, in a continuous speech recognition system, or in machine translation (Bellegarda 2000; Klebanov and Wiemer-Hastings 2002; Kim, Chang, and Zhang 2003).<sep> A question the present study does not answer concerns the possibility of employing a corpus drawn from another source, such as another newspaper.<sep> Bellegarda (2000) observed in speech recognition tasks that such a semantic space is definitely less effective.<sep> However, evaluating the semantic proximity between two sentences is probably less affected by the source of the corpus than predicting the next word of a statement.<sep> Recently, several authors have proposed segmentation algorithms, based mainly on dynamic programming, that equal or even outperform Choi’s results (Ji and Zha 2003, Kehagias et al. 2003; Utiyama and Isahara 2001).<sep> These algorithms do not rest on additional semantic knowledge.<sep> The results of the present study suggest that their effectiveness could still be improved by taking into account such knowledge.<sep> Finally, other techniques than the ASL have been proposed to extract semantic knowledge from large corpora such as pASL (Brants et al., 2002). The latent semantic analysis being relatively simple to implement thanks to the availability of very powerful programs such as SVDPACKC (Berry et al., 1993), its main advantage is that it is used by an increasingly large community of researchers. An important limitation of this work lies in the task used to evaluate the effectiveness of the segmentation algorithm.<sep> Identifying the boundaries between concatenated texts is an artificial task and certainly less complex than locating changes of themes within texts.<sep> The fact that the procedure and the material designed by Choi have become a sort of "standard" used by a series of researchers to evaluate their algorithm is not enough to legitimize it. It would therefore be useful to confirm the conclusions of this study in a task of intratext segmentation.<sep> Acknowledgments<sep> Yves Bestgen is research fellow of the Belgian National Fund for Scientific Research (FNRS).<sep> This work was supported by grant FRFC 2.4535.02 and by a "Concerted Research Action" of the government of the French-language community of Belgium.<sep> 1 The error rate is in fact slightly better than that reported by Choi et al. (2001). The difference could be due to several factors, such as the pre-processing of the Brown corpus (e.g., tokenization and paragraph identification) or the scaling function applied to the raw frequencies, which was here the standard information-theoretic weighting described in Landauer, Foltz, and Laham (1998).
Evolutionary approach of basic notions for a thematic representation of general knowledge<sep> Abstract<sep> In the field of Natural Language Processing, in order to work out a thematic representation system of general knowledge, methods relying on thesaurus have been used for about twenty years.<sep> A thesaurus consists of a set of concepts which define a generating system of a vector space modelling general knowledge.<sep> These concepts, often organized in a treelike structure, constitute a fundamental, but completely fixed tool.<sep> Even if the concepts evolve (we think for example of the technical fields), a thesaurus as for it can evolve only at the time of a particularly heavy process, because it requires the collaboration of human experts. This is the problem we are addressing here.<sep> After detailing the characteristics which a generating system of the vector space of knowledge modelling must have, we define the “basic notions”.<sep> These, whose construction is initially based on the concepts of a thesaurus, constitute another generating system of this vector space.<sep> We then approach the determination of the acceptions expressing the basic notions, which naturally leads us to ask the question of their number.<sep> Lastly, we clarify how, being freed from the concepts of the thesaurus, the basic notions evolve progressively with the analysis of new texts by an iterative process.<sep> Keywords : thesaurus, conceptual vectors, basic notions, evolution.<sep> 1. Introduction: thematic representation of general knowledge<sep> (Lafourcade and Sandford 1999) then (Lafourcade 2001) developed a system of thematic representation[1] of general knowledge.<sep> This system is based on a vector representation which is initially built from the hierarchy of concepts of the Larousse thesaurus (Larousse 1999).<sep> This thesaurus initially defines the extent of general knowledge: we consider that a term belongs to general knowledge when it belongs to one of the non-specialized dictionaries (ex: Larousse or Robert for French language).<sep> The use of a vector space for modelling has existed for a long time in Information Retrieval, for example (Salton and MacGill 1983).<sep> The thesaurus we used features a treelike structure, hierarchised in 4 levels, plus the root consisting of the universal concept; it contains 873 leaf concepts.<sep> These concepts form a generative system of the vector space named C873; this space constitutes a modelling of our thematic representation system of general knowledge.<sep> This vector approach, based on a set of predetermined concepts, is the one that (Chauché 1990) recommended.<sep> The concepts defining the generative system constitute the fundamental elements in representing knowledge.<sep> The purpose of a generative system is thus to be able to represent the maximum of general knowledge in a minimum number of vectors.<sep> Do the 873 concepts of the thesaurus used, given a priori, establish the “best” generative system?<sep> This question is all the more legitimate that other general thesauruses were published, for example the Roget Thesaurus (Kipfer 2001). The oldest is probably the Roget's Thesaurus (Kipfer, 2001) whose first edition dates from the mid-19th century, organized in a hierarchical structure that counts 1075 concepts in its current version, grouped into 15 classes. This thesaurus has served as a basis for different works, for example Yarowsky (1992).<sep> The 873 concepts used do not constitute a base of the C873 vector space.<sep> Indeed, it is possible to find relations between some of these 873 generative vectors; for example, between the concepts 1_EXISTENCE and 2_INEXISTENCE there is a relationship of antonymy; even if it would be naive to consider that their associated vectors are opposite (Schwab, 2005), it is obvious that the dimension of the C873 space is therefore smaller than 873.<sep> However, for reasons of simplicity, the decomposition of an acception remains unique in the considered thesaurus.<sep> This interdependence between concepts has sometimes been processed, as for example in the LSA model (Deerwester and al. 1990).<sep> Every acception, that is, every meaning of a term, is thus represented on C873 by a unique vector, called abstract vector (Schwab 2005): each of the 873 components of an abstract vector represents the intensity of one of the 873 generative ideas.<sep> The abstract vectors are at the moment built from the hierarchy of a thesaurus, thus totally fixed.<sep> This construction is achieved by automatic learning from various sources: dictionaries, lists of synonyms or antonyms, etc.<sep> For example, in the case of a definition of an acception, we combine the abstract vectors of the various acceptions that we meet in the text of this definition to form the abstract vector of the defined acception.<sep> To obtain a base of relevance, Schwab et al. (2004) showed the need for permanent learning.<sep> The 873 concepts of the Larousse thesaurus establish a generative system.<sep> This system is not unique!<sep> Each human individual has his own generative system that allows him to make his own representation of knowledge;<sep> Furthermore, our personal knowledge increases over the course of our lives and so this individual system evolves over time.<sep> We can consider that the generative system of the Larousse thesaurus corresponds in fact to that of a typical individual. The individual generative system does not correspond to that of the thesaurus used (none of us is truly reduced to a typical individual).<sep> Can we find a “better” generative system of the vector space modelling the thematic representation of knowledge than the generative system defined by the concepts of the used thesaurus, considering only general knowledge, i.e. abstracting from any specialisation?<sep> What is the meaning of “better”?<sep> Even if it seems delicate, even impossible, to measure the pertinence of a set of concepts defining a generative system, what are the criteria that such a set must meet?<sep> 2. What are the criteria of a good generative system?<sep> It could be pretentious to assert what a good generative system of a vector space modelling our thematic representation of general knowledge would be.<sep> It is however possible to clarify several minimal characteristics that such a system must have.<sep> This is close to the work of (Wilks 1977).<sep> 2.1 Extent: it is a generative system<sep> A generative system has to cover the whole generalist domain (because it is the domain considered here).<sep> What do we mean by “the whole non-specialized domain”?<sep> Even if it is impossible to define the limits of the domain in a clear way, we can consider that the terms belonging to common non-specialized dictionaries give us a reasonable idea of what these limits are.<sep> We cannot however conclude that any new acception that could be expressed according to already existing acceptions can be considered as being part of the domain. For example, Quidditch is a flying ball game played between two teams of apprentice students in wizardry schools. The term Quidditch is not (yet) part of the general vocabulary.<sep> 2.2 Representativeness: it is a generative system close to a base<sep> If the generalist nature of the generating system is to be preserved, it is not appropriate to include any new meaning automatically.<sep> To return to the example above, the term Quidditch is not in the Petit Larousse.<sep> A generative system should distinguish, in a minimum number of concepts, a maximum of “common” notions: our experiments show that a thousand of concepts seem sufficient to be such a system.<sep> The generative system, even if it is not a base of the representation space (can we really verify it?), must be relatively close to it.<sep> 2.3 Evolution capacities: it is not a fixed system<sep> A thesaurus is mainly criticized for its fixed character.<sep> A generative system must be able to take into account the evolution of notions easily.<sep> Furthermore, a generative system, like a thesaurus, cannot a priori be exhaustive: it seems difficult, even impossible, to define the limits of the considered domain.<sep> This shows the need, depending on the requirements, for the generative system to be evolutionary.<sep> It will be necessary however to make sure that this evolvability does not work against the representativeness.<sep> Does a generating system necessarily have to be organised in a hierarchical tree structure, as is the case with the Larousse thesaurus or Roget’s?<sep> In the current state of our work, we do not use this feature.<sep> However, the issue is addressed in section 3.3.<sep> 3. Method: definition and evolution of the basic notions<sep> 3.1 Definition of the basic notions<sep> In an incremental way, as texts are analysed, we meet words.<sep> Let k be the number of different terms met. (For the French language, most current general dictionaries have around 80,000 entries).<sep> Most of the terms being polysemous, these different k terms have k’ acceptions and thus generate k’ vectors on the C873 vector space.<sep> Furthermore, it is necessary to balance these k’ vectors according to how often they appear in the texts studied.<sep> Indeed, some meanings of terms are much more frequent than others and therefore play a more important role in our knowledge[2]. It seems natural that this weighting function, which is necessarily increasing, is a logarithmic function of the frequency of appearance.<sep> Indeed, it is necessary to carry out an amortization of the impact of this frequency on the norm of the corresponding acceptance vector.<sep> It also seems reasonable to weight every occurrence of these k’ vectors according to the depth of the corresponding acception in the syntactic analysis tree of the text studied; indeed, it is logical to think that the more a word is “lost” in the depths of a sentence, the less important it is for the global meaning of this sentence[2] .<sep> It seems natural that this weighting function, inevitably decreasing, should be a negative exponential function of depth.<sep> In a more formal way, if we call p the depth of a term t in the tree of syntactic analysis of the studied text, the norm of the vector v representing the corresponding acception (after disambiguation between the possible various acceptions of t) is: ||v|| = e[-][α][p] where α is a weighting coefficient.<sep> The ith occurrence of this acception a of the term t will be represented on C873 by a vector va,i the norm of which will be: ||va,i|| = e[-][α][p][a,i] where pa,i indicates the depth in the analysis tree of the ith occurrence of the acception a.<sep> In order to take into account the frequency of the acceptions, it seems reasonable to consider a (logarithmic) summation of the different vectors representing every occurrence of a same acception.<sep> As a result, the vector va representing the acception a on all the texts processed will have as norm: ||va|| = Log ( Σi f(||va,i||) ), because, as explained above, we want ||va|| to be a function of the logarithm of the frequency of appearance of the acception a .<sep> ||va|| being a norm, it must verify its properties: - 1°/ ||va|| ≥ 0 - 2°/ ||va|| = 0 <-> va is the null vector - 3°/ ||va,i + va,j|| ≤ ||va,i|| + ||va,j||<sep> which translates here as: ||va|| ≤ Σi ||va,i||.<sep> - If there is only one occurrence of the meaning a, then ||va|| = ||va,1||.<sep> - If there are several occurrences of the meaning a, then ||va|| < Σi ||va,i||.<sep> These different conditions lead to consider: ||va|| = Log ( Σi e[||][v][a,i||] ).<sep> For the purpose of simplification, and taking into account the thematic closeness[4] , the k’ vectors va obtained can be grouped together in n clusters, with n << k’.<sep> The n barycentric vectors of these n clusters form a generative system of a vector space Bn.<sep> So, we group together the terms thematically close to a same concept.<sep> Although the method is different, our aim resembles the one developed by (Landauer and Dumais 1997) for the Latent Semantic Analysis (LSA) method.<sep> By considering a relatively large number n, probably from several hundreds to a few thousands, this Bn space can almost be confused with C873, provided that the texts studied sweep all the general knowledge.<sep> What do these n vectors correspond to?<sep> They are the “basic notions” deducted from the analysis of texts.<sep> Figure 1 illustrates the principle of our methodology.<sep> 3.2 Labelling the basic notions<sep> The space Bn depends strongly on the texts encountered;<sep> it may in fact correspond to the thematic representation space of knowledge for a human individual.<sep> Each of us has our own references and our own definitions: the Bn spaces, as well as their generating systems, are similar for different individuals, but are not necessarily absolutely identical.<sep> For each of these n basic notions, called bi, it is possible to find the closest term by using the notion of thematic distance defined on C873.<sep> Providing that a term close enough of bi exists, it will express this basic notion.<sep> Figure 1.<sep> This diagram illustrates the method used to define the basic concepts<sep> The study of texts makes it possible to obtain the morpho-syntactic analysis trees of the sentences that constitute them.<sep> This analysis is carried out using the SYGFRAN tool (for French) developed with SYGMART (Chauché, 1984).<sep> A semantic analysis as described in Schwab (2005) is then performed and each occurrence of a meaning is translated by a vector on C873 whose norm is a function of its depth in the tree.<sep> By summing (logarithmically) the vectors of the different occurrences of the same meaning, we obtain the vector corresponding to this meaning on C873.<sep> The vectors of the different meanings can be grouped into clouds whose barycentres define the basic notions.<sep> In fact, it is not a question of finding the closest term, but the closest acception of bi.<sep> The question of how to express it can be asked to avoid any risk of ambiguity.<sep> Furthermore, it is essential to take into account the frequency of the candidate acception to name the basic notion: can a rare acception be a good concept?<sep> (for example, is it too outdated? or too specialized?)<sep> On the other hand, the most frequent acception, or more exactly the one the vector of which has the biggest norm in the cluster (see fig.2), is not necessarily the ‘best’ concept, if it is relatively far from the barycenter of the cluster of vectors which it is supposed to represent. But then, how can we have an idea of the size of the domain concerned by bi?<sep> This bi-bj differentiation depends mainly on the value of n and therefore on the definition of the clouds, i.e. the parameters of the cloud discretization.<sep> As we have seen above, it is clear that the more precision we want, the smaller the clouds will be, and the more numerous they will be: the more basic concepts are fine and precise, the more numerous they will be (this is the classic precision-simplicity trade-off of a model).<sep> If there are many clouds, each of them will have a relatively low weight;<sep> They will therefore be more likely to evolve more quickly when analysing new texts (this is the trade-off between precision and stability).<sep> Consequently, the more basic concepts there are, the more difficult it will be for them to find unambiguous terms that are "sufficiently" close.<sep> 3.3. How many basic concepts should be considered?<sep> By not grouping together terms that are thematically close and therefore considering each meaning as a concept, each meaning vector is a generating vector;<sep> This is equivalent to setting n = k’.<sep> Naively, it could then be possible to represent everything without ambiguity.<sep> But, on the one hand, a vector space of dimension 400,000 seems voluminous in the current state of computer technology at the level of storage volume, and it could lead to processing times that are difficult to accept.<sep> On the other hand, is it really "unambiguous"?<sep> The fact that any interpretation is "decomposable" only in one concept does not, in particular, allow the notion of angular distance between vectors to be implemented.<sep> Between any two vectors of concepts-acceptations, the angular distance would invariably be equal to π/2.<sep> It is clear that this solution, which consists in considering that the distances between meanings are all identical, does not correspond to reality: intuitively, if it is possible to establish a thematic relationship between two meanings, their distance seems to be less than that which separates two meanings which have no common point;<sep> For example, if there is a co-hyponym relationship (example: between CAT and DOG) or a hyperonym/hyponym relationship (example: between CAT and MAMMAL), the distance between the meanings is clearly less than that which separates two meanings for which no relationship is clearly apparent (example: between CAT and NON-EXISTENCE, whose semantic fields apparently have little in common).<sep> It would, however, be possible to define an ultrametric distance between concepts (Schwab, 2005) which is calculated according to the minimum path between the two concepts considered in the hierarchical structure of the thesaurus.<sep> This distance could even be improved by a weighting that takes into account the order of the concepts in their sibships, in cases where such an order represents relevant information.<sep> But for that, you would need a thesaurus.<sep> However, in constructing Bn, we want to free ourselves from C873 and the constrained and fixed aspect of a fixed thesaurus defined a priori.<sep> One solution could be to consider that the space Bn is not homogeneous and therefore to cut up the space Bn into regions.<sep> For each of the n vectors belonging to a region, the distance between two vectors would depend on whether or not they belong to the same region.<sep> It could even be considered to group certain regions into super-regions[5];<sep> Only experience could show whether such a multi-level structure is clearly apparent.<sep> On the other hand, it is clear that a value that is too low for the number of concepts severely limits the quality of the discretization.<sep> To give an example based on the Larousse thesaurus, by simply going up one level in its hierarchical structure, and therefore only considering the 95 level 3 concepts (the 873 C873 generating concepts are level 4), all animals are grouped under the C3:ANIMALS concept, and it would then be difficult to discriminate between them, even by considering their characteristics or their behaviour.<sep> Too great a simplification of concepts, and therefore too great a reduction in their number, leads to a much too loose mesh of the space, generalist or specialist, that one wishes to model.<sep> This solution, which leads to a too imprecise thematic representation in the case of a fine analysis, could however be used in text classification.<sep> Indeed, for a given sentence or paragraph, it allows to quickly determine the thematic domain concerned.<sep> There is no optimal value for the number of basic concepts;<sep> Only experience can give an order of magnitude.<sep> In the context of general knowledge, it seems logical, in view of the existing thesauri, that this order of magnitude is around a thousand.<sep> The work carried out by Lafourcade et al. (2002) seems to show that a number of a few thousand would lead, without overburdening the system, to better results.<sep> 3.4. Scalability of the system<sep> As new texts are analysed, the clusters of vectors evolve: it is “the evolution of the notions”, with a possible phenomenon of differentiating clusters or grouping them together.<sep> This is to be set against the definition of the 873 basic concepts which are unchangeable.<sep> It is still worth noting that these evolving basic notions are initially expressed according to the 873 fixed concepts (is it not reassuring to have fixed landmarks to allow us to check the relevance of the vectors?).<sep> From the generative system of the fixed concepts, we built the generative system of the basic notions.<sep> Any acception can now be expressed in the space of the basic notions; therefore, any new acception expressed according to an already existing acception (which is the case of the definitions from dictionaries) can be expressed in the space of the basic notions.<sep> So, the thesaurus concepts are used for initializing the process.<sep> After a first definition of the basic notions, it is possible to break free from concepts, because any new acception can be decomposed on the space generated by the basic notions.<sep> It should be noted, however, that the process of evolution is necessarily relatively heavy. Indeed, it is carried out in two stages:<sep> 1. evolution of the basic notions, that is, evolution of the generative system:<sep> Every introduction of a new acception modifies the cluster to which it belongs.<sep> The barycenter of this cluster is thus moved, which leads to a modification of the vector of the corresponding basic notion.<sep> In some cases, the introduction of a new acception may have such an influence on the cluster that it can split in more restricted clusters, or on the contrary regroup with a nearby cluster.<sep> 2°/ modification of the coordinates of the acception vectors for which the components on the vectors of the modified basic notions is not equal to zero:<sep> After modifying the vector of a basic notion, it is essential to go through the existing acception vectors and to modify the coordinates of those for which the projection on the modified basic notion vector is not equal to zero: it is a classical change of reference. It should be remembered that the vector database is in permanent learning and the revision of basic notions can be carried out simultaneously with this learning.<sep> Indeed, during the revision of a vector of acception, we revise not only the intensity of its components, but also its components themselves, namely the basic notions on which it leans.<sep> Figure 2, which explains this evolutionary process, clearly shows its iterative principle: every introduction of a new acception generates an iteration leading to an evolution of the generative system of the space of the basic notions. Figure 2. This diagram, which briefly recalls the definition of the basic notions, illustrates the iterative structure allowing their evolution after the introduction of a new acception.<sep> This updating, even if it can be relatively long, is totally automatic.<sep> It is not the case with a fixed thesaurus defined a priori that can be modified only by a human expert.<sep> In this last case, the first stage, completely ‘manual’, is actually much heavier; the second stage, which is automatic, is similar to the one realized in the space of the basic notions.<sep> 4. Conclusion<sep> The modelling by a vector space for representating thematically general knowledge has been used for about twenty years.<sep> The definition of the generative system of this space usually rests on the hierarchy of a thesaurus: it is a fundamental, but totally fixed structure.<sep> Evolution of knowledge requires a generative system which can evolve.<sep> That is why we defined the basic notions.<sep> Their construction initially relies on the skeleton which constitutes the concepts of a thesaurus.<sep> As new texts are analyzed, the appearance of acceptions allows the evolution of the generative system of the space of knowledge representation.<sep> This evolutionary definition of the basic notions totally frees itself from the fixed hierarchy of the concepts.<sep> It allows to contemplate applications that will follow the evolution of notions, particularly in specialised fields where notions evolve more rapidly than in general fields.<sep> 1 We only consider thematic relations; “transverse” relations between objects not belonging to the same sub-tree of the hierarchy are not taken into account.<sep> To give just one example that illustrates our point, the link between Harry Potter and his owl Hedwig is only made through the concepts of fantasy literature and witchcraft, as well as the concepts associated with them.<sep> This link will not be any stronger<sep> that connects any Hogwarts student with any of their animals.<sep> To take this difference into account, we would need to consider the co-occurrences of the terms Harry Potter and Hedwig in the texts concerned, possibly weighted by the distances separating them in the morpho-syntactic analysis trees of the sentences where they are found.<sep> 2 Depending on the corpus of texts studied, in particular if it is a dictionary, one must be wary of general terms that are very frequently used in the labels of definitions, such as “action”, “part of”... which, according to Schwab et al. (2004) belong to metalanguage and which must obviously not be counted here.<sep> 3 Of course, this is a generality. The importance of a word also depends on its function in the sentence, and its depth in the tree of syntactic analysis is only a criterion of the importance of the word in question.<sep> 4 It is possible to measure this thematic closeness by means of the angular distance between conceptual vectors: this one is based on the notion of similarity between vectors, often used in information retrieval, for example (Baeza-Yates and Ribeiro-Neto 1999). 5 As an illustration, this could be compared to the spatial structure of the Universe.<sep> Galaxies group together in clusters of galaxies, which in turn group together in superclusters: our Galaxy belongs to the Local Cluster, which is itself part of the Virgo Supercluster.
Confusing the culprit: lexical corrections suggested by a grammar<sep> Abstract<sep> The success of the syntax analysis of a sentence depends on the quality of the underlying grammar but also on the correctness of the lexicon that feeds the parser.<sep> A first step towards the improvement of a lexicon consists in identifying potentially erroneous lexical entries, for instance by using error mining techniques on large corpora (Sagot and de La Clergerie, ACL/COLING 2006).<sep> This paper explores the next logical step, namely the suggestion of corrections for those entries.<sep> This is achieved by running new analysis on the sentences rejected at the previous step, after having modified the information carried by the identified lexical entries.<sep> A statistical computation on the new results then highlights the most relevant corrections.<sep> Keywords: parsing, lexicon, machine learning, correction .<sep> 1. Introduction<sep> The syntax analysis of a language is based on the use of the most accurate and correct linguistic resources possible.<sep> Obtaining resources with such wide coverage is a difficult and time-consuming task that can be alleviated through the use of tools that automate their creation and correction.<sep> We present here a technique of automatic generation of suggestions of corrections for potentially erroneous entries in a lexicon.<sep> We focus on methods to reduce the inaccuracy and incompleteness of a lexicon starting from a set of lexical forms suspected to be incorrectly or only partially described in a lexicon.<sep> Our work extends the error mining technique on large corpora originally proposed by (van Noord, 2004), and improved by (Sagot & Villemonte de La Clergerie, 2006).<sep> The relevance of the latter is particularly evident in our results.<sep> This detection technique relies on the following idea: given a large corpus of valid sentences, the more a form (and indirectly its associated lemmas) appears (or not) in non-parsable sentences, the more likely (or unlikely) its features are to be incorrect.<sep> Nevertheless, the context of the forms is important: a form is even more suspicious if it appears in non-parsable sentences along with forms that tend to appear in parsable ones.<sep> The implementation of the error mining technique has provided us with a list of 5344 suspicious forms with, for each form f , a suspicion rate and a list of unanalysable sentences (56089 in total) where f is suspected of being the cause of the parsing failures.<sep> If a form is actually responsible for those failures, and not the grammar,[1] then the information associated with this form (in fact with its underlying lemmas) is likely to be incorrectly or only partially described in the lexicon.<sep> Therefore, by releasing or modifying the constraints on the information carried by the suspicious form, new parses of the associated sentences will succeed.<sep> The representations of the sentences produced by the new successful parses provide useful grammatical information for the suspicious form. These data typify the conditions in which the parses could be achieved, that is, the expectations of the grammar for the form.<sep> By examining this information on a set of sentences, it is then possible to provide useful correction hypotheses.<sep> The technique presented is independent of the language studied.<sep> Related work.<sep> Acquisition of lexical knowledge from natural (i.e. not annotated) corpora using some grammatical knowledge has been first studied by Brent (1993) in order to infer the syntactic frames of English verbs.<sep> (Horiguchi et al., 1995) use the results of the analysis provided by an HPSG-based system in order to acquire lexical entries of unknown Japanese words.<sep> Finally, the reconstruction of missing lexical information for robust analysis, as studied by Grover and Lascarides (2001) and by Crysmann et al. (2002), should also be mentioned.<sep> We begin by explaining how to generate correction hypotheses (Sect. 2) and how to sort them (Sect. 3).<sep> Then, we introduce the notion of synchronisation between a lexicon and a grammar (Sect. 4), just before presenting the results obtained (Sect. 5) and the future developments (Sect. 6).<sep> 2. Hypotheses Generation<sep> The main goal of a parser is to check the syntactic correctness of a sentence and to produce one or more representations of it.<sep> In general, we intend to avoid overgeneration, that is, to generate as few representations as possible.<sep> We say that a sentence is ambiguous for a parser when its parse allows several interpretations.<sep> This happens mostly when the sentence is inherently ambiguous, i.e. when additional information, such as the semantic context, is needed in order to filter the interpretations, or when the resources used (lexicon, grammar...) are not restrictive enough and accept a wider language than intended.<sep> In order to reject sentences that do not belong to the language, we need the lexicon to be as accurate and detailed as possible.<sep> Indeed, the more a lexical form is specified, the less it combines with the other constituents of the sentence, and therefore, the less incorrect interpretations are permitted.<sep> 2.1. Causes of parsing failure<sep> Each form, through its lemmas, has different information that can be grouped into two sets: firstly the syntactic category (noun, verb, adjective, etc.), secondly the morphological features (number, gender, person, tense, mood, etc.) and the syntactic features (valence, argument facultativeness, reflexivity, passivation, etc.).<sep> A parsing failure due to a form is the consequence of a problem related to at least one of those sets.<sep> 2.1.1. Category Defect<sep> A single lexical form can be associated with several lemmas with distinct syntactic categories.<sep> The processing of such ambiguous forms within a sentence is managed by passing a lattice of words (or DAG) to the syntax analyzer (Sagot & Boullier, 2005).<sep> A successful parse validates at least one possible path of reading in this DAG.<sep> However, the lexicon may not contain all the homonyms of a form, and this can lead to parsing failures.<sep> For instance, the French word “fiche” is a noun and a flexion of the verb “ficher”.<sep> If no entry with a “noun” category is present, the sentence “Ma fiche contient une erreur”/ My card contains an error will be represented by the single sequence ma/possessive-pronoun fiche/verb contient/verb une/det erreur/noun .<sep> Unless a grammatical rule accepts such a construction, its analysis should fail.<sep> 2.1.2. Overspecification<sep> Usually, grammar rules are enriched with feature structures, in order to further constrain the language recognized by the grammar backbone (Abeillé, 1993).<sep> For example, a skeleton checks for the presence of a subject noun phrase and a verb in a sentence, while the decorations check for agreement (same person, number, and possibly gender).<sep> As we have explained, it is desirable that the lexical forms are as specific as possible in order to reduce ambiguity.<sep> Nonetheless, if they are too restrictive, i.e. overspecified, then feature unification on the syntactic backbone might fail. This issue arises with scarce uses of a form for which some features should have been marked as optional.<sep> For instance, the exhaustive enumeration of all the possible uses of a verb is a tedious task, because of polysemy, optional arguments, possible verbal alternations (“to buy something” will give “something is bought”), and various realizations of the arguments.<sep> Consequently, some aspects may sometimes be marked as mandatory when, in some cases, they are only optional.<sep> This observation extends to other syntactic categories as soon as they are assigned categorization frameworks.<sep> 2.2 Re-parsing by specifying sub-sentences<sep> Since only the sentences that failed to be parsed are kept during the error detection step, their parsing rate is null.<sep> If changing some features of a suspicious form f allows their parsing rate to increase noticeably, it seems natural to assume that f was responsible for the previous failures.<sep> The difficulty is then to identify which changes allow for significant increases.<sep> Rather than testing all possible combinations of changes, which is exponential and thus inefficient, we rely upon the ability of our parser to handle underspecified forms.<sep> Once new parsing results are obtained, we are able to extract and compute correction hypotheses (see Sect. 2.2.2).<sep> 2.2.1. Joker Generation and Use<sep> In order to make sentences that were initially non-parsable, we introduce special underspecified lexical forms called jokers .<sep> In the current approach (which needs to be refined), they only have one syntactic category (among the "open" categories: verb, noun, adjective or adverb).<sep> Thus, a joker is not constrained with fixed morphological or syntactic informations, and always fulfills the grammar requirements.<sep> Since their use does not raise any conflict during analysis (except for the syntax category), substituting them for a suspicious form in a rejected sentence enhances the chances of successful parsing.<sep> Nevertheless, it can introduce a noticeable ambiguity because there is no more filtering on the decorations.<sep> Since, so far, we are not able to know which kind of error (overspecification or category defect) is responsible for the parsing failures, we consider both simultaneously when generating the jokers.<sep> To handle an overspecification, we replace a form of category X with a joker of the same category X.<sep> The characteristics then allow the parser to explore the same grammar rules as the ones used for the initial sentence without being stopped by the decorations.<sep> In order to deal with a category defect, we use jokers with syntactic categories distinct from the ones of the suspicious form f.<sep> By doing so, the re-analyses will explore other productions.<sep> These jokers are generated from the information provided by a lemmatizer (stemmer) or by a probabilistic tagger such as TREETAGGER (Schmid, 1999).<sep> We could have used a single joker without any syntactic category, hence without any information, which would cover all the situations described above.<sep> However, such a joker introduces a very strong ambiguity, leading to parsing failures caused by timeouts or memory shortage, or to an overgeneration of interpretations.<sep> In the first case, we do not collect any information; in the second case, the huge amount of data prevents its efficient analysis.<sep> Our approach allows (to a large extent) to avoid these problems while avoiding multiplying the number of jokers by suspicious form.<sep> During our experiments, we tested 2.05 jokers per suspicious form (10 978 all in all), resulting in 117 655 new analyses.<sep> FIG. 1 – Extract from the graphical representation of a shared forest of dependencies<sep> 2.2.2. Syntactic Signature Extraction<sep> Assuming that a suspicious form has been correctly identified by the error mining step, exchanging it with jokers in the associated sentences allows some parses to succeed.<sep> In fact, we observe a clear relationship between the success rate of the analysis of the modified sentences and the suspicion rate of the form concerned.<sep> The parser we use returns the set of all possible interpretations for the parsed sentence as a shared dependency forest (see Fig. 1). This forest is available in XML format, allowing easy manipulation. In such forests, vertices represent the lemmas and edges represent the syntactic dependencies between lemmas.<sep> Each node has information about the lemma and the anchored grammatical production (in the context of a lexicalized grammar). Each dependency is characterized by a governor source node, a governee target node, a nature and a label that depends on the grammar.<sep> The label often (but not always) indicates the syntactic function of the target (subject, object, …).<sep> In order to manage ambiguities, additional information, local to the governor, links lemmas and dependencies to one or more interpretations.<sep> Thus, the representation resulting from the analysis of the sentence for "La vie est belle" (Fig. 1) gives rise to four possible readings, due to (a) the ambiguity of "est" as a copula verb, a common noun (in apposition to "vie") and an adjective, and (b) the ambiguity of "belle" as an adjective and a noun.<sep> Without any additional information, both interpretations as a noun and an adjective of "is" should have been rejected because they introduce a rare apposition and/or construct a sentence without a verb.<sep> The forests contain incoming and outgoing dependencies to and from the joker.<sep> We now call syntactic signature the set of dependencies around a joker in a particular interpretation and group of signatures the set of all possible syntactic signatures for a given sentence.<sep> Those signatures represent the conditions in which the analysis could be achieved; in other words, it represents the data the grammar would have accepted for the suspect form.<sep> Because of the ambiguity we introduced, the parser can produce several interpretations and thus several signatures.<sep> Among these interpretations, there is one that fits the true meaning of the sentence better than any other.<sep> Therefore, its corresponding signature contains the most relevant and interesting data. This is the data we need in order to infer the corrections we should apply to the lexicon.<sep> 3 Identify the best signatures<sep> Within only one group (produced from one sentence) we are unable to differentiate the relevant signatures from the ones that are just a consequence of the ambiguity we introduced.<sep> The variability of contexts induced by several groups of signatures (produced from several sentences) brings us a solution to this problem: this variability implies the diversification of non-relevant signatures, which contrasts with the stability of the relevant ones that correspond to the correct sense of the form.<sep> A clear repetition of particular signatures across all sentences suggests a pattern of use expected by the grammar for the form.<sep> In order to observe it, we promote/devalue the signatures through a simple two-step statistical computation.<sep> First step: local distribution of weights between signatures.<sep> The interest we have for a group of signatures depends on its size: the more signatures it contains, the less interest it has, since it is probably related to several permissive syntactic skeletons, as shown by the interpretations represented in Fig. 1.<sep> So, for each group, we compute a score P = c^n with c being a numerical constant in ]0, 1[ (eg. 0.95) and n the size of the group.<sep> At the level of a group, all the signatures are of equal importance, so we distribute the weights assigned to the group in an equitable manner: each signature receives a weight pg = P/n = c^n / n which thus depends twice on the size n of the group.<sep> Second step: global score computation.<sep> Once the previous step is complete, we add the scores received by a same signature σ in the different groups where it appears in order to compute its global score sσ = Σgpg.<sep> The best signatures, i.e. those that appear in several groups and in small groups, receive a higher score sσ.<sep> 4.2. Lexicon and Grammar Synchronization<sep> This technique allows the grammar to express its expectations about the suspicious forms.<sep> If it is not perfect, the interpretations it produces and the signatures that are extracted from it are not perfect either.<sep> In fact, in the case where the grammar is perfect, we can qualify the suggestions made by this technique as allowing a correction of the lexicon.<sep> Conversely, this technique is a method that attempts to decrease the number of conflicts between a grammar and a lexicon in order to better “synchronize” them.<sep> It is important to note that a set of incorrect signatures represents an interesting source of information on the gaps and inaccuracies of a grammar.<sep> 5 Results<sep> The work presented here, like the error-searching technique, is a mechanism for error feedback.<sep> This term refers to mechanisms that reuse the errors produced by a program in order to automatically or semi-automatically improve its quality.<sep> In order to ensure that the errors produced are indeed due to the program, the data analyzed must be reliable.<sep> In this case, the errors we are working on come from an analysis campaign of a corpus of 331,000 phrases extracted from Le Monde Diplomatique, carried out during the validation of the error detection technique (Sagot & Villemonte de La Clergerie, 2006). The lexicon we are trying to improve is the Lefff (Le lexique des formes flexionnelles du français) (Sagot et al., 2006).<sep> This morpho-syntactic lexicon, which covers a wide range of French, is partly acquired automatically and is constantly being developed. It currently has more than 520,000 entries.<sep> The FRMG grammar (Thomasset & Villemonte de La Clergerie, 2005) that we use is a TAG/TIG hybrid grammar with decorations.<sep> It is built from a more abstract meta-grammar that produces a set of 134 highly factored trees.<sep> Despite its very small number of trees, its factorization allows it to cover a large number of frames of categorization for verbs, passivation, extractions (relative, interrogative, split), certain subject inversions, certain verb-support constructions (“take care of”).<sep> Nevertheless, many phenomena are not yet treated (such as subcategorization on adjectives and nouns).<sep> In 2005, the FRMG grammar coupled with Lefff provided coverage of around 41% of the MD corpus.<sep> FIG. 2 – Success rates of reanalyses (Y axis) according to suspicion rates (X axis)<sep> 5.1. Precision of the automatic detection of suspicious forms<sep> The curve of Fig. 2 allows us to observe a very clear correlation between the success rates of the reanalyses and the suspicion rates of the forms.<sep> This confirms the validity of the information produced by the previous error detection stage.<sep> The values used for this curve are averages after grouping the suspicious forms by range of suspicion rate.<sep> Without this grouping, the curve would present many variations making its observation difficult.<sep> These variations are mainly explained by the fact that some forms were suspected instead of the grammar, which explains why exchanging them with jokers did not bring any parsing rate increase.<sep> Indeed, some forms have a marked affinity for specific constructions; for example, subject inversion in the presence of the adjective 'rare' as in "Rares sont ceux qui tentent d'en sortir" or 'nombreux' as in "Nombreux sont ceux qui refusent" [2].<sep> These forms have then paid for this affinity with an unfairly increased suspicion towards them.<sep> Another less important reason for these variations is that the use of jokers increases the timeout rate for sentences noticeably, even if we impose a 40 word limit on the length of the parsed sentences.<sep> Because those two phenomena are observed at all levels of suspicion rates, grouping the values by range reduces their effects on the curve of figure 2.<sep> Always with a view to correcting errors, it is tempting to see sentences from highly suspicious forms with low rates of reanalysis as indicating a lack of grammar.<sep> It would then be interesting to analyze them using a grammar inference system.<sep> 5.2. Assessing Signature Quality<sep> In order to evaluate the quality of the signatures produced, we ordered the suspicious forms according to the following calculation: Mf = Sf .ln(NSf ), where Sf is the suspicion rate of a form and NSf is the number of associated phrases[3].<sep> We then examined many of them through a web interface (Fig. 3) that allowed us to access, for each form, the tested wildcards, the rates of reanalyses obtained, the tested phrases and the best signatures retained.<sep> It also allows us to leave comments and submit requests to the lexicon and parser.<sep> In the long term, this interface is intended to be used by linguists.<sep> FIG. 3 – Signature exploration interface<sep> The study of the best signatures has confirmed some doubts we had: the technique is still “young”.<sep> We have identified a number of phenomena that prevent us from correctly quantifying the quality of the signatures.<sep> Nevertheless, we already know how to face most of them (see Sect 6.).<sep> However, in many cases, we have obtained relevant and instructive results that have allowed us to improve our tools (and not only our lexicon).<sep> For instance, we found correct signatures, such as for “prospères”/ prosperous . We can observe its use as an attributive adjective (shown by joker syntactic category and the signature), whereas it was only described as a verb in the Lefff .<sep> For the verbal form "révéler", the hypotheses show that it expects an attributive argument ("ce choix pourrait se révéler catastrophique."), but that it lacks a reflexive aspect, due to prepositional constructions such as "contraint de révéler X" or "penser à révéler X".<sep> Even if it is still maturing, our approach has proved to be viable. We will continue to develop it in order to obtain a fully functional tool.<sep> Once some improvements are achieved, new computation campaigns will be performed.<sep> 6. Future Improvements<sep> During our experiments, we have established a list of problems to solve and solutions to fix them:<sep> It is very frequent to be able to apply several grammar rules to a sequence of words, especially when the syntactic category of a word changes, like when we try various jokers.<sep> Nevertheless, these productions are not used with the same frequency and, consequently, the resulting signatures do not carry the same amount of useful information.<sep> Such data on the frequency of use would be useful to us in order to weight the signatures and reduce the interference of "parasitic" signatures in the results.<sep> Signatures should be cleaned to avoid irrelevant adjuncts on suspects.<sep> This would allow us to consolidate signatures currently separated by unnecessary assistants.<sep> However, at this stage, it is not always easy to judge the importance of an adjunct.<sep> We need to group the forms by family of underlying lemmas in order to increase the variability of the contexts tested and thus identify what they have in common.<sep> Nevertheless, we must keep in mind that some problems only concern some specific forms. For example, a bad assignment of the auxiliary to use for past participles (example of "larvé" falsely listed in Lefff as using the auxiliary "avoir"). We also mentioned that sometimes the problem results from the lack of one of the possible lemmas in the lexicon for a suspicious form.<sep> - We should group signatures that represent a common syntactic phenomenon under various aspects;<sep> For instance, the subject and other verbal arguments have various realizations (nominal, clitics, relatives and pronouns, …) or a transitive verb used in a passive construction.<sep> The grouping of forms by lemma is likely to help. - Some suspicious forms give signatures equivalent to the syntactic information already present in the lexicon. This kind of case implies that the signatures are incomplete. At present, they mainly lack morphological information.<sep> The next logical step for the signature model will be to assimilate this available information, which is already present in the dependency forests but has not yet been exploited.<sep> - Some forms have been unfairly suspected because of their affinity with syntactic constructions not handled by grammar.<sep> The use of several syntax analyzers with different grammars during the preliminary error search stage would possibly allow for the filtering of a portion of the suspicious forms.<sep> - Signatures are composed of a set of syntactic dependencies between words and the wildcard in the generated representations of a sentence.<sep> These signatures are directly dependent on the grammar used and can be difficult to understand for someone not familiar with this formalism.<sep> An effort must therefore be made to translate them into a representation that is independent of grammar and more humanly understandable.<sep> 7. Conclusion<sep> The experiments presented firstly confirm the ability of the error mining technique to correctly identify true suspicious forms.<sep> Their transformation into jokers increases the rate of successful reanalyses in a coordinated manner with the rate of suspicion of a form.<sep> Secondly, they validate the feasibility of an automatic mechanism for suggesting lexical corrections for suspicious forms (i.e. to their underlying lemmas). They also show that it is possible to obtain feedback on grammatical shortcomings.<sep> Still, work remains to be carried out in order to improve the quality of the suggested corrections by distinguishing what is essential from what is not in signatures, particularly through improvements introduced previously.<sep> 1We suppose that failures caused by the previous parse steps (segmentation, punctuation, detection of named entities, … ) have been identified.<sep> The erroneous forms and their associated sentences caused by such errors are therefore excluded from those that interest us here.<sep> 2 These examples also reflect the style sought in the journalistic corpus studied!<sep> 3 A high rate of reanalysis on a small number of sentences is not significant.
Verbal sequences - study of time and aspect using unsupervised learning techniques<sep> Abstract<sep> Unsupervised learning allows the discovery of categories that were previously unknown.<sep> Current techniques allow the exploration of sequences of phenomena, whereas one usually tends to focus on isolated phenomena or on the relation between two phenomena.<sep> They offer valuable tools for the analysis of data organized in sequences, and in particular, for the discovery of textual structures.<sep> We report here the results of an attempt at using it for inspecting sequences of verbs from French accounts of road accidents.<sep> Verbs were encoded as pairs (cat,tense), where cat represents the aspectual category of a verb and tense its grammatical tense.<sep> The analysis, based on an original approach, provided a classification of the links between two successive verbs into four distinct clusters, allowing text segmentation.<sep> We give here an interpretation of these clusters by comparing the statistical distribution of independent semantic annotations.<sep> Keywords: time, tense, aspect, semantics, unsupervised learning, data mining.<sep> 1 Introduction<sep> The advantage of unsupervised learning is that it allows the discovery of categories that were previously unknown.<sep> Current techniques make it possible to explore sequences of phenomena, whereas there is a tendency to focus on the analysis of isolated phenomena or on the relationship between two phenomena.<sep> They thus offer valuable tools for the analysis of data organised in sequences, and in particular, for the discovery of textual structures.<sep> Our aim is to use them for this purpose and we present here the interpretation of the results of a first attempt.<sep> Many studies have shown the importance of tense in the narrative structure of texts (Vuillaume, 1990).<sep> The contrast between the passé simple and the imparfait has been the subject of much ink.<sep> But many links between time and aspect, the idea of a coupling of time and aspectual category seemed natural and interesting to us.<sep> It has been shown that one could not carry out the analysis of the succession of events in time using only tenses without referring to aspect (see e.g. Kamp, Vet or Vlach in (Martin and Nef, 1981), (Kamp and Rohrer, 1983), (Vet, 1994), (Gosselin, 1996), etc.).<sep> There are also links between aspect and other semantic domains, such as intentions or causality, in literature.<sep> In this first study, we sought to see if we could detect a certain regularity in the sequences of verbs within sentences by coupling the tense and the aspectual category of the verbs, and if it was possible, within a restricted framework, to assign them a "meaning".<sep> The texts we analyze are short accounts of road accidents from the "observations" part of an amicable report intended for the insurers.<sep> They were graciously provided to us by the MAIF, whom we thank.<sep> Their main purpose is to describe an accident, its causes, and to identify those who are responsible, in a limited space.<sep> These texts have already been used in the LIPN for work on causal inferences (Nouioua and Kayser, 2006).<sep> Our approach is nevertheless different since it is a statistical approach aiming to categorize sequences of verbs - the bet being that if such classes of sequences exist, they have a general meaning, at least for the type of narrative considered. We are fully aware of the difficulty concerning the evaluation of this first work, the latter being based on the postulate that such sequences (relatively poor from a syntactic and semantic point of view) can be given a meaning and are not the reflection of contingent statistics.<sep> But the low resource usage is a valuable advantage for future TAL applications, and the experiment was therefore worthwhile.<sep> Let us add that the mathematical tools used here make it possible to check the statistical validity of the categories obtained, and that our semantic validation has been carried out with annotations completely independent of the learning process.<sep> 1.1 Advantages of our formal approach<sep> In this framework, the connectionist Self Organizing Maps (SOM) of Kohonen (Kohonen, 1995) provide an efficient unsupervised learning (clustering) with simultaneous visualization of the results of the classification.<sep> This visualization is given by the topological map of the data (two similar data are close on the map) providing at the same time an “intelligent” coding of the data in the form of prototypes.<sep> Since these prototypes are of same nature as the data, they are interpretable, and the map thus provides a summary of the data.<sep> From this coding, we took the Hidden Markov Models (HMM) to model the dynamics of the sequences of data (here, the verbs within a sentence).<sep> The HMM (Rabiner and Juang, 1986) are the best approach to treat sequences of variable length and to capture their dynamics.<sep> This is the reason why these models have been widely used in the field of voice recognition and are particularly well adapted to our objective.<sep> To validate our approach, we used both genetic and textual data (the interpretation of which is presented here).<sep> For technical details see (Rogovschi, 2006) or (Rogovschi et al., 2006).<sep> 1.2 Coding of sentences<sep> The analysis was carried out on a hundred texts containing 700 occurrences of verbs.<sep> In these texts, we considered all the sequences of at least two verbs delimited by the end of a sentence.<sep> To cope with the paucity of the data, we used re-sampling techniques based on sliding windows, which increase the redundancy (redundancy ensures a better classification of the data).<sep> For coding, the four aspectual categories of verbs originally due to Vendler and Kenny (Vendler, 1967), namely state, activity, accomplishment and achievement, were combined with the grammatical tense.<sep> Table 1 summarizes the differences between these four semantic categories.<sep> The indexing was done manually based on our conception of these categories (Recanati C., Recanati F., 1999).<sep> Table 1: The four aspectual categories of verbs<sep> These accounts of road accidents mostly use the imparfait (24%) and the passé composé (34%), with a few sentences in the present.<sep> In addition, there are also some (rare) occurrences of passé simple and of plus-que-parfait.<sep> There are however a significant number of present participles (11%) and infinitives (20%).<sep> We have therefore decided to retain them, even though they do not participate in the same way in the grammatical structure.<sep> We decided to retain all these “codes” and carried out the training by using nine codes[1] for the tenses that appeared on the verbs.<sep> Example « Le véhicule B circulait sur la voie de gauche des véhicules allant à gauche (marquage au sol par des flèches).<sep> Celui-ci s’est rabattu sur mon véhicule, me heurtant à l’arrière.<sep> Il a accroché mon pare-choc et m ’a entraîné vers le mur amovible du pont de Gennevilliers que j ’ai percuté violemment.<sep> » This description will be first reduced to the sequences of verbs: (circulait, allant) / (s’est rabattu, heurtant)/ (a accroché, a entraîné, ai percuté) – which are then numerically encoded as (tense, category) pairs: (act., IM) (acc., pp) / (acc., PC) (ach., pp) / (ach., PC) (acc., PC) (ach., PC).<sep> 2 First results<sep> The first results are the statistics on verbs and categories, independently of their sequences.<sep> In this type of narrative, the verbs of state account for 24% of the corpus, of activity only 10%, and 34% of verbs of accomplishment and 32% of verbs of achievement.<sep> The non-uniform distribution of tenses by category confirms the interest of our tense/aspectual category pairings (cf. Figure 1).<sep> Figure 1: Distribution of main tenses by category<sep> The nature of the aspectual categories, the aspectual specialization of grammatical tenses, and the typical structure of these accounts explain these percentages rather naturally.<sep> Verbs of states (24%) are distributed over more than 70% in the imparfait, the present, and the participe présent.<sep> This is not surprising since states are homogeneous and often durative, or characterize a disposition (habitual, generic).<sep> The significant proportion of passé composé is probably due to the frequency of verbs like “want” or “can”, which are classified as state verbs because of their dispositional aspect (“I wanted to slow down”, “I could not avoid”).<sep> The small proportion of present arises from the fact that the account is in the past and the historic present is a literary style not appropriate for this kind of account.<sep> Verbs of activities (10%) indicating homogeneous and unbounded processes, they are quite naturally distributed with more than 79% in the imparfait tense and in the form of present participles.<sep> The presence of 10% of infinitives can be easily explained by the fact that these are processes which have a beginning, and which can thus be the complement of verbs like “start”, “want”, or be introduced to mention a future goal of the driver (with the preposition “ pour ” + infinitive in French).<sep> Accomplishments (34%) and Achievements (32%) are very frequent in the passé composé because of their telic character (limited by a finish).<sep> Achievements are mostly in the passé composé because they are punctual or of short time span, and they do not support the imparfait tense.<sep> In contrast, accomplishments often occur in the imparfait and as present participles, because they stress rather the process than its end - which brings them very close to activities.<sep> The global importance of these two categories is undoubtedly linked to the typology of the texts analysed, because an account of an accident implies a description of the sequence of the successive events that caused it.<sep> Perfective/imperfective distinction.<sep> For (Smith, 1991), there are three points of view in the aspectual system of French.<sep> A perfective viewpoint shows a situation as being closed, including states (the full stop is then a change of state).<sep> The perfective is expressed by the passé composé and the passé simple.<sep> The imperfective and neutral viewpoints present on the contrary open situations.<sep> A neutral viewpoint is expressed by the present.<sep> The imperfective viewpoint is expressed by the imparfait, or by the locution “en train de”. Paul J. Hopper (Hopper, 1979) has described very well the characteristics of these two modes in relation to narrative structure, focus and aspect (see Table 2).<sep> Here, the opposition perfective/imperfective will be mainly embodied in these texts by the opposition imparfait/passé composé .<sep> This opposition is nevertheless global and it would be wrong to systematically attribute an imperfective aspect to all imperfects.<sep> Table 2: Perfective/imperfective opposition<sep> A typical structure.<sep> A description of an accident generally starts with one or two sentences describing the circumstances and the conditions before the accident.<sep> This first part of the text is thus in the imparfait , and contains many present participles.<sep> In addition, there are also a few verbs in the present tense and many infinitives introduced by “ pour ”, or occurring as complements of other verbs (“je m’apprêtais à tourner”, “le feu venait de passer au rouge”: “I was on the point of turning”, “The stop light had just turned red”).<sep> This first part is mainly circumstantial and contains a majority of verbs of states, but also some of activities and of accomplishments.<sep> It is characterized by an overall imperfective point of view, and the account is in background.<sep> The next part of the text contains a description of the accident that mentions the succession of events leading to the accident and finishes with the crucial moment of the impact.<sep> This part of the text uses mostly verbs of accomplishment and achievement, generally in the passé composé.<sep> It is characterized by a perfective mode, but since the goal is to indicate the responsibilities of the various actors, one still finds here many present participles and infinitive constructions connecting several verbs (“J’ai voulu freiner pour l’éviter”, “wanting to avoid the bollard, I couldn’t”).<sep> At the end of the account, one occasionally finds a third section with comments and an inventory of the damage.<sep> This third part is often short and less easy to characterize stylistically.<sep> 3 Categorization of verbal sequences<sep> Our unsupervised approach provided a classification of the sequences of two successive verbs (within the same sentence) in four groups.<sep> It should be pointed out that since this number of four is particularly small, it is interesting because it confirms the validity of our time/aspect pairing (no combinatorial explosion).<sep> Let us recall that with 9 tenses and 4 categories, we obtain 36 kinds of verbs, or 1296 virtual couples.<sep> The distribution of times over the categories has indeed restricted the number of couples.<sep> But it is also the reduction capacity of the method that makes it possible to obtain this result.<sep> A first reduction in dimension was carried out by the SOM maps, which here represent the classes with 36 pairs, then a pruning of the map, carried out from the transition probability matrices coming from the HMM, further reduced these classes to a smaller number of typical pairs.<sep> Semantic interpretation.<sep> To facilitate the interpretation of the clusters, we carried out a certain number of semantic annotations.<sep> These annotations were not used for learning but they will allow us to characterize the semantic classes of verbal transitions in a global way.<sep> Thus, to account for the typical structure of these texts, we indexed all the verbs with a number indicating the part of the text in which they occurred (1- circumstance , 2- accident or 3- comment ).<sep> We have also marked some of the verbs with the attributes foreground or background to indicate that the narrative is in the foreground or background.<sep> In order to detect possible causal chains leading to the accident, we marked some verbs with the attributes causal and impact when the verb was describing a direct cause of the accident, or the impact itself.<sep> We also marked the verbs of action according to the agent responsible for the action (A for the driver and author of the text, B for the "adversary", and C for a third person).<sep> We also noted the presence of negation, and the more general description of objectives or possible worlds that did not occur (attribute inertia for goals and alternatives).<sep> Table 3 symbolically summarizes the results we obtained by statistically analyzing our semantic labels in these four classes.<sep> The marking of negation was not very discriminating, and that of agent not very helpful.<sep> Table 3: Summary of semantic annotations<sep> 3.1 Cluster (C) of Circumstances<sep> This group makes a clear distinction between the first and the second verb of a sequence.<sep> The first verb is 93% in the imparfait , but only 7% in the present, while the second is 63% in the infinitive and 30% in the present participle.<sep> From the point of view of aspectual categories, the first verb is a verb of state 56% of the time, and the second a verb of accomplishment 63% of the time. (The other categories divide themselves in a regular way between 12% and 16%).<sep> One can generally summarise the transitions of this group as presenting a verb of state (or activity) in the imparfait, followed by a verb of accomplishment in the infinitive or in the present participle.<sep> Table 4 (see below) provides a finer synthesis.<sep> This group favors states and activities to the detriment of achievements - accomplishments on the other hand are overwhelmingly present in the second verbal occurrence.<sep> The cluster (C) is the one where the inertia attribute (indicating a goal or an alternative world) is the most important.<sep> This is explained by the many accomplishments introduced by the French preposition “pour” (“je reculais pour repartir”, “je sortais du parking pour me diriger” - “I backed up to set out again”, “I left the carpark to find my way”), or by the auxiliaries in the imparfait introducing an infinitive indicating the intentions of the driver (“j’allais tourner à gauche”: “I was on the point of turning left”).<sep> This is one of the reasons why we called this cluster (C) “Circumstances”.<sep> Another reason is that it contains a strong majority of verbs belonging to the first part of the account (63%), and very little to the second or the third.<sep> Moreover, this cluster hardly contains verbs indicating the causes of the accident or describing the impact.<sep> Actor A is represented the most there, and the account is in background.<sep> 3.2 Cluster (CA) of Circumstances or of the Appearance of an incident<sep> The second cluster (CI) is that of the circumstances or of the appearance of an incident.<sep> One notes here a great number of verbs of states (37.5%) and activities (17%), even more than in the preceding cluster and much higher than average.<sep> There are, on the other hand, an average number of achievements (29%), absent from the first verb but quite often present on the second.<sep> This distinguishes this cluster from the preceding one, where accomplishments played this role.<sep> Here, on the contrary, accomplishments are excluded from the second place, and are clearly under-represented (16.5%).<sep> One can synthesize the transitions of this cluster by saying that one generally has a state or an activity in the imparfait tense, followed by a state or an achievement in the imparfait or in the passé composé .<sep> (One thus connects two imperfective points of view, and sometimes, an imperfective point of view and a perfective one).<sep> In this group 36% of verbs come from the first part of the account (“je circulais à 45 km/h environ dans une petite rue à sens unique où des voitures étaient garées des deux côtés”: “I drove at approximately 45 km/h in a small oneway street where cars were parked on each side”), but also sequences finishing by an achievement in the passé composé , coming from the second part (34%, “je roulais rue Pasteur quand une voiture surgit de la gauche”: “I drove on Pasteur street when a car emerged from the left”).<sep> This cluster contains also 25% of verbal sequences located between the two parts (providing thus half of such sequences).<sep> This is why we called it the cluster of circumstances or of the appearance of an incident.<sep> The account is mainly in the background.<sep> Actor A (or a third person C) are strongly represented to the detriment of actor B.<sep> There are few allusions to the causes of the accident and to the impact.<sep> The evocation of goals or alternative worlds is insignificant.<sep> 3.3 Cluster (AA) of Actions leading to the Accident<sep> The verbs of the third cluster (AA) come essentially from the account of the accident itself.<sep> This group is characterized by the abundance of achievements, to the detriment of states and activities. This is why we have named it the "group of actions leading to an accident".<sep> The mode is generally perfective but includes many infinitives.<sep> The most typical elements are listed in Table 4.<sep> These pairs lend themselves well to constructions of three verbs as in, “J’ai voulu m’engager pour laisser” (“I wanted to turn into to let”), or “n’ayant pas la possibilité de changer de voie et la route étant mouillée” (“not having the possibility of changing the lane and the road’s being wet”).<sep> Nevertheless, as in cluster (C), the present participles and infinitives allow the expression of goals and alternative worlds (“désirant me rendre à”, “commençant à tourner” - “wishing to go to”, “starting to turn”), so 26% of the pairs come from the first part of the account.<sep> We note here a rather strong proportion of actors A and B, with little of C, and very little relief - the account being neither in the foreground nor in the background.<sep> Many verbs describe the causal chain, but relatively few mention the impact.<sep> 3.4 Impact or Comments Cluster<sep> The verbs of achievements (45%) appear here in a larger number than elsewhere (32% on average), to the detriment of activities (6.5%), and states (only 14.5%).<sep> This explains that this group supports the descriptive part of the accident (57%).<sep> Here also one observes an increase in infinitives and participles on the first verb to the detriment of the imparfait and of the present, and a large increase in passé composé on the second verb to the detriment of all tenses - except the present (8%, slightly higher than the average).<sep> This occurrence of the present may explain the presence of the commentary section (29% instead of 18% on average).<sep> The mention of goals or alternatives is average.<sep> It is here on the other hand that foregrounding is most marked.<sep> There is an important number of references to actor B (the driver of the other vehicule) and it is here that one finds most verbs relating to the causes of the accident and the impact itself.<sep> Table 3 indicates only two typical elements in this group, which, although quite large, is more difficult to characterize.<sep> The analysis in terms of viewpoints shows nevertheless that the sequence generally finishes with a perfective viewpoint.<sep> Table 4: Most typical elements of the four groups<sep> 3.5 Summary and comments<sep> This categorization distinguishes quite well states and activities (groups C, CA) from telic events (groups AA, CC).<sep> In a more interesting way, accomplishments are also distinguished from achievements, justifying the distinction accomplishment/achievement (as opposed to the more general notion of telic events).<sep> It should also be noticed that the expression of goals or alternatives often accompanies the use of verbs in the present participle or infinitive - which explains the ratio displayed by groups C and AA.<sep> However, the lexical category used influences also this expression, because the second verb in these two groups is generally an accomplishment.<sep> Moreover, the groups C and CI (unmarked for this index) differ precisely in the type of event appearing in second place.<sep> In the same way, elements differentiating the groups AA and CC (which contain a majority of telic events) show that the group AA (which favors accomplishments), although conveying a perfective mode, is little marked for narrative foreground.<sep> This group is also less concerned with the causes of the accident than the group CC, and it makes little allusion to the impact.<sep> Goals and intentions would thus be expressed more easily by accomplishments than by achievements - which would carry more causality.<sep> Indeed, the group CC, which favors achievements, is more strongly marked for narrative foregrounding, the impact itself, and the causal chain of events, which directly caused it.<sep> It may be that for achievements and activities, the subject has a relation of power over the direct object (or over the oblique object).<sep> One can check its existence by using adverbs of manner (gently, with caution, etc).<sep> This explains perhaps also the stronger responsibility of the subject with the use of verbs of achievements.<sep> But although the perfective/imperfective contrast emerges rather neatly (clusters AA and CC vs. C and CI), surprisingly cluster (CA) hosts both imperfective sequences and imparfait / passé composé sequences.<sep> One of the explanations is that our training algorithm did not take into account the linking of two sentences (nor the distinction between texts), so that the succession of several sentences in the imperfect mode, and the typical structure of these accounts (such as we perceive it) could not be detected.<sep> We thus missed a significant part of our objective.<sep> However, the results obtained are already promising, since the three parts have still been distributed in a non-uniform way over the four groups.<sep> It should also be noted that this classification underlines the importance of infinitive turns and present participles, and the subtlety of their linking (cf. Table 4).<sep> Possible technical improvements .<sep> The HMMs were built here by moving a window of size 2: verbs are analyzed by taking into consideration the verbs that precede and follow them, but not the N-preceding verbs or the N-following ones.<sep> This is not very important if we are at the sentence level, (and in these accounts, a sentence contains rarely more than three verbs), but for an analysis of the entire structure of a text, we will need to add this.<sep> In addition, we would have liked to produce typical sequences of variable length.<sep> Thus, clusters AA and CC would have provided sequences of several verbs.<sep> (This is seen in the elements of Table 4, and we have also noted this on the segmentation of texts).<sep> This result could be obtained automatically from the HMM, but we have not had enough time to implement this method.<sep> 4 Conclusion<sep> Our general project is to apply techniques of data mining to explore textual structures.<sep> For this purpose we developed an original approach of unsupervised learning allowing the detection of sequential structures.<sep> It allowed the analysis of sequences of verbs constituting a sentence, and the proposal of a classification of the appearance of two successive verbs in four groups.<sep> We succeeded in validating these groups satisfactorily, by basing our judgment on semantic annotations and the application of statistical analyses.<sep> This confirms the validity of the technique used, and that of our coupling of the grammatical tense with the aspectual lexical category of a verb.<sep> However, this work is still in its early stages, and many points remain to be elucidated.<sep> We first regret not to have been able to compare our statistical analysis on cross tense/category uses with those of other types of texts (and in particular with that of simple accounts of incidents).<sep> It indeed remains to be determined what the “typological” part of the isolated sequences is.<sep> Nor did we have time to exploit the probabilistic automata obtained from our method, and these could prove interesting for applications (in particular in generation).<sep> Finally, there are still improvements to be made to the general method to take into account the overall structure of the texts (which is not the case here), and the modelling still needs to be pursued for the search of sequences of length higher than 2.<sep> Acknowledgments<sep> We would like to thank Y. Bennani for the valuable help he provided in the development of the technique used, without which this work could not have been completed.<sep> We also warmly thank A. Nazarenko and D. Kayser for their kind proofreading.<sep> 1 IM = imparfait , PR = présent , PC = passé composé , PS = passé simple , PQP = plus-que-parfait , inf = infinitif , ppr = participe présent , pp = participe passé and pps = participe passé surcomposé .<sep> As for the past participles (few here), we have not always counted the contingent adjectival uses, and from the point of view of the categorizer, they are rather noise.
Characterization of scientific and popular science discourse in French, Japanese and Russian<sep> Abstract<sep> The primary goal of our work is to study the notion of comparability of corpora, and we approach this question in a monolingual context by trying to distinguish scientific and popularized documents.<sep> We work separately with corpora composed of documents from the medical domain in three languages (French, Japanese and Russian) which present an important linguistic distance between them.<sep> In our approach, documents are characterized in each language by their topic and by a discursive typology positioned at three levels of document analysis: structural, modal and lexical.<sep> The document typology is implemented with two learning algorithms (SVMlight and C4.5).<sep> Evaluation of results shows that the proposed discursive typology is portable from one language to another, as it indeed allows to distinguish the two discourses.<sep> However, we observe that performances vary a lot according to languages, algorithms and types of discursive characteristics.<sep> Keywords: corpus linguistics, comparable corpus, learning algorithms, stylistic analysis, degree of comparability.<sep> 1. Introduction<sep> A comparable corpus is a set of texts that share a number of characteristics. The first of these characteristics is to bring together documents that deal with similar subjects. For example, in a multilingual context, comparable corpora will bring together documents that share a common theme but are not translations of each other (Bowker & Pearson, 2002).<sep> In a monolingual context, comparable corpora can contain documents that deal with the same subject but belong to different discourses.<sep> The comparable term is thus used to indicate that the corpora have a number of characteristics in common.<sep> These characteristics can refer to the text creation context (period, author…), or to the text itself (topic, genre…).<sep> The choice of these characteristics depends on the objectives set.<sep> This affects the degree of comparability, a notion used to quantify how comparable two corpora are (at maximum values in a parallel corpus, for example).<sep> In our work, we study a comparable corpus in the medical field in three languages with high linguistic distance: French, Japanese and Russian.<sep> In order to guarantee a better comparability of the documents in our corpus, we take into account a classic characteristic, relative to the theme of the corpus, but also a discursive characteristic: the distinction between documents according to whether they belong to the scientific or popular science discourse.<sep> We base our choice on the notion of discourse as defined by Ducrot and Schaeffer (1999): "Every set of utterances of an enunciator characterized by a global unity of theme".<sep> To implement this characterization, we perform a contrastive stylistic analysis, inspired by the works of (Karlgren, 1998), and propose a typology for the automatic distinction of scientific and popular science documents in different languages.<sep> This typology has three levels of analysis of documents: structural, modal and lexical.<sep> The primary goal of our work is to check if this three levels typology can actually characterize a Web document’s discourse, and refine the notion of corpus comparability.<sep> By working on a trilingual corpus, we may also observe the performance of this typology according to the languages.<sep> Finally, this typology is used to adapt learning algorithms to our corpus.<sep> In the following section, we first present the corpus studied (sec. 2), the typology established for the characterization of scientific and popular discourse (sec. 3), and the methods used for the automatic detection of these discourses (sec. 4).<sep> We then present the results (sec. 5) and conclude (sec. 6).<sep> 2. Collection and characteristics of the comparable trilingual corpus<sep> Our working corpus is a comparable one, involving documents in three languages with a large linguistic distance: French, Japanese and Russian.<sep> In the context of our study, which is about multilingual and cross-language information retrieval, we want to have a corpus with a high degree of comparability, without erasing the cultural and linguistic differences of each language.<sep> We consider two comparability levels:<sep> - as is often the case in information research, we ensure a first level of comparability thanks to the common theme shared by the documents in three languages.<sep> We chose the medical field and more specifically the theme "diabetes and diet": this theme concerns a large public and presents a potential guarantee of collecting a diversity of documents from the web.<sep> Furthermore, from an applicative point-of-view, comparable trilingual corpora being partly dedicated to the extraction of multilingual information, a common theme reinforces the guarantee of finding common linguistic features and vocabulary for each languages.<sep> - level of comparability and distinguish the texts of the corpus according to their type of discourse, scientific and popular science.<sep> In the following section, we present our methodology for trilingual corpus compilation and give its main characteristics.<sep> 2.1 Methodology for corpus compilation<sep> The corpus of this study is a comparable corpus in French, Japanese and Russian languages.<sep> Documents are extracted from the Web.<sep> Corpus compilation consists of three steps: 1. Web documents search, according to the chosen topic; 2. Selection of relevant web pages; 3. Classification of these web pages according to their discourse.<sep> Thus, in the first stage of the web page search, we used three approaches: (1) Web search using general search engines;<sep> (2) Internal search on (medical) portals using the search engines specific to the sites if necessary; (3) Exploitation of the links between the pages.<sep> The first two methods require the use of keywords.<sep> In order to collect a wide range of documents, queries are composed of various combinations of keywords as diet , diabetes and obesity extended with i) synonymous terms found in thesaurus; ii) semantically linked terms found in web documents.<sep> Note also that in the case of using a search engine specific to a portal, the keywords are also specific to that portal.<sep> Among these documents, we manually selected the documents relevant to the topic.<sep> And finally, the selected pages were then classified according to the type of discourse emanating from them.<sep> Manual classification is based on the following heuristics: - a scientific document is written by specialists, for specialists; - we distinguish two levels of popular science: texts written by specialists for the general public and texts written by the general public for the general public.<sep> We will not distinguish between these two levels but will give greater importance to documents written by specialists at the expense of discussions on forums, for example. Documents written by specialists are indeed richer in vocabulary and more complete in content.<sep> Manual classification is therefore based on these heuristics, and is supported by additional elements: the nature of the site containing the document, the vocabulary used in the document, etc.<sep> However, it should be noted that the manual classification task is still empirical. This led us to not include certain "ambiguous" documents (unclassifiable documents or for which opinions differed) in the training corpus.<sep> 2.2. Corpus characteristics<sep> Table 1 presents the main features of the corpus: the number of documents and the number of words for each language and discourse (SC: scientific; PS: popular science).<sep> TABLE 1 – Characteristics of the corpus<sep> This corpus is composed of more than 1.5 million words in three languages.<sep> The figures given for the Japanese language correspond to the number of characters, the number of words being difficult to estimate.<sep> All the documents collected use more than three alphabets (Cyrillic, Latin, Hiragana, Katakana...) and several different encodings.<sep> That is why all texts have been transcoded into Unicode UTF-8, the only encoding allowing the processing of Latin, Cyrillic and Japanese alphabets.<sep> The documents in the corpus belong to different formats, including the usual web formats (html, xhtml, php, etc.), but also other formats (pdf, ps, doc, etc.).<sep> All pages have been preserved in their original format, but also converted into plain text.<sep> All the Web genres (Bretan et al., 1998) are not present in the French corpus, which holds mostly reports and articles (press and scientific), unlike the Japanese corpus which holds a great variety (from scientific reports to job offers).<sep> The Russian corpus also shows a variability of genres (articles, books, cooking recipes, guides of good practice, discussions on specialized forums, etc.).<sep> 3. A typology for the stylistic analysis of the corpus<sep> Stylistic analysis is a linguistic field with a scientific application in the textual classification domain.<sep> This work is based on machine learning methods.<sep> Most known algorithms are support vector machines (SVM), neural networks, Bayesian classifiers, decision trees (Sebastiani, 2002).<sep> We distinguish two types of stylistic analysis.<sep> The inductive approach consists in the analysis of a corpus, and the detection of correlations specifying similarity classes (which can vary according to the chosen characteristics).<sep> This method leads to create inductive typologies.<sep> In the automatic learning field, this method is called unsupervised learning or clustering (Biber, 1989).<sep> The second approach, called the deductive approach, consists of analysing a set of pre-classified documents to characterise the membership of an element to a class, in the form of a typology.<sep> This approach is similar to supervised learning (Bretan et al., 1998).<sep> In this approach, two methods lead to create a typology: an analysis of the documents one at a time, or a contrastive analysis of documents from two different classes.<sep> In our work, we chose to use the contrastive approach.<sep> Textual classification algorithms are applied to several kinds of typologies.<sep> Most frequent kinds are topic or genre typologies (Bretan et al., 1998).<sep> Since works on discourse typologies are less frequent, we adapt deductive and contrastive approaches to discourse typology.<sep> The documents from our corpus, collected from the web, present a proper structure that we cannot overlook.<sep> Thus, unlike a large number of works dealing with the stylistic analysis of texts, for example (Malrieu & Rastier, 2002; Biber, 1989), we take into account both the textual content and the structure of the documents.<sep> We base ourselves on these two types of information to create a typology specific to the targeted discourses.<sep> Sinclair (1996) introduced the concept of levels in textual typologies in his typological work.<sep> Indeed, according to him, it is more relevant to distinguish two categories of criteria: external criteria, which are characteristics of the context of creation of the text; and internal criteria, which are linguistic characteristics of the text.<sep> Since our corpus is made of web documents, we consider external criteria as all the features related to the creation of documents and their structure (non-linguistic features).<sep> Internal criteria are the linguistic features of the documents.<sep> However, stylistic analysis enlights several granularity levels among internal criteria.<sep> The distinction between scientific and popular science documents involves taking the speaker into account in his speech, i.e. the modality.<sep> Furthermore, scientific discourse can be characterized by the vocabulary used, the length of words, and other lexical features.<sep> Therefore our typology distinguishes three levels of analysis of documents:<sep> - Structural criteria : textual and graphical structure of documents; - Modal criteria : elements characterising the modality in texts; - Lexical criteria : lexical features of texts.<sep> TAB. 2 – Structural characteristics<sep> TAB. 3 – Modal characteristics<sep> TAB. 4 – Lexical characteristics<sep> Structural features (table 2) gather mainly graphical (format, images, tables…) and structural elements of documents, by dint of HTML tags (paragraphs, item lists, titles…).<sep> All of these structural criteria are detectable in the three languages.<sep> Table 3 presents modal characteristics, which correspond to the modality in texts, i.e. the position of the speaker in his own speech.<sep> These features are directly inspired from Charaudeau (1992) and adapted to our corpus (Krivine et al., 2006; Nakao, 2008).<sep> Among the acts of locution from Charaudeau (1992), we kept those which were operational in the documents analysed.<sep> For example, opinion modality can be detected in French using verbs like penser (to think), parâıtre (to appear), sembler (to seem).<sep> Most of these features appear in the three languages, but some (judgement, interdiction) are specific to one or two of the languages treated, essentially because the instantiation of the typology was based on rather isolated studies of the corpus in each language.<sep> Finally, in Table 4, we present lexical features.<sep> More than in the previous two types, these criteria show a dependence on the language, like the use of hiragana or katakana characters in Japanese texts or Latin alphabets in Russian texts.<sep> Note that some of these criteria are specific to scientific documents, such as bibliographies and bibliographic quotes, specialized vocabulary or units of measurement.<sep> 4. Automatic discourse classification<sep> The tripartite typology (structural, modal and lexical characteristics) serves as the basis for machine learning algorithms.<sep> In this section, we present the method: the machine learning algorithms used and the principles of evaluation of the results.<sep> 4.1 Learning<sep> As we announced, the objective of our work is to adapt the learning algorithms to the categorization of documents according to two discourses, scientific and popularized.<sep> In our work, the stylistic analysis and categorization of documents is carried out through the typology of criteria proposed (sec. 3).<sep> Indeed, machine learning algorithms perceive documents as vectors, where each element of the vector represents the value of a criterion for the corresponding document.<sep> The length of a vector corresponds to the frequency (raw or weighted) of each criterion in the processed document.<sep> Starting from a learning corpus, where documents are divided into two classes (science and popular science) and a list of criteria, machine learning algorithms create a classification model.<sep> This procedure is then applied to new data to perform new classifications.<sep> There are several automatic text classification algorithms (neural networks, Bayesian classifiers, support vector machines, etc.) for which Sebastiani (2002) carried out a gathering and comparison work.<sep> Applied to a corpus of Reuters news wires, these techniques have shown variable performances depending on the use of supervised or unsupervised approaches, the size of the corpus, the number of categories, etc.<sep> We chose to use support vector machines with SVMlight (Joachims, 2002) and decision trees with C4.5 (Quinlan, 1993).<sep> As we want a fast classification system, we have privileged, for the implementation of the criteria, simple techniques based on lexical or lexico-syntactic patterns that analyze superficially the documents and their content.<sep> The categorization system is based on the recognition of lexical forms in documents, whether for graphical criteria (recognized through HTML tags), modal (recognized through modal markers) or lexical.<sep> 4.2. Evaluation<sep> The corpus must be sampled in two parts: one sample is reserved for learning, the other for testing.<sep> To do this, we use N-fold cross validation (Cornuéjols and Miclet, 2002).<sep> This method consists in splitting our corpus into N equal parts.<sep> Then one of the n samples (the one of number i) is chosen for the testing part, the other n − 1 samples are used to learn a model.<sep> Once the results are collected, this operation is reiterated, i varying from 1 to n.<sep> We set n = 5.<sep> We have 80% of our documents (in terms of characters) in the learning sample, the other 20% in the test sample.<sep> The results presented in section 5 are averages of the 5 partitions.<sep> We use precision and recall metrics to evaluate our results: - recall, corresponding to the number of documents correctly classified in a class C divided by the number of documents belonging to this class; - precision, corresponding to the number of documents correctly classified in class C divided by the number of documents classified in class C.<sep> 5. Results and discussion<sep> We applied SVMlight and C4.5 to our corpus.<sep> Classification results for these two algorithms are presented in tables 5 and 6.<sep> TAB. 5 – Precision and recall for each category of criteria obtained for the SVM light and C4.5 algorithms on the three languages<sep> TABLE 6 - Results for each category of criteria. According to table 5, whatever the language and the algorithm, the documents of the popular science discourse are always better classified.<sep> It is noted that the results obtained with French documents are generally satisfactory, with an average recall of 87%, and an average precision of 90% for the C4.5 classifier (which represents more than 200 well classified documents on the 250 of the corpus).<sep> Classification results for Japanese documents are good for popular science documents, but quite bad for scientific ones.<sep> At last, classification of Russian documents gives good results with SVMlight , with a recall higher than 75% and a precision of 87%.<sep> Low results for classification of Japanese and Russian scientific documents can be explained by the high proportion of popular science documents in the corpus (see table 1).<sep> Vector normalization is performed to overcome this ratio but a larger learning corpus would provide more information, represent larger range of scientific documents and generate a fuller language model.<sep> However, this result is quite surprising for French: the number of occurrences in scientific documents is almost twice as important, even if the number of scientific documents remains lower.<sep> Results for Japanese documents are in average lower than the others, it can be explained by the high diversity of genres in the corpus.<sep> Thus it is harder to characterize a discourse with a stable set of features.<sep> The criteria used for manual classification (see section 2.1) may not be sufficient in this language and should be refined.<sep> Table 6 presents results of each algorithm for each category of the typology.<sep> Each category shows its importance in the typology.<sep> In fact, whatever the classifier is, results in each language show that it is possible to classify more than a half of the documents using only features of one category.<sep> However, none of the categories can be distinguished from the others within this test, and best categories varies according to the classifier used.<sep> With SVMlight , structural and lexical categories seem to be the most effective in the three languages.<sep> With C4.5 , the best category varies according to the language: modality for French, lexicon for Japanese and structure for Russian.<sep> In more detail, we also found that among the most discriminating criteria, we find the type of URL (URL format: hospital, university, etc.), the delocutive pronouns and the number of narrative sentences for the French corpus; the length of the documents, the elocutive pronouns and the politeness maker at the end of sentences for Japanese; the title of the documents, images and specialized vocabulary for the Russian corpus.<sep> 6. Conclusion and perspectives<sep> Starting with a comparable corpus composed of Web documents in French, Japanese and Russian, we made a contrastive stylistic analysis and created a typology for science and popular science web documents.<sep> This typology is based on three aspects of web documents: structural, modal and lexical.<sep> Our typology, implemented through machine learning algorithms support vector machines (SVMlight) and decision trees (C4.5) gives good results.<sep> Thus we can "calculate" the type of discourse of a web document.<sep> Furthermore, these results show that each level of the typology is relevant to characterize the categorization system.<sep> In fact, each of them provide satisfying results, and their combination improves the results.<sep> The discourse of a web document can therefore be characterized through these three aspects.<sep> We note that some of the features appear in all languages, so we assume that our typology may be universal.<sep> There seems to be recurrent elements appearing in documents from different languages that characterise their type of discourse, and our typology seems to be portable from one language to another.<sep> One of the major limits of our work seems to come from the limited size of the corpus, especially for Japanese and Russian scientific documents.<sep> Moreover, low results for Japanese scientific documents can be explained by a high genre diversity in the corpus.<sep> This observation leads us to question the composition and manual categorisation of the Japanese corpus.<sep> Thus, following the hierarchical classification of genres and discourse of Malrieu and Rastier (2002), one can wonder if this distinction would not help us refine our results.<sep> By respecting the gender distinction, we can make the learning categories more homogeneous and thus guarantee a higher degree of comparability in the corpora.<sep> Furthermore, following our work, we question the legitimacy of the binary categorisation. We think it would be more interesting to consider the scientific and popular science classes of documents as a continuum.<sep> This would lead us to attribute a "degree of vulgarisation" to each document rather than a type of discourse.<sep> Acknowledgements<sep> This work was carried out as part of the DECO project, a CNRS-TCAN program for 2004-2006 in partnership with NII and INaLCO.<sep> We thank Estelle Dubreil, Sonia Krivine and Masaru Tomimitsu for their participationin comparable corpus compilation.
Automatic processing of disfluencies in linguistically constrained spoken dialogue Corpus Linguistic Analysis<sep> Robust comprehension. ATC. Phraseology. Disfluencies.<sep> Natural Language Processing Spoken Speech Modeling Dialog Corpus Linguistic Analysis Robust Understanding<sep> Modèles linguistiques de phraséologie pour le contrôle du trafic aérien<sep> Natural Language Processing<sep> This article presents a work of modeling and detection of phenomena disfluencies.<sep> One of the specificity of this work is its framework: the Air Traffic Control.<sep> We show that this particular framework implies some specific choices about modeling and implementation.<sep> Thus we can see that the syntax-based modeling often used in natural language processing is not the most appropriate here.<sep> We explain how the implementation was carried out.<sep> In a final part we present the validation of this device carried out on 400 statements.<sep> Introduction<sep> The disfluencies are a frequently occurring phenomenon in spontaneous speech.<sep> They have given rise to numerous studies both in Natural Language Processing and Speech Processing.<sep> Indeed their study and accurate identification are essential.<sep> From a theoretical perspective in order to better understand and model the problems that can happen during any spoken communication.<sep> The potential applications are also numerous for improving the robustness of automatic spoken dialog systems.<sep> However, taking into account disfluencies in the context of TALN is particularly difficult.<sep> Indeed these phenomena are apparently totally disorganized; besides their appearance usually leads to disturbances in the regularity of the spoken production.<sep> Nevertheless their processing is the subject of several studies though still quite rare.<sep> This article also provides a work of this kind.<sep> One of its features is that it is carried out in a particularly constrained framework, particularly from a linguistic point of view, by using a specific phrasology: Air Traffic Control (ATC).<sep> As this article shows this implies a number of specific theoretical and practical choices.<sep> The presentation of our work is done in four phases.<sep> First the description of the corpus and of its characteristics.<sep> Then the presentation of the various types of disfluencies found in the corpus and the way they were modelled.<sep> Finally we give the principles of the implementation obtained before presenting the validation we have implemented as well as the results obtained.<sep> Presentation of the study corpus<sep> The communication between controllers and pseudo-pilots.<sep> The corpus used in our study is made up of recordings of spontaneous oral dialogues between air traffic controllers in training and "pseudo-pilots".<sep> These are instructors simulating the role of pilots in training.<sep> Two languages are used: French (majority) and English.<sep> The aim of the recorded exercises is to train apprentice controller activities and then to evaluate them.<sep> It consists of managing several planes that are in a controlled area for example by assigning them a given speed and/or position.<sep> The audio channel can be "occupied" by only one speaker at a time, preventing any overlap of speech.<sep> The oral productions of the controllers and the pilots are governed by a strict phraséology 1.<sep> It describes for example the way the speaker must pronounce the plane call signs or the order that the different components of a message have to follow. This is described in the decree of 27 June 2000 concerning radiotelephony procedures for general air traffic (J.O n° 171 of 26 July 2000 p. 11501).<sep> During training, as well as in real working conditions, the phrasology is not always systematically applied.<sep> The general framework it sets is however respected.<sep> It is also important to note that the recorded dialogues are part of the category of spontaneous oral speech.<sep> We insist on that point because the preponderant role played by phrasology could make one think that all utterances are already planned in advance.<sep> This is not true: neither the controllers nor the pilots know in advance what they will have to say.<sep> The phraseology only sets up a general framework for utterances; what is actually said depends on the dynamic interaction between a given controller and pilot or pseudo-pilot depending on a variable situation.<sep> Characteristics of the study corpus<sep> We transcribed dialogues as well as annotated them according to the specifications described in (Coullon et al. 2000)<sep> These specifications were defined firstly to determine the elements to be transcribed and secondly to obtain homogeneity of transcriptions in case where several annotators are involved.<sep> Recordings were made with a DAT (Digital Audio Tape) and sampled at 16 kHz (16 bits).<sep> For recording reasons the sound quality sometimes suffers from saturation or noises such as interferences.<sep> However the dialogues are intelligible.<sep> The corpus is 36h50mn long and includes 76 306 words.<sep> 16 different speakers took part in its production.<sep> Proposed modeling<sep> To take into account the disfluencies we proceeded into two main stages.<sep> As a first step, we identified precisely the phenomena to be treated.<sep> Once it was done we then proceeded to the modeling of their patterns of occurrence.<sep> This process is described in the two next sections.<sep> Identification of phenomena disfluencies<sep> The task is not as trivial as it sounds especially when it comes to disfluencies.<sep> In fact, in the literature devoted to this phenomenon, the terms used to describe a given phenomenon often vary from one author to another (see for example (Candéa 2000) (Henry et al. 2004) (Kurdi 2003) or (Schriberg 1994) ).<sep> We identified 7 different categories of disfluencies.<sep> When it's necessary we give some examples to illustrate our purpose (with the disfluencies in bold).<sep> For comparisons with other terminologies and the distributions of each category we refer to (Bouraoui et al. 2006).<sep> Hesitation: it is the interjection "uh";<sep> Example: France Air Force 900 893<sep> Fragment of word: one or more unidentifiable phonemes (as opposed to false starts).<sep> Example (the fragment is in brackets): "speed 200 Knots [mak] minimum".<sep> due to [ou] due traffic euh descend level 9 0<sep> Elongation: the elongation of a phonetic unit of a word superior to 05 seconds;<sep> can be combined with hesitations.<sep> Long pause: any pause longer than 05 seconds and included within a turn of speech.<sep> Modeling of phenomena<sep> In most of the studies on disfluencies the modeling when it is done is based on the syntactic and/or semantic representation of the phenomena.<sep> However, we believe that, given the very specific linguistic nature induced by the phrasal semantics and its restrictions, it is useless and even counter-productive to embark on a modelling based on lexico-syntactic relations.<sep> Indeed, the constraints posed by the phraseology allow, in large part, to describe the linguistic system formed by it independently or almost independently of the "parts of discourse" to which the elements belong.<sep> More concretely, we are looking for a representation language that has at least the following characteristics: adapted to the object of study (disfluencies), great expressive and representational capacity, simplicity of the patterns obtained and, finally, modularisation according to the user's needs.<sep> We have found these properties to be met in the annotation schema proposed by (Bear et al. 1993)<sep> With this annotation scheme, which we augmented with some symbols more specific to the task of air traffic control, we systematically modeled all occurrences of disfluencies in our corpus.<sep> From these patterns we identified more general patterns which have been useful in the last part of this work: the implementation.<sep> Implementation<sep> Implementation Framework<sep> The system in which we integrate our model was developed as part of the VOICE project and is described in (Truillet et al. 2005)<sep> Specifically the purpose of this system is to manage the spoken inputs produced by the pseudo-pilots to extract their meaning and to interpret them so that the orders are executed.<sep> It has already worked in a simulation of air traffic control even if a number of constraints remain to be taken into account including the management of disfluencies!<sep> The VOICE system has a modular architecture of software components which communicate with each other.<sep> They are each dedicated to a task.<sep> Notably one of them is speech recognition.<sep> From the results it provides another component chooses the most likely solution depending on the context of the dialog (historical of the actual dialog but also task knowledge etc.).<sep> Finally the decision is added to the history.<sep> We refer to (Truillet et al. 2005) for a detailed description of the other components and the role of each.<sep> The VOICE system operates from a Context Free Grammar (CFG) which dynamically changes depending on the context of interaction.<sep> It takes the form of non-probabilistic rewriting rules.<sep> This formalism is particularly well adapted to the ATC phraseology given the standardization of the production and the low number of lexico-syntactic patterns used.<sep> However, these rules did not yet take into account the modelling of disfluencies that we described above;<sep> Furthermore, some complex disfluencies cannot be handled only by CFG rules.<sep> Therefore, an additional treatment is necessary, which is described in the following section.<sep> Computational modeling and processing<sep> We distinguish two types of phenomena to be addressed.<sep> On the one hand "ad hoc" disfluencies.<sep> We include in this category: hesitations and fragments of words.<sep> We call them "punctual" because they do not question the organization of the sequence of words in which they appear.<sep> Therefore we consider that only the identification of their occurrences is necessary and sufficient for the automatic processing (whatever use is made subsequently of their identification).<sep> This is not the same with disfluencies that are more complex: false starts repetitions and self-corrections.<sep> Indeed they affect a larger span than the only position in which they appear.<sep> For these disfluencies we do not only identify their occurrences but we also distinguish the repetitive items (in the case of false starts we distinguish the corrected element from its correction).<sep> What can we learn from the analysis of the different patterns of these disfluencies?<sep> In most cases we find a symmetry of the components located on both sides of the editing point.<sep> This observation will serve as a central point for implementation.<sep> We do not describe here all of the algorithms but the general principles underlying them and of which they are just the development:<sep>  In a first time to associate to each lexical item from the utterance a corresponding word class.<sep> This is provided by the CFG used in VOICE recognition system to which we added some modifications (for example the definition of word classes to add a "semantic" level.<sep> For instance the verb "descend" would be labeled as "verb_level" class).<sep> This is where the treatment of "ad hoc" disfluencies is carried out.<sep> If we are dealing with a more complex disfluency a more extensive treatment is needed.<sep> 2 For more details on the linguistic features of the phraseology, see in particular (Falzon 1989).<sep> 3 One could object here that the appearance of this type of disfluency is often concomitant with larger perturbations of the context where they appear.<sep> However, are these relationships a cause or a consequence?<sep> The question remains to be resolved...<sep> In the meantime, we adopt as a working hypothesis the independence of causality of phenomena between them.<sep> Parse the utterance with a sliding window.<sep> This latter with a maximum size of 10 lexical items moves from the left to the right of the utterance.<sep> The principle is to detect within the window the occurrence of a repetition of a pattern (either class of words or word from the lexicon corresponding to the scheme of ).<sep> When this happens, moving the window stops time for several processes within it:<sep> 1. To find the position of the editing point.<sep> For this, we run a CFG rule analysis from the beginning of the window, on the entire content of the window as if it were a complete statement.<sep> When the analysis ends before any of the terminal elements of the CFG has been reached it indicates with certainty the presence of the editing point. Once this point is found we have to distinguish each of these repeated items (or for correction to distinguish the corrected items from their correction).<sep> The comparison is done between the items located at the left of the editing point and those at its right.<sep> The repeated items (from a lexical point of view) correspond to a "repetition" while the repeated items (at the word class level) correspond to a "self correction".<sep> Eventually the moving window is resumed from the element located furthest to the right during its last instance.<sep> We have given the broad outlines of the proposed computer processing.<sep> For example, they do not include the processes necessary to distinguish, for example, a disfluent repetition from a "normal" repetition, as well as other problems of this kind.<sep> Evaluation<sep> Evaluation Methodology<sep> We accept the following as relevant to the validation of the component that we propose:<sep>  Execution time: this parameter determines whether the component that we propose can be reasonably integrated into a system to operate in real time.<sep> Indeed beyond a certain threshold the question of the relationship between the gain provided by the device and the loss in processing time would arise;<sep> Precision rate: it allows establishing the number of correct detections in regard to the total number of detections (including "false positives"); Recall rate: it determines the number of correctly detected disfluencies compared to the total number of occurrences; Delimitation rate: the delimitation of the borders of the start and end of disfluencies.<sep> Delimitation: the delimitation of the beginning and end of disfluencies is one of the tasks performed by our module.<sep> It is therefore important to determine its performance.<sep> For this measure, we also use the rates of precision (here the number of correct boundaries in relation to the total number of boundaries identified automatically) and of recall (number of correct boundaries in relation to the total number of disfluencies);<sep> Identifying the appropriate category: the aim is to determine if a disfluency even properly detected and defined is also correctly classified.<sep> For instance it can happen that a repetition is labeled as a self-correction or reciprocally.<sep> This risk is even more important given that our detection algorithm is based on the occurrence of repetitions either at a lexical or a semantic level.<sep> The performance for this parameter is important: to detect and to label correctly a given item from the disfluent area is the first step to be able to correct it (for example to remove surplus repetitions or to replace a corrected word by its correction).<sep> Evaluation corpus creation For the evaluation it was necessary to acquire a second independent corpus from which the modeling was carried out.<sep> Results<sep> The context and phrasing help to understand that the controller is starting to say "maximum."<sep> He realizes that this does not suit him and stops himself (“mak”).<sep> Finally, he says the correct word: "minimum".<sep> The aim of this diagram is to be able to account for certain phenomena of spontaneous oral speech, for example in transcriptions by labelling them.<sep> The authors refer to the phenomena in question using the generic term "repairs".<sep> This term corresponds roughly to what we have called repetitions, beginnings and self-corrections.<sep> But the schema can also account for other disfluencies.<sep> The authors propose a whole set of generic symbols that can represent the majority of disfluencies.<sep> For example FP (Filled Pauses) for hesitations, C (Cues) for words like "sorry" etc.<sep> Each occurrence of a symbol is associated with a numerical index which allows it to be distinguished in the same sentence if necessary.<sep> The scheme also makes it possible to account for the different zones involved in more complex disfluencies such as repetitions or self-corrections.<sep> To do this, the authors use the vertical bar ("|") to indicate the position of the edit point.<sep> This is the 'place' after the disfluency occurs, from which the speaker realizes there is a problem in their oral production and attempts to remedy it.<sep> For example,<sep> It is very difficult to get hold of spoken corpora of air traffic control dialogues because of the sensitive nature of this work.<sep> As a result, we had to produce "artificially" a corpus of disfluencies appearing in this context.<sep> For this, we took inspiration from the "par défi" (by challenge) campaign by GDR I34 (Antoine et al., 2002).<sep> It consists of selecting a set of statements considered representative of the task domain studied (Antoine et al. 2002 p. 563).<sep> Derived statements are constructed from these basic statements.<sep> The process of deriving involves transforming each initial statement so that it contains a phenomenon that can pose a problem to a given system of understanding.<sep> We were forced to make some modifications to this methodology in order to adapt it to our study context.<sep> First, we selected a set of utterances from our study corpus that were chosen because they did not contain any disfluency.<sep> From each of these sentences we constructed manually 6 sentences with a disfluency (hesitation, repetition or self-correction) in each.<sep> We generated 306 statements in this way.<sep> We also added two other subsets to this main corpus.<sep> On the one hand, there were the 51 basic statements that contained no disfluencies.<sep> Indeed, we thought it would be interesting to have them processed by our module in order to determine if it does not cause any "false positives".<sep> On the other hand, 43 statements contained at least one disfluency, taken from transcriptions of air traffic control dialogues recorded in a "real" situation (and not in a learning situation, unlike our corpus of study).<sep> In total, our validation corpus thus comprises 400 different statements distributed over four different subsets (each subset corresponding to the verification of one or more hypotheses) 5.<sep> The statements are presented to the module in written form (and not orally): this avoids any bias linked to speech recognition problems, in order to concentrate on validating the identification capabilities of our module.<sep> (Bouraoui 2008)ace we cannot present here all the results that we obtained.<sep> We only report the most representative ones and refer to (Bouraoui 2008) for more details.<sep> Overall, the results obtained are satisfactory and validate the module.<sep> Thus the execution time is very quick: the maximum execution time is less than 5 milliseconds.<sep> In terms of disfluency detection, the performance is also good or very good depending on the sub-set of the corpus: the precision rate varies between 84% and 95% and the recall rate between 56% and 93%.<sep> For this last result, the 56% rate corresponds to the difficulty of the module for the task of delimiting self-corrections in particularly complex disfluencies.<sep> Finally, the comparison with the performances of other disfluency detection devices described in the literature makes it possible to determine that our results are in the “upper range”.<sep> In this paper, we have described the complete automatic processing pipeline that we propose to account for disfluencies in spontaneous air traffic control dialogues.<sep> It first involved a detailed analysis of the context and the disfluencies observed.<sep> We then proceeded with the implementation of this model in the context of an existing system, but one that did not allow for the processing of this type of phenomenon.<sep> Finally we have validated the disfluency identification module that we designed.<sep> It appears that our module achieves good or even very good performance and is robust.<sep> Our hypothesis on the specificity of the automatic processing of disfluencies in phrasology is also confirmed.<sep> The evaluation also shows that the system we are proposing is very well adapted to modelling and automatic processing of disfluencies in constrained language.<sep> The proposed treatment is not exhaustive since certain very complex cases are not taken into account;<sep> Nevertheless, it theoretically covers a large part of the disfluencies.<sep> In the long term, we intend to investigate to what extent the proposed model can be applied to other types of tasks than just air traffic control.<sep> Indeed, we are convinced that at least some of the treatments we have proposed are applicable in other contexts, even less restricted than that of phrasology.<sep> ReferencesANTOINE J-Y. BOUSQUET C. GOULIAN<sep> J. ZAKARIA KURDI<sep> M. ROSSET<sep> S. VIGOUROUX N. VILLANEAU J. (2002) "Predictive and objective evaluation of speech understanding: the 'challenge' evaluation campaign of the I3 workgroup of the French CNRS" Third International Conference on Language Resources and Evaluation (LREC'02) Las Palmas Espagne Vol.II p. 529-536 2002.
Adaptation of a Statistical Machine Translation System with Monolingual Resources<sep> Abstract<sep> The performance of a statistical translation system depends greatly on the quality and quantity of the available training data. Most of the freely available parallel texts to train a statistical machine translation system are from international organizations.<sep> The jargon observed in these texts is not very suitable for building a translation system for other domains. In this article, we present a technique for adapting the translation model to a different domain using texts in the source language only.<sep> We obtain significant improvements in BLEU score in Arabic to French and English translation systems. Keywords: Statistical translation, translation model adaptation, monolingual corpus, unsupervised learning.<sep> 1 Introduction<sep> Statistical machine translation is now considered a serious alternative to rule-based translation systems.<sep> The latter first perform an analysis of the source sentence, then a transfer step and then the generation of the sentence in the target language.<sep> The development and maintenance of such a system generally requires a lot of human work by specialists (bilingual).<sep> A statistical system, on the other hand, can in principle be developed without knowledge of the languages being processed.<sep> Consider the translation of a French sentence f into English e: e[∗] = arg max p ( e|f ) = arg max p ( f |e ) P ( e ) e e (1)<sep> The translation model p ( f | e ) is learned from translation examples, i.e. texts in the source language and the corresponding translations, aligned at the sentence level.<sep> These texts are commonly referred to as "parallel texts" or "bitexts".<sep> The P(e) language model is built from texts in the target language.<sep> This automatic learning from examples is generally advanced as a great advantage of statistical translation systems.<sep> This has made it possible, in particular, to quickly build translation systems for all combinations of the 22 European languages (Koehn et al., 2009), thanks to the use of texts translated by the European Commission.<sep> This parallel corpus is known as Europarl.<sep> At the same time, it is clear that the performance of any machine learning approach depends largely on the quantity and quality of the available learning data.<sep> Often, performance improves as more training data is used, although this effect quickly levels off.<sep> On the other hand, it often happens that the field of learning data corresponds little or not at all to the field of intended use of the translation system.<sep> To give an example, it is easy to understand that translations learned automatically from translation examples in the field of finance are not suitable for translating medical texts. Indeed, the vocabularies are likely to be different and there are words that are translated differently depending on the field.<sep> Unfortunately, it happens that practically all freely available bitexts come from the parliamentary or political domain: the Europarl corpus, the French and English transcripts of the Canadian Parliament (Hansard) or texts of the United Nations.<sep> The translation model learned on this data is likely to favour specific translations in this field. It is also noted that the first person is not frequently used in these texts.<sep> However, it can be assumed that there are enough monolingual texts for a wide variety of languages and domains.<sep> These texts can often be found on the Internet or are available from the user of the translation system. It is therefore much easier to build a language model specific to a domain.<sep> In this paper, we propose a method that allows to adapt a generic translation model to a particular domain using monolingual data in the source language.<sep> This article is organized as follows.<sep> In the next section, we first summarize other research that addresses the problem of insufficient resources.<sep> Section 3 presents the reference translation systems and section 4 summarizes our experiments.<sep> The article concludes with a conclusion and a discussion of future research directions.<sep> 2 Previous research<sep> Several techniques have been proposed in the literature to address the problem of insufficient bilingual resources.<sep> One could, for example, try to extract parallel texts from comparable corpora.<sep> A comparable bilingual corpus can be defined as a collection of texts in two languages that deal with the same subject without being perfect translations.<sep> Wikipedia is a well-known example of a large comparable corpus.<sep> Another approach is to adapt the translation model to the task without using additional bilingual resources.<sep> One can distinguish two types of translation model adaptation: first, adding new source words or/and new translations to the model; and second, modifying the probabilities of the existing model to better fit the topic of the task.<sep> These two directions are complementary and could be simultaneously applied.<sep> A common way to modify a statistical model is to use a mixture model and to optimize the coefficients to the adaptation domain.<sep> This was investigated in the framework of SMT by several authors, for instance for word alignment (Civera and Juan, 2007), for language modeling (Zhao et al., 2004; Koehn and Schroeder, 2007) and to a lesser extent for the translation model (Foster and Kuhn, 2007; Chen et al., 2008).<sep> This mixture approach has the advantage that only few parameters need to be modified, the mixture coefficients.<sep> However, many translation probabilities are modified at once and it is not possible to selectively modify the probabilities of particular phrases.<sep> Comparable corpora are commonly used to find additional parallel texts, candidate sentences being often identified with help of information retrieval techniques, for instance (Hildebrand et al., 2005).<sep> Recently, a similar idea was applied to adapt the translation and language model using monolingual texts in the target language (Snover et al., 2008).<sep> Cross-lingual information retrieval was applied to find texts in the target language that are related to the domain of the source texts.<sep> However, it was difficult to find the alignments between the source and target phrases and an over-generalizing IBM1-style approach was used.<sep> Another direction of research is self-enhancing of the translation model.<sep> This was first proposed by (Ueffing, 2006).<sep> The idea is to translate the test data, to filter the translations with a confidence score and to use the most reliable ones to train an additional small translation model that is jointly used with the generic translation table.<sep> This is actually a mixture model approach with a model being built explicitly for each test set.<sep> In practice, such an approach is only feasible when a certain amount of data is available to be translated at once. This is typically the case during NIST or WMT evaluations with test sets of around 50,000 words, but the use of this method seems to be more difficult in the context of an online translation service. In such an application, only the translation of a few sentences is usually requested.<sep> This approach was improved later (Ueffing, 2007) and applied to other statistical models in a translation system (Chen et al., 2008).<sep> Another comparable approach is slightly supervised learning (Schwenk, 2008).<sep> In that work, a statistical translation system is used to translate large amounts of source language data. These translations are then filtered and the best ones are added to the existing bitexts.<sep> This technique seems to be very similar to self-enhancing as proposed by (Ueffing, 2006), but there are several conceptual differences.<sep> Firstly, we do not use the test data to adapt the translation model, but a large monolingual corpus. Secondly, we create a completely new model that can be applied to any test data without additional modification of the system.<sep> Thus, it is possible to use an adapted system in this way in an Internet translation service.<sep> In this paper, we study the usefulness of this approach to adapt Arabic to English and French translation systems.<sep> The Arabic translation is interesting because it is a morphologically rich language.<sep> Thus, the Arabic text is usually decomposed to detach prefixes and suffixes from a word, which helps to significantly reduce the size of the translation vocabulary.<sep> Several authors report an improvement in the quality of translations thanks to this morphological decomposition, for example (Habash & Sadat, 2006).<sep> This morphological decomposition also results in many different and infrequent phrases which may lead to bad relative frequency estimates of the phrase translation probabilities.<sep> Our goal is to improve the estimation of these probabilities by using monolingual texts.<sep> 3 Baseline translation systems.<sep> In this article, a statistical translation system based on segments is used (in English "phrase-based statistical machine translation system") for both language pairs, using the free software Moses (Koehn et al., 2007).<sep> Equation 1 can be rewritten to show characteristic functions fi (e, f):<sep> It uses fourteen features functions, namely phrase and lexical translation probabilities in both directions, seven features for the lexicalized distortion model, a word and a phrase penalty, and a target language model.<sep> The systems are constructed as follows: first, the GIZA++ software is used to obtain word alignments in both directions.<sep> There is a version that allows to speed up the calculation on multi-core machines (Gao & Vogel, 2008).<sep> [1] Then the phrases and lexical reorderings are extracted, using the default settings of the Moses toolkit.<sep> Finally, the coefficients of the characteristic functions are optimized by the CMERT tool.<sep> Language models are four-grams with folding, constructed with the SRILM tool (Stolcke, 2002).<sep> The training data corresponds to the English side of the bitexts plus an important collection of newspaper texts.<sep> These texts are available from the LDC under the name Gigaword corpus.<sep> In most studies, tools such as the Buckwalter analyzer and the MADA and TOKAN tools from Columbia University are used to perform morphological analysis of Arabic texts (Habash & Sadat, 2006).<sep> In this work, we use the analysis module of the SYSTRAN translation system to perform this task.<sep> Decomposition rules are first applied, assisted by a word dictionary.<sep> The most likely decomposition of words that are not known in the dictionary is carried out.<sep> In general, all possible decompositions of each word are generated and then filtered in the context of the sentence.<sep> This step uses lexical knowledge and a global analysis of the sentence.<sep> The French texts were tokenized using the tools of the Moses suite.<sep> Punctuation and case were preserved.<sep> 3.1 Arabic/English translation<sep> For a number of years now, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) has been organising international evaluation campaigns of automatic translation systems.<sep> These assessments are commonly regarded as the benchmark in the field.<sep> The Arabic/English translation system described here is one of the best systems in the evaluation organized in 2009.<sep> The detailed conditions and results are available on the NIST website.[2]<sep> The translation model is learned on various parallel texts available from the LDC as part of the NIST evaluation for a total of about 56 million Arabic words.<sep> We also added 133M words from the United Nations corpus.<sep> The language model is learned on a total of more than 3 billion words.<sep> These resources were the same for all participants in this trial (‘controlled condition’).<sep> The parameter optimization was performed on the evaluation data of 2006. We also give results on the evaluation data of 2008 which were used as an internal test set. In both cases, it is a matter of data from the field of radio and television news and discussions on the Internet.<sep> Four translation references are available and the formatting and punctuation are preserved.<sep> TAB. 1 – BLEU scores of the Arabic/English reference system.<sep> The BLEU scores of these reference systems are given in Table 1.<sep> It is noted that the UN data brings a low gain of the BLEU score despite a considerable size.<sep> This is because the data is out of range.<sep> Although this bitext provides a lot of translations, it also changes the translation probabilities calculated by relative frequency.<sep> Translations from the "UN" domain thus seem to dominate the more appropriate translations of the domain bitexts.<sep> We will show in this article that this can be "corrected" by adapting the translation model with monolingual data.<sep> 3.2 Arabic/French translation<sep> We also consider translation from Arabic to French.<sep> This pair of languages seems interesting to us for several reasons.<sep> Firstly, they are both morphologically rich languages, compared to the usual translation into English.<sep> Secondly, there are few bitexts well adapted to the field of translation and a large corpus outside the field.<sep> These are exactly the conditions that motivated our approach to adapting the translation model.<sep> Finally, one can easily identify applications of an Arabic-to-French translation system.<sep> The development of the first statistical machine translation systems for this language pair probably started with the DGA TRAMES project[3] which aimed at translating Arabic speech to French.<sep> As part of this project, around 90 hours of radio and television speeches were recorded, transcribed and then translated into French.<sep> The DGA gave us access to these parallel texts of around 260 thousand words.<sep> This data is perfectly suited to the domain but is of course too small to train a good statistical translation model.<sep> So we supplemented them with 1.1 million words of text downloaded from the Syndicate project website[4] and about 200 million words of UN data.<sep> The latter corpus was collected by the company SYSTRAN.<sep> The DGA also produced a test set with 4 reference translations.<sep> This corpus was randomly divided into a development set and a test set of about 10 thousand words each.<sep> The performances of the reference systems are given in Table 2.<sep> The language model is a quad-gram trained on a little over 1.3 billion words (French side of bitexts, French Gigaword corpus and other newspapers).<sep> TAB. 2 – BLEU scores of the Arabic/French reference system.<sep> To our knowledge, only one other Arabic/French statistical translation system has been developed, specifically as part of the TRAMES project (Hasan & Ney, 2008).<sep> In this work, the same test set was used, but the bitexts are different: the parallel texts of the TRAMES project, UN data from 2001 to April 2007, Amnesty International archives and articles from Le Monde Diplomatique.<sep> The authors give a BLEU score of 41.1 on the full test set of about twenty thousand words.<sep> This system therefore uses other resources than ours and it is not possible to directly compare the performance.<sep> However, it can probably be concluded that BLEU scores above 40 points seem to correspond to the state of the art for this language pair.<sep> This is also in line with the results observed in the NIST evaluations for the Arabic/English language pair (see Table 1).<sep> In both cases, the translation of radio and television texts is concerned, and four references of translations are available.<sep> 4 Translation model adaptation<sep> The goal of this work is to adapt the translation model without using additional bilingual data, but with monolingual data in the source language.<sep> Usually it is relatively easy to obtain large collections of such data, in particular in the news domain as considered in this work.<sep> We use parts of the LDC Arabic Gigaword corpus.<sep> These texts are translated by the reference systems described above.<sep> Then, the automatic translations are filtered in order to keep only the "best" ones.<sep> This selection could take advantage of word-based confidence scores (Ueffing, 2007).<sep> In our case, we used the log-likelihood provided by the decoder, normalized by the number of words in each sentence.<sep> The selected translations are added to the existing bitexts and the complete procedure to build a statistical translation system is performed, i.e. word alignment with GIZA++, extraction of word groups and optimization of the coefficients λi.<sep> Alternatively, we could reuse the alignments established by the Moses decoder.<sep> This would speed up the process of creating the adapted SMT system since we skip the timeconsuming word alignment performed by GIZA++.<sep> The characteristics of the Gigaword corpora from LDC are given in Table 3.<sep> The French/Arabic system was only adapted on the AFP corpus while we used the AFP, XIN and NHR corpora for the Arabic/English system.<sep> Note that LDC’s English and French texts are used in the construction of the P(e) language model.<sep> It is likely that these texts contain the translations of some phrases from the Arabic texts, which should help produce good automatic translations.<sep> Thus we speak of a slightly supervised learning by the language model (Schwenk, 2008).<sep> TAB. 3 – Characteristics of the Gigaword corpora from LDC (number of words).<sep> 4.1 Arabic/English system adaptation<sep> The BLEU scores after adapting the Arabic/English system to the Arabic texts of AFP, XIN and HYT respectively are given in Table 4.<sep> Although the BLEU scores on the development data change little, there is a clear improvement in performance on the test data.<sep> It is also noted that the adapted systems use fewer bitexts than the reference system.<sep> This is because the UN data is no longer used in the adapted systems since these out-of-domain data are replaced by the automatic translations of the Arabic domain corpora. For each corpus, we tried different thresholds on the normalized likelihood of the decoder.<sep> The choice of the best threshold was of course based only on the performance obtained on the development data.<sep> TAB. 4 – Adaptation du système arabe/anglais. Finalement, nous avons effectué une simple combinaison des trois systèmes adaptés indépendamment : les listes des n meilleures hypothèses sont concaténées et la meilleure hypothèse est extraite.<sep> This made it possible to obtain a small additional gain (last line of table 4).<sep> This system was very well placed in the 2009 NIST evaluations.[5]<sep> The official system includes another component that we have omitted here for lack of space (linguistic modeling in continuous space (Schwenk, 2010)). 4.2 Adaptation of the Arabic/French system TAB. 5 – Adaptation of the Arabic/French translation system.<sep> The performance of the adapted Arabic/French system is summarized in table 5. Here, we note a very appreciable gain in BLEU score of more than 3.5 BLEU points on the test data.<sep> This significant improvement could be explained by the low number of bitexts in the domain compared to the very voluminous but out-of-domain UN data.<sep> This report was more balanced for the Arabic/English language pair.<sep> We analyzed the translation table of the original system trained on more than 200M words and the reference system.<sep> This is summarized in table 6.<sep> The original phrase table had 329M entries out of which 22.9M could be potentially applied on the test data.<sep> The translation table of the adapted system on the other hand used only 700k out of a total of 8.6M entries.<sep> It seems clear that the translation table obtained by training on the UN data contains many entries that are not used, or even correspond to wrong translations.<sep> It is surprising to see that the translation table of the adapted system is smaller and contains 11% more source language segments (18029 with respect to 16263).<sep> All these entries correspond to new sequences of words since unsupervised learning does not allow to increase the vocabulary of the source words.<sep> TAB. 6 – Characteristics of the translation table of the two systems.<sep> In both cases, the table was filtered to only contain the word groups that could be applied to the test data.<sep> We conjecture that this is particularly important with the morphological decomposition of the Arabic words.<sep> This decomposition reduces the vocabulary size of the source language, but produces on the other hand many possible sequences of tokens.<sep> It seems important to include in the translation table sequences that appear in the domain texts.<sep> As a side effect, the smaller translation table leads to a 40% faster translation.<sep> We compared the translations of the unadapted and adapted systems: the TER is about 30 in both directions, meaning that the outputs differ substantially.<sep> Some example translations are shown in figure 1.<sep> The adapted system clearly produces better translations for these examples.<sep> There remain of course some errors in these sentences, but the quality of the translations is high enough for an human being to capture most of the meaning of the sentences.<sep> FIG. 1 – Examples of automatic translations from the test set (reference system, adapted system and human translation reference).<sep> 5 Conclusion<sep> Statistical machine translation is today used to rapidly create automatic translations systems for a variety of languages.<sep> In general, we only need all available parallel texts to train the translation model.<sep> However, most of these texts come from a very specific domain - parliamentary speeches - which makes them unsuitable for other domains.<sep> On the other hand, monolingual texts generally exist in most fields of interest.<sep> In this work, we proposed an approach that uses monolingual source language texts to adapt a generic translation model.<sep> For this, the texts are translated by an initial generic system, filtered and the most reliable are added to the parallel texts.<sep> After a new learning cycle, we obtain an adapted system.<sep> This technique has allowed significant improvements in the BLEU score in Arabic/English and Arabic/French translation systems.<sep> Several extensions of the proposed approach can be envisioned, namely improved confidence scores for filtering the most reliable translations, processing of n -best lists instead of using the most likely translation only, and reuse of the decoder-induced word alignments instead of rerunning GIZA++. We are currently working on these issues.<sep> Acknowledgments<sep> This research was partially funded by the French government under the INSTAR project (ANR JCJC06_143038) and the European Commission under the EuromatrixPlus project.<sep> The Arabic/French corpus of radio and television data as well as the corresponding test set were made available to us by the DGA.<sep> Some of this work has been done in collaboration with the company SYSTRAN. 1 The sources are available at http://www.cs.cmu.edu/~qing/ 2 http://www.itl.nist.gov/iad/mig/tests/mt/2009/<sep> 1 Traduction Automatique par Méthodes Statistiques<sep> 4 http://www.project-syndicate.org<sep> 5 http://www.itl.nist.gov/iad/mig/tests/mt/2009/<sep> 6 Translation Edit Rate (Snover et al., 2006)
A hybrid translation/correction approach for normalizing SMS messages<sep> Abstract<sep> This paper presents a hybrid method of normalizing SMS, halfway between spelling correction and machine translation.<sep> The normalization part of the system is entirely based on models trained from a corpus.<sep> Evaluated in French by 10-fold-cross validation, the system achieves a 9.3% Word Error Rate and a 0.83 BLEU score.<sep> Keywords: SMS messages, normalization, finite-state machines, hybrid approach, machine translationlike, spell checking-like, corpus-based learning.<sep> 1 Introduction<sep> Introduced a few years ago, Short Message Service (SMS), a means of communication that has been quickly adopted by users, offers the possibility of exchanging written messages between mobile phones.<sep> These messages often greatly deviate from traditional spelling conventions.<sep> As shown by specialists (Thurlow and Brown, 2003; Fairon et al., 2006), this variability is due to the simultaneous use of numerous coding strategies, like phonetic plays ( 2m1 read ‘demain’, “tomorrow”), phonetic transcriptions ( kom instead of ‘comme’, “like”), consonant skeletons ( tjrs for ‘toujours’, “always”), misapplied, missing or incorrect separators ( j esper for ‘j’espère’, “I hope”; j’croibi1k , instead of ‘je crois bien que’, “I am pretty sure that”), etc.<sep> These deviations are due to three main factors: the small number of characters allowed per text message by the service (140 bytes), the constraints of the small phones’ keypads and, last but not least, the fact that people mostly communicate between friends and relatives in an informal register.<sep> Whatever their causes, these deviations considerably hamper any standard TAL system, which is not designed to handle so many Out-Of-Vocabulary words.<sep> For this reason, as noted by Sproat et al. (2001), an SMS normalization, i.e. the rewriting of an SMS in conventional spelling, must be performed before a more standard TAL module (for example, a speech synthesis system) can be applied.<sep> SMS standardisation has so far been approached from three different angles: spelling correction, automatic translation and voice recognition.<sep> Each approach, based on different assumptions, effectively manages some of the phenomena present in SMS.<sep> However, on the whole, standardising SMS remains a complex and unresolved problem: the best systems, in fact, hardly manage to get below 11% of errors per word.<sep> The normalization method we present here, developed in the general framework of an SMS-to-speech synthesis system[1] , is located halfway between the correction and translation oriented approaches.<sep> As in correction, the system distinguishes different types of units within the text, and only normalizes the units considered as noisy. As in translation, the normalization models are exclusively learned from parallel corpora.<sep> This paper is organized as follows.<sep> Section 2 proposes an overview of the state of the art.<sep> Section 3 presents the general architecture of our system, while Section 4 focuses on how we learn and combine our normalization models.<sep> On this basis, section 5 evaluates the system and compares it to previous works.<sep> Section 6, finally, makes a point on the work accomplished and proposes some possible improvements.<sep> 2 Related work<sep> As highlighted by Kobus et al. (2008), SMS normalization, up to now, has been handled through three well-known NLP metaphors: spell checking, machine translation and automatic speech recognition.<sep> The correction-oriented metaphor (Guimier de Neef & Fessard, 2007; Choudhury et al., 2007; Cook & Stevenson, 2009) performs the normalization task on a word-per-word basis.<sep> Assuming that most words are correct for the purpose of communication, its principle is to keep known words out of the normalisation process.<sep> Guimier de Neef & Fessard (2007) proposed a rule-based system that uses only a few linguistic resources dedicated to SMS, like specific lexicons of abbreviations.<sep> Choudhury et al. (2007) and Cook and Stevenson (2009) preferred to implement the noisy channel metaphor (Shannon, 1948), which assumes a communication process in which a sender emits the intended message W through an imperfect (noisy) communication channel, such that the sequence O observed by the recipient is a noisy version of the original message.<sep> On this basis, the idea is to recover the intended message W hidden behind the sequences of observations O , by maximizing:<sep> where P ( O ) is ignored because constant, P ( O|W ) models the channel’s noise, and P ( W ) models the language of the source.<sep> Whatever the system, the main limitation of the spell checking approach is the excessive confidence it places in word boundaries.<sep> The translation-oriented metaphor (Aw et al., 2006) considers the normalization process as a translation task from a source language (the SMS) to a target language (its standard written form).<sep> This standpoint is based on the observation that, on the one side, SMS messages greatly differ from their standard written forms, and that, on the other side, most of the errors cross word boundaries and require a wide context to be handled.<sep> On this basis, Aw et al. (2006) proposed a statistical model working at the group level.<sep> While this approach achieves really good results, Kobus et al. (2008) consider that a translation at the group level is not able to capture the great lexical creativity of SMS messages.<sep> Moreover, the basic principles of automatic translation, which are designed to handle many-to-many correspondences between source and target, exceed the needs of SMS normalization, which is almost deterministic.<sep> Based on this analysis, Kobus et al. (2008) proposed to handle SMS normalization through an automatic speech recognition (ASR) metaphor.<sep> It is true that SMS messages present a lot of phonetic plays that sometimes make the SMS word ( sré , mwa ) closer to its phonetic representation ([sKe], [mwa]) than to its standard written form ( serai , moi ).<sep> Typically, an ASR system tries to discover the best word sequence within a lattice of weighted phonetic sequences.<sep> Applied to the SMS normalization task, the ASR metaphor consists in first converting the SMS message into a phone lattice, before turning it into a word-based lattice using a phoneme-to-grapheme dictionary.<sep> A language model is then applied on the word lattice, and the most probable word sequence is finally chosen by applying a best-path algorithm on the lattice.<sep> One of the advantages of this approach is its intrinsic ability to handle word boundaries.<sep> However, this step also presents an important drawback, raised by the authors themselves: it prevents next normalization steps from knowing what graphemes were in the initial sequence.<sep> Our approach, which is detailed in Sections 3 and 4, shares similarities with both the spell checking approach and the machine translation principles, trying to combine the advantages of these methods, while leaving aside their drawbacks: like in spell checking systems, we detect unambiguous units of text as soon as possible and try to rely on word boundaries when they seem reliable enough ; but like in the machine translation task, our method intrinsically handles word boundaries in the normalization process if needed.<sep> 3 Overview of the system<sep> In our system, all lexicons, language models and sets of rules are compiled into finite-state machines (FSMs) and combined with the input text by composition ( ◦ ).<sep> The reader who is not familiar with FSMs and their fundamental properties is urged to consult the state-of-the-art literature (Hopcroft et al., 1979; Roche & Schabes, 1997).<sep> We used our own finite-state tools: a finite-state machine library and its associated compiler (Beaufort, 2008).<sep> FIG. 1 – System architecture<sep> As shown in Figure 1, an SMS message first goes through three SMS modules, which normalize its noisy parts.<sep> Two TAL modules then produce a morphosyntactic analysis of the normalized text.<sep> The last module, finally, depends on the type of output desired: either a synthesizer, which constructs the speech signal corresponding to the normalized text based on its linguistic analysis, or a printing module, which produces the normalized text and applies the basic rules of typography (capitalization at the beginning of a sentence, presence or absence of spaces between units of the text, etc.) based on the units detected by the pre- and post-processing SMS modules.<sep> Because this paper focuses on the normalization task, the rest of this section only presents the SMS modules.<sep> Preprocessing module.<sep> This module exclusively identifies the following sequences in a text: end of paragraphs and sentences, URLs, phone numbers, dates, units of measurement and time, currencies and, very frequent in the context of SMS, smileys[2] .<sep> These sequences, identified using local grammars, are considered as non-ambiguous units and are kept out of the normalization process. Any other sequence of characters is considered as noisy and undergoes the normalization process.<sep> This brings the method closer to the correction-oriented metaphor.<sep> The normalization module.<sep> The models and lexicons used here are all learned from a detailed training in Section 4.<sep> Inspired by the noisy channel metaphor (see section 2), our approach differs in that the model dedicated to channel noise varies depending on whether the noisy sequence is known (known sequence, KN) or not (unknown sequence, UNK): This model is the result of numerous tests, which have highlighted the fact that distinguishing between known and unknown sequences considerably improves the system's efficiency, without detracting from its performance.<sep> On this basis, our algorithm is divided into three stages.<sep> The first step of the algorithm consists in composing a noisy unit U with a finite-state transducer (FST) Seg whose task is to differentiate between known sequences and unknown sequences, by labelling them with symbols of the alphabet considered as markers: KN and UNK.<sep> The unit is then split in n segments Oi according to these markers:<sep> In a second step, each segment is composed with a rewrite model according to its kind: the RKN rewrite model for known sequences, and the RUNK rewrite model for unknown sequences:<sep> All rewritten segments are then concatenated together in order to get back the complete token:<sep> where ⊙ is the concatenation operator.<sep> The third and last normalization step is applied on a complete sentence S .<sep> All tokens Tj of S are concatenated together and composed with the lexical language model LM .<sep> The result of this composition is a word lattice, of which we take the most probable word sequence S[′], that is the best path of the lattice:<sep> where m is the number of tokens of S .<sep> In S[′] , each noisy token Tj of S is mapped onto its most probable normalization.<sep> The post-processing module.<sep> The latter SMS module is applied only to the standardized version of the noisy units, in order to identify any non-alphabetic sequences and isolate them in a separate unit.<sep> At this stage, for example, a dot becomes a "strong punctuation".<sep> The local grammars used here are more comprehensive than those of the pre-processing, because they can – and must – detect numerical and alphanumerical sequences, data fields (such as credit card numbers), punctuation and symbols.<sep> 4.2 The normalization models<sep> Our normalization models were trained on a French SMS corpus of 30,000 messages, gathered in Belgium, semi-automatically anonymized and manually normalized by the Catholic University of Louvain (Fairon and Paumier, 2006).<sep> Together, the SMS corpus and its transcription constitute parallel corpora aligned at the message-level.<sep> In order to learn from these corpora, we needed a string alignment at the character-level .<sep> This alignment was obtained completely automatically by applying the iterative algorithm described in (Cougnon & Beaufort, 2009).<sep> In short, this algorithm gradually learns the best way of aligning strings, by gradually refining the probability of each classic editing operation (substitution, insertion and deletion) according to the characters to be aligned. The learning achieved on the alignment obtained brings the method closer to the translation-oriented metaphor.<sep> 4.1 The segmentation model Seg<sep> This model segments a noisy unit into an alternating sequence of known and unknown sequences.<sep> Segmentation is therefore carried out according to the known sequences, collected during the learning process.<sep> During the examination of our parallel corpora aligned at the character-level, we decided to consider as a sequence “the longest sequence of characters parsed without meeting the same separator on both sides of the alignment”.<sep> For instance, the following alignment is split as follows according to our definition:<sep> where the underlined (_) notes the insertions, gives according to our definition the segmentation (b), since the separator in “J esper” is different from its transcription, and that “ktu” does not contain any separator.<sep> This notion of sequence is based on the fact that, in SMS, separators are perhaps indicative, but certainly not reliable.<sep> A first parsing of our parallel corpora provided us with a list of known sequences corresponding to our lexicon, KN.<sep> The segmentation FST Seg is built on this basis:<sep> where:<sep> - Kn is an FST corresponding to the lexicon KN, in which each known sequence is projected onto the marker KN.<sep> – Unk is the complement of Kn[3], where the unknown sequences are projected onto the UNK marker.<sep> - • S is an FST corresponding to the list of separators (any non-alphabetic and nonnumeric character), mapped onto a SEP marker.<sep> - G is an FST able to detect consecutive sequences of known (resp. unknown) words, and to group them under a unique KN (resp. UNK) marker.<sep> During this process, all SEP markers disappear from Seg and the separators surrounding an unknown sequence are associated with it.<sep> Figure 2 illustrates the result of applying Seg to a noisy unit.<sep> Figure 2 – Result of the application of the Seg segmentation model to the unit “J esper kcv b1” (“I hope you are well”).<sep> In this example, the sequence "kcv" was not encountered during the training;<sep> It is therefore considered as unknown by Seg, and labeled UNK.<sep> 4.2 The IV rewrite model RIV<sep> This model is built during a second parsing of our parallel corpora, whose objective is to identify the normalisations associated with the sequences of the KN lexicon.<sep> During this second parsing and contrary to the previous one, the sequences of the lexicon are searched in the corpus regardless of the context (with or without separators), in order to ensure that all possible normalizations are collected.<sep> Each normalization w ¯ for a given SMS sequence w is weighted as follows:<sep> where Occ( x ) is the number of occurrences of x in the corpus.<sep> The FST RKN is then built as follows:<sep> where:<sep> - KNR is a weighted lexicon, in which each KN sequence is associated with the weighted list of its normalizations.<sep> - SKN is a weighted lexicon of separators, in which each separator is mapped onto the list of its possible normalizations.<sep> Often, the deletion of the separator is one of the possible normalizations.<sep> Otherwise, the deletion is added and is weighted by the following smoothed probability:<sep> 4.3 The OOV rewrite model RUNK<sep> The two previous models were regular expressions made of weighted lexicons.<sep> This, on the other hand, corresponds to a list of rewriting rules weighted φ → ψ / w , learned from the alignment, where the replacement φ → ψ is assigned the weight w .<sep> Why this difference in modelling?<sep> The regular expressions in the previous models were designed to constrain the accepted language, and more particularly the place of separators, in order to force the system to favour certain solutions.<sep> In the case of unknown sequences, we know that in absolute terms, everything must be possible.<sep> It was therefore not necessary to define a different language from Σ [∗] .<sep> The targets of our rules ( φ ) are sequences of 1 to 5 characters taken from the SMS side of the alignment, while outputs ( ψ ) are their corresponding normalizations.<sep> An important constraint expressed on lists of rules is that rules are classified from the most specific to the most general, so that a given rule is only applied if no more specific and relevant rule has been met higher in the list.<sep> For this reason, our rules are sorted in descending order of the length of their targets, so that the rules with the longest targets are chosen as often as possible.<sep> This reduces the number of normalizations proposed for a given sequence, since the longer sequences tend to have fewer different normalizations.<sep> Among the wide set of possible sequences of 2 to 5 characters gathered from the corpus, we only kept in our list of rules the sequences that allowed at least one normalization made solely of words belonging to the language: while gathering the candidate sequences from the corpus, we systematically checked each normalized form in a lexicon of standard French forms.<sep> The lexicon we used contains about 430,000 inflected forms and is derived from Morlex[4] , a French lexical database.<sep> 4.6 The language model<sep> Our language model is a 3-gram of lexical forms, smoothed by linear interpolation (Chen and Goodman, 1998), estimated on the normalized part of our training corpus and compiled into a weighted FST LMw .<sep> At this point, this FST cannot be combined with our other models, because it works on lexical units and not on characters .<sep> This problem is solved by composing LMw with another FST L , which represents a lexicon mapping each input word, considered as a string of characters, onto the same output word, but considered here as a lexical unit.<sep> Lexical units are then permanently removed from the language model by keeping only the first projection (the input side) of the composition:<sep> 5 Evaluation<sep> The performance and the efficiency of our system were evaluated on a MacBook Pro with a 2.4 GHz Intel Core 2 Duo CPU, 4 GB 667 MHz DDR2 SDRAM, running Mac OS X version 10.5.8.<sep> The evaluation was performed on the corpus of 30,000 SMS presented in Section 4.2, by ten-fold cross-validation (Kohavi, 1995).<sep> The principle of this method of evaluation is to split the initial corpus into 10 subsets of equal size (here, 3000 SMS).<sep> The system is then trained and tested 10 times, each time leaving out one of the subsets from the training corpus, but using only this omitted subset as test corpus.<sep> Table 1 shows the average number of inputs/outputs of the 10 models learned during the cross-validation.<sep> If the unknown sequences (1 to 5 characters) are much less numerous than the known sequences, their number of rewrites is however significantly higher, which is due to the fact that these sequences are selected independently of any possible separators.<sep> Despite the large number of known learned sequences, the system still processed on average 85% of SMS sequences using the UNK model.<sep> TAB. 1 – Inputs/outputs of the models.<sep> ( ∗ ) SMS Traffic.<sep> ( ∗∗ ) Standard forms.<sep> TAB. 2 – Performance.<sep> (∗) Kobus 2008-2 corresponds to a combination of the ASR model of Kobus 2008-1 and a “translation-oriented” model created from a set of free software.<sep> (∗∗) Scores obtained on noisy data only, outside the context of the sentence.<sep> With an average speed of 1836.57 characters/sec (standard deviation of 159.65), the system processes a 140-character SMS in 76.23 ms (standard deviation of 22.34 ms).<sep> The system seems efficient, given the considerable time spent in the UNK model. Unfortunately, it is not possible to compare it with other systems, which do not provide us with this information.<sep> Table 2, part 1, presents the performance of our approach (Hybrid) and compares it to a simple copy-paste (Copy).<sep> The system was evaluated in terms of BLEU score (Papineni et al., 2001), Word Error Rate (WER) and Sentence Error Rate (SER). Concerning WER, the table presents the distribution between substitutions (Sub), deletions (Del) and insertions (Ins).<sep> The copy-paste results give an idea of the noise actually present in the SMS corpus, and highlight the fact that our system is still having difficulties to significantly reduce the SER, while results in terms of WER and BLEU score are quite encouraging.<sep> Table 2, part 2, provides the results of the other approaches from the literature.<sep> The majority of the results are difficult to compare to ours, because they were obtained either in a different language (English) or on a different corpus: this is the case of Kobus et al. (2008), who on the one hand combined the corpus we used with another SMS corpus, and on the other hand performed a single test, based on a larger training corpus (36,704 SMS) for a test corpus comparable to one of our blocks (2,998 SMS). The only truly comparable results are those of Guimier de Neef & Fessard (2007), who evaluated their approach on the same corpus as us, but without cross-validation, because their expert system does not require learning.<sep> In any case, Table 2 shows that our method compares very well with the best previous methods.<sep> Analysis of the standards produced by our system has highlighted three important features:<sep> 1. Missing separators (Pensa ms → Pense à mes) or superfluous separators (G t → J’étais) are generally well managed, which is reflected in our low deletion and insertion rates.<sep> 2. Pretreatment is useful, since non-ambiguous units are not modified.<sep> 3. Errors are often contextual: they concern the gender (quel(le), “what”), the number (bisou(s), “kiss”), the person ( [tu t’]inquiète(s), “you are worried”) or the tense (arrivé / arriver, “arrived”/“to arrive”).<sep> However, as Kobus et al. (2008) point out, the frequency of these errors is not surprising. In French, as mentioned by Kobus et al. (2008b), n - gram models are unable to catch this information, as it is generally out of their scope.<sep> 6 Conclusion and perspectives<sep> In this paper, we presented an SMS normalization framework based on finite-state machines and developed in the context of an SMS-to-speech synthesis system.<sep> In order to avoid the erroneous modification of non-ambiguous units, we have designed a hybrid method, between correction and translation.<sep> Our normalization algorithm is original in two ways.<sep> First, it is entirely based on models learned from a training corpus.<sep> Second, the rewrite model applied to a noisy sequence differs depending on whether this sequence is known or not.<sep> Evaluated by ten-fold cross-validation, the system seems efficient, and the performance in terms of BLEU score and WER are quite encouraging.<sep> However, the SER remains too high, which emphasizes the fact that the system needs several improvements.<sep> First of all, the model should take phonetic similarities into account, because SMS messages contain a lot of phonetic plays.<sep> The phonetic model, for instance, should know that o , au , eau , … , aux can all be pronounced [o], while è , ais , ait , … , aient are often pronounced [E].<sep> However, unlike Kobus et al. (2008), we feel that this model must avoid the grapheme-phoneme conversion step, which prevents the following steps from identifying the graphemes present in the initial sequence.<sep> Instead, we propose to learn phonetic similarities from a dictionary of words with phonemic transcriptions, and to build graphemes-to-graphemes rules.<sep> These rules could then be automatically weighted, by learning their frequencies from our aligned corpora.<sep> Furthermore, this model should be able to allow for timbre variation, like [e]–[E], in order to allow similarities between graphemes frequently confused in French, like ai ([e]) and ais / ait / aient ([E]).<sep> It would also be interesting to test the impact of another lexical language model, learned on nonSMS sentences.<sep> Indeed, the lexical model presents a major drawback in the context of SMS messages: it must be learned from standard forms, which, in the context of SMS, implies the transcription of the corpus, an expensive process that reduces the amount of data on which the model will be trained.<sep> However, the corpus that would replace the transcribed SMS corpus should share two important features with the SMS language: it should mimic the oral language and be as spontaneous as possible.<sep> Based on these constraints, our intention is to gather sentences from Internet forums, by carefully selecting these forums, because their texts share another feature with SMS: they are noisy.<sep> Thus, the idea is to choose a forum whose philosophy is explicitly to avoid the use of SMS language and to pay attention to spelling and grammar.<sep> The last improvement we propose here is more correction oriented: the idea is to allow spelling correction inside the TAL modules of the system.<sep> At this stage of the process, more sophisticated correction methods, guided by morphosyntactic analysis and combined with it, could thus focus on the non-trivial problem of contextual errors.<sep> Acknowledgments<sep> This research was co-financed by the FIRST Post-Doc "Vocalise" (convention 716619) and WIST2 "Expressive" (convention 616422) projects of the Walloon Region.<sep> 1 The Vocalise project.<sep> See cental.fltr.ucl.ac.be/team/projects/vocalise/.<sep> 2 Our list contains about 680 smileys.<sep> 3 Actually, the true complement of Kn accepts all sequences with separators, while Unk does not.<sep> 4 See http://bach.arts.kuleuven.be/pmertens/.
Automatic evaluation of summaries with and without reference<sep> Abstract<sep> We study different methods of content-based document summarization evaluation. We are particularly interested in the correlation between evaluation measures with and without human reference.<sep> We apply our comparison framework to various well-established contentbased evaluation measures in text summarization such as coverage, Responsiveness, Pyramids and ROUGE studying their associations in various text summarization tasks including generic and focus-based multi-document summarization in English and generic single-document summarization in French and Spanish. The research is carried out using a new content-based evaluation framework called FRESA to compute a variety of divergences among probability distributions.<sep> Keywords: Evaluation measures, Text Automatic Summarization.<sep> 1 Introduction<sep> The evaluation of automatically produced summaries has always been a complex and controversial issue in Automatic Language Processing (ALP).<sep> In the last years, large scale evaluations independent of the system designers have emerged and several evaluation measures have been proposed.<sep> As for the evaluation of automatic summary systems, two evaluation campaigns have already been carried out by the American agency DARPA (Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency).<sep> The first, called SUMMAC, took place from 1996 to 1998 under the TIPSTER program (Mani et al., 2002), and the second, called DUC (Document Understanding Conferences) (Over et al., 2007), followed from 2000 to 2007. Since 2008, the Text Analysis Conference (TAC) (TAC, 2008) has taken over and is the forum for the evaluation of different technologies for accessing textual information, including text summarization.<sep> Evaluation in text summarization can be extrinsic or intrinsic (Spärck Jones & Galliers, 1996).<sep> In an extrinsic evaluation, the summaries are assessed in the context of a specific task carried out by a human or machine; in an intrinsic evaluation, the summaries are evaluated in reference to some ideal model.<sep> SUMMAC followed an extrinsic evaluation paradigm and DUC/TAC followed an intrinsic evaluation paradigm.<sep> In order to intrinsically evaluate summaries, the candidate summary (peer) has to be compared to a model summary or summaries.<sep> DUC used an interface called SEE to allow human judges compare a peer summary to a model summary.<sep> The judges thus assign a coverage score to the candidate summary and the final score is the average of the scores obtained.<sep> The final score can then be used to rank the automatic summary systems.<sep> In the case of query-focused summarization (e.g. when the summary has to respond to a question or set of questions) a Responsiveness score is also assigned to each summary which indicates how responsive the summary is to the question(s).<sep> Because manual comparison of candidate summaries with model summaries is an arduous and costly process, a body of research has been produced in the last decade on automatic content-based evaluation procedures.<sep> Early studies used text similarity measures such as cosine similarity (with or without weighting schema) to compare candidate and reference summaries (Donaway et al., 2000). Various vocabulary overlap measures such as set of n-grams overlap or longest common subsequence between candidate and model have also been proposed (Radev et al., 2003).<sep> The Bleu machine translation evaluation measure (Papineni et al., 2002) has also been tested in summarization (Pastra and Saggion, 2003).<sep> The DUC conferences adopted the ROUGE package for content-based evaluation (Lin, 2004).<sep> It has been shown that system rankings produced by some ROUGE measures (e.g., ROUGE-2 which uses bi-grams) correlate with rankings produced using coverage.<sep> In recent years the Pyramids evaluation method (Nenkova and Passonneau, 2004) was introduced.<sep> PYRAMIDS is based on the distribution of the informativeness of a set of model summaries.<sep> Summary Content Units (SCUs) are first identified in the model summaries, then each SCU receives a weight which is the number of models containing or expressing the same unit.<sep> The SCUs of the identified candidate abstracts are aligned against those of the references, and then weighted.<sep> The Pyramids score given to the candidate is the ratio of the sum of the weights of its units and the sum of the weights of the best possible ideal summary with the same number of SCUs as the candidate.<sep> Pyramids scores are also used for ranking systems. Nenkova & Passonneau (2004) showed that Pyramids scores produce reliable rankings when multiple (4 or more) references are used and that Pyramids rankings correlate with rankings produced by ROUGE-2 and ROUGE-SU4 (ROUGE with skip 2-grams).<sep> However, this method requires the creation of references and the identification, matching, and weighting of SCUs in the references and in the candidates.<sep> Nenkova & Passonneau (2004) proposed to use the full document directly for comparison purposes and argued that content-based measures which compare the document to the summary may be acceptable substitutes for those using model summaries.<sep> A method for evaluation of summarization systems without models has been recently proposed (Louis and Nenkova, 2009).<sep> It is based on the direct comparison of the information contained between the summaries and their corresponding source documents.<sep> Louis and Nenkova (2009) evaluated the effectiveness of the Jensen-Shannon (Lin, 1991) theoretic measure in predicting systems ranks in two summarization tasks query-focused and update summarization.<sep> They have shown that ranks produced by Pyramids and ranks produced by the Jensen-Shannon measure correlate, even if the query was not taken into account in the evaluation, i.e. if the task of guided summarization is reduced to that of generic summarization.<sep> However, we can study the effect of the measure J S in a real multi-document generic summary task by referring to task 2 of DUC'04, which we do here. We are also interested in other types of summaries such as biographical summary (DUC'04 task 5), opinion summary (TAC'08 OS) and summary in languages other than English.<sep> In this paper we present a series of experiments aimed at a better understanding of the value of the Jensen-Shannon divergence for ranking summarization systems.<sep> We have carried out experimentation with the proposed measure and have verified that in certain tasks (such as those studied by (Louis and Nenkova, 2009)) there is a strong correlation among Pyramids and Responsiveness and the Jensen-Shannon divergence, but as we will show in this paper, there are datasets in which the correlation is not so strong.<sep> We also present experiments in Spanish and French showing positive correlation between the Jensen-Shannon measure and ROUGE.<sep> The rest of the paper is organized in the following way: First in Section 2 we introduce related work in the area of content-based evaluation identifying the departing point for our inquiry; then in Section 3 we explain the methodology adopted in our work and the tools and resources used for experimentation.<sep> In Section 4 we present the experiments carried out and the results obtained on the different corpora and tasks.<sep> Section 5 discusses the results and Section 6 concludes the paper.<sep> 2 State of the art<sep> Donaway et al. (2000) is one of the first works to mention the use of content-based measures. It presented a method of evaluating automatic summary systems using recall and cosine-based distance calculations between the text and the summary produced.<sep> The latter calculation is clearly a content-based measure.<sep> They showed that there was weak correlation between rankings produced by recall, but that content-based measures produce rankings which were strongly correlated, thus paving the way for content-based measures in text summarization evaluation.<sep> Saggion et al. (2002) presented a set of evaluation measures based on the notion of vocabulary overlap that includes n-grams, cosine similarity and longest common subsequence.<sep> They applied them to the multi-document automatic summary in English and Chinese.<sep> However, they did not evaluate the performance of these measures on different summarization tasks.<sep> Radev et al. (2003) also compared various evaluation measures based on vocabulary overlap.<sep> Although these measures were able to separate random from non-random systems, no clear conclusion was reached on the value of each of the measures studied.<sep> Nowadays, a widespread summarization evaluation framework is ROUGE (Lin and Hovy, 2003) which, as we have mentioned before, offers a set of statistics that compare peer summaries with models.<sep> Various statistics exist depending on the used n -gram and on the type of text processing applied to the input texts (e.g., lemmatization, stopword removal).<sep> Lin et al. (2006) proposed a method of evaluation based on the use of “distances” or divergences between two probability distributions (the distribution of units in the automatic summary and the distribution of units in the model summary).<sep> They studied two different Information Theoretic measures of divergence: the Kullback-Leibler ( KL ) (Kullback and Leibler, 1951) and Jensen-Shannon ( J S ) (Lin, 1991a) divergences.<sep> The Jensen-Shannon ( J S ) divergence is defined as follows:<sep> This measure can be applied to the distribution of units in system summaries P and reference summaries Q and the value obtained used as a score for the system summary.<sep> The method has been tested by (Lin et al., 2006) over the DUC 2002 corpus for single and multi document summarization tasks showing good correlation among divergence measures and both coverage and ROUGE rankings.<sep> Louis and Nenkova (2009) went even further and, as in (Donaway et al., 2000), proposed to directly compare the distribution of words in full documents with the distribution of words in automatic summaries to derive a content-based evaluation measure.<sep> They found high correlation among rankings produced using models and rankings produced without models.<sep> This work is the starting point for our research into the value of measures that do not rely on human models.<sep> 3 Methodology<sep> The methodology of this paper mirrors the one adopted in past work (Donaway et al., 2000; Louis and Nenkova, 2009).<sep> Given a particular summarization task T , a set of p textual specifications: {Ii}i[p] =0 [−][1] (e.g. document(s), questions, topics) to guide the produced summaries, s candidate summaries { SUM i,k}[s] k =0 per input [ i] , and [m] reference summaries {[REF] [i,j]}mj =0 per input i , we will compare rankings of the s peer summaries produced by various evaluation measures.<sep> Some measures are used to compare automatic summaries with n out of the m human references:<sep> while other measures compare the candidate abstracts with the input or part of the input:<sep> where Ii′ is some subset of input [I][i] .<sep> The values produced by the measures for each summary SUM i,k are averaged for each system k = 0 , … , s − 1 and these averages are used to produce a ranking.<sep> Rankings are compared using Spearman Rank correlation (Spiegel and Castellan, 1998) used to measure the degree of association between two variables whose values are used to rank objects.<sep> We chose to use this correlation to directly compare results to those presented in (Louis and Nenkova, 2009).<sep> The calculations of correlations were done using the Statistics-RankCorrelation-0.12[1] software, which computes the rank correlation between two vectors.<sep> We also verified the good conformity of these results with the Kendall's τ correlation test calculated with the R statistical software.<sep> The two non-parametric tests of Spearman and Kendall are really only distinguished by the treatment of ties.<sep> The good correspondence between the two tests shows that they do not introduce any bias in our analyses.<sep> In the following we will only mention the ρ of Sperman, which is more widely used in this field.<sep> 3.1 Tools<sep> The experiments were carried out using a new summary evaluation system: FRESA – FRamework for Evaluating Summaries Automatically – which includes document-based summary evaluation measures based on probability distribution.<sep> As in the ROUGE package, FRESA uses n-grams and skip n-grams in the calculation of probability distributions.<sep> The FRESA environment can be used in the evaluation of summaries in English, French, Spanish and Catalan, and it integrates filtering and lemmatization in the treatment of summaries and documents.<sep> It is developed in Perl and made available to the community.<sep> We also use the ROUGE package to compute various ROUGE statistics in new datasets.<sep> 3.2 Summarization Tasks and Data Sets<sep> We have conducted our experimentation with the following summarization tasks and data sets:<sep> 1. Generic multi-document summary in English (i.e. production of a short summary of a cluster of related documents) using data from DUC 2004[3] corpus task 2: 50 clusters (10 documents each) – 294,636 words.<sep> Focused-based summarization in English (i.e. production a short focused multi-document summary focused on the question “who is X?”, where X is a person’s name) using data from the DUC 2004 task 5: 50 clusters ( 10 documents each plus a target person name) – 284,440 words.<sep> 3. Update-summarization task that consists of creating a summary out of a cluster of documents and a topic.<sep> Two sub-tasks are considered here: A) an initial summary has to be produced based on an initial set of documents and topic; B) an update summary has to be produced from a different (but related) cluster assuming documents used in A) are known.<sep> The English TAC 2008 Update Summarization dataset is used which consists of 48 topics with 20 documents each – 36,911 words.<sep> 4. Opinion summary where systems summarize the opinions about a target in a set of blog articles.<sep> The TAC 2008 Opinion Summarization in English[4] data set (taken from the Blogs06 Text Collection) is used: 25 clusters and targets (i.e., target entity and questions) were used – 1,167,735 words.<sep> 5. Generic single-document summary in Spanish, Medicina Clínica[5] corpus composed of 50 biomedical articles, each with its corresponding author abstract, 124,929 words.<sep> 6. Generic single document summary in French, reviewed by Perspectives interdisciplinaires sur le travail et la santé (PISTES)[6] ;<sep> It contains 50 sociological articles in French with their corresponding author abstracts – 381,039 words. 7. Multi-document generic summary in French, corpus RPM2[7] (journalistic);<sep> 20 different themes composed of 10 articles and 4 summary references per theme, 185,223 words.<sep> For experimentation in the TAC and the DUC datasets we directly use the candidate summaries produced by systems participating in the evaluations (official data).<sep> For experimentation in Spanish and French (single-document and multi-document summaries), we have created summaries at the compression rates of the model summaries using the following summarization systems:<sep> - CORTEX (Torres-Moreno et al., 2002), a single-document sentence extraction system for Spanish and French that combines various statistical measures of relevance (angle between sentence and topic, various Hamming weights for sentences, etc.) and applies an optimal decision algorithm for sentence selection; - ENERTEX (Fernandez et al., 2007), a summarizer based on a theory of textual energy;<sep> - SUMMTERM (Vivaldi et al., 2010), a terminology-based summarizer that is used for summarization of medical articles and uses specialized terminology for scoring and ranking sentences;<sep> - REG (Torres-Moreno & Ramirez, 2010), a summary system based on a greedy algorithm;<sep> - JS summarizer, a summarization system that scores and ranks sentences according to their Jensen-Shannon divergence to the source document;<sep> - Baseline-first sentences, which selects the first sentences of the document to build summaries;<sep> - Random-based, selects sentences at random to build summaries;<sep> - the multilingual word-frequency Open Text Summarizer (Yatsko and Vishnyakov, 2007);<sep> - the commercial multi-language summary systems Word, SSSummarizer[8] , Pertinence[9] and Copernic[10] .<sep> 3.4 Evaluation Measures<sep> The following measures derived from human assessment of the content of the summaries are used in our experiments:<sep> - Coverage: the amount of information shared between a candidate summary and a reference summary (Over et al., 2007).<sep> It was used in DUC evaluations.<sep> - Responsiveness ranks summaries in a 5-point scale indicating how well the summary satisfied a given information need (Over et al., 2007).<sep> It is used in focused-based summarization tasks, as was the case in some tasks of the DUC and TAC campaigns.<sep> - PYRAMIDS: it checks that the essential information units (as found in human-generated reference abstracts) are present in the candidate abstracts.<sep> Pyramids is the adopted metric for content-based evaluation in the TAC evaluations.<sep> For DUC and TAC datasets the values of these measures are available and we used them directly.<sep> In our experiments we used the following automatic evaluation measures: - ROUGE: recall metric that uses n-grams as content units to compare candidate summaries vs. those of reference.<sep> The ROUGE equation specified in (Lin, 2004) is as follows:<sep> where R is the summary to be evaluated, M is the set of model (human) summaries, countmatch is the number of common n-grams in m and P, and count is the number of n-grams in the model summaries.<sep> For the experiments presented here we used uni-grams, bigrams, and the skip bi-grams with maximum skip distance of 4 (ROUGE-1, ROUGE-2 and ROUGE-SU4).<sep> ROUGE is used to compare a candidate summary to a set of model summaries in our framework.<sep> - Jensen-Shannon divergence formula given in Equation 1 is implemented in our FRESA package with the following specification for the probability distribution of words w .<sep> Where P is the probability distribution of words w in text T and Q is the probability distribution of words w in summary S ; N is the number of words in text and summary<sep> N = NT + NS , B = 1 . 5 |V | , Cw[T] is the number of words in the text and Cw[S] is the number of words in the summary.<sep> For smoothing the summary’s probabilities we have used δ = 0 . 005.<sep> We have also implemented other smoothing methods (e.g., Good-Turing Manning & Schütze (1999) which uses the Perl statistics smoothing package Statistics-Smoothing-SGT-2.1.2[11]) in FRESA, but we do not use them in the experiments reported here.<sep> Similar to the ROUGE approach, in addition to uni-grams of words we have used bi-grams and skip bi-grams for the calculation of divergences such as J S (using uni-grams), J S 2 (using bi-grams), J S 4 (using skip bi-grams of ROUGESU4) and J S M which is the mean of J S i .<sep> J S measures are used to compare the candidate abstracts to its source document(s) in our framework.<sep> 4 Experiments and Results<sep> First, we replicated the experiments presented in (Louis and Nenkova, 2009) to verify that our implementation of JS produced correlation results compatible with that work.<sep> We used the TAC 2008 Update Summarization data set and computed JS and ROUGE measures for each peer summary.<sep> We produced two system rankings (one for each measure), which were compared to rankings produced using the manual Pyramids and Responsiveness scores.<sep> Spearman correlations were computed among the different rankings.<sep> The results are presented in Table 1 with their p-value[12] .<sep> These results confirm a high correlation among Pyramids, Responsiveness, and JS .<sep> We also verified high correlation between JS and ROUGE-2 (0 . 83 Spearman correlation, not shown in the table) in this task and dataset.<sep> Then, we experimented with data from DUC 2004 and TAC 2008 Opinion Summarization pilot and with single document summarization in Spanish and French.<sep> In spite of the fact that the experiments for French and Spanish corpora use less data points (i.e., less summarizers per task) than for English, results are still quite significant.<sep> For DUC 2004, we computed the JS measure for each peer summary in tasks 2 and 5 and we used JS and the official ROUGE, coverage, and Responsiveness scores to produce systems’ rankings.<sep> The various Spearman’s rank correlation values for DUC 2004 are presented in Tables 2 (for task 2) and 3 (for task 5).<sep> For task 2, we have verified a strong correlation between JS and coverage.<sep> For task 5, the correlation between JS and coverage is weak, and the correlation between JS and Responsiveness weak and negative.<sep> Although the Opinion Summarization task is a new type of summarization task and its evaluation is a complicated issue, we have decided to compare JS rankings with those obtained using Pyramids and Responsiveness in TAC 2008.<sep> Spearman’s correlation values are listed in Table 4.<sep> As can be seen, there is weak and negative correlation of JS with both Pyramids and Responsiveness.<sep> The correlation between Pyramids and Responsiveness rankings is high for this task (0.71 Spearman’s correlation value).<sep> For experimentation in Spanish and French, we have run 11 multi-lingual summarization systems over each of the documents in the two corpora, producing summaries at a compression rate close to the compression rate of the provided authors’ abstracts.<sep> We have computed JS and ROUGE measures for each summary and we have averaged the measure’s values for each system.<sep> These averages were used to produce rankings per each measure.<sep> We computed Spearman’s correlations for all pairs of rankings.<sep> Results are presented in Tables 5-6.<sep> All results show medium to strong correlation between JS and ROUGE measures.<sep> However the JS measure based on uni-grams has lower correlation than the one using n -grams of higher order.<sep> TAB. 1 – Spearman correlation, informativeness measures, TAC’08 Update Summarization<sep> TAB. 2 – Spearman correlation, J S and RED measures vs. Coverage, DUC’04 task 2<sep> TAB. 3 – Spearman’s correlation, J S and ROUGE vs. Responsiveness and Coverage, DUC’04 task 5<sep> TABLE 4 – Spearman correlation, J S vs. Responsiveness and PYRAMIDS, TAC’08 OS<sep> 5 Discussion<sep> The departing point for our inquiry into text summarization evaluation has been recent work on the use of content-based evaluation metrics that do not rely on human models but that compare summary content to input content directly (Louis and Nenkova, 2009).<sep> We have some positive and some negative results regarding the direct use of the full document in content-based evaluation.<sep> We have verified that in both generic and topic-based multi-document summarization in English, the correlation among measures that use human models (Pyramids, Responsiveness, and ROUGE) and a measure that does not use models (the Jensen Shannon divergence) is strong.<sep> We have found that correlation among the same measures is weak for summarization of biographical information and summarization of opinions in blogs.<sep> We believe that in these cases content-based measures should consider in addition to the input document, the summarization task (i.e. its text-based representation) to better assess the content of the peers, the task being a determinant factor in the selection of content for the summary.<sep> Our multi-lingual experiments in generic single-document summarization confirm a strong correlation among the Jensen-Shannon divergence and ROUGE measures.<sep> It is worth noting that ROUGE is in general the chosen framework for presenting content-based evaluation results in non-English summarization.<sep> For the experiments in Spanish, we are aware that we only have one reference summary to compare with the candidate summaries.<sep> Nevertheless, these references are the abstracts written by the authors.<sep> As the experiments in (da Cunha et al., 2007) show, the professionals of a specialized domain (as, for example, the medical domain) adopt similar strategies to summarize their texts and they tend to choose roughly the same content chunks for their summaries.<sep> Previous studies have shown that it is possible to accurately paraphrase the content of a text from author abstracts (Chuah, 2001).<sep> Because of this, the summary of the author of a medical article can be taken as reference for summaries evaluation.<sep> In the French corpus PISTES, we suspect the situation is similar to the Spanish case.<sep> TAB. 5 – Spearman correlation, J S vs. RED, mono-document corpus Medicina Clínica (Spanish)<sep> TAB. 6 – Spearman correlation, measures J S vs. ROUGE, mono-document corpus PISTES (French)<sep> Table 7: Spearman system rank correlation of content-based measures with ROUGE in the RPM2 Corpus (French)<sep> 6 Conclusions and Future Work<sep> In this article, we have studied the validity of the measures of evaluation of the content of summaries without the use of reference summaries.<sep> It should be noted that there is debate about the number of references to use when evaluating abstracts (Owkzarzak & Dang, 2009).<sep> We have carried out extensive experimentation with different summarization tasks from generic single document summary to summary of opinions.<sep> The main contributions of this paper are as follows:<sep> - We have shown that if we are only interested in ranking summarization systems according to the content of their automatic summaries, there are tasks where references could be substituted by the full document in the computation of the Jensen-Shannon divergence measure obtaining reliable rankings.<sep> However, we have also found that the substitution of references by full documents is not always advisable.<sep> We have found weak correlation among different rankings in complex summarization tasks such as the summarization of biographical information and the summarization of opinions about an “entity”.<sep> - We have also carried out large-scale experiments in Spanish and French which show positive medium to strong correlation among system’s ranks produced by ROUGE and divergence measures that do not use the model summaries.<sep> - We have presented the results of the FRESA system, for the calculation of measures based on Jensen-Shannon divergence.<sep> Following the ROUGE approach, FRESA implements word uni-grams, bi-grams and skip n - grams for the computation of divergences.<sep> Many other developments and experiments are possible.<sep> In order to verify correlation between ROUGE and JS , in the short term we intend to extend our investigation to other languages and datasets such as Portuguese and Chinese for which we have access to data and summarization technology.<sep> We also plan to apply our evaluation framework to the rest of the DUC and TAC summarization tasks.<sep> In the long term we plan to incorporate a representation of the task/topic in the computation of the measures.<sep> To carry out all these comparisons, however, we are dependent on the existence of references, without which we cannot measure the proximity between automatic summaries and human performance.<sep> Finally, FRESA will be used in the new Question Answering (QA) task of the INEX campaign (http://www.inex.otago.ac.nz/tracks/qa/qa.asp) for the evaluation of long answers.<sep> This task consists of answering an encyclopedic-type question by extracting and agglomerating sentences from Wikipedia.<sep> This type of text and question is similar to those in the tasks for which we found high levels of correlation between the JS and human-rater measures.<sep> Furthermore, the calculation of the divergence will be made between the summaries produced and a representative set of relevant passages from Wikipedia.<sep> FRESA will be used to compare three types of systems applied to the same task: query-driven multi-document summarizers, focused IR systems and QA systems.<sep> Acknowledgements.<sep> Horacio Saggion is grateful to the Programa Ramón y Cajal from the Ministerio de Ciencia e Innovación, Spain and to a Comenc¸a grant from Universitat Pompeu Fabra (COMENC¸ A10.004). This work is partially supported by a postdoctoral grant (National Program for Mobility of Research Human Resources; National Plan of Scientific Research, Development and Innovation 2008-2011) given to Iria da Cunha by the Ministerio de Ciencia e Innovación, Spain.<sep> 1 CPAN, http://search.cpan.org/~gene/Statistics-RankCorrelation-0.12/<sep> 2 Available at: http://lia.univ-avignon.fr/fileadmin/axes/TALNE/Ressources.html<sep> 3 http://www-nlpir.nist.gov/projects/ duc/guidelines/2004.html<sep> 4 http://www.nist.gov/tac/data/index. html<sep> 5 http://www.elsevier.es/revistas/ ctl servlet? f=7032&revistaid=2<sep> 6 http://www.pistes.uqam.ca/<sep> 7 http://labs.sinequa.com/rpm2/ 8 http://www.kryltech.com/summarizer.htm<sep> 9 http://www.pertinence.net<sep> 10 http://www.copernic.com/en/products/summarizer<sep> 11 CPAN, http://search.cpan.org/~bjoernw/Statistics-Smoothing-SGT-2.1.2/<sep> In statistics, the p-value is the smallest level at which the null hypothesis is rejected.
Development of resources for Persian: morphological lexicon and surface processing chain<sep> Abstract<sep> We introduce PerLex, a large-coverage and freely-available morphological lexicon for the Persian language.<sep> We describe the main features of the Persian morphology, and the way we have represented it within the Alexina formalism, on which PerLex is based.<sep> We focus on the methodology we used for constructing lexical entries from various sources, as well as the problems related to typographic normalisation.<sep> The resulting lexicon shows a satisfying coverage on a reference corpus and should therefore be a good starting point for developing a syntactic lexicon for the Persian language.<sep> 1. Introduction<sep> Most Natural Language Processing (NLP) tasks such as part-of-speech tagging, shallow or deep parsing and natural language generation, as well as most NLP applications such as data mining, information extraction, or automatic translation require or strongly benefit from the availability of large-scale lexical resources and quality surface processing.<sep> Among the lexical resources, morphological lexicons are the most basic yet the most needed resources.<sep> They associate a lemma and a morphosyntactic tag with each inflected form (or form, in short).<sep> However, for at least two reasons, such resources are virtually available only for a restricted set of welldescribed languages.<sep> First, many languages are resource-scarce, and even when there are resources for these languages, they are often limited in coverage.<sep> Second, existing lexical resources are not always freely available, although experience shows that free availability is the fastest way to high-quality resources.<sep> Surface treatments, on the other hand, cover all the operations that can be carried out on raw text to extract as much information as possible without resorting to syntactic analysis.<sep> They can therefore be implemented as such or as a preliminary to a syntactic or even semantic analysis.<sep> Tasks that are generally considered to be part of surface-level processing include spelling correction, compound word identification, and recognition of the many types of named entities in a broad sense (from names of people to URLs, addresses, and dates).<sep> Among these tasks, many benefit from the availability of lexical information, particularly morphological information.<sep> Conversely, a chain of surface treatments allows the implementation of effective protocols for improving lexical resources.<sep> In this paper, we introduce PerLex, a large-scale and freely available morphological lexicon for the Persian language, which was already presented at the LREC conference in May 2010 (Sagot & Walther, 2010), as well as a Persian version of the SXPipe surface processing chain (Sagot & Boullier, 2008).<sep> After a brief state of the art of automatic processing of Persian (section 2), we present in section 3 some characteristics of this language, and in particular its morphology.<sep> We then present the Alexina framework that underlies the PerLex lexicon (section 4) and our description in this framework of Persian morphology (section 5). We describe the methodology of construction of PerLex and the lexicon obtained in section 6.<sep> Finally, we present in section 7 the work done in SXPipe to enable processing of Persian, as well as a sense of the coverage rate of PerLex[1].<sep> 2. Automatic processing of Persian: state of the art<sep> The first automatic processing project of importance on Persian language is the Shiraz project, targeted towards Persian to English automatic translation (Amtrup et al., 2000).<sep> It resulted, among others, in the construction of a 50,000 terms bilingual lexicon,[1] based in part on a unification-based description of the Persian morphology (Megerdoomian, 2000), later redesigned for using the Xerox finite-state machinery (Megerdoomian, 2004).<sep> Apart from the work related to the Shiraz project, some other NLP tools, such as morphological tools and lemmatisers, have been developed. Yet they have not led to the construction of a large-scale lexicon.<sep> Among those works are those of Dehdari & Lonsdale (2008), especially their freely available lemmatiser PerStem.[2]<sep> In recent years, various NLP tools and resources have been developed for Persian processing. These are mostly focused on designing part-of-speech taggers (QasemiZadeh and Rahimi, 2006; Tasharofi et al., 2007; Shamsfard and Fadaee, 2008), parsers (Hafezi, 2004; Dehdari and Lonsdale, 2008) or automatic translation systems (Feili and Ghassem-Sani, 2004; Saedi et al., 2009).<sep> 3. The Persian Language<sep> The Persian language is an Indo-European language of the Indo-Aryan family, and more precisely of the Western Iranian group. Persian is characterized by a relatively fixed SOV word order.<sep> It is spoken by around 130 million people, mainly in Iran, Afghanistan and Tajikistan and Uzbekistan but also in Pakistan, Bahrain, Iraq, Kazakhstan and the Iranian diaspora.<sep> 3.1. Persian Script and Transliteration<sep> Persian is written from right to left and uses a modified version of the Arabic script. Some characters have been added, others are not used and some show a slightly modified shape.<sep> As in Arabic, the short vowels are not transcribed and there is no difference between capital and lower case letters.<sep> Moreover, two adjacent characters may either be joined (that is written with one uninterrupted line, possible only with some letters) or juxtaposed (that is following each other directly yet without being joined) or separated by a white space.<sep> Depending on whether a given character is joined to or isolated from its adjacent characters, this same character can adopt up to four different shapes.<sep> Therefore, encoding these characters within Unicode can be done in two different ways: either one directly uses the appropriate contextual character which represents the exact shape a given character has to adopt in that one given context (left- or right-joined or not), or one resorts to the use of generic characters whose shape automatically varies according to the context.<sep> Using contextual characters has however become obsolete nowadays since they do not allow for the representation of each character by one unique character.<sep> Using the generic character therefore sometimes requires the insertion of zero-width non-joiners ( ZWNJ ) between two characters to indicate that in a particular case they must not be joined whereas otherwise they could.<sep> Indeed, in Persian, some affixes are written attached but not joined to the morpheme to which they belong, even if this attachment brings two characters closer that would otherwise be separated.<sep> Some of the resources we developed during on our work is based on a transliteration of Persian into Latin characters.<sep> We have adopted the bijective transliteration system which has been developed within the PerGram project and which has a version solely based on characters that can be found within the ISO-8859-2 (or Latin-2) encoding.<sep> The advantage is that one can then use without problem tools that only handle 8-bit representations, i.e., representations for which the typographic and electronic notions of character coincide.[4]<sep> In addition to a transliteration tool that switches Persian characters to the corresponding Latin characters in one direction or the other, we have developed two normalization tools.<sep> The first replaces any contextual character with the corresponding generic character, inserting zero-length spaces if necessary.<sep> The second one replaces any character that is not part of the strict Persian alphabet with its appropriate counterpart.<sep> 3.2. Persian Morphology in Brief<sep> Within Persian morphology, the nominal system is relatively simple.<sep> There is no case system, nor gender distinction (except for a few animate Arabic loanwords which take the feminine ending -e ).<sep> Persian shows but two number features, singular and plural, of which only the plural is marked by either the suffix -hâ (which works for all countable nouns) or, for some animated nouns only, the more formal suffix -ân , or one of the Arabic plural markers -ât , -un , -in etc. attaching solely to Arabic loanwords (Lazard et al., 2006).<sep> Persian also possesses a few broken plurals directly inherited with Arabic loanwords. But those plurals are no longer treated within morphology.<sep> Furthermore, there is also a specific enclitic particle, called Ezafe, which functions as a marker of dependence.<sep> It can mark both nouns and full noun phrases as modified elements (Samvelian, 2007; Lazard et al., 2006).<sep> Moreover, Persian has an enclitic indefinite article -i which doesn't have separate forms for singular and plural; if it attaches to a noun modified by an adjective, it may either directly follow the noun or the adjective.<sep> Other enclitic particles in Persian are -i combined with the relative particle -ke , the optional definiteness marker -(h)e and the direct object postposition -râ .<sep> Adjectives only vary in degree by taking the suffixes -tar for the comparative and -tarin for the superlative form.<sep> But they can also take the Ezafe enclitic when following a further modified noun or taking a direct or indirect object.<sep> This last point especially holds for adjectives derived from verbal forms (Lazard et al., 2006).<sep> The simple verbs in Persian are very limited in number.<sep> They form a closed word class of about 200 elements. Most verbal meanings known from the more extensively described Indo-European languages are expressed through complex verbal predicates built from a light verbal head and a predicative element which can be either a noun or an adjective.<sep> Verbal morphology is slightly more complex but follows a rather simple pattern.<sep> It is usually admitted (Lazard et al., 2006) that there are two distinct verbal stems, one for the present tense forms (SI), one for the past tense forms (SII), the present participle, the gerund, the imperative and the infinitive.<sep> Compound tenses as well as the passive voice are derived from the past participle.<sep> The verbal paradigms of Persian are based on a prefix-root-suffix model.<sep> In this model, the possible prefixes are the two TAM prefixes [5] mi- and be- , the suffixes are the personal endings -am , -i , -ad/-e/ø , -im , -id/-in and -and/-an .<sep> These combinations generate seven different tensed forms for six different persons each, as well as five nominal verb forms to which the above mentioned enclitics can be attached.<sep> The negational prefixes n- or m- (more formal, used for the imperative only) can also be attached to the thereby created verb forms (Lazard et al., 2006).<sep> Moreover, Persian also has two distinct paradigms of the auxiliary verb "to be", one being constituted of full words, the other of enclitic forms that can be attached to nouns or adjectives, but also to the past participle form with which they form the paradigms of the perfect and the compound imperfect (Lazard et al., 2006).<sep> Finally, Persian also has pronominal suffixes which can combine with nouns, verbs, prepositions, adjectives and some adverbs (Lazard et al., 2006).<sep> 4. The Alexina Framework<sep> We developed the morphological lexicon PerLex within the Alexina framework (Sagot, 2010).<sep> This framework covers both the morphological and the syntactic level (e.g., valency), which shall be useful in further stages of PerLex development.<sep> Alexina allows for representing lexical information in a complete, efficient and readable way, that is meant to be independent of the language and of any grammatical formalism. It is compatible with the LMF standard[4] (Francopoulo et al., 2006).<sep> Numerous lexical resources exist within this framework, such as the Le fff , a large-coverage morphological and syntactic lexicon for French (Sagot et al. , 2006; Sagot, 2010), the Le ff e for Spanish, SoraLex for Sorani Kurdish, and lexical resources for Galician, Polish, Slovak and soon English.<sep> The Alexina model is based on a two-level representation that separates the description of a lexicon from its use: - The intensional lexicon factorises the lexical information by associating each lemma with a morphological class (defined in a formalised morphological description) and deep syntactic information; it is used for lexical resource development; - The extensional lexicon, which is generated automatically by compiling the intensional lexicon, associates each inflected form with a detailed structure that represents all its morphological and syntactic information; it is directly used by NLP tools such as parsers.<sep> 5. Formalising Persian Morphology<sep> Among the various enclitic particles listed in Section 3.2, not all shall be treated within morphology.<sep> In this matter, PerLex makes the following linguistically motivated choices (Samvelian, 2007): - plural markers, the Ezafe -(y)e (when it has a written counterpart), the indefinite marker -i , comparative and superlative markers -tar and -tarin , personal suffixes and enclitic forms of the auxiliary (except when used for building the perfect forms) are considered as inflectional suffixes, - combined with the relative ke , the enclitic particle -i forms a compound i ke that is agglutinated to the preceding form, - other enclitics, including the copula and the -râ definite direct object marker, are considered as independent (agglutinated) forms.<sep> Having in mind the linguistic choices mentioned in 3.2., we developed a complete description of Persian morphology in the Alexina morphological language (Sagot, 2007), based on the data in (Lazard et al., 2006).<sep> In this format, inflection is modelled as the affixation of a prefix and a suffix around a stem, while sandhi phenomena may occur at morpheme boundaries, sometimes conditioned by stem properties.<sep> Our description contains in particular 27 verb tables and 5 nouns tables.<sep> 6. The Construction of the PerLex Lexicon<sep> We gathered lexical information from various sources, the importance of which is variable among categories: - the BijanKhan corpus (BijanKhan, 2004; Amiri et al., 2007), an automatically POS-annotated corpus,<sep> - a lexicon of Persian nouns under development by M. Ghassemi at Université Paris-Est (Ghassemi, p.c.), - the reference grammar of (Lazard et al., 2006), - introspection by linguists who are native speakers of Persian.<sep> The lexical entries were created in three steps: 1. construction of lexical entries from the resources above; 2. cleaning of the entries obtained;<sep> 3. Manual addition of missing entries from the forms found in the BijanKhan corpus but not covered by the entries already constructed.<sep> Building a Base Lexicon<sep> Firstly, we developed and manually verified a list of verbal lemmas (infinitive form) from freely available online conjugators.<sep> We associated each of them with one (sometimes several) inflection class(es) from our morphological description.<sep> The Persian Wikipedia was used in the following way.<sep> We made an inventory of Wikipedia categories indicating an article concerning a person or a city.<sep> By collecting and normalising the titles of each article concerned, as well as the titles of all the articles redirecting towards them, we were able to build a lexicon of proper nouns consisting of person and city names which we completed with a list of country names found in the corresponding Wikipedia article.<sep> The result is a set of over 10,000 proper noun lemmas which all received a inflectional noun class that doesn’t allow for the formation of plural forms.<sep> A list of nominal lemmas was extracted from Ghassemi’s data.<sep> Some of them were already associated with their plural form.<sep> For others, a statistical look-up in the BijanKhan corpus allowed us to assign their corresponding plural form(s).<sep> Finally, we passed the BijanKhan corpus through our normalizer, and we extracted from the result other nominal entries, as well as entries for the other categories[9] . These entries, especially for the closed classes, were manually completed on the basis of (Lazard et al., 2006).<sep> We have assigned to all adjectival entries the unique flexional class of this category. For the remaining categories, all entries have been considered as invariable, except for some adverbs that may receive the indefinite marker -i , the Ezafe or personal suffixes.[10]<sep> 6.3. Cleaning the Base Lexicon<sep> At this stage, and despite the filtering mentioned in footnote 9, many lexical entries are incorrect, notably a significant proportion of those extracted from the BijanKhan corpus.<sep> This is an immediate consequence of the fact that the latter has been annotated automatically, that is with a nonzero error rate.<sep> We therefore removed a certain amount of lexical entries, especially all the nominal and adjectival entries that had been extracted from the BijanKhan corpus and looking like typical plural forms (that is that seemed to end in the plural suffix -hâ , followed or not by the Ezafe, the indefinite suffix or the personal suffixes).<sep> We also eliminated numerous entries which seemed to contain typographic errors, especially those whose ZWNJ had been omitted or replaced by a white space (such as the incorrect entries for the pronouns ân hâ and ânhâ instead of correct ân hâ ).<sep> Finally we suppressed all superfluous characters, although they were correctly taken into account by our tools (diacritic signs, etc.).<sep> The resulting base lexicon forms the first version of our morphological lexicon for the Persian language.<sep> Expanding the basic lexicon<sep> Once this first version of PerLex had been completed, we have searched the corpus for attested word forms that had not yet been taken into account by our lexicon.<sep> Of course, those forms may correspond to missing entries, incorrect entries, spelling errors or typographical errors.<sep> We therefore sorted them according to their frequency of apparition and manually completed the lexicon from the resulting list.<sep> The missing entries were mostly proper nouns belonging to categories other than those extracted from the Persian Wikipedia (continent names, names of different regions of Iran, etc.), and several broken plurals.<sep> However we were able to observe that a very large amount of unknown forms were in fact due to typographical errors that had not been spotted during the cleaning step.<sep> The obtained lexicon<sep> The resulting lexicon contains 35,914 intension entries (at the level of the lemma) that generate 524,700 extension entries (at the level of the form) for 494,488 distinct forms.<sep> Some additional information on the distribution of the speech is given in Table 1.<sep> Table 1: Quantitative data about PerLex<sep> 7 Surface treatments for Persian<sep> SXPipe In (Sagot & Boullier, 2008), the authors present SXPipe, a multilingual pipeline for surface processing that takes raw texts as input.<sep> SXPipe, originally developed for French, has since been extended to other languages.<sep> Before the work reported here, and in addition to French, SXPipe handled Spanish, English, Dutch, Polish, Slovak and Italian to varying degrees.<sep> SXPipe is used for French as a preliminary to various syntax analyzers, but also for various languages as such, for example for the detection of named entities, the correction and normalization of texts or the detection and attribution of verbatim quotes.<sep> The processing of a corpus by SXPipe can be broken down into six main stages: (1) typographical normalisation of the corpus (e.g. handling of encodings);<sep> (2) recognition of certain named entities in the raw text (URLs, dates, numbers, addresses, etc.);<sep> (3) segmentation of the raw text into tokens and sentences;<sep> (4) recognition of certain entities named at the level of tokens (foreign language sequences…);<sep> (5) non-deterministic grouping of tokens into forms (spelling correction and treatment of compounds and amalgams), which results in a graph of forms (TEXT2DAG tool);<sep> (6) recognition of certain entities named in the graph of shapes (numbers in full, names of people, places, organizations, etc.).<sep> Processing Persian in SXPipe<sep> Until now, SXPipe only handled languages using variants of the Latin alphabet.<sep> We have therefore adapted SXPipe, particularly at stage 1 and by adding a stage at the end of the chain, so that it can process languages using variants of the Arabic alphabet.<sep> In particular, we have added at the beginning of step 1 the normalization tools mentioned in section 3.1.<sep> We have also inserted our transliteration tool into the chain to allow modules that need it to process 8-bit text.<sep> This is the case of TEXT2DAG, for which we compiled a version for Persian from PerLex and (weighted) rules of spelling correction, some of which are specifically adapted to this language.[12]<sep> However, no work has yet been done to adapt the various named entity recognition modules.<sep> Only numbers written in figures are recognized, simply because the transliteration of numbers written in Persian gives precisely similar numbers to those encountered in French, which are therefore recognized by the corresponding module.<sep> Evaluating the coverage of PerLex The spelling correction and amalgam and compound recognition tool built for Persian makes it possible to distinguish between a token that is a true “unknown word” and a token that does not correspond to a known form in the lexicon but that can be analysed as amalgams of known forms in the lexicon.<sep> Thus, we were able to evaluate the coverage rate of PerLex on a large corpus.<sep> To do this, we converted the original BijanKhan corpus into a “raw” corpus, by reconstructing the sentences from the words that make them up, and by reattaching the punctuation marks to the words that precede them.<sep> We then tried to distinguish the tokens that could be analyzed, the tokens that contained residual typographical imperfections, and the tokens that corresponded to truly unknown words.<sep> The estimate we get is as follows: 97.0% coverage (96.2% of tokens analyzable and 0.8% of tokens correctable into analyzable tokens by typographical normalization), and 3% of tokens out of coverage.<sep> 8. Conclusion and Future Work<sep> We introduced the first version of PerLex, a morphological lexicon for the Persian language with a large coverage, as well as a Persian version of the surface processing chain SXPipe.<sep> PerLex is distributed under the free LGPL-LR license on the Alexina project's web page[13].<sep> SXPipe is distributed under the free LGPL license, as a sub-project of the Alpage Linguistic Chain, for example on the page of this project[14].<sep> For the moment, the PerLex lexicon is only morphological and requires a complete manual validation, which is currently underway within the Franco-German ANR/DFG PerGram project.<sep> In parallel, the addition of syntactic information (including subcategorisation frames) is underway for entries for simple verbs. The other categories will also have their entries completed with syntactic information.<sep> In parallel, PerLex will be extended for describing the important phenomenon of complex verbal predicates in Persian.<sep> Both these tasks shall be achieved by semi-automatic techniques already used for the development of other Alexina lexicons, and followed by a manual validation step.<sep> As for the SXPipe surface treatment chain, it only performs a portion of the tasks available for other languages on Persian, namely typographical normalization, romanization (if requested), recognition of a very limited number of types of named entities and spelling correction and recognition of compound words.<sep> The more standard named entities (names of people, places, organizations, but also dates, addresses, etc.) will have to be managed.<sep> But SXPipe already constitutes a viable chain, which we intend to complete with the morphosyntactic tagger MElt (Denis & Sagot, 2009) trained on the BijanKhan corpus and coupled with PerLex.<sep> This will improve the PerLex morphological lexicon using techniques such as those described in (Nicolas et al., 2008), for example.<sep> 1 The development of PerLex is part of a larger project called PerGram (Franco-German Project ANR/DFG MU 2822/3-1).<sep> The primary goal of PerGram is (1) to establish an HPSG modeling of a number of syntactic phenomena of Persian (such as that of complex predicates), (2) to implement an HPSG grammar covering the essentials of the linguistic phenomena of Persian and (3) to set up PerLex as a lexicon associated with this grammar and for which it is planned to include in the long term both morphological and syntactic information of lexemes. PerGram is a project jointly directed by Pollet Samvelian (Université Paris 3) and Stefan Müller (Freie Universität Berlin).<sep> 2 This lexicon doesn’t seem to be freely available.<sep> 3 http://sourceforge.net/projects/perstem/<sep> 4 For better readability, we use a more standard phonetic transcription here, which also includes short vowels. 5 Tense-Aspect-Mode. 6 In this article, we do not take into account the syntactic information, since our work concerns the construction of a morphological lexicon.<sep> 7 Transformations on the radical and/or the affix caused by the juxtaposition of the latter.<sep> Thus, in French, when the suffix -ons is juxtaposed with the root mang-, a sandhi phenomenon occurs which induces the insertion of an e.<sep> 8 The Persian Wikipedia is available online at the following URL http://fa.wikipedia.org.<sep> We used the extracted wiki version of February 16th 2010.<sep> 9 For lemmas with several categories in the BijanKhan corpus, we automatically discarded entries corresponding to categories that were assigned with a frequency below 1% among occurrences of this lemma.<sep> This reduces the amount of noise that comes from annotation errors in the corpus.<sep> In Persian, almost any adjective can be used as an adverb.<sep> Therefore, adverbial entries that corresponded to an adjectival entry for the same lemma were discarded.<sep> 11 The underscore (_) indicates a space of zero length.<sep> 12 No evaluation of this spell checker has been performed so far.<sep> 13 http://alexina.gforge.inria.fr<sep> 14 http://lingwb.gforge.inria.fr
Symbolic and statistical learning for chunking: comparison and combinations<sep> ABSTRACT<sep> In this paper, we describe the use of grammatical inference algorithms for the chunking task, and then compare and combine them with CRFs (Conditional Random Fields), which have proven to be effective for this task. Our corpus is extracted from the French Treebank.<sep> We then propose two distinct ways to combine both symbolic and statistical models learned by a CRF and show that in both cases they benefit from one another.<sep> 1 Introduction<sep> Supervised machine learning approaches, especially when they have access to huge amounts of data, have now extensively proved their effectiveness for a lot of text mining tasks like text classification, sentence annotation and information extraction.<sep> Most effective learning approaches rely on a theoretical background which is either optimization (SVM), statistics (Naive Bayes) or both (HMMs, MaxEnt models, CRFs).<sep> The main drawback of models produced by these methods is that they are difficult to read by humans.<sep> There also exists other branches of Machine Learning, referred to as symbolic , whose particularity is to provide a more human-readable output.<sep> The most illustrious members of this family are decision trees, Inductive Logic Programming (ILP) or Grammatical Inference (GI in the following).<sep> The latter is our main interest here.<sep> It can be defined as the study of how it is possible to automatically learn a formal grammar or any other device able to represent a language (such as an automaton, a regular expression…) from a sample of (possibly enriched) sequences known to belong (or not) to this language.<sep> This domain, which has its origins in theoretical computer science and formal language theory, is often not very well known.<sep> GI algorithms’ known drawback is their lack of efficiency on real data: they are often time consuming, sensitive to errors and do not behave well with large alphabets (for example alphabets containing every word of a natural language).<sep> In this article, we want to give some classical IG algorithms a chance to compete with the state of the art of statistical machine learning approaches, in this case CRF (Lafferty et al., 2001).<sep> The task we deal with for this purpose is chunking (Abney, 1991) for French, which can be done with hand-made automata (Antoine et al., 2008; Blanc et al., 2010).<sep> To our knowledge, trying to automatically learn these automata instead of writing them by hand has never been tested for any language before.<sep> On the other hand, chunking can also be treated as an annotation task (object of the Shared Task CoNLL'2000) and thus be approached by statistical machine learning methods.<sep> This context thus seemed to be the ideal playground on which both approaches can be fairly compared.<sep> But this comparison is not our only purpose.<sep> Our intuition is that both approaches are complementary, as they focus on very distinct properties of the dataset.<sep> We also provide in this article two distinct ways to combine them according to different purposes.<sep> The first one is effectiveness-oriented: it consists in enriching the CRF by automata-based features to improve again its effectiveness.<sep> The second strategy is readability-oriented: it consists in analyzing the behavior of an automaton produced by GI thanks to CRF-computed weights which are interpretable with respect to this automaton.<sep> The paper is organized as follows.<sep> In the first section, we introduce the task of chunking and describe the dataset we have used in all our experiments.<sep> The second section is dedicated to grammatical inference.<sep> After a brief review, we focus on the k-RI-algorithms (Angluin, 1982) and provide the best experimental results we could reach with them on the task.<sep> In the next section, we apply CRFs (Lafferty et al., 2001) to the same task.<sep> As expected, CRFs give far better results than those obtained by GI.<sep> In the last section, we describe and evaluate two ways to combine automata and CRFs.<sep> The results of both combinations are promising and suggest original trails to associate symbolic and statistical learning.<sep> 2 Chunking: the Task and the Data<sep> In this section, we describe the task of chunking as a labeling one and introduce the dataset we used for our experiments.<sep> The latter are a continuation of those presented in (Tellier et al., 2012).<sep> As our purpose is to build a chunker for French, our starting point is the French Treebank (Abeillé et al., 2003).<sep> 2.1 The Task<sep> The task of chunking, also called shallow parsing, consists in identifying elementary syntactic phrases.<sep> Chunks are indeed contiguous and non-recursive sequences of lexical units linked to a single strong head (Abney, 1991).<sep> Each chunk is characterized by the type (or syntactic category) of its unique head.<sep> So, there are as many different types of chunks as there are of considered heads.<sep> Chunking has been the target of the CoNLL shared task in 2000[1] , in which the training set was composed of about 9 000 English sentences taken from the Penn Treebank with two levels of annotation: a POS level provided by the Brill tagger and a chunk level.<sep> The winners used SVM and “Weighted Probability Distribution Voting”.<sep> The same corpus was used to show the effectiveness of CRFs (Sha and Pereira, 2003).<sep> 2.2 The Data<sep> The French Treebank (FT in the following) has been built from a collection of sentences extracted from articles of the French newspaper “Le Monde”, published between 1989 and 1993 (Abeillé et al., 2003).<sep> The sentences are tokenized (with respect to some multi-word units), lemmatized, tagged and parsed.<sep> There are several versions of the FTB, the one we have used contains about 8 600 XML trees, enriched by syntactic functions which were necessary to identify some chunks.<sep> For POS, we used the set of 30 morpho-syntactic tags defined by Crabbé and Candito (2008), thus ensuring continuity with our previous work (Constant et al., 2011).<sep> We consider 7 distinct types of chunks: AP (adjectival phrases), AdP (Adverbial phrases), CONJ, NP (noun phrases), PP (prepositional phrase), VP (verbal phrases) and UNKNOWN chunks (usually for those containing foreign words).<sep> Punctuation marks, except for exceptions (some quotes for example) are outside chunks (label O as Out).<sep> We have decided to modify certain choices we made in (Tellier et al., 2012). For example, the CONJ chunk only contains the conjunction token(s). The PP, on the other hand, always integrates the chunk introduced by the preposition. And, unlike (Paroubek et al., 2006), the epithetic adjectives are always part of the NP containing the noun they qualify, whether they appear before or after this noun.<sep> AP chunks are thus relatively rare, as they only concern detached adjectives (syntactic functions available in the XML trees are needed to identify some of them).<sep> L'exemple de phrase suivante illustre notre notion de parenthésage en chunks[2] : (la/DET dépréciation/NC) NP (par_rapport_au/P dollar/NC) PP (a/V été/VPP limitée/VPP) V P (à/P 2,5/DET %/NC) PP<sep> We extracted from the FT two distinct corpora: • a corpus where every distinct chunk is extracted and labeled with the BIO (Begin/In/Out) convention.<sep> Chunks are distributed according to the following proportions: PP: 33,86%, AdP: 7,23%, VP: 17,11%, AP: 2,21%, NP: 32,95%, CONJ: 6,61%, UNKNOWN: 0,03%.<sep> • a corpus where only NPs are labeled, every other token being considered as out (label O).<sep> This corpus is not a subpart of the previous one, as many PPs include an NP. These “hidden NPs” become visible in the second corpus only, as in the previous example:<sep> (la/DET dépréciation/NC) NP par_rapport_au/P (dollar/NC) NP a/V été/VPP limitée/VPP à/P (2,5/DET %/NC) NP<sep> 3 Grammatical inference<sep> Grammatical Inference (GI) is a very rich research domain which emerged in the 60s and thus has a long history which cannot be easily summed-up.<sep> We focus in this section on GI of automata from positive examples only .<sep> After a brief review, we describe the k-RI algorithms (Angluin, 1982) that we used in our experiments and the results we could reach with them.<sep> 3.1 Brief state of the art<sep> GI is the study of how it is possible to automatically learn a symbolic device able to represent a language (a formal grammar, an automaton…) from a sample of (possibly enriched) sequences known to belong (or not) to this language (de la Higuera, 2010).<sep> When only sequences belonging to the target language are available, the problem is known as GI from positive examples .<sep> We are in this context because the sequences available to us do not contain any counter-example.<sep> This problem is much harder than when negative examples are available, because it is very difficult to avoid overgeneralization .<sep> Ultimately, if a learning program hypothesizes that the language to be learned is the universal one (Σ [∗] , where Σ is the alphabet of the language), no positive example can disprove it, even if it over-generalizes.<sep> The first concern of GI was to provide a precise definition of what it means for a program to be able to “learn a language by positive examples”.<sep> The criterion is theoretical and formal, not empirical.<sep> Let's draw a parallel with children's language acquisition.<sep> A child is not “programmed” to learn any specific language, (s)he is able to learn whatever language is spoken in his(her) environment.<sep> Similarly, a GI program by positive presentation must be able to learn a class of formal languages, that is to be able to identify any member of such a class, when they are provided with examples of sequences (phrases) belonging to this member.<sep> The main important "learnability criteria" (also called learning models) are known as "identification in the limit" (Gold, 1967) and "PAC learning" (Valiant, 1984), which we cannot describe here.<sep> Unfortunately, even for regular languages, the simplest class of the Chomsky hierarchy, those criteria are impossible to fulfill with positive examples only: there is no algorithm able to learn from positive examples the whole class of regular languages satisfying these criteria (Gold, 1967; Kearns and Vazirani, 1994).<sep> Researchers have thus tried to identify smaller or transverse classes in Chomsky’s hierarchy, which are learnable, as characterised in (Angluin, 1980).<sep> k-reversible languages (Angluin, 1982) are such classes, and were the starting point of our experiments.<sep> Since then, many other learnable subclasses have been described and studied (Garcia and Vidal, 1990; Denis et al., 2002; Kanazawa, 1998; Koshiba et al., 2000; Yokomori, 2003).<sep> Other advances in the domain concern the learnability of devices integrating probabilities, such as probabilistic automata and their links with HMMs (Thollard et al., 2000; Dupont et al., 2005).<sep> In parallel, competitions[4] allowed to test the effectiveness of the proposed algorithms when confronted with real data.<sep> 3.2 k-RI Algorithm<sep> In this section, we describe the GI algorithms used for our experiments.<sep> They are intended to learn an automaton for a specific type of chunk, from the different POS sequences appearing in this type of chunks in the training data.<sep> GI algorithms from positive examples seem adapted to this problem, as the considered vocabulary is limited (30 distinct tags at most) and the variability of the POS sequences that can describe a same chunk is relatively low.<sep> k-Reversible Inference ( k-RI) algorithm (Angluin, 1982) has the property of identifying in the limit any k-reversible language, for any fixed k ∈ N.<sep> K-reversible languages are regular, and therefore representable by finite automata.<sep> A finite automaton defines a k-reversible language if it is deterministic and its mirror[4] is deterministic with a look-ahead of k .<sep> When k = 0, a 0-reversible language can be represented by a deterministic DFA whose mirror is also deterministic, the algorithm being called Zero Reversible (ZR).<sep> If k 1 < k 2, the class of k 1-reversible languages is stricty included in the one of k 2-reversible lanugages.<sep> Given a set of positive sequences S, the first step of k-RI is to build PTA(S), the Prefix Tree Acceptor of S.<sep> PTA(S) is the smallest (in terms of number of states) DFA (Deterministic Finite Automata) in the form of a tree recognizing exactly the language defined by S.<sep> The root of PTA(S) is its initial state.<sep> The search space of a GI algorithm for a given training set S of positive examples is a lattice whose bottom element is PTA(S) and top element is the universal language built from the alphabet of the examples (Dupont et al., 1994).<sep> Most GI algorithms follow the same pattern: they start by building the PTA of the set of available positive examples, then try to generalize the recognized language by merging some of the states of this automaton.<sep> k-RI, detailed below, works according to this principle.<sep> The merging operation here is deterministic, as it propagates recursively through the automaton to preserve determinism.<sep> Algorithm k-RI<sep> In Figure 1, we illustrate how ZR behaves with the following set of positive examples of sequences of POS tags: S = {DET NC, DET ADJ NC} .<sep> On this example, we see that ZR already generalizes PTA(S) to output an automaton recognizing the language defined by the regular expression: DET ADJ[∗] NC .<sep> This generalization is linguistically relevant.<sep> But if we add to the previous positive sample the sequence made of NC alone, ZR will output an automaton recognizing the language {DET |ADJ}[∗] NC , which is a more doubtful generalization.<sep> Step 1: PTA(S) Step 1: mirror of PTA(S) Step 2: the final states of PTA(S) are merged (otherwise the mirror is not deterministic) Step 3: q 1 and q 2 are merged (otherwise the mirror is not deterministic) Figure 1: Step-by-step demonstration of ZR<sep> 3.3 GI Experience Results on NP Chunking<sep> We applied k-RI for different values of k ( k = 0 , k = 1 , k = 2) on POS tags sequences matching NP chunks in the corpus of NP chunks only.<sep> BIO annotations are obtained by using the learned automata as regular expressions according to a sequential path of the sentence.<sep> We have tried to recognize either the longest sequences (“Longest Match”, LM) or the shortest sequences (“Shortest Match”, SM).<sep> The labelling in NP alone is the task for which GI is the most appropriate.<sep> It is also possible to learn a distinct automata for each type of chunk. But the application of several distinct automata on new data poses a problem of frontier covering.<sep> Therefore, we only use them in combination with a statistical model, in section 5.<sep> ZR is really sensitive to the available data. A single incorrect sequence can force many states to merge.<sep> This is the case with our dataset from the FTB, where outliers or tagging errors are not absent.<sep> But some erroneous examples can be easily detected: for example, sequences of tags for a special kind on chunk which do not even contain any possible head tag of this chunk can be removed.<sep> We have considered various other ways of cleaning the data.<sep> Cleaning that removes any sequence that occurs less than a fixed proportion was the most effective.<sep> This strategy nevertheless results in the loss of useful sequences, due to the low proportion of certain heads (clitics, for example).<sep> Our experiments were made following a 5-fold cross-validation protocol partitioning the data into five (4/5 for the learning of an automaton, 1/5 for the test).<sep> The equality required on chunks is strict, i.e. to be equal, they must share exactly the same frontiers.<sep> The precision, recall and F1-measure of NP-chunks are computed without taking into account O labels.<sep> Table 1 contains various F-measures that we managed to obtain by grammatical inference on NP chunks only, with a longest match strategy.<sep> Cleaned versions are obtained by deleting every POS sequence that appeared strictly less than 0.01%.<sep> Values between parentheses are the average number of states of the 5 automata calculated during the learning phase.<sep> PTA versions, whose performances are sometimes good, can be seen as “learning by heart” devices, as they are not generalized.<sep> Automata of size 1 are those, probably overgeneralized, that recognize the universal language of POS tags present at least once in NP chunks.<sep> k ≥ 2 is necessary to obtain an automaton behaving better than the PTA on cleaned data.<sep> Table 1: GI results for NP chunking<sep> 4 Statistical learning for annotation<sep> In this section, we focus on the best up-to-date statistical approach to perform an annotation task: Conditional Random Fields (or CRFs), which work very well on our problem (Tellier et al., 2012).<sep> We also recall how some HMMs can be “transformed” into a CRF, as this transformation will be a source of inspiration for one of the combinations presented later.<sep> 4.1 Conditional Random Fields and HMMs<sep> CRFs have been introduced by Lafferty et al. (2001). They belong to the family of graphical models.<sep> When the graph expressing the dependencies between labels is linear (which is most often the case when labelling sequences), the probability distribution of the annotation sequence y associated with the input sequence x is expressed by:<sep> Where Z ( x ) is a normalization factor depending on x and the K features (or characteristic functions) fk are provided by the user.<sep> The feature fk is activated (i.e. fk ( t, yt, yt− 1 , x ) = 1) if a configuration occurring at the current position t in the sequence, concerning yt , yt− 1 (i. e. the values of the annotation at the positions t and t − 1) and x is observed.<sep> Each feature fk is associated with a weight λk which are the parameters of the model, to be estimated during the learning step.<sep> To define a large set of features, software implementing CRFs allow the use of templates which are instantiated into as many features as there are positions in the training data where they can apply.<sep> The most current efficient implementation of linear CRFs is Wapiti[5] , which uses a L1 penalization allowing to select the best features during the learning step (Lavergne et al., 2010).<sep> It is the software we have used.<sep> CRFs have been applied with great success to various annotation tasks, among which POS labeling (Lafferty et al., 2001), named entity recognition (McCallum and Li, 2003), chunking (Sha and Pereira, 2003) and even full parsing (Finkel et al., 2008; Tsuruoka et al., 2009).<sep> Their main drawback is that they appear as “black boxes”.<sep> A CRF model is simply characterized by a list of weighted features that can contain several million elements, which makes it difficult to interpret.<sep> Table 2: The template boss and the results obtained with CRF alone for each task<sep> HMMs, which were the previous state of the art for annotation tasks, have the merit to be more understandable.<sep> However, every discrete HMM can be “transformed” into a CRF model defining exactly the same probability distribution (Sutton and McCallum, 2006; Tellier and Tommasi, 2011).<sep> To do this, for a given HMM, we must define two families of features: • features of the form f ( yt, xt ) associating an individual label yt with an individual input xt : they correspond to the states yt of the HMM where xt can be emitted; • features of the form f ( yt− 1 , yt ) corresponding to the transitions of the HMM linking the states yt− 1 and yt .<sep> they are worth 1 when the transition between these two states is used.<sep> If θ is a probability of emission or of transition of the HMM, then choose λ = log ( θ ) as the weight of the corresponding feature in the CRF.<sep> The computation of p ( y|x ) then writes exactly the same in both cases.<sep> A HMM can thus be seen as a special case of CRF.<sep> But CRFs are more general because they allow features to be more general than those used in this transformation.<sep> This correspondence inspired us to use CRFs to diagnose automata learned by IG.<sep> This idea will be studied in section 5.<sep> But before, we present the results obtained with CRF alone on our data.<sep> 4.2 Experimental Results<sep> Tables 2 shows the feature templates and results obtained by using CRFs alone on both chunking tasks.<sep> For these experiments, as in section 3.3, we followed a 5-fold cross-validation protocol and a strict criterion of chunk equality.<sep> For the complete chunking task, we computed both the micro-average of F-measures (i.e. the average of the F-measures of every kind of chunk weighted by their proportions) and their macro-average (i.e. without any weight).<sep> As expected, CRFs alone provide excellent results.<sep> It is to be noted that they use words in their features along with POS tags, while GI algorithms have only access to the latter.<sep> These results can be compared with those obtained during the PASSAGE campaign (Paroubek et al., 2006), even if the notions of chunks adopted on both sides differ (in PASSAGE, epithet adjectives located after a noun are not part of the nominal chunk, for example) and if the corpora are not the same.<sep> The best participants in the PASSAGE campaign achieved a micro-average of 92.7, which still places the performance of our CRFs.<sep> Table 3: Dataset Enriched by the Output of Specific Automata for Each Chunk<sep> 5 Combinations<sep> In the previous sections, we have applied either pure symbolic learning or pure statistical learning to the task of chunking.<sep> In this section, we want to combine both strategies. There are two different possible viewpoints for this combination:<sep> • if the only goal is performance, then we will favor statistical learning.<sep> However, the automata provided by our GI algorithms capture global (and not local, as is the case in features) relationships between POS tags of the same chunk that could be useful for a CRF.<sep> So, we can try to integrate the results of symbolic learning as an external resource of statistical learning.<sep> • if we stand from the viewpoint of readability, we will favor the automata produced by GI.<sep> As evoked in 4.1, it is possible to simulate a HMM (and, similarly, an automaton) with CRF’s features.<sep> We could therefore evaluate the quality of the states and transitions of an automaton according to the weights associated with the features that represent them in a CRF, thus offering a way to improve it.<sep> 5.1 Automata as an external resource<sep> We attack here both types of chunking.<sep> The first combination considered is to enrich the data of the CRF with attributes from the external resource, as in (Constant and Tellier, 2012).<sep> In the case of complete chunking, we applied GI on each distinct type of chunk, leading to as many automata as there are types of chunks. This is done according to a 5-fold cross-validation protocol (the PTAs in these experiments are therefore only extracted from the learning corpus).<sep> Each chunk-specific automaton provides an independent BIO tagging, as shown in Table 3. (The automata are assumed to provide perfect tagging here).<sep> Therefore, there are as many new attributes as there are types of chunks in our data.<sep> The left tables in Tables 4 and 5 give the templates used to obtain the best results (micro resp. macro-average resp. F-measure) for the complete chunking or the NP chunking.<sep> The lines “Automaton” take into account the output of each automaton independently, whereas “POS+Automata” represents the concatenation of POS columns along with the output of every single automaton.<sep> Matching results are given in the tables on the right.<sep> They show that attributes taken from automata allow to significantly improve the results of CRFs.<sep> This is particularly true for the macro-average, which gives equal importance to the F1-measure of each type of chunk.<sep> The information brought by the automata mostly improve the recognition of rare chunks.<sep> In the experiment leading to the best macro-average, the best improvements are the following: the F1-measure of UNKNOWN goes from 41.67 to 61.22, the one of AP from 96.78 to 97.44 and the one of AdP from 98.72 to 98.92.<sep> Table 4: Best micro-aver. for complete chunking Table 5: Best macro-aver. for complete chunking Table 6: Best F-measure for NP chunking<sep> 5.2 Evaluating an automaton by CRF-computed weights<sep> Here, we want to obtain information on the automaton produced by IG using CRF, by making a learning that only uses features interpretable relative to it.<sep> The weights associated by the CRF with these features will provide a fine diagnosis of the automaton.<sep> This idea is similar to (Roark and Saraclar, 2004), where a CRF was learned according to the structure of a weighted automaton to "correct" it using weight estimation.<sep> However, it differs in that we are not trying to obtain a weighted automaton but to find any possible modifications to be made to the automaton according to the diagnosis provided by the CRF, while preserving its purely symbolic nature.<sep> To illustrate our approach, we focus on the NP-only chunking task, because only one automaton is to be considered.<sep> It may be easier to understand the following by imagining deterministic finite automata (DFA) "à la Unitex" (http://www-igm.univ-mlv.fr/unitex/). Thus, the result of the ZR algorithm on Figure 1 (the final automaton, bottom right) is identical to that of Figure 2.<sep> This representation has the advantage of showing POS tags and transitions between two POS tags as two distinct objects.<sep> To build a CRF based on such an automaton, we consider the BIO labeling effect of this automaton, as in section 5.1<sep> Figure 2: Automate represented “à la Unitex”<sep> Inspired by the relationship between HMMs and CRFs mentioned in section 4.1, we define feature patterns which can be interpreted relatively to the automaton:<sep> • the unary feature-template only takes into account the current correct BIO NP-label together with the current POS tag and the current BIO label predicted by the automaton at the same position.<sep> The POS tag matches one (or multiple) state(s) of the automaton.<sep> If both BIO labels match for a given POS tag, then the automaton is somehow right to be in this state by analyzing the data.<sep> • the bigram feature-template only takes into account the current correct couple of BIO NP-labels together with the corresponding couple of consecutive POS tags as well as the corresponding couple of BIO automaton-predicted labels.<sep> The couple of POS tags characterize a (or several) transition(s) of the automata.<sep> If the corresponding two couples of BIO labels coincide, it means that the transition is correctly used.<sep> Note that words themselves are not taken into account in these patterns, in order to preserve the interpretation of the features relative to the automaton, hence the absence of words.<sep> Table 5 is a confusion matrix comparing “automata-generated” BIO labels (AL) with the corresponding correct BIO label (CL), for a given POS tag.<sep> We can build as many such tables as there are distinct POS tags in NP chunks, each cell corresponding to an unigram feature.<sep> The cells of Table 5 are filled with the weights learned by the CRF for the features in question, where the colors display how they can be interpreted with respect to the initial automaton.<sep> As expected, weights on the diagonal, meaning a correct tagging, are greater than those outside it, meaning a tagging error.<sep> Bigram features are a bit more complicated, but it is also possible to obtain interpretable confusion matrices.<sep> Table 5: A coloured confusion matrix for the DET tag (2-RI, Table 1)<sep> Table 8: Labeling results of the CRFs based on the best automata for NP-chunking<sep> Generally, the weight associated to a feature in a CRF represents its discriminative power .<sep> These weights are therefore much more relevant than simple occurrence counts of how many times the features are satisfied or not in the training data.<sep> The weights on the diagonals can thus be seen as evaluating the quality of the states/transitions of the automaton, while the weights in the other cells correspond to the gains obtained by taking a decision of labelling not recommended by the automaton.<sep> The whole set of confusion matrixes therefore offers an extremely fine and precise measure of the quality of the automaton.<sep> Table 6 recalls the best result obtained by the "pure" IG on the NP chunking of section 3.3 and gives the results of the CRFs constructed as previously on the best automaton produced by k-RI for each value of k .<sep> As expected, the CRFs built on NP automata are better than NP automata alone, but not as good as a CRF using more attributes and features.<sep> The results of the confusion matrices still need to be examined in detail. We hope to draw a precise diagnosis to analyze where and why the automata make good or bad decisions, and modify them accordingly. The improvements observed in Table 6 suggest that on many occasions the CRF was right to make a decision different from that recommended by the automaton.<sep> Conclusion and perspectives<sep> In this paper, we have applied two distinct machine learning approaches on the same dataset and proposed two distinct ways to combine them.<sep> As for symbolic learning alone, it is possible that other algorithms of positive presentation IG could give better results than ours, such as those of Garcia and Vidal (1990; Denis et al. (2002).<sep> The choice of a greater value of k could also improve our results, but at the cost of a greater time complexity[6] .<sep> But the most original part of our work concerns CRFs and automata combinations.<sep> It is to be noted that these combinations can also be applied to hand-made automata, likely to be more linguistically relevant than those obtained by GI.<sep> We focused here on automata produced by machine learning to show that, even without any linguistic expertise, it is possible to combine symbolic and statistical models.<sep> The intuition behind this work is that both types of models are complementary, and that they can benefit from one another.<sep> CRFs are based on a huge number of weighted local configurations.<sep> It is theoretically possible to use in a CRF features that relate to the entire sequence x but in practice, this is rarely done.<sep> GI on the contrary applies to a set of global sequences and is able to provide a generalization of a set of sequences.<sep> It has already been observed that CRFs benefit from features expressing more general properties than simple local configurations (Pu et al., 2010).<sep> Our intuition was that GI could provide such useful generalizations, via the first combination mode.<sep> The obtained results confirm this intuition.<sep> It is also interesting to see that symbolic models enhance the treatment of rare cases, which are not well taken into account by statistical models.<sep> CRF-generated confusion matrices for the analysis of an automaton still need to be further investigated. How to better interpret or take advantage of them is of particular interest.<sep> Some of the cells of these matrices are empty, because Wapiti eliminates the non-relevant features of the initial set according to a penalty criterion.<sep> It should be possible, thanks to this information, to modify the automaton on which the CRF is based by removing/adding states or transitions according to the diagnosis of the confusion matrices.<sep> A CRF-directed GI strategy still needs to be defined.<sep> Another challenge would be to study the link between the automata associated with the weights calculated by CRF that we define and the more classic HMM or probabilistic automata for which learning algorithms already exist (Thollard et al., 2000).<sep> 1 http://www.cnts.ua.be/conll2000/chunking<sep> 2 complete guide available at: http://lattice.cnrs.fr/sites/itellier/guide.html 3 the most recent ones were Stamina (http://stamina.chefbe.net) and Zulu (http://labh-curien.univst-etienne.fr/zulu)<sep> 4 The mirror automaton is obtained by switching initial and final states and by reversing every transition<sep> 5 http://wapiti.limsi.fr<sep> 6 k-RI time complexity is | Σ |k|Q|k +3 where |Q| is the number of states of the PTA.
Learning a hierarchy of specialized pairwise models for coreference resolution<sep> ABSTRACT<sep> This paper proposes a new method for significantly improving the performance of pairwise coreference models.<sep> Given a set of indicators, our method learns how to best separate types of mention pairs into equivalence classes, each of which gives rise to a specific classification model.<sep> The proposed algorithmic procedure finds the best feature space (derived from combinations of elementary features and indicators) for discriminating coreferential mention pairs.<sep> Although our approach explores a very large space of possible feature spaces, it remains efficient by exploiting the structure of the hierarchies built from the indicators.<sep> Our experiments on the CoNLL-2012 Shared Task English datasets indicate that our method gives performance gains compared to the initial model using only the basic features, regardless of the chain training method or the evaluation metric chosen.<sep> Our best system obtains a competitive 67 . 2 of average F1 over MUC, B[3] , and CEAF which, despite its simplicity, places it above the mean score of other systems on these datasets.<sep> 1 Introduction<sep> Coreference resolution is the problem of partitioning a sequence of noun phrases (or mentions ), as they occur in a natural language text, into a set of referential entities .<sep> A common approach to this problem is to separate it into two modules: on the one hand, one defines a model for evaluating coreference links, in general a discriminative classifier that detects coreferential mention pairs.<sep> Then, the detected links are grouped into clusters by a decoder to form a coherent output.<sep> Typically, this step is performed using greedy heuristics (McCarthy and Lehnert, 1995; Soon et al., 2001; Ng and Cardie, 2002; Bengston and Roth, 2008), although more sophisticated clustering approaches have been used, too, such as cutting graph methods (Nicolae and Nicolae, 2006; Cai and Strube, 2010) and Integer Linear Programming (ILP) formulations (Klenner, 2007; Denis and Baldridge, 2009).<sep> Despite its apparent simplicity, this two-step strategy remains competitive even when compared to more complex models utilizing a global loss (Bengston and Roth, 2008).<sep> In this kind of architecture, the performance of the entire coreference system strongly depends on the quality of the local pairwise classifier.[1]<sep> Consequently, a lot of research effort has focused on trying to improve the performance of this classifier.<sep> Numerous studies are concerned with feature extraction, typically trying to enrich the classifier with more linguistic knowledge and/or more world knowledge (Ng and Cardie, 2002; Kehler et al., 2004; Ponzetto and Strube, 2006; Bengston and Roth, 2008; Versley et al., 2008; Uryupina et al., 2011).<sep> A second line of work explores the use of distinct local models for different types of mentions, specifically for different types of anaphoric mentions based on their grammatical categories (such as pronouns, proper names, definite descriptions) (Morton, 2000; Ng, 2005; Denis and Baldridge, 2008).[2]<sep> An important justification for such specialized models is (psycho-)linguistic and comes from theoretical findings based on salience or accessibility (Ariel, 1988).<sep> From a machine learning point of view, this is related to feature extraction in that both approaches in effect recast the pairwise classification problem in higher dimensional feature spaces.<sep> In this paper, we claim that mention pairs should not be processed by a single classifier, and instead should be handled through specific models.<sep> In short, we are interested in learning how to construct and select such models.<sep> Our argument is therefore based on statistical considerations, rather than on purely linguistic ones[3] .<sep> The main question we raise is, given a set of indicators (such as grammatical types, distance between two mentions, or named entity types), how to best partition the pool of mention pair examples in order to best discriminate coreferential pairs from non coreferential ones.<sep> In effect, we want to learn the “best” subspaces for our different models: that is, subspaces that are neither too coarse (i.e., unlikely to separate the data well) nor too specific (i.e., prone to data sparseness and noise).<sep> We will see that this is also equivalent to constructing a single very large feature space to represent all the data.<sep> Our approach generalizes earlier approaches in important ways.<sep> For one thing, the definition of the different models is no longer restricted to grammatical typing (our model allows for various other types of indicators) or to the sole typing of the anaphoric mention (our models can also be specific to a particular type antecedent or to the two types of the mention pair).<sep> More importantly, we propose an original method for learning the best set of models that can be built from a given set of indicators and a training set.<sep> These models are organized in a hierarchy, wherein each leaf corresponds to a mutually disjoint subset of mention pair examples and the classifier that can be trained from it.<sep> Our models are trained using the Online Passive-Aggressive algorithm or PA (Crammer et al., 2006), a large margin version of the perceptron.<sep> Our method is exact in that it explores the full space of hierarchies (of size at least 2[2] [n] ) definable on an indicator sequence, while remaining scalable by exploiting the particular structure of these hierarchies with dynamic programming.<sep> This approach also performs well, and it largely outperforms the starting model that uses only the elementary traits.<sep> As will be shown based on a variety of experiments on the CoNLL-2012 Shared Task English datasets, these improvements are consistent across different evaluation metrics and for the most part independent of the clustering decoder that was used.<sep> The rest of this paper is organized as follows: in section 2, we discuss the underlying statistical hypotheses of the standard pairwise model and define a simple alternative framework that uses a simple separation of mention pairs based on grammatical types.<sep> Next, in section 3, we generalize the model by introducing indicator hierarchies and explain how to learn the best models associated with them.<sep> Section 4 provides a brief system description and Section 5 evaluates the various models on CoNLL-2012 English datasets.<sep> 2 Modeling pairs<sep> Pairwise models basically employ one local classifier to decide whether two mentions are coreferential or not.<sep> When using machine learning techniques, this involves certain assumptions about the statistical behavior of mention pairs.<sep> 2.1 Statistical assumptions<sep> To begin, let us adopt a probabilistic point of view to describe the prototype of pairwise models.<sep> Given a document, the number of mentions is fixed and each pair of mentions follows a certain distribution (that we partly observe in a feature space).<sep> The basic idea of pairwise models is to consider mention pairs independently from each other (that is why a decoder is necessary to enforce transitivity).<sep> If we use a single classifier to process all pairs, then they are supposed to be identically distributed.<sep> We think that pairs are not identically distributed, but that we should separate different "types" of pairs and create specific models for each of them.<sep> Separating different kinds of pairs and handling them with different specific models can lead to more accurate global models.<sep> For instance, some coreference resolution systems process different kinds of anaphors separately, which suggests for example that pairs containing an anaphoric pronoun behave differently from pairs with non-pronominal anaphors.<sep> One could rely on a rich set of features to capture complex distributions, but here we actually have a rather limited set of elementary features (see section 4) and, for instance, using products of features must be done carefully to avoid introducing noise in the model.<sep> Instead of imposing heuristic product of features, we will show that a clever separation of instances leads to significant improvements of the pairwise model.<sep> 2.2 Feature spaces<sep> 2.2.1 Definitions<sep> Let's start by giving a more formal view of modeling.<sep> Every pair of mentions mi and mj is represented by a random variable:<sep> where Ω classically represents randomness, X is the space of objects (“mention pairs”) that is not directly observable and yij ( ω ) ∈Y = { +1 , − 1 } are the labels indicating whether mi and mj are coreferential or not.<sep> To lighten the notations, we will not always write the index ij .<sep> Now we define a function:<sep> that casts pairs into a feature space F through which they are observed.<sep> For us, F is simply a vector space over R (in our case many features are Boolean; they are cast into R as 0 and 1).<sep> For technical coherence, we assume that φF 1( x ( ω )) and φF 2( x ( ω )) have the same values when projected on the feature space F 1 ∩F 2: it means that common features from two feature spaces have the same values.<sep> From this formal point of view, the task of coreference resolution consists in fixing φF , observing labeled samples { ( φF ( x ) , y ) t}t∈TrainSet and, given partially observed new variables { ( φF ( x )) t}t∈TestSet , recovering the corresponding values of y .<sep> 2.2.2 Another view on statistical assumptions<sep> We claimed before that all mention pairs seemed not to be identically distributed since, for example, pronouns do not behave like nominals.<sep> We can formulate this more rigorously: since the object space X is not directly observable, we do not know its complexity.<sep> In particular, when using a mapping to a too small feature space, the classifier cannot capture the distribution very well: the data is too noisy.<sep> Now if we say that pronominal anaphora do not behave like other anaphora, we distinguish two kinds of pairs i.e. we state that the distribution of pairs in X is a mixture of two distributions.<sep> In this way, we may separate positive and negative pairs more easily if we cast each kind of pair into a specific feature space.<sep> Let us call these feature spaces F 1 and F 2.<sep> We can either create two independent classifiers on F 1 and F 2 to process each kind of pair or define a single model on a larger feature space F = F 1 ⊕F 2.<sep> If the model is linear (which is our case), these approaches happen to be equivalent.<sep> So we can actually assume that the random variables Pij are identically distributed.<sep> A new issue arises: we need to find a mapping φF that represents the best view on the distribution of the data (which makes them easily separable).<sep> From a theoretical viewpoint, the higher the dimension of the feature space (imagine taking the direct sum of all feature spaces), the more we get details on the distribution of mention pairs and the more we can expect to separate positives and negatives accurately.<sep> In practice, we have to cope with data sparsity: there will not be enough data to properly train a linear model on such a space.<sep> Finally, we seek a feature space situated between the two extremes of a space that is too big (sparseness) or too small (noisy data).<sep> The core of this work is to define a general method for choosing the most adequate space F among a huge number of possibilities when we do not know a priori which is the best.<sep> 2.2.3 Linear models and independent spaces<sep> In this work, we try to linearly separate positive and negative instances in the large space F with the Online Passive-Aggressive (PA) algorithm (Crammer et al., 2006): the model learns a parameter vector w that defines a hyperplane that cuts the space into two parts.<sep> The predicted class of a pair x with feature vector φF ( x ) is given by:<sep> Linearity implies an equivalence between: (i) separating instances of two types, t 1 and t 2, in two independent models with respective feature spaces F 1 and F 2 and parameters w[1] and w[2] , and (ii) a single model on F 1 ⊕F 2.<sep> To see why, let us define the map:<sep> and the parameter vector w =<sep> Now we must ensure that this property is checked when the parameter w is learned.<sep> In this work we used the online Passive-Aggressive algorithm for binary classification (Crammer et al., 2006).<sep> This model is an extension of the perceptron, whose objective at each iteration is, on the one hand, to minimize the changes made to the existing model (hence the “passive” characteristic) and, on the other hand, to ensure that the current example is correctly classified with a large margin (hence the “aggressive” characteristic).<sep> For each new instance of the training set, the weight is updated according to the following rule[4] : where l ( w ; ( xt, yt )) = min(0 , 1 −yt ( w ·φF ( xt ))), so that when F = F 1 ⊕F 2, the minimum if x is 1 typed t 1 is w t +1 = w t +1 and if x is typed w t[2] t 2 is w t +1 = w t[1] where the w t[i] +1 w t[2] +1 correspond to the updates in space Fi independently from the rest.<sep> This result can be extended easily to the case of n feature spaces.<sep> Thus, with a deterministic separation of the data, a large model can be learned by decomposing it into independent models on smaller spaces.<sep> 2.3 An example: separation by gramtype<sep> To motivate our approach, we introduce a simple separation of mention pairs which creates 9 models obtained by considering all possible pairs of grammatical types {nominal, name, pronoun} for both mentions in the pair (a similar fine-grained separation can be found in (Chen et al., 2011)).<sep> This is equivalent to using 9 different feature spaces F 1 , … , F 9 to capture the global distribution of pairs.<sep> With linear classifiers, we get a single model in the feature space F = F 1 ⊕··· ⊕F 9.<sep> We will call it the GRAMTYPE model.<sep> As we will see in Section 5, these separated models significantly outperform a single model that uses the same base feature set.<sep> But we would like to define a method that adapts a feature space to the data by choosing the most adequate separation of pairs.<sep> 3 Hierarchizing feature spaces<sep> In this section, we present our method for automatically finding an optimal separation of mention pairs.<sep> In this section, we have to keep in mind that separating the pairs in different models is the same as building a large feature space in which the parameter w can be learned by parts in independent subspaces.<sep> 3.1 Indicators on pairs<sep> For establishing additional feature spaces, we use indicators which are deterministic functions on mention pairs with a small number of possible outputs.<sep> Indicators classify pairs in predefined categories in one-to-one correspondence with independent feature spaces.<sep> We can reuse some features of the system as indicators, e.g. the grammatical or named entity types.<sep> We can also employ functions that are not used as features, e.g. the approximate position of one of the mentions in the text.<sep> The small number of outputs of an indicator is required for practical reasons: if a category of pairs is too refined, the associated feature space will suffer from data sparsity.<sep> Indicators using distances must therefore be approximated by coarse histograms.<sep> In our experiments the outputs never exceeded a dozen values. (This will be more than enough to generate enough combinatory).<sep> One way to reduce the output span of an indicator is to binarize it like binarizing a tree (many possible binarizations).<sep> This operation produces a hierarchy of nested indicators, which is exactly the structure we exploit in what follows.<sep> 3.2 Hierarchies for separating pairs<sep> We hierarchies as combinations of indicators creating finer categories of mention pairs: given a finite sequence of indicators, a mention pair is classified by applying the indicators successively, each time refining a category into subcategories, just like in a decision tree (each node having the same number of children as the number of outputs of its indicator).<sep> We allow the classification to stop before applying the last indicator, but the behavior must be the same for all the instances.<sep> So a hierarchy is basically a sub-tree of the complete decision tree that contains copies of the same indicator at each level.<sep> If all the leaves of the decision tree have the same depth, this corresponds to taking the Cartesian product of outputs of all indicators for indexing the categories.<sep> In that case, we refer to product-hierarchies .<sep> The GRAMTYPE model can be seen as a two level product-hierarchy (figure 1).<sep> Figure 1: GRAMTYPE seen as a product-hierarchy.<sep> Product-hierarchies will be the starting point of our method to find a feature space that fits the data.<sep> Now, to choose a relevant sequence of indicators, one must call upon linguistic intuitions and theoretical work on the subject.<sep> The system will find by itself the best usage of the indicators when optimizing the hierarchy.<sep> The sequence of indicators is therefore a parameter of the model.<sep> 3.3 Relation between hierarchies and feature spaces<sep> Like we did for the GRAMTYPE model, we associate a feature space Fi to each leaf of a hierarchy.<sep> Likewise, the sum F = F- ⊕i Fi defines a large feature space. The corresponding parameter w of the model can be obtained by learning the w i in Fi .<sep> Given a sequence of indicators, the number of different hierarchies we can define is equal to the number of sub-trees of the complete decision tree (each non-leaf node having all its children).<sep> The minimal case is when all indicators are Boolean.<sep> The number of full binary trees of height at most n can be computed by the following recursion: T (1) = 1 and T ( n + 1) = 1 + T ( n )[2] .<sep> So T ( n ) ≥ 2[2] [n] : even with small values of n , the number of different hierarchies (or large feature spaces) definable with a sequence of indicators is gigantic (e.g. T (10) ≈ 3 . 8 . 10[90] ).<sep> Among all the possibilities for a large feature space, many are irrelevant because for them the data is too sparse or too noisy in some subspaces.<sep> We need a general method for finding the best space without enumerating and testing each of them.<sep> 3.4 Optimizing hierarchies<sep> Let us assume now that the sequence of indicators is fixed, and let n be its length.<sep> To find the best feature space among a very high number of possibilities, we need a criterion we can apply without too much additional computation.<sep> For that we only evaluate the feature space locally on pairs, i.e. without applying a decoder on the output.<sep> We employ 3 measures on pairwise classification results: precision, recall and F1-score.<sep> Selecting the best space for one of these measures can be achieved by using dynamic programming techniques.<sep> In our experiments, we try to optimize the F1-score.<sep> Training the hierarchy: Starting from the product-hierarchy, we associate a classifier and its proper feature space to each node of the tree[5] .<sep> The classifiers are then trained as follows: for each instance there is a unique path from the root to a leaf of the complete tree.<sep> Each classifier situated on the path is updated with this instance.<sep> The number of iterations of the Passive-Aggressive is fixed (we did not try to optimize this parameter).<sep> Computing scores: After training, we test all the classifiers on another set of development pairs[4] .<sep> Again, a classifier is tested on an instance only if it is situated on the path from the root to the leaf associated with the instance.<sep> We obtain TP/FP/FN numbers[7] on pair classifications that are sufficient to compute the F1-score.<sep> As for training, the data on which a classifier at a given node is evaluated is the same as the union of all data used to evaluate the classifiers corresponding to the children of this node.<sep> Thus we are able to compare the scores obtained at a node to the “union of the scores” obtained at its children.<sep> Cutting down the hierarchy: For the moment we have a complete tree with a classifier at each node.<sep> We use a dynamic programming technique to compute the best hierarchy by cutting this tree and only keeping classifiers situated at the leaf.<sep> The algorithm assembles the best local models (or feature spaces) together to create larger models.<sep> It goes from the leaves to the root and cuts the subtree starting at a node whenever it does not provide a better score than the node itself, or on the contrary propagates the score of the sub-tree when there is an improvement.<sep> The details are given in algorithm 1.<sep> ALGORITHM 1 – Hierarchy breakdown<sep> Let us briefly discuss the correctness and complexity of the algorithm.<sep> Each node is seen two times so the time complexity is linear in the number of nodes which is at least O (2 [n] ).<sep> However, only nodes that have encountered at least one training instance are useful and there are O ( n × k ) such nodes (where k the size of the training set).<sep> So we can optimize the algorithm to run in time O ( n × k ) (which is also the training time of the hierarchy).<sep> If we scan the list obtained by breadth-first search backwards, we are ensured that every node will be processed after its children, so that the optimal model will be built from close to the root.<sep> ( node.children ) is the set of children of node , and ( node.score ) its score.<sep> sum-num provides TP/FP/FN by simply adding those of the children and sum-score computes the score based on these new TP/FP/FN numbers.<sep> (line 6) cuts the children of a node when they are not used in the best score.<sep> The algorithm thus propagates the best scores from the leaves to the root which finally gives a single score corresponding to the best hierarchy.<sep> Only the leaves used to compute the best score are kept, and they define the best hierarchy.<sep> Relation between cutting and the global feature space:<sep> We can see the operation of cutting as replacing a group of subspaces by a single subspace in the sum (see figure 2).<sep> So cutting down the product-hierarchy amounts to reducing the global initial feature space in an optimal way.<sep> We see here the link between the best hierarchy and the space of strokes that makes it possible to separate the pairs as well as possible.<sep> Figure 2: Cutting down the hierarchy reduces the feature space<sep> 4 System description<sep> Our system consists of the pairwise model obtained by cutting a hierarchy (the PA with selected feature space) and using a greedy decoder to create clusters from the output.<sep> It is parametrized by the choice of the initial sequence of indicators.<sep> The basic features<sep> We used classical features that can be found in details in (Bengston and Roth, 2008) and (Rahman and Ng, 2011): grammatical type and subtype of mentions, string match and substring, apposition and copula, distance (number of separating mentions/sentences/words), gender/number match, synonymy/hypernym and animacy (using WordNet), family name (based on lists), named entity types, syntactic features (gold parse) and anaphoricity detection.<sep> As indicators we used: grammatical types and subtypes for the left (antecedent) and right (anaphore) mentions according to the order of the text, types of named entities, a boolean indicating if the mentions are in the same sentence, and a very coarse histogram of distance in terms of sentences.<sep> We systematically started the sequences (of different lengths) with the gramtype right and left, then added other indicators.<sep> The parameter was optimized by document categories using a development set after decoding the output of the pairwise model.<sep> We tested 3 classical greedy link selection strategies that form clusters from the classifier decision: Closest-First (merge mentions with their closest coreferent mention on the left) (Soon et al., 2001), Best-first (merge mentions with the mention on the left having the highest positive score) (Ng and Cardie, 2002; Bengston and Roth, 2008), and Aggressive-Merge (transitive closure on positive pairs) (McCarthy and Lehnert, 1995).<sep> Each of these decoders is typically used in tandem with a specific sampling selection at training (although not always).<sep> Thus, Closest-First for instance is used in combination with a sample selection that generates training instances only for the mentions that occur between the closest antecedent and the anaphor (Soon et al., 2001).<sep> 5 Experiments<sep> 5.1 Data<sep> We evaluated the system on the English part of the corpus provided in the CoNLL-2012 Shared Task (Pradhan et al., 2012), referred to as CoNLL-2012 here.<sep> The corpus contains 7 categories of documents (over 2K documents, 1 . 3M words).<sep> We used the official train/dev/test data sets.<sep> 5.2 Settings<sep> The hierarchies were trained with 10-fold crossvalidation on the training set (the hierarchies are cut after cumulating the scores obtained by crossvalidation) and their parameters are optimized by document category on the development set: the sequence of indicators obtaining the best average score after decoding was selected as parameter for the category.<sep> In the results, we will refer to the obtained hierarchy as the BEST HIERARCHY.<sep> We fixed the number of iterations for the Passive-Aggressive for all models.<sep> Our baselines are the initial model with the elementary features (single model) and the gramtype model (section 2) associated with each of the gluttonous decoders, and also the versions where these decoders are used with a particular sampling.<sep> In our experiments, we only consider the gold mentions (no singletons or non-referential mentions).<sep> This is not entirely realistic, but our goal is to compare various local pairwise models rather than to set up a complete coreference resolution system.<sep> Also, we wanted to avoid having to consider too many parameters in our experiments.<sep> 5.3 Evaluation metrics<sep> We use the three metrics that are most commonly used, namely:<sep> MUC (Vilain et al., 1995) computes for each true entity cluster the number of system clusters that are needed to cover it.<sep> Precision is this quantity divided by the true cluster size minus one.<sep> Recall is obtained by reversing true and predicated clusters.<sep> F1 is the harmonic mean of recall and precision.<sep> B[3] (Bagga and Baldwin, 1998) computes recall and precision scores for each mention, based on the intersection between the system/true clusters for that mention.<sep> Precision is the ratio of the intersection and the true cluster sizes, while recall is the ratio of the intersection to the system cluster sizes.<sep> Global recall, precision, and F1 scores are obtained by averaging over the mention scores.<sep> CEAF (Luo, 2005) scores are obtained by computing the best one-to-one mapping between the system/true partitions, which is equivalent to finding the best optimal alignment in the bipartite graph formed out of these partitions.<sep> We use the φ 4 similarity function from (Luo, 2005).<sep> These metrics were recently used in the CoNLL2011 and -2012 Shared Tasks .<sep> In addition, these campaigns use an unweighted average over the F1 scores given by the three metrics.<sep> Following common practice, we use micro-averaging when reporting our scores for entire datasets.<sep> 5.4 Results<sep> The results obtained by the system are reported in tables 1, 2 and 3.<sep> The original sampling for the single model associated to Closest-First and Best-First decoder are referred to as SOON and NGCARDIE.<sep> The single model corresponds to a simple model trained without specific sampling.<sep> Despite the use of greedy decoders, we observe a large positive effect of pair separation in the pairwise models on the outputs.<sep> The use of distinct models rather than a single model has a positive effect on the mean score, with an increase from 6.4 to 15.5 depending on the decoder.<sep> It is interesting to note that irrespective of the decoder being used, the gramtype model always outperforms the single model and is itself outperformed by the best hierarchy model.<sep> We found some variations in the optimal parameter of the hierarchies, however a frequently well-classified parameter was: right gramtype → left gramtype → same sentence → right named entity type.<sep> Looking at the different metrics, we notice that overall, pair separation improves B[3] and CEAF (but not always MUC) after decoding the output: GRAMTYPE provides a better mean score than the single model, and BEST HIERARCHY gives the highest B[3] , CEAF and mean score.<sep> The best combination of classifier-decoder achieves a score of 67.19, which would place it at the level of the best systems that took part in the CoNLL-2012 Shared Task on the gold mentions configuration (mean score 66.41, the first isolated at 77, the best following at 68-69).<sep> TABLE 1 – Scores on CoNLL-2012 with gold mentions, Closest-First decoder.<sep> TABLE 2 – Score on CoNLL-2012 with gold mentions, Best-First decoder.<sep> TABLE 3 – CoNLL-2012 scores with gold mentions, Aggressive-Merge decoder.<sep> 6 Conclusion and perspectives<sep> In this paper, we described a method for constructing a feature space separating the pairs, by exploiting linearity and by combining indicators to separate the instances.<sep> We employed dynamic programming to efficiently compute the feature space providing the best pairwise classifications among a very large number of possibilities.<sep> We applied this method to optimize the pairwise model in a coreference resolution system.<sep> By testing different kinds of greedy decoders, we showed a significant improvement of the system.<sep> For this work, we only considered standard heuristic strategies for creating clusters such as Closest-First and Best-First.<sep> So a natural extension of this work would be to combine our method for learning pairwise models with more sophisticated decoding strategies (like Mincut or Integer Linear Programming).<sep> We will then be able to evaluate the impact of hierarchies in more realistic conditions.<sep> Our approach is flexible in that it can be applied with a variety of indicators.<sep> In the future we will apply the hierarchies on finer feature spaces to make more accurate optimizations.<sep> Moreover, since the general method of cutting down hierarchies is not specific to the modelling of mention pairs, but can be applied to other problems having Boolean aspects, we plan to use hierarchies to address other tasks in computational linguistics (e.g. anaphoricity detection or discourse and temporal relation classification wherein position information may help separating the data).<sep> The selection of spaces with hierarchies, if the indicators are all lines of the model, is similar to the methods of polynomial kernels.<sep> It would be interesting to compare them.<sep> Furthermore, we will be able to develop this method by using statistical criteria to choose the indicators and build starting hierarchies that are more complex than product hierarchies, in the manner of decision trees. The system will then be easier to set up.<sep> 1 There are however no theoretical guarantees that improving local classification will always result in overall improvements if the two modules are optimized independently.<sep> 2 Sometimes, distinct sample selections are also adopted during the training of the distinct local models (Ng and Cardie, 2002; Uryupina, 2004).<sep> 3 In the experiments, the classifiers use a copy of a same feature space, but not the same data, which corresponds to crossing the features with the categories of the decision tree.<sep> 6 The training set is cut into two parts, for training and testing the hierarchy.<sep> 5. "True positives", "false positives" and "false negatives".
Improving distributional thesauri by exploring the graph of neighbors<sep> Abstract<sep> In this paper, we address the issue of building and improving a distributional thesaurus.<sep> We first show that existing tools from the information retrieval domain can be directly used in order to build a thesaurus with state-of-the-art performance.<sep> Secondly, we focus more specifically on improving the obtained thesaurus, seen as a graph of nearest neighbors.<sep> By exploiting information about the neighborhood contained in this graph, we propose several contributions.<sep> 1) We show how the lists of neighbors can be globally improved by examining the reciprocity of the neighboring relation, that is, the fact that a word can be close of another and vice-versa.<sep> 2) We also propose a method to associate a confidence score to any lists of nearest neighbors (i.e. any entry of the thesaurus).<sep> 3) Last, we demonstrate how these confidence scores can be used to reorder the closest neighbors of a word.<sep> These different contributions are validated through experiments and offer significant improvement over the state-of-the-art.<sep> Keywords: distributional thesaurus, k nearest neighbor graph, Parzen window, Hungarian algorithm, T-norms, information retrieval.<sep> 1 Introduction<sep> Distributional thesauri are useful for many NLP tasks and their construction is an issue widely discussed for several years (Grefenstette, 1994).<sep> However this is still a very active research field, maintained by the increasingly large number of available corpus and by many applications.<sep> These thesauri associate each of their entry with a list of words that are desired semantically close to the entry.<sep> This notion of proximity varies (synonymy, other paradigmatic relations, syntagmatic relations (Budanitsky and Hirst, 2006; Adam et al., 2013, for a discussion)), but the methods used for the automatic construction of thesauri are often shared.<sep> For the most part, these methods rely on the distributional hypothesis of (Firth, 1957): each word is characterized by the set of contexts in which it appears, and the semantic proximity of two words can be inferred from the proximity of their contexts.<sep> This hypothesis has been implemented in different ways, and several propositions to improve the results have been explored (see next section for a state of the art).<sep> The work presented in this article are part of this framework. We propose several contributions on the creation of these distributional thesauri and their improvement.<sep> We first show that information retrieval (IR) models are adapted to the task of creating these thesauri, offering very competitive results compared to the state of the art, while benefiting from existing tools (Section 3).<sep> The most important part of our work then focuses on the exploitation of such semantic neighborhood relations.<sep> The IR models indeed provide lists ordering all words by decreasing similarity, that form a graph of nearest neighbors.<sep> We propose to take advantage of some of the neighborhood information contained in this graph and we derive three contributions.<sep> 1) We show how to globally improve neighbor lists by taking into account the reciprocity of the neighborhood relationship, that is to say the fact that a word is a close neighbor of another and vice versa (Section 4).<sep> 2) We also propose a method that associates each neighbor list (i.e. each entry of the thesaurus built) with a confidence score (Section 5).<sep> This method uses the nearest neighbor graph to estimate the probabilities that a given word is the i -th neighbor of another word.<sep> 3) Finally, on the basis of this work, we show how to use this confidence score and these probabilities to reorder the list of nearest neighbors (Section 6).<sep> To achieve this goal, we model the reranking as an optimization problem of assignments, solved by the Hungarian algorithm (Kuhn and Yaw, 1955).<sep> 2 State of the art<sep> The notion of distributional thesaurus is both well known and at the same time relatively little addressed in a specific way, probably because of its close links with the notion of semantic similarity.<sep> Many works focus on improvements concerning the semantic similarity measures of a distributional nature, that is to say directly to the construction of the thesaurus. We examine them in the following subsection. But some works presented in subsection 2.2 have also sought, once the thesaurus obtained, to improve it, as we propose to do by examining it as a graph of nearest neighbors.<sep> 2.1 Construction of thesauri<sep> If we consider as a reference point the paradigm defined by Grefenstette (1994), taken up by Lin (1998) and Curran & Moens (2002), a first avenue of improvement has been the weighting of the elements that make up the distributional contexts, simple words in the case of graphical co-occurrents and pairs (word, syntactic dependency relation) in the case of syntactic co-occurrents.<sep> In this perspective, Broda et al. (2009) proposed to replace the weights associated with co-occurrents by a function that takes into account their rank in these contexts, which has the advantage of making this weight less dependent on a specific weighting function. Zhitomirsky-Geffet & Dagan (2009) operates this weight modification through a bootstrapping mechanism by assuming that the first neighbors of an entry are more relevant than others and that, as a result, the co-occurrents that are most strongly associated with them in their distributional contexts are also more representative of the entry from a semantic point of view.<sep> The weight of these co-occurrents is then increased to increase their influence during the reordering of the neighbors.<sep> Yamamoto & Asakura (2010) is a variant that takes into account a larger set of co-occurrents in contexts.<sep> Beyond changes in weighting, some work has focused on the very content of distributional contexts.<sep> From this point of view, a first distinction, already made by Grefenstette (1994) but explored in more detail by Curran & Moens (2002), was made between graphic and syntactic co-occurrents, with an advantage given to the latter.<sep> In parallel with the nature of the information contained in the contexts, the question of its form was raised by assuming that the information carried by the co-occurrents can be represented in a denser way by underlying dimensions.<sep> This idea is, moreover, reinforced by the observation of Hagiwara et al. (2006), through the selection of characteristics in a supervised framework, that many co-occurrents can be filtered without significantly altering the identification of semantic similarities between words.<sep> However, most of the work related to this issue has focused on the fact that the “traditional” representation of distributional contexts is very sparse and redundant, as illustrated by Hagiwara et al. (2006). Hence, several methods for dimension reduction were tested in this context: from Latent Semantic Analysis (Landauer and Dumais, 1997), extended for syntactic co-occurrents (Pad´o and Lapata, 2007), to Random Indexing (Sahlgren, 2001), Non-negative Matrix Factorization (Van de Cruys, 2010) and more recently, lexical representations learnt by neural networks (Huang et al., 2012; Mikolov et al., 2013).<sep> 2.2 Improved thesauri<sep> The work we present in this article focuses on improvements that exploit more specifically the structure of the thesaurus to improve its quality as we propose to do.<sep> Zhitomirsky-Geffet & Dagan (2009) could to some extent be related to this category insofar as its response to the context elements of a term depends on its semantic neighbors, and therefore on the structure of the thesaurus.<sep> Two other avenues have also been explored.<sep> The first consists in using an initial thesaurus to select, in an unsupervised way, a set of positive and negative examples of semantically similar or related terms (Ferret, 2012, 2013b). This set is used to train a classifier that then reorders the initial neighbors. In the case of (Ferret, 2012), this selection is based on a criterion of symmetry of the relationship of semantic similarity: if A is found as a close neighbor of B and B as a close neighbor of A, A and B are probably positive examples of semantically similar words.<sep> This is the reciprocity condition that we explore in another context in section 4.<sep> (Ferret, 2013b) is based on the hypothesis that similar constituents, in the sense of their proximity in a thesaurus, occupying the same syntactic role in similar compound words are likely to be positive examples of similar words. The second approach, proposed in (Ferret, 2013a), is more indirect.<sep> It rearranges the semantic neighbours through a process of detection and downgrading of the neighbours that are less likely to be semantically related to their entry.<sep> This detection is carried out by applying a discriminant model of the context entry to a sample of the occurrences of its neighbours and by judging the proximity between the entry and the neighbour on the basis of the decisions of this model.<sep> As in our previous work, we aim to improve the quality of the produced thesauri, in particular by reordering the lists of neighbours.<sep> Our work is based in part on similar considerations, particularly with regard to reciprocity, but in a different perspective in which the lists of nearest neighbors are directly reordered according to the neighborhoods observed in the thesaurus. In this respect, our work can be similar to that of (Pedronette et al., 2014), carried out in a completely different applicative context (image search), but also based on the examination of the neighborhoods observed in a graph of k nearest neighbors.<sep> 3 IR models for building distributional thesauri<sep> 3.1 Principles<sep> As mentioned in the state of the art, distributional approaches aim to calculate similarities between textual representations of word contexts.<sep> Methods to calculate similarities from IR seem then relevant for this problem.<sep> For a given word, the set of contexts of all its occurrences is considered as a document.<sep> for a word wi , we note this document Cwi .<sep> The proximity between two words is then measured on their contexts by a similarity function from IR.<sep> This idea has many links with the work from the state of the art, but seems relatively unexplored, with the exception of Vechtomova & Robertson (2012) in the specific context of similar named entities.<sep> It offers the advantage of being easily implementable because of the numerous IR tools available.<sep> Some adaptations are of course required.<sep> In the experiments reported below, the context considered is two words before and after each occurrence.<sep> In contrast to IR, the stop words are kept as well as their positions relative to the considered occurrence.<sep> For example, in ” the excerpt: … all forms of restrictions on freedom of expression, threats …”, the indexing terms restriction-2, on-1, of+1, expression+2 are added to the context of freedom noted C (freedom).<sep> The whole set of collected contexts for a word is used as a query in order to find its distributional neighbors. According to an IR similarity measure, the nearest words of this query (those whose contexts are closest) are returned.<sep> We tested some of the most classical similarity measures used in IR: Hellinger (Escoffier, 1978; Domengès and Volle, 1979), TF-IDF/cosinus, and Okapi-BM-25 (Robertson et al., 1998).<sep> The last model can be seen as a variation of TF-IDF that better takes into account the difference between document sizes.<sep> This point is of importance since in our case the documents (namely the set of contexts of a word) are actually of very variable sizes, due to the very variable number of occurrences of each word.<sep> The Okapi-BM25 similarity between a word wi (C(wi) is seen as a query), and wj (C(wj) is seen as a document), is expressed by the equation 1 in which the components correspond respectively to the weight of the word considered in the query, its TF and its IDF in the document.<sep> qtf is the number of occurrences of the word t in the query ( C ( wi )), dl is the size of C ( wj )), dlavg the average size of all contexts, n is the number of documents (that means in our case the number of considered words/thesaurus entries). df ( t ) is the number of contexts ( C ( · )) containing t . Finally, k 1, k 3 and b are some constants, with default values k 1 = 2, k 3 = 1000 and b = 0 . 75.<sep> We also propose in the experiments reported below a so-called adjusted version of the OkapiBM25 similarity, in which the influence of the document size is enhanced, by taking b = 1, and by squaring the IDF to give more importance to the most discriminating context words. These very classical IR models are not detailed further here; the interested reader will find the useful notions and details in the references cited or in general works (Boughanem & Savoy, 2008, for example).<sep> 3.2 Experimental setup<sep> The data and references used for our experiments throughout this article are those used by Ferret (2013a) and made available to us by the author.<sep> This allows us to have an experimental framework that is completely comparable to the published results.<sep> The corpus used to build the distributional thesaurus is AQUAINT-2. It is a collection of articles from the press containing about 380 million words.<sep> All the nouns in the corpus with a frequency > 10 are considered, which represents 25,000 entries (i.e. unique nouns), denoted by n in the remaining.<sep> The corpus is labeled in parts of speech by TreeTagger, which allows us to identify the names that will form the thesaurus entries and thus compare to existing work.<sep> However this information is not used to build the thesaurus, ensuring the portability of the method to other languages, similarly to (Freitag et al., 2005).<sep> To evaluate the built thesauri, WordNet 3.0 synonyms (Miller, 1990) and Moby (Ward, 1996) are used as references, either separately, or jointly.<sep> These two resources have quite different and complementary characteristics;<sep> As a result, WordNet provides lists of 3 neighbors on average for the 10,473 names of the corpus it covers, while Moby provides lists of 50 neighbors on average for 9,216 names.<sep> When combined, the two resources provide a reference of 38 neighbors on average for 12,243 names.<sep> It is this combination of WordNet and Moby that will be used as the main reference in all evaluations of this article.<sep> This intrinsic evaluation framework therefore concerns a small half of the entries of the thesaurus considered, which can be considered, given its size, as a significant evaluation set compared to classical benchmarks such as WordSim 353 for instance (Gabrilovich and Markovitch, 2007).<sep> This kind of intrinsic evaluation is of course limited by the nature of the relations present in the reference resources.<sep> In our case, this limitation is quite restrictive for WordNet’s synonyms but can be considered as far less restrictive for the related words of Moby, due to the diversity of their underlying relation types.<sep> 3.3 Results<sep> TABLE 1: Performance of IR models for building distributional thesauri on the WordNet+Moby reference<sep> For a given name, our approach by IR models, like other state-of-the-art approaches, orders the other names by decreasing similarity.<sep> The list obtained is compared to the reference list, and classical evaluation measures are calculated. These are the precision at various thresholds (after 1, 5, 10, 50, 100 neighbours, noted P@1, P@5...), the Mean Average Precision (MAP, average of the precisions calculated after each word of the reference found), the R-precision (Rprec, precision after R neighbours or R is the number of neighbours in the reference list for the name examined). They are all expressed in percentage in the following article.<sep> Table 1 indicates the performance of different models of IR similarities.<sep> For purposes of comparison, we show the results obtained under the same conditions by Ferret (2013a), with both a standard state of the art approach based on using mutual information over contexts (referred as base in the table), and an improved version by learning as described in section 2 (referred as best rerank). We also detail some of these results according to the WordNet and Moby references taken separately.<sep> Several elements are worth noting in these initial results.<sep> First of all, we note that, as with other works in literature, our results are generally weak, which attests to the difficulty of the task. In addition to these precision measures, the recall at 100 is, for example, 21.2% for the adjusted version of Okapi on the WordNet+Moby reference.<sep> In these early results, it is worth noting that some IR similarities are quite inefficient, including the TF alone or Hellinger similarity.<sep> This is hardly surprising since these similarities use very basic weights that do not enhance the discriminative contexts of words.<sep> The similarities that include a notion of IDF get better results in this.<sep> Okapi BM25-based similarities offer good results.<sep> The standard Okapi version yields performance similar to the state of the art, and the adjusted version even widely outperforms the two systems from Ferret (2013), in particular in terms of overall quality (measured by the MAP).<sep> This latest version of the system serves as reference for the rest of this article.<sep> 4 Reciprocity in the graph of k-NN<sep> Computing all the similarities between all pairs of words produces a weighted graph of neighbors: Each word is connected with certain strength to the n other words.<sep> The results above do not reflect this structure.<sep> The following sections aim to examine how take advantage of the neighborhood relations embedded in this graph.<sep> It must be first noted that some of the IR similarity measures we used are not symmetric, including Okapi-BM25.<sep> The similarity between a word wi , used as query, and another word wj does not give the same value as the similarity between the query wj and wi .<sep> Apart from that, even if the similarity measure itself is symmetric, nearest neighbor relationships are not. A word wj can be in the k-nearest neighbors of wi, but the inverse may not be true.<sep> It seems then reasonable to assume that the reciprocity between two adjacent words (each belonging to the k nearest neighbors of the other) is a sign of confidence on the proximity between these words.<sep> Using this information to improve the previous results is discussed in this section.<sep> In the following, τwi ( wj ) denotes the rank of the word wj in the list of neighbors of wi. τwi ( wj ) thus varies from 1 to n .<sep> 4.1 Distributional neighborhood graph<sep> Reciprocal relationship in distributional neighborhood has already been discussed and used in some work (Ferret, 2013) on distributional semantic, or more generally, on nearest neighbors graphs (Pedronette et al., 2014).<sep> In these papers, the reciprocity was considered for giving a new similarity score in a simple way.<sep> For a word wi and its neighbor wj , the maximal or the minimal rank between τwi ( wj ) and τwj ( wi ) is taken as the new rank.<sep> These two operators appear to be too brutal as only one rank is taken into consideration to decide the final score, which leads to highly degraded performance as shown later.<sep> However, many other aggregation operators with behaviors that may be more appropriate to the task have been proposed in other contexts, including fuzzy logic (Detyniecki, 2000, for a very complete review).<sep> These operators carry some semantic that allow to comprehend their behavior, such as T-norms (fuzzy logic AND) and S-norms (or T-conorms, fuzzy OR).<sep> In this section, we test some of these operators without claiming to be exhaustive.<sep> These are defined on [0 , 1][2] , 1 being the certainty. They are used to generate a new similarity score according to: score wi ( wj ) = Agreg(1 − τwi ( wj ) /n, 1 − τwj ( wi ) /n )<sep> where Aggreg is an aggregation operator (see below for the test of some possible functions).<sep> The new scores are then used to produce a new list of nearest neighbors of wi (the higher the score, the greater proximity is proven).<sep> We thus have the semantic associated with these operators.<sep> For example, if the aggregation function is max, we get the expected behavior of the fuzzy OR associated with this S-norm: wj will be ranked very close to wi in the new list if wj was close to wi or if wi was close to wj .<sep> For the T-norm min, this happens if wj is close to wi and wi is close to wj .<sep> 4.2 Results<sep> For the aggregation function Agreg, besides the min and max, we report in Figure 1 the results obtained with the following T-norms (or T-norm families dependent on a parameter γ ):<sep> We also tested the standard related S-norms, obtained by generalization of the De Morgan’s law: S ( x, y ) = 1 − T (1 − x, 1 − y ).<sep> For the T-norm families dependent on a parameter, we varied this parameter value in a systematic way. The results reported correspond to the parameter values that maximize the MAP.<sep> We notice that these operators get very different results.<sep> Some operators, such as min, max, Lukasiewicz, and others for some γ , induce a threshold effect which degrades the quality of the list of nearest neighbors: they return a default value generating too much ex aequo among the neighbors, for some values of τwi ( wj ) and τwj ( wi ).<sep> TABLE 2: Performance and gains (%) by reciprocal rank aggregation over the WordNet and Moby references separately with rank aggregation by SHamacher γ = 0.95<sep> T-norms, focusing on pairs of words symmetrically close to each other, are too restrictive.<sep> This is consistent with the conclusions of the work cited: if the reciprocity condition is applied too strictly, it does not improve the nearest neighbor lists over all the words.<sep> In contrast, S-norms seem better able to take advantage of the ranking.<sep> The improvements are modest in terms of overall quality (MAP), but important at some ranks (e.g. P@10, P@50).<sep> Finally, it is important to note that these results depend heavily on the resource used as reference, as we illustrate in Table 2 by testing the aggregation rank with SHamacher γ = 0 . 95 on Moby and WordNet references separately.<sep> To ensure that differences are statistically significant, we perform a Wilcoxon test (p < 0.05) (Hull, 1993);<sep> Non significant results are indicated in italics.<sep> Because Wordnet is based on a synonymy relationship strong enough (and therefore reciprocal), the performance gains on WordNet are much higher than on Moby.<sep> 5 Confidence estimation for a distributional neighborhood list<sep> In the previous section, the rank of wi in the list of neighbors of wj is used to improve the ranking of wj in the list of neighbors of wi .<sep> We can also be interested in a more general way to the relative positions of wi and wj in all neighbor lists of all the words. Thereby, we expect to derive a more complete information.<sep> As a first step, we propose to define a confidence criterion associated with each list of nearest neighbors, only based on the neighborhood graph.<sep> 5.1 Principle<sep> We make the following assumption: the nearest neighbor list of a word w is probably of good quality if the distance (in terms of rank) between w and each of its neighbors wi , denoted δ ( w, wi ), is consistent with the distance observed between these same words ( w , wi ) in other lists.<sep> The intuition here is that words supposed to be close should also be found close to the same other words.<sep> For example, if wi is a very close neighbor of w, and w is a very close neighbor of wj, we expect wi to be a very close neighbor of wj as well.<sep> If k nearest neighbors of w have this property, then we attribute a high confidence to the neighbor list of w .<sep> Formally, we define the confidence of the k -nearest neighbor list of w in probabilistic terms:<sep> where p ( δ ( w, wi ) = τw ( wi )) is the probability that wi is the τw ( wi )-th neighbor of w .<sep> The problem is then to estimate the probability distribution p ( δ ( w, wi )) for each pair of words ( w, wi ).<sep> To achieve this goal, we use the Parzen window which is a method for nonparametric density estimation.<sep> We describe below how this classic method (Parzen, 1962; Wasserman, 2005) is applied in our context.<sep> 5.2 Parzen-window density estimation<sep> Let xab = δ ( wa, wb ) be the distance (in terms of ranks) between two words wa and wb in a list of neighbors of any given word.<sep> We have a sample of n realizations assumed iid : ( x[1] ab , x[2] ab, … , x[n] ab ), which are the observed distances between wa and wb in each (complete) neighbor list of each word. We assume they are iid ;<sep> This hypothesis is certainly not fulfilled since these distances are calculated in part on similar contexts, but this simplification allows for a simple and effective formalization.<sep> Indeed, we can then estimate the probability density of xab with the Parzen window technique using a kernel density estimator with Eqn 4 where h is a smoothing parameter called the bandwidth, and K is a kernel that we choose to estimate the density locally. In our case, we choose a Gaussian kernel (Eqn 3).<sep> Thus, the resulting probability is a mixture of Gaussians centered on each x[i] .<sep> It is shown that the choice of kernel has a small influence on the estimation.<sep> These methods are known to be sensitive to the choice of the smoothing parameter h , which controls the regularity of the estimation.<sep> The problem of choosing h is crucial in density estimation and was widely discussed in the literature.<sep> We use Silverman’s rule of thumb (Silverman, 1986, page 48, eqn (3.31)) to set its value.<sep> Under the assumption of normality of the underlying distribution, this rule provides a simple way to calculate the optimal parameter h when Gaussian functions are used to approximate univariate data (Eqn 5 where σ ˆ is the standard deviation of the samples, and q 3 − q 1 is the interquartile range).<sep> Once these probabilities have been estimated on each of the k -nearest neighbors of w , we can calculate the confidence score Q ( w ).<sep> The complexity of this estimation for all neighbor lists is O ( k ∗ n[2] ).<sep> Figure 2: (a) Example of two histograms (blue and red) of the distances xab and xac between a word wa and two of its neighbors wb and wc.<sep> (b) Two probability densities (in blue and red) estimated by Parzen windows, corresponding to the data in figure 2a.<sep> 5.3 Using the confidence score<sep> The expected benefit of using the confidence score is to have an a priori indication on the quality of a neighbor list for a given word.<sep> Such a score may thus be useful for many applications using thesauri produced by our approach.<sep> An evaluation of the confidence score through such applications would certainly be the most suitable, but beyond the scope of this article.<sep> We use default direct assessment towards the MAP: we measure the correlation between MAP and the confidence score, the idea being that an entry with a neighbor list of low quality matches an entry with low MAP.<sep> Several correlation indices can be used.<sep> The Pearson r index measures a linear correlation between score and MAP. We also use Spearman's correlation ρ and Kendall's rank correlation coefficient τ, which do not make any assumption about linearity and compare only the order of words classified according to their MAP with the order according to their confidence score.<sep> The results of these three coefficients are given in Table 3 (1 indicates a perfect correlation, 0 no correlation and -1 an inverse correlation), with the p-value of the associated test of significance for each (a low p-value, for example < 0.05, indicates a statistically significant result).<sep> The confidence scores are obtained with k = 20.<sep> Other experiments, not reported here, show that this parameter k has little influence on the correlation, for values between 5 and 100.<sep> These measures attest to some statistically significant correlation between our confidence score and the MAP, however this correlation is imperfect and non-linear.<sep> We compute the average MAP on neighbor lists with a confidence score lower than a threshold q . Figure 3 represents the average MAP (y-axis) in function of the threshold q (x-axis). It shows that the confidence score is still a good indicator of quality, as the MAP decreases with the confidence score.<sep> FIGURE 3: MAP of words with a confidence score below a certain threshold (given on the abscissa (log)) and cumulative proportion of words concerned<sep> The confidence score can be used to improve the performance of aggregation techniques presented in Section 4.<sep> The idea is simply to integrate the confidence score into the final score: score wi ( wj ) = Q ( wj ) ∗ Agreg(1 − τwi ( wj ) /n, 1 − τwj ( wi ) /n )<sep> As shown in Table 4, the addition of this information allows even greater gains than those reported in the previous section. As before, these gains are more significant at the end of the list (P@50, P@100).<sep> In the next section, we propose another use of the confidence scores to improve results more specifically on the top of the lists, that is to say on the neighbors judged closest.<sep> Table 4: Performance gains (%) by reciprocal rank aggregation using the confidence score, on WordNet+Moby reference.<sep> 6 Local reranking<sep> The previous method gives an overall score to the list, but one can also make use of the individual ranking probabilities p ( δ ( wi, wj )), estimated according to the method of Parzen windows.<sep> For a given word w , we have for each of its neighbors wj the probability of his current rank: p ( δ ( w, wj )) = τw ( wj ). For a given neighbor wj , we can also calculate the probability of any other rank τ : p ( δ ( w, wj )) = τ with τ = 1 , 2 , …<sep> In this section, we propose to use this more local information to improve the results by reordering the k-nearest neighbors.<sep> 6.1 Reranking by the Hungarian algorithm<sep> A simple approach would be to reorder the list based on this criterion, from the most probable neighbors to the least ones.<sep> But our quality criteria associated with each word is imperfect, and such a reranking strongly degrades the results.<sep> We therefore propose instead a method to reorder the k-nearest neighbors in a more local and controlled manner (a word that was not originally in the k-nearest neighbors can not become a k-nearest neighbor, and a word can not be reranked too far from its original rank).<sep> Our problem is expressed by the following matrix, called the profit matrix, in which the rows correspond to words in their original ranks (denoted w 1 to wk ), the columns to new ranks τ at which these words can be assigned, and matrix values are the probabilities of each word wj to appear at rank τ .<sep> Given these probabilities of each word wj appearing at a rank τ, the goal is to find the most likely permutation of the k -nearest neighbors, that is, the one that "benefits" the most.<sep> As pointed out, we want to avoid that an initially very close neighbor is moved far away and vice versa.<sep> This constraint is added to the profit matrix by multiplying the penalty matrix M penalty (see below) with the Hadamard product (element by element matrix product, denoted ◦ ) with the matrix M profit.<sep> We then face a combinatorial optimization problem which can be solved in polynomial time by the Hungarian method (Kuhn and Yaw, 1955, for a description of the algorithm) on the matrix of assignment costs M profit ◦M penalty.<sep> This algorithm was originally proposed to optimize the assignment of workers (in our case, the neighbors) on tasks (in our case, ranks), according to the profit generated by each worker for each task (in our case, the probability that a neighbor stands at a given rank).<sep> It allows to find the optimal assignment given a profit matrix.<sep> The result of this algorithm therefore indicates a new rank for each word.<sep> The algorithm converges to an optimal solution with a complexity O ( k[3] ) (for reranking the k -nearest neighbors).<sep> 6.2 Results<sep> Table 5 presents the performance achieved by our local reranking method compared to the adjusted Okapi-BM25 reference using the same experimental conditions as above.<sep> As before, the considered neighborhood is set to k = 20.<sep> Precisions beyond this threshold are unchanged and thus not reported.<sep> We test the effectiveness of the local reranking on all neighbor lists and on a third of lists with the lowest quality scores.<sep> It appears that the reranking on the whole lists does not provide a real gain.<sep> However, the gain is substantial on the lists with low confidence score.<sep> Moreover, unlike the experiments of section 4, these gains apply by construction to the heads of lists, which are most likely to be used in practice.<sep> This difference between results on the whole set of words and on those with the lowest confidence scores can be explained in two ways.<sep> First, the lists with the highest confidence scores correspond largely to the lists with the best MAP, as expected and illustrated in Figure 3.<sep> This therefore suggests a priori little room for improvement.<sep> Second, regardless of MAP, we can also assume that these lists already have an optimum arrangement of individual probabilities that explains the high confidence score. The reranking thus concerns only few neighbors.<sep> 7 Conclusion and future work<sep> The different contributions proposed in this article do not place themselves all at the same level.<sep> The thesaurus construction using tools from the IR is not a major conceptual innovation, but this approach seems curiously unexplored although it provides very competitive results while requiring minimum implementations through existing tools from IR.<sep> The various propositions exploiting the neighborhood graph to improve the thesaurus are part of a more original approach where the whole thesaurus is considered.<sep> We have specifically examined the aspects of reciprocity and distance, in terms of rank, between two words to offer several contributions.<sep> Some hypotheses, such as reciprocity, are easily defended for relationships such as synonymy, but remain to be validated for more complex relationships.<sep> As such, a more detailed analysis by type of relationship based on the Moby typology remains to be done.<sep> However, the improvements obtained by aggregation over all neighbors or by the local reranking from confidence scores validate our approach.<sep> It should be noted that the gains are small in absolute terms, but, compared to those observed in the field, correspond to significant improvements.<sep> A contrastive analysis between Moby and WordNet would also provide interesting and complementary elements to Ferret (2013b).<sep> The various aspects of this work open up many prospects of research.<sep> For example, many other aggregate functions in addition to those tested in section 4 exist in the literature.<sep> Some may even offer the possibility of integrating the confidence score associated with each neighbor, as Choquet’s or Sugeno’s integrals (Detyniecki, 2000).<sep> More generally, it would be interesting to iteratively use improvements of neighbor lists to update the confidence scores, etc., in the spirit for example of what is proposed by Pedronette et al. (2014).<sep> Beyond the distributional thesauri construction, the proposed methods to compute confidence scores or reorder lists of neighbors can be applied to other problems where the k -nearest neighbor graphs of are built.<sep> Also note that we have only considered a small part of the information carried by the neighborhood graph.<sep> We focused on the aspects of reciprocity, but taking into account other aspects of the graph (in particular the transitivity, or more generally its topology), could lead to further improvements.
Unsupervised extraction of semantic lexical relations [∗]<sep> Abstract<sep> This paper presents a knowledge base containing triples involving pairs of verbs associated with semantic or discourse relations, extracted from the French corpus frWaC by a method based on the presence of a discourse connector linking two adjacent instances of the verbs in the triple.<sep> We detail several measures that evaluate the relevance of the triples and the strength of their association between the semantic/discursive relation and the verb pair.<sep> Intrinsic evaluation is performed with respect to manual annotations. We also evaluate the coverage of our resource with respect to the discourse annotated corpus Annodis.<sep> This study produces promising results demonstrating the potential usefulness of our resource for discourse analysis tasks as well as other semantically oriented tasks.<sep> 1 Introduction<sep> Relational lexical resources, which describe semantic relations between lexical items, have traditionally focused on relations like synonymy or similarity in thesauri, perhaps including some hierarchical semantic relations like hyperonymy or hyponomy or part-whole relations as in the resource Wordnet (Felbaum, 1998).<sep> When they include more varied relations, for example in distributional thesauri (Grefenstette, 1994), these relations are not typed.<sep> The exceptions are rare: the semantic lexicon FrameNet (Baker et al., 1998) includes causal and temporal relations between items designating events, within prototypical scenarios, but these relations are few and relatively negligible compared to the content of this lexicon; the Verbocean database (Chklovski and Pantel, 2004) contains semantic relations of several types between transitive verbs: causal relations (enablement, for example fight/win), temporal precedence (marry/divorce), similarity, antonymy, force (wound/kill), but its coverage is quite low (about 4000 pairs of verbs in its filtered version).<sep> In both cases the validations are partial, and these works seem to have been left pending.<sep> Lexical relations, in particular between verbs, are nevertheless crucial for understanding natural language and for many information processing tasks. They are needed for textual inference, in which one has to infer certain relations between eventualities (Hashimoto et al., 2009; Tremper and Frank, 2013), for information extraction tasks, like finding temporal relations between eventualities mentioned in a text (UzZaman et al., 2013), for automatic summarization (Liu et al., 2007), and for discourse parsing in the absence of explicit discourse markers (Sporleder and Lascarides, 2008). Some works have been dedicated to the inventory of such links for specific relations: for example causal links (Do et al., 2011), temporal links (Chambers and Jurafsky, 2008), implication links (Hashimoto et al., 2009), implication and presupposition (Tremper and Frank, 2013).<sep> The goal of our work is the extraction of certain semantic relations that are essential for discourse analysis. By discourse analysis, we mean the establishment of links between statements, beyond the sentence, as in example (1), where in the absence of an explicit mark (for example with a connector such as therefore or thus), a causality can be inferred between events by knowledge of the semantics of the two highlighted verbs.<sep> (1) The candidate demonstrated his expertise during the last test.<sep> The jury was completely convinced.<sep> Discourse analysis is a difficult task, even for humans.<sep> Indeed, rhetorical relations are frequently implicit and require inference for their identification.<sep> This makes the annotation of corpus tedious and often inaccurate, and relatively little annotated data is currently available. As a result, inductive approaches by learning have a reduced impact, since they require a very large amount of data.<sep> Many works attempt to overcome these limitations by developing weakly supervised approaches, using non-annotated data but containing explicit marks that can be automatically detected to find typical contexts of certain relations.<sep> These approaches (Sporleder & Lascarides, 2008; Braud & Denis, 2013) rely on the hypothesis of regularity of contexts, notably of lexical associations, but indirectly.<sep> Conversely, some approaches (Wellner et al., 2006; Feng & Hirst, 2012) attempt to enrich learning models with fine lexical relations, of the type mentioned above, but are hampered by the low coverage of existing resources.<sep> An explicit, manually compiled list of all possible associations between two verbs and the semantic relations they suggest is infeasible, so we present here an automatic method for compiling such a list, inspired by the Verbocean project (Chklovski and Pantel, 2004).<sep> If our final objective is to help the prediction of discursive (rhetorical) relations, we think it is useful to constitute this lexical resource as an interesting intermediary of other tasks of a semantic nature.<sep> The essence of the method is to identify pairs of verbs in adjacent clauses in a large corpus.<sep> These clauses are often linked by adverbs or more generally by discourse connectors marking one or more discourse relations;<sep> These markers suggest a discursive relation that is recorded in association with the pair. The idea is to retrieve pairs of verbs that are often marked with a discursive (or temporal) relation and to deduce that this pair of verbs can suggest such a relation even in the absence of a marker.<sep> This supposes that the relationship is based not only on the connector, but also on the pair of verbs used: we thus hypothesize partial redundancy of the marker. This hypothesis has been previously discussed in the literature, notably by (Sporleder & Lascarides, 2008) and (Braud, 2011), who tend to support it.<sep> The rest of the article is organized as follows.<sep> We first describe the knowledge base that we have constructed (section 2), then we present our methods for isolating verb pairs implicating discourse or temporal information (section 3).<sep> A third section describes our methods of evaluation (section 4) and a fourth discusses related work (section 5).<sep> 2 Exploring relations between verbs in a corpus<sep> The knowledge base of verbal relations[2] was built from the frWaC corpus, which is part of the WaCKy corpus set (Baroni et al., 2009).<sep> frWaC contains about 1.6 billion words and was collected on the Web on the .fr domain.<sep> We first parsed the documents in our corpus using BONSAI[2] , which first produced a morpho-syntactic labeling using MElt (Denis and Sagot, 2012) and then a syntactic analysis in the form of dependency trees via a French version of the MaltParser (Nivre et al., 2007). The output format is of type CONLL.<sep> Our goal is to find pairs of verbs linked by a relation explicitly marked by a discourse connector in the corpus, as an indication of a regular semantic relation between the two verbs.<sep> The English corpus of the Penn Discourse TreeBank, the PDTB, (Prasad et al., 2008) defines a hierarchy of about thirty relations with a superior level of four groups: a group of causal relations (contingency), a group of temporal relations, a group of "comparison" relations (essentially contrastive links), and a group of "expansion" relations (essentially elaboration or continuation of discourse).<sep> To find explicitly marked relations, we used a lexicon of discourse connectors for French, the manually constructed LEXCONN resource (Roze et al., 2012)[3] .<sep> LEXCONN includes 358 connectors of discourse and their associated syntactic categories and discourse relations, which are close to those of SDRT (Asher & Lascarides, 2003).<sep> Some connectors are ambiguous in that they are associated with several relations.<sep> As a first step, for the sake of simplification, we chose to keep only the unambiguous connectors, which number 263.<sep> Afterwards, disambiguation can be performed to allow all connectors to be taken into account.<sep> LEXCONN distinguishes about twenty relations, and as for the PDTB, we have constituted significant groupings[5] : the relations of explanation ( parce que /because) and result ( ainsi /thus) form the causal group, the relations of temporal organization ( puis, après que /then,after that) have been grouped into a group of narration relations.<sep> We also considered other relations like contrast ( mais /but), continuation ( et, encore /and,again), background ( alors que /while), temporal location ( quand, pendant que /when), detachment ( de toutes façons /anyway), elaboration ( en particulier /in particular), alternation ( ou /or), commentary ( au fait /by the way), rephrasing ( du moins /at least), and evidence ( effectivement /indeed).<sep> A syntactically parsed corpus is therefore searched for these relations.<sep> When a connector is found and its syntactic category verified, if it is close enough to the root of the sentence (at most one dependency link from the root), we look for an inter-sentential link.<sep> The first verb of our pair corresponds in this case to the last verb of the previous sentence in the case of connectors for narration, or to its main verb for all the other relations.<sep> We search for the second verb in the pair within a window of two dependency links after the connector.<sep> If the connector is not close enough to the root of the sentence, we look for an intra-sentential link.<sep> For this, the two verbs of the pair are looked for in the same sentence, on either side of the connector, in a window of two dependency links.<sep> If two verbs are found, we examine their local context to better characterize their usage and to improve our results.<sep> First, if one of the detected verbs is a modal or support verb, the focus is shifted to the verb supported by the modal or support verb, if it exists, while keeping the presence of the support verb in memory.<sep> The presence or absence of negation and reflexive particle are criteria for distinguishing verbs (e.g., comprendre /understand vs. ne pas comprendre /not understand, agir /act vs. s’agir /concern are all distinct entries). In addition, two types of processing are carried out to distinguish the different meanings of verbs.<sep> To get at different verb senses, we search for idiomatic usage of prepositions using the Dicovalence resource (Van Den Eynde and Mertens, 2010), which contains valency frames for more than 3700 simple French verbs.<sep> In addition, the Lefff resource (Lexique des Formes Fléchies du Français) (Sagot, 2010) allows us to identify idiomatic verbal locutions (examples: prendre garde, faire référence).<sep> We also encode other information that do not lead to distinct lexical entries : tense, and voice.<sep> The following two examples illustrate this extraction method (the dependency scheme is presented, with the links used for extraction represented in bold). Example of intraphrasal relation:<sep> Example of interphrastic relation:<sep> Once we have obtained a list of verb pairs associated with a connector, we aggregate this data to get a list of distinct triple types (verb1, verb2, relation).<sep> Given that we have used only unambiguous connectors, the association of a relation with a connector is immediate.<sep> We associate to each triplet the number of intra-sentential, intersentential and total number of occurrences.<sep> The other data collected mentioned above (time, verb support...) are also stored in a separate table.<sep> This method has isolated more than 2 million occurrences of triplets, of which 95% are intra-sentential[6] , in the corpus. These occurrences have been grouped into more than 1 million distinct types of triplets in the knowledge base.<sep> Among these triples, 6.2% have 5 or more occurrences.<sep> TABLE 1 – The distribution of relationships in the database;<sep> The comment, reformulation and evidence relations have an almost zero frequency of appearance.<sep> Table 1 summarizes the distribution of triples by relation.<sep> Note that triples with contrast and causal relations comprise the majority in the database.<sep> This does not mean that these are the most frequent relations in the corpus but only that they are the most frequently marked by the connectors we considered.<sep> Taking as a point of comparison the Annodis resource (Afantenos et al., 2012), a corpus annotated manually in discourse relations, we can thus note that the continuation and elaboration relations are much more frequent than in our automatic annotations.<sep> This means that these relationships are probably less based on the presence of an explicit mark such as a connector.<sep> 3 Measuring the semantic association of a pair of verbs<sep> In the last section we presented the data collected on the verb pairs linked by the chosen markers. We now present the measures we have used to rank verb pairs with respect to the strength of their association.<sep> We were inspired by the classic measures of lexical association, based on the study of co-occurrences, and adapted them to the context, and added some measures used on specific relations, such as the measures of Do et al. (2011) to detect the causal links between verbs.<sep> Measures of lexical association used in research on co-occurrences in distributional semantics pick out significant associations, taking into account the frequency of the related items.<sep> They are an essential component of distributional approaches to semantics and in the construction of word vector spaces.<sep> We have retained a simple measure, PMI (pointwise mutual information) and its variants, local, normalized, weighted, which are designed to reduce biases in the original measure (Evert, 2005).<sep> The idea behind PMI is to estimate whether the probability of the co-occurrence of two items is greater than the a priori probability of the two items appearing independently.<sep> We applied this measure to triplets consisting of a pair of verbs with a semantic/discursive relation, because what interests us is to see if the probability of the two items with a particular semantic relation is higher than the a priori probability of the three items occurring independently.<sep> For all our measures, we actually consider the event consisting of the appearance of two lexical items in a certain relation indicated by an explicit discourse marker.<sep> This is similar to the syntactic approaches in distributional semantics, which weighted the associations of lexical items in a certain syntactic relation (such as subject-verb-object, or verb-object-noun).<sep> In the case of complete co-occurrence of the three items, we have:<sep> Thus, the normalized PMI is defined as follows :<sep> Note that this measure is between -1 and 1, approaching -1 when the items never appear together, taking the value 0 in the case of independence, and the value 1 when they always appear together.<sep> The weighted PMI proposed by Lin & Pantel (2002) is supposed to correct the bias of PMI for rare triples:<sep> The local PMI, on the other hand, makes it possible to take into account the absolute frequency of occurrence of the triplet:<sep> We were also inspired by a measure of (Mirroshandel et al., 2013), originally defined to measure the precision of subcategorization frames, to define the specificity measure :<sep> Do et al. (2011) give a complex measure for the contribution of two predicates that support a causal relation, which we have used as a basis for the following measure:<sep> Note that the initial measure of (Do et al., 2011) is also a function of the IDF (inverse document frequency), which measures the inter-document frequency of the two verbs, and the distance between the two instances.<sep> These last two factors are not applicable to our triplets, and have therefore been ignored.<sep> We also defined a measure to evaluate the contribution of each element in the triplet to its informativeness, similar to the specificity described above.<sep> 4 Evaluating relationships<sep> To evaluate the interest of the extracted verb pairs, we carried out several evaluations that are intended to be complementary.<sep> First, we want an intrinsic evaluation of the link between verbs, in order to validate the base as a semantic resource, which can be used for different tasks. This is presented below (section 4.1). We then present a beginning of extrinsic validation, by studying the potential impact of the resource on a specific task, namely the prediction of discursive relations in the absence of explicit marking (section 4.2).<sep> 4.1 Intrinsic evaluation<sep> To evaluate the links extracted intrinsically, we first studied the possibility of reliably assigning a semantic link to a verb pair in an "inherent" way, that is, independently of any linguistic context.<sep> For example, is it possible to judge that there is a typical causality link between push and fall , in scenarios where they share some arguments (subject, object, …), these scenarios being left to the annotator’s imagination (section 4.1.1).<sep> In a second stage, we selected several verb pairs and a hundred contexts in which these pairs appear together in the original corpus, to judge the semantic link in context (section 4.1.2).<sep> In both cases we restricted the study to three relation groups : causal, contrastive, and narrative.<sep> These are the most often marked relations and correspond to different types of links with a meaningful semantic aspect (as opposed to the “continuation” relation for instance, which is often marked too).<sep> 4.1.1 Out of context evaluation of pairs<sep> For out of context judgments, we adopted the following protocol : one of the authors chose for each relation 100 verbs with equivalent proportions of good and bad normalized PMI scores.<sep> Then the other three authors judged the validity of associating each of the 300 pairs with the corresponding relation, without any knowledge of the source of these pairs.<sep> The table summarizes the inter-annotator agreements, estimated with Cohen’s Kappa (Carletta, 1996).<sep> It quickly became apparent that the task was very difficult or impossible for causality, difficult for narration, and moderately difficult for contrast, if one judges classically that a kappa around 0.6 is acceptable, especially for a judgment of a semantic nature.<sep> We decided to ignore these judgments for the cause and narration, and kept the judgments on contrast, after adjudication between the three annotators. To evaluate the association measures chosen, we statistically tested if they could discriminate between the two groups of verb pairs (those judged positively and negatively by the annotators).<sep> Table 3 summarizes these tests, where we see that all measures statistically discriminate the two groups, except for the raw counts of co-occurrence.<sep> TABLE 2 – Inter-annotator agreements for out-of-context annotations: kappa by pairs of annotators and mean kappas.<sep> TABLE 3 – MannWhitney-U tests to estimate the difference of measures on groups of contrastive or non-contrastive verb pairs. The measures are sorted by increasing p-value, with non-significant values in the second part of the table.<sep> 4.1.2 In context evaluation<sep> For a more precise evaluation of semantic links, we also considered contextual association judgments: in addition to facilitating the judgment, the idea is also that the typicality of the relationship between two verbs can be estimated by the proportion of contexts where they appear together with the link we consider.<sep> We can then observe if this proportion is correlated with the association measures we already presented.<sep> The pitfall of this method is its cost in annotation: if we want to evaluate a link between two specific verbs, we need a certain number of contexts to support the judgment, and we need to repeat this evaluation on a sufficient number of pairs of verbs.<sep> It is also necessary to have a sample of pairs that cover enough different values to observe significant correlations, while we cannot predict in advance how they will be judged by the annotators.<sep> We selected 40 contexts for each of the 15 pairs of verbs we chose, 5 for each of the target relation (cause, narration, contrast).<sep> Selected pairs range over different values of normalized PMI, again chosen by one of the authors independently of the others, who annotated the 600 contexts separately, before proceeding to the adjudication of the reference.<sep> Prior to adjudication, raw agreement was 78% on average, for an average kappa of 0.46 (and a maximum of 0.49).<sep> These values seem low, which highlights the difficulty of the task.<sep> The result of this annotation is presented in table 4. TABLE 4 – The list of verb pairs manually evaluated in context, with the relation to be judged and the association ratio resulting from the human adjudication.<sep> We then measured the correlation between this association index obtained from human annotation, and the association measures presented above. We report two separate correlations here: one based on all annotated contexts, and one on the subset of contexts devoid of explicit markers of the considered relation (implicit contexts).<sep> The latter is important to quantify the actual impact of the method, and to avoid tautology which would consist of finding explicitly marked links in the corpus to identify the same marked links in particular contexts.<sep> In fact, contexts without explicit marks are the only ones that did not intervene in the calculation of the association measures.<sep> TABLE 3 – Pearson correlation for the 15 pairs considered and measures from section 3, in decreasing order.<sep> That being said, we can observe that the mutual information measures are well correlated, even the simple PMI, and that the W_combined measure that we proposed in section 3 is also useful.<sep> We also observed results on each relation separately, although one should be careful drawing conclusions from these results since the correlations are then computed on 5 points only. These results (not shown here) show a lot of variation between relations.<sep> The U_do measure, designed for causal relations, does indeed produce good results for these relations, but does not generalize well to our other chosen relations.<sep> Also, the measure of local PMI seems to work very well on narration and causal relations.<sep> These results allowed us to identify the three best measures: normalized PMI, specificity, and W_combined.<sep> We observed that the last two assign their maximal value to several pairs, so we used them in a lexicographical ordering to sort all associated pairs, using normalized PMI to break ties.<sep> Table 6 thus presents the best pairs obtained for the narration, continuation, cause and contrast relations.<sep> TABLE 6 – Lists of the 10 best pairs of the base according to our lexicographical ranking.<sep> 4.2 Extrinsic evaluation<sep> The primary goal of our work is to create a resource of semantic relations, the main intended application of which is to help predict rhetorical relations. In order to evaluate the performance of our triplet database in this context, we intend to use it as additional features to an inductive prediction model.<sep> We first tried to assess the potential impact of our resource on the prediction task by studying its coverage in relation to a corpus of French texts annotated with rhetorical relations, the Annodis corpus (Afantenos et al., 2012).<sep> To improve existing models, a significant number of the predictions to be made must involve a verb pair for which we have information in the resource.<sep> A strong indicator of the potential success of the task is also the proportion of relations between two segments containing two verbs existing in the base, and of which the majority of the link is part of the group concerned by the relation, for example for an explanation relation, the fact that the two verbs are linked by a causal link.<sep> This is interesting only in the absence of an explicit marking of the target relation via a discourse connector, i.e. for implicit relations.<sep> Furthermore, always in the case of implicit links, it is interesting to have the information that two verbs are in a certain semantic relationship, even if it does not correspond directly to a group linked to the relationship being sought: a potential causal link between two events could at least indicate that a temporal link is relevant for considering the link between two units of discourse.<sep> To conduct this study, we relied again on the Lexconn marker database.<sep> As an approximation we considered that a relation between two discourse units is explicit when a Lexconn marker is present in any of the two segments, and one of the potential senses of the marker is the annotated relation.<sep> This may overestimate the number of explicit instances but ensures that all implicit instances are indeed implicit (assuming a good enough coverage of the marker resource).<sep> To simplify, we only considered the links between simple discourse units, Annodis also having relations between sets of simple segments (so-called "complex" segments).<sep> Table 7 presents the coverage results, for the main relations.<sep> Note that only a small part of the corpus is concerned (400 out of about 2000 relations between simple segments), the others often involving only a verb, and some being forgotten due to tagging or detection errors.<sep> Again, these figures should be taken as conservative estimates.<sep> TABLE 7 – Coverage of verb pairs in the V[2] R database with respect to instances of the Annodis corpus involving two verbs.<sep> Pair = pair of verbs in segments connected by a rhetorical relation, Triplet = the pair of verbs associated with the rhetorical relation in one instance of the corpus.<sep> Except for the first line, all numbers are percentages.<sep> AR = background, cont = continuation, elab = elaboration. We have listed several types of information: the presence in the database of verb pairs of instances of the discursive corpus, the presence of verb pairs associated with the relation that links them in the instance of Annodis considered [7], that is to say the presence of the triplet (verb1, verb2, relation) in the database, and the restriction of these statistics to contexts where there is a presence or absence of an explicit marker of a relation.<sep> We can see that almost all the verbs in the corpus are in the database in at least one pair (the two exceptions are a verb not lemmatised by the tagger and a verbal phrase), but the pairs in the database only partially cover the pairs appearing in Annodis. In fact, between 60 and 70% of the instances associate verbs in the database (depending on the relation), and a little less if we consider implicit instances (around 50% on average), except for the contrast relation, which is strongly marked in Annodis.<sep> It is very encouraging to note that a high proportion of unmarked contexts contain verb pairs that are collected in a marked context, even for rarely marked relations like elaboration or continuation—contexts with these relations are the majority in Annodis. Furthermore, more than half of these contexts are correctly associated with the right relation in the database (possibly among others).<sep> The hypothesis of the partial redundancy of connectors appears useful when considering the corpus as a whole to isolate verbal associations relevant for discourse.<sep> All of this obviously needs to be pursued by integrating this information into a discursive relation tagger, but it seems promising in this perspective.<sep> 5 Related work<sep> There are two different types of work related to our approach.<sep> The first group aims to alleviate the lack of annotated data for discourse parsing by using a weakly supervised approach, exploiting the presence of discourse connectors in a large non-annotated corpus.<sep> Each pair of elementary discourse units is automatically annotated with the discourse relation triggered by the presence of the connector (connectors are often filtered for non-discursive uses).<sep> Those markers are then eliminated from the corpus so that the model will not be informed by the presence of those markers, thus creating artificial implicit relations.<sep> The pioneering article in this approach is Marcu and Echihabi (2002).<sep> The relations used in this article correspond to a coarser level of granularity compared to the relations typically used in RST (Mann & Thompson, 1988), nevertheless obtaining fairly low scores.<sep> The same approach was also pursued by Sporleder & Lascarides (2008) obtaining results barely above chance as shown in Braud & Denis (2013). The latter observed the relatively low performance of this method of predicting implicit relations with "artificial" data (explicit relation made artificially implicit by the removal of the marker) compared to the results obtained with "natural" data (implicit relation annotated by a human being).<sep> They then proposed a method consisting of combining these two types of data either at the level of the data set or directly at the level of the learning algorithm, thus obtaining a significant improvement on the ANNODIS corpus.<sep> Our approach is different in that it explicitly isolates the links between pairs of verbs, to extend the use of this information to other tasks.<sep> In a next step, however, we will try to measure the contribution of our resource for this task of predicting relationships compared to previous approaches, thus allowing an extrinsic evaluation.<sep> A second group aims at identifying discourse relations (implicit or not) by focusing on the use of finegrained lexical relations as another feature during the training phase.<sep> Most of this work focuses mainly on the use of lexical relations between two verbs.<sep> Chklovski and Pantel (2004), for example, rely on specific patterns constructed manually for each semantic relation between ( similarity, strength, antonymy, enablement and temporal happens-before ).<sep> The web was then used as a corpus in order to estimate the PMI between two verbs and a pattern (a precise measurement cannot be achieved over the web since the probability of a pattern is not precisely known over the entire web).<sep> A threshold on the value of the PMI (manually fixed) permits thus to determine the pairs of verbs that are related to the relation denoted by the pattern.<sep> In the same spirit, Kozareva (2012) is using a weakly supervised approach for the extraction of pairs of verbs that are potentially implied in a cause-effect relation.<sep> Her method consists in using patterns applied to the web in order to extract pairs and generate new seeds.<sep> Similar work was done by Do et al. (2011), however, they took into account not only verbs but also event denoting nouns.<sep> They focused on causal relationships, using discursive markers as a clue.<sep> According to their work, an event is a predicate with a specific number of arguments and thus the association of events is the sum of the association between predicates, between predicates and arguments and between arguments.<sep> All their measures are based on PMI corrected for certain cases (too frequent pairs, textual distance between the predicates of a pair, frequency of predicates).<sep> Using Gigaword as a corpus and a reimplementation of Lin et al. (2014) they have extracted discourse relations.<sep> An inductive logic programming approach is finally used exploiting the interaction between causal pairs and discourse relations in order to extract causal links.<sep> Those papers focus on specific relations with the exception of Chklovski and Pantel (2004) who do not present a systematic evaluation of their results.<sep> Finally, we must mention the approaches which while focusing on the learning of discourse structures, nonetheless enrich their systems with lexical information.<sep> Feng and Hirst (2012) have used HILDA (Hernault et al., 2010) adding more features.<sep> A specific family of features represents lexical similarity based on the hierarchical distance in VERBNET and WORDNET.<sep> In a similar fashion, Wellner et al. (2006) focus on intra-sentential discourse relations adding lexical information on the features based on measures proposed by Lin (1998) calculated on the British National Corpus.<sep> Those approaches use thus only information on lexical similarity without semantically typing this link. The impact of this information seems limited.<sep> As far as evaluation is concerned, our method is similar to that followed in Tremper and Frank (2013) for implication relations combining in and out of context evaluation for verbal associations.<sep> Their inter-annotator agreement is similar to ours (0.42-0.44 of Kappa) with very different choices : the annotators were supposed to discriminate verbal links between the different possible sub-cases.<sep> The pairs of verbs were identified by the system of Lin and Pantel.<sep> These authors also present a classification model among the different types of relationships, assuming that two verbs are semantically related.<sep> 6 Conclusions<sep> We have presented a knowledge base of triples involving pairs of verbs associated with semantic or discourse relations. We extracted these triples from the large French corpus, frWaC, using discourse connectors as markers of relations between two adjacent clauses containing verbs.<sep> We investigated several measures to evaluate the pertinence of the triplets and the strength of association between the semantic/discursive relation and the pair of verbs.<sep> We used manual annotations to evaluate our method and select the best measures, and we also studied the coverage of our resource on the discourse annotated corpus Annodis.<sep> This allowed us to verify that a large number of implicit triples in Annodis are present in our knowledge base.<sep> Our positive results encourage us to continue our work with a view to using this resource to improve methods of discourse analysis, but also for tasks of a semantic nature.<sep> This work has been supported by the French agency Agence Nationale de la Recherche (ANR-12-CORD-0004).<sep> 1. The PDTB English corpus, for example, contains 52% unmarked relations (Prasad et al., 2008).<sep> 2. Available as an SQLite database at https://dl.dropboxusercontent.com/u/78938139/v2r_db<sep> 3. Available at http://alpage.inria.fr/statgram/frdep/fr_stat_dep_parsing.html, cf also (Candito et al., 2010)<sep> 3. Freely available at : https://gforge.inria.fr/frs/download.php/31052/lexconn.tar.gz.<sep> 5. We illustrate each relation with examples of potentially ambiguous explicit markers between parentheses.<sep> 6. The low proportion of inter-sentential occurrences comes from the conservative scheme we chose for finding these occurrences, which only considers connectors at the beginning of the second sentence.<sep> We have indeed judged the risk of producing noise by widening the possible schemes too important.<sep> 7. Each pair of verbs extracted from annodis is present only once.
Kernels for sentence rewriting with lexical-semantic types<sep> Abstract<sep> Many high level natural language processing problems can be framed as determining if two given sentences are a rewriting of each other.<sep> An effective solution is to learn rewrites based on kernel methods that measure the similarity between two rewrites of pairs of sentences.<sep> However, these methods generally do not take into account semantic variations between words, which would allow for capturing a greater number of rewriting rules.<sep> In this paper, we propose the definition and implementation of a new class of kernel functions, based on type-enriched string rewriting, to fill this gap.<sep> We evaluate it on two tasks, the recognition of paraphrases and textual implications.<sep> 1 Introduction<sep> The recognition of the proximity of meanings between sentences is a fundamental aspect of many natural language processing applications (NLP). This includes the recognition of textual entailment (RTE) (Dagan et al., 2006), paraphrase identification (Dolan et al., 2004) and semantic textual similarity (Agirre et al., 2012).<sep> These problems are generally represented as classification problems solved by supervised learning methods based on different representations of phrases and linguistic phenomena.<sep> In (Wan et al. , 2006; Lintean & Rus, 2011; Jimenez et al. , 2013), sentences are represented by bags of words or n-grams, and rely mostly on exact lexical matching.<sep> The recognition of lexical variations between two statements of close meaning is handled by the addition of external resources, such as WordNet (Mihalcea et al., 2006; Islam & Inkpen, 2009). The consideration of a structured representation of sentences to treat variations in surface forms is based on the comparison of syntactic trees (Calvo et al., 2014).<sep> (Heilman & Smith, 2010) introduce a model of editing distance on these trees.<sep> (Socher et al. , 2011) use recursive auto-encoders operating on constituent trees to learn to identify paraphrases. The best systems combine different methods, such as the meta-classifier of (Madnani et al. , 2012), based on machine translation metrics, and to date have the best results on paraphrase recognition.<sep> Some methods (Zanzotto et al., 2007; Zanzotto et al., 2010; Bu et al., 2012) use kernel functions to learn what makes two sentence pairs similar. (Zanzotto et al., 2007) propose a kernel function for comparing pairs of syntactic trees, which is then extended to graphs (Zanzotto et al., 2010). (Bu et al., 2012) introduce a string rewriting kernel.<sep> FIGURE 1 - The rewrite rule (A) rewrites (B) but not (C).<sep> In this article, we propose to extend these methods, by giving the possibility to specify in a fine-grained way how two words can be paired and we define a new type-enriched string rewriting kernel.<sep> We detail how to efficiently compute this type of kernel and evaluate it on two TAL tasks.<sep> Our method obtains state-of-the-art results on paraphrase identification and outperforms comparable methods on RTE.<sep> 2 State of the art of kernel methods for string rewriting<sep> Kernel functions measure the similarity between two elements.<sep> Used in machine learning methods like SVM, they allow complex decision functions to be learned in classification tasks (Vapnik, 2000).<sep> The goal of a well-designed kernel function is to have a high value when computed on two instances of same label, and a low value for two instances of different label.<sep> Kernel methods have been rapidly employed in natural language processing.<sep> (Lodhi et al., 2002) use the string kernel to count the number of common substrings between two texts and apply it to text classification.<sep> However, classifying sentence rewrites involves classifying pairs of sentences and requires capturing two types of links: the link between one sentence and the other in the same rewrite pair, and the link between one pair and another.<sep> (Zanzotto et al., 2007) propose a kernel function for comparing pairs of syntactic trees, which is then extended to graphs (Zanzotto et al., 2010).<sep> Their method first calculates the best pairing of the nodes of the trees in a pair, in order to capture the entities that the two sentences are about and form a single tree.<sep> A tree kernel, introduced by (Moschitti, 2006), then counts the common subtrees of the two pairs.<sep> (Bu et al., 2012) introduce a string rewriting kernel to capture syntactic dependencies over pairs of sentences viewed as sequences of words, which allows to learn complex types of rewriting.<sep> Where the alignment of the words of the two phrases of a same couple is carried out a priori in (Zanzotto et al., 2010) to reduce the calculation cost, the contribution of (Bu et al., 2012) proposes an efficient algorithm to integrate the optimal calculation of these links in the final calculation of the kernel.<sep> However, all these methods are incapable of introducing lexical variations between words or a semantic typing of them, thus limiting the types of rewritings learned.<sep> This is the problem that we propose to solve in this article, by introducing the notion of type to enrich the sentence rewriting kernels of (Bu et al., 2012).<sep> 3 Phrase rewriting kernels<sep> Recently defined, the string rewriting kernels count the number of common rewritings between two pairs of sentences seen as sequences of words (Bu et al., 2012).<sep> The rewriting rule (A) in Figure 1 can be viewed as a kind of phrasal paraphrase with linked variables (Madnani and Dorr, 2010).<sep> Rule (A) rewrites (B)’s first sentence into its second but it does not however rewrite the sentences in (C).<sep> However, it could be interesting that rule (A) also triggers on (C), in order to increase the similarities between the rewrites.<sep> This is the motivation behind our contribution: we present and implement typed phrase rewriting kernels that take into account lexical-semantic variations in word pairs.<sep> In the following, we understand by phrase a sequence of words, without adding more linguistic constraints.<sep> We denote ( s, t ) ∈ (Σ [∗] × Σ [∗] ) an instance of string rewriting, with a source string s and a target string t , both finite sequences of elements in Σ the finite set of characters.<sep> Suppose that we are given training data of such instances labeled in { +1 , − 1 } , for paraphrase/nonparaphrase or entailment/non-entailment in applications.<sep> We can use a kernel method to train on this data and learn to automatically classify unlabeled instances.<sep> A kernel on string rewriting instances is a function:<sep> where Φ maps each instance into a high dimension feature space of these characteristics.<sep> Kernels allow us to avoid the potentially expensive explicit representation of Φ through the inner product space they define.<sep> The purpose of the string rewriting kernels is to measure the similarity between two pairs of strings in term of the number of rewriting rules of a set R that they share.<sep> Φ is thus naturally defined by Φ( s, t ) = ( φr ( s, t )) r∈R with φr ( s, t ) = n the number of contiguous substring pairs of ( s, t ) that rewriting rule r matches.<sep> According to the definition of R, Φ can be of unbounded dimension and is not directly calculable, hence the interest of this kernel approach.<sep> 4 Sentence rewriting cores with types<sep> 2.2 Typed rewriting rules<sep> Let the wildcard domain D ⊆ Σ [∗] be the set of strings which can be replaced by wildcards.<sep> We now present the formal framework of the typeenriched string rewriting kernels.<sep> Let Γ p be the set of pattern types and Γ v the set of variable types .<sep> To a type γp ∈ Γ p , we associate the typing relation γp ≈ ⊆ Σ × Σ.<sep> To a type γv ∈ Γ v ,we associate the typing relation γv ; ⊆ D × D .<sep> Together with the typing relations, we call the association of Γ p and Γ v the typing scheme of the kernel.<sep> Let Σ p be defined as<sep> We finally define typed rewriting rules.<sep> A typed rewriting rule is a triple r = ( βs, βt, τ ), where βs, βt ∈ (Σ p ∪{∗} ) [∗] denote source and target string typed patterns and τ ⊆ ind∗ ( βs ) ×ind∗ ( βt ) denotes the alignments between the wildcards in the two string patterns.<sep> Here ind∗ ( β ) denotes the set of indices of wildcards in β .<sep> We say that a rewriting rule ( βs, βt, τ ) matches a pair of strings ( s, t ) if and only if the following conditions are true:<sep> - string patterns βs , resp. βt , can be turned into s , resp. t , by: - substituting each element [ a|b ] of Σ p in the string pattern with an a or b ( ∈ Σ)<sep> - substituting each wildcard in the string pattern with an element of the wildcard domain D - ∀ ( i, j ) ∈ τ , s, resp. t, substitutes the wildcards at index i , resp. j , by s∗ ∈ D , resp. t∗ , such that there exists a variable type γ ∈ Γ v γ with s∗ ; t∗ .<sep> A type-enriched string rewriting kernel (TESRK) is simply a string rewriting kernel as defined in Equation 1 but with R a set of typed rewriting rules.<sep> This class of kernel functions depends on wildcard domain D and the set R, which can be chosen to allow for more flexibility in the matching of pairs of words in the rewritings.<sep> Within this framework, the k-gram bijective string rewriting kernel (kb-SRK) is defined by the wildcard domain D = Σ and the ruleset R = { ( βs, βt, τ ) | βs, βt ∈ (Σ p∪{∗} ) [k] , τ bijective }<sep> 4.2 Example<sep> In this section, we present an example of how kb-SRK is applied to real pairs of sentences, highlighting the limitations of the core and how we can overcome them by changing the typing scheme.<sep> Let us consider again Figure 1,<sep> (A) is a rewriting rule with βs = ( heard , ∗ , ∗ ), βt = ( ∗ , was , ∗ ), τ = { (2 , 1); (3 , 3) } .<sep> Each string pattern has the same length, and pairs of wildcards in the two patterns are aligned bijectively.<sep> This is a valid rule for kb-SRK.<sep> It rewrites the pair of sentences (B): each aligned pair of wildcards is substituted in source and target sentences by the same word and string patterns of (A) can indeed be turned into pairs of substrings of the sentences.<sep> However, it cannot rewrite (C) with the original definition of kb-SRK.<sep> We change Γ p to { hypernym, id } where a ≈ b if and only if a and b have a common hypernym in WordNet.<sep> And we change Γ v to Γ v = { same pronoun, en- same pronoun tailment, id } where a ;b if and only if a and b are a pronoun of the same person and same number, and a[entailment] ; b if and only if verb a has a relation of entailment with b in WordNet.<sep> By redefining the typing scheme, rule (A) can now match (C).<sep> 5 Computing TESRK<sep> 5.1 Formulation of the problem<sep> The k-SRK kernel can be computed efficiently (Bu et al., 2012).<sep> This section shows that it is possible to compute an enriched version of its type effectively. While it is impossible to keep the same theoretical complexity bounds in time, experiments show that the computing time is of the same order of magnitude.<sep> A type-enriched kb-SRK is parameterized by k the length of k-grams, and its typing scheme the sets Γ p and Γ v and their associated relations.<sep> We will omit the annotations of Γ p and Γ v to Kk and K[¯] k for clarity and because they typically will not change while we test different values for k .<sep> We rewrite the scalar product of Equation 1 to better fit the k-gram framework:<sep> where K[¯] k (( αs 1 , αt 1) , ( αs 2 , αt 2)) is the number of different rewriting rules which match two pairs of k-grams (the same rule cannot trigger twice in k-gram substrings):<sep> with 1 r the indicator function of rule r : 1 if r matches the pair of k-grams, 0 otherwise.<sep> Computing Kk as defined in Equation 3 is obviously intractable.<sep> There is O (( n − k + 1)[4] ) terms in the sum, where n is the length of the longest string, and each term involves enumerating every rewriting rule in R .<sep> 5.2 Computing K[¯] k in type-enriched kb-SRK<sep> The enumeration of the rewriting rules themselves, in Equation 4, is not calculable in a reasonable time: there are | Σ |[2] [k] rules without wildcards and without any other type of relation than identity, and | Σ | is conceivably the size of a typical lexicon in any relevant application.<sep> In fact, we just have to constructively generate the rules which substitute their string patterns correctly to simultaneously produce both pairs of k-grams ( αs 1 , αt 1) and ( αs 2 , αt 2).<sep> Let the operator ⊗ be such that α 1 ⊗ α 2 = (( α 1[1] , α 2[1]) , …, ( α 1[ k ] , α 2[ k ])).<sep> This operation is generally known as zipping in functional programming.<sep> We use the function CountPerfectMatchings computed by Algorithm 1 to recursively count the number of rewriting rules matching both ( αs 1 , αt 1) and ( αs 2 , αt 2).<sep> We present the formula we use to calculate K[¯] k , and we explain its correction by detailing the algorithm:<sep> Algorithm 1 takes as input the remaining character pairs in αs 1 ⊗ αs 2 and αt 1 ⊗ αt 2 and outputs the number of ways they can be rewritten in common.<sep> First (lines 2 and 3), the base case where both inputs are empty is handled.<sep> There is exactly 1 way to rewrite the empty set itself: do nothing.<sep> In lines 4 to 9, there are no more source pairs, so the algorithm continues to deplete target pairs as long as they have a common pattern type.<sep> If a target couple has no common type of motif, it means that these two mismatched words should substitute a joker in a valid rule, but as the source is empty, this joker cannot be aligned and the algorithm returns 0.<sep> In the general case (lines 11 to 19), consider the first character pair ( a 1 , a 2) in the reminder of αs 1 ⊗ αs 2 in line 12.<sep> What follows in the computation depends on its types.<sep> Every character pair in αt 1 ⊗ αt 2 that can be paired through variable types with ( a 1 , a 2) (lines 15 to 19) is a new potential wildcard alignment, so we try all the possible alignment and recursively continue the computation after removing both aligned pairs.<sep> And if ( a 1 , a 2) are words with a common pattern type, they do not need to substitute a wildcard (lines 13 and 14) and we can choose not to create a new alignment at this stage, but just continue the recursion by "forgetting" the pattern pair.<sep> This algorithm enumerates all configurations such that each character pair has a common pattern type or is matched 1-for-1 with a character pair with common variable types, which is exactly the definition of a rewriting rule in TESRK.<sep> Algorithm 1: Naive Counting of Perfect Matchings<sep> FIGURE 2 – Bipartite graph of word pairs, with edges between potential jokers<sep> The name of the function CountPerfectMatchings is justified because this problem is actually equivalent to counting the perfect matchings of the bipartite graph of potential wildcards, i.e. the graph having as vertices the potential wildcards and with an edge between two couples of words if they verify the condition of line 15 on their variable types.<sep> (Valiant, 1979) demonstrates that this problem is not efficiently calculable.<sep> In our implementation we represent the graph with its biadjacency matrix, and if our typing relations are constant in time with respect to k , the function has a O ( k ) time complexity without including its recursive calls.<sep> The number of recursive calls can be greater than k [2] which is the number of perfect matchings in a complete bipartite graph of 2 k vertices.<sep> In section 6 we show however that on linguistic data, the algorithm performs a linear number of recursive calls for low values of k , and up to a quadratic number for k > 10 –which is way past the point where the kernel becomes ineffective.<sep> As an example, Figure 2 shows the zipped k- grams for source and target as a bipartite graph with 2 k vertices and potential wildcard edges.<sep> Assuming that vertices ( a, a ) and ( b, b[′] ) have common pattern types, they can be ignored as in lines 7 and 14 of algorithm 1.<sep> However, the word pairs ( c 1 , c 2) to ( f 1 , f 2) must substitute wildcards in a matching rewriting rule.<sep> If we align ( c 1 , c 2) with ( e 1 , e 2) in line 16, the recursive call will return 0 because the other two pairs cannot be aligned.<sep> A valid rule is generated if c ’s are paired with f ’s and d ’s with e ’s.<sep> The kb-SRK did not have to test all these possibilities thanks to the transitivity of its only type (identity) (Bu et al., 2012).<sep> In type-enriched kb-SRK, wildcard pairing is less constrained, which gives better expressiveness but also leads to combinatorial explosion in the calculation.<sep> 5.3 Calcul de Kk<sep> Even with an efficient method for computing K[¯] k , implementing Kk directly by applying Equation 3 remains impractical.<sep> The main idea of our algorithm is to efficiently compute a reasonably sized set C of elements (( αs 1 , αt 1) , ( αs 2 , αt 2)) which has the essential property of including all elements such that K ¯ k (( αs 1 , αt 1) , ( αs 2 , αt 2)) ̸ = 0.<sep> By definition of C, it follows that it is possible to compute efficiently:<sep> There are a number of ways to do it, with a trade-off between computation time and size of the reduced domain C.<sep> Our method follows the following property: Kk (( αs 1 , αt 1) , ( αs 2 , αt 2)) = 0 if there exists a couple of words ( a 1 , a 2) ∈ αs 1 ⊗ αs 2 without a common pattern type such that there is no couple ( b 1 , b 2) ∈ αt 1 ⊗ αt 2 compatible with it for a variable type, i.e. with a 1 γ⇝ b 1 and a 2 γ⇝ b 2 for a γ ∈ Γ v .<sep> This is obviously also applicable for a couple of αt 1 ⊗ αt 2.<sep> More simply, character pairs with no common pattern type are mismatched and have to substitute a wildcard in a rewriting rule matching both ( αs 1 , αt 1) and ( αs 2 , αt 2).<sep> If it happens that no wildcard alignment can be found for such a word pair, no rule rewrites the two k-gram pairs and it is possible to ignore these entries in the calculation of Kk.<sep> This filtering can be done in reasonable time and the resulting set C contains only a linear number of entries in function of n according to our experiments.<sep> Algorithm 2 computes a set C to be used in Equation 6 for computing the final value of kernel Kk .<sep> All maps in the algorithm are hash table based and are maps to multisets.<sep> Multisets are used throughout the calculation: they are an extension of sets where elements can appear multiple times, the number of times being called the multiplicity .<sep> Typically implemented as hash tables from set elements to integers, they allow for constant-time retrieval of the number of a given element.<sep> Union ( ∪ ) and intersection ( ∩ ) have special definitions on multisets, which is good to remember since these operations are used in the algorithm.<sep> If 1 A ( x ) is the multiplicity of x in A , we have 1 A∪B ( x ) = max (1 A ( x ) , 1 B ( x )) and 1 A∩B ( x ) = min (1 A ( x ) , 1 B ( x )).<sep> Let us now comment on how the algorithm unfolds.<sep> In lines 1 to 4, it indexes the words in the source strings by the words in the target strings which have common variable types, and vice versa.<sep> It allows lines 15 to 19 to efficiently associate a character pair with the set of opposing k-gram pairs with a matching character pair with common variable types, i.e. the k-gram pairs with which it could substitute an aligned wildcard.<sep> In lines 20 to 28 we keep only the k-gram quadruples whose wildcard candidates (character pairs with no common pattern) from one side all find matches on the other side.<sep> At line 26, we did not find any character pair with no common pattern, so we save the k-gram pair as ”all-pattern”.<sep> Pure motif k-grams will be paired in lines 8 to 10 in the result.<sep> Finally, in line 11, the algorithm calculates the multi-set union of the entries satisfying the joker inclusion test; calling swap in one case is necessary to always have the sources on the left side and the targets on the right side.<sep> Algorithm 2: Calculation of a set including all entries such that K[¯] k = 0<sep> TABLE 1 – Types defined for experiments<sep> 6 Experiments<sep> 6.1 Presentation of systems<sep> Our experiments focus on two tasks: paraphrase identification and textual entailment recognition.<sep> The setup we used for all experiments was the same save for the few parameters we explored such as: k, and typing scheme.<sep> We implemented 2 kernels, kb-SRK, henceforth simply denoted SRK , and the type-enriched kbSRK, denoted TESRK .<sep> The morpho-syntactic tagging is done with OpenNLP (Baldridge & G., 2010) and the words are rooted by the Porter algorithm (Porter, 2001) in the case of SRK.<sep> Various other pre-processing steps were applied in the case of TESRK: they are considered as types in the model and are detailed in Table 1.<sep> We used LIBSVM (Chang and Lin, 2011) to train a binary SVM classifier on the training data with our two kernels.<sep> The default SVM algorithm in LIBSVM uses a parameter C, roughly akin to a regularization parameter.<sep> We optimize this parameter for f-score by cross-validation on the training data.<sep> All kernels were normalized using K[˜] ( x, y ) = K ( x,y ) √K ( x,x ) [√]K ( y,y ).<sep> We denote by ”+” a sum of kernels, with normalizations applied both before and after summing.<sep> Following Bu et al. (Bu et al., 2012) experimental setup, we introduced an auxiliary vector kernel denoted PR of features named unigram precision and recall , defined in (Wan et al., 2006).<sep> In our tests, the linear kernel provided the best results.<sep> 6.2 Paraphrase identification<sep> Paraphrase identification asks whether two sentences have the same meaning.<sep> The dataset we used to evaluate our systems is the MSR Paraphrase Corpus (Dolan and Brockett, 2005), containing 4,076 training pairs of sentences and 1,725 testing pairs.<sep> For example, the sentences ”An injured woman co-worker also was hospitalized and was listed in good condition.” and ”A woman was listed in good condition at Memorial’s HealthPark campus, he said.” are paraphrases in this corpus.<sep> On the other hand, ”’There are a number of locations in our community, which are essentially vulnerable,’ Mr Ruddock said.” and ”’There are a range of risks which are being seriously examined by competent authorities,’ Mr Ruddock said.” are not paraphrases.<sep> TABLE 2 – Evaluation results on MSR Paraphrase Corpus<sep> FIGURE 3 – Evolution of the number of recursive calls to CompterCouplagesParfaits as a function of k<sep> We report in Table 2 our best results, the system TESRK + PR , defined by the sum of PR and typed-enriched kb-SRKs with k from 1 to 4, with types Γ p = Γ v = {stem, synonym} .<sep> We observe that our results are state-of-the-art and in particular, they improve on the orignal kb-SRK by a good margin.<sep> We also tried other combinations of types but it did not yield good results, this is probably due to the nature of the MSR corpus, which did not contain much more advanced variations of words.<sep> We made a special effort to try to reproduce as best as we could the original kb-SRK performances (Bu et al., 2012), although our implementation and theirs should theoretically be equivalent.<sep> Figure 3 plots the average number of recursive calls to CountPerfectMatchings (algorithm 1) during a kernel computation, as a function of k .<sep> As we have composed this number with logk , it is very easy to see if the complexity observed is closer to O ( k ) or O ( k[2] ).<sep> We observe that the complexity is linear for low values of k but seems to explode rapidly when k exceeds 7.<sep> Thankfully, counting common rewriting rules on pairs of 7-to-10-grams rarely yields non-zero results, so in practice using high values of k is not interesting.<sep> Figure 4 plots the average size of set C computed by algorithm 2, as a function of k (divided by the sum of lengths of the 4 sentences involved in the kernel computation).<sep> We can observe that this quantity is linear with respect to the size of the inputs, with a peak for small values, which is not an issue, since the calculation of K[¯] k is very fast for those values of k .<sep> 6.3 Recognizing textual involvement<sep> Figure 3: Evolution of the number of C elements produced by algorithm 2 with k<sep> Table 3: Evaluation results on RTE-3<sep> Recognizing Textual Entailment asks whether the meaning of a sentence hypothesis can be inferred by reading a sentence text .<sep> The dataset we used to evaluate our systems is RTE-3 (Dagan et al., 2006), in English.<sep> Following similar work (Heilman and Smith, 2010; Bu et al., 2012), we kept in training the whole text-hypothesis pairs of RTE-1 and 2, combined with the training data of RTE-3, which gives 3,767 sentence pairs.<sep> To test, we simply took the RTE-3 test set containing 800 sentence pairs.<sep> For example, a valid textual entailment in this dataset is the pair of sentences ”In a move widely viewed as surprising, the Bank of England raised UK interest rates from 5% to 5.25%, the highest in five years.” and ”UK interest rates went up from 5% to 5.25%.” : the first entails the second.<sep> On the other hand, the pair ”Former French president General Charles de Gaulle died in November.<sep> More than 6,000 people attended a requiem mass for him at Notre Dame cathedral in Paris.” and ”Charles de Gaulle died in 1970.” does not constitute a textual entailment.<sep> We report in Table 3 our best results, the system TESRK (All) + PR , defined by the sum of PR, 1b-SRK and typed-enriched kb-SRKs with k from 2 to 4, with types Γ p = { stem, synonym } and Γ v = { stem, synonym, hypernym, hyponym, entailment, holonym } .<sep> It seems interesting to compare our results only with systems using techniques and resources of the same nature, but we still include the best system at RTE-3 for reference (Hickl et al., 2006).<sep> This time we did not manage to fully reproduce Bu et al. 2012’s performance, but we observe that type-enriched kb-SRK greatly improves upon our original implementation of kb-SRK and outperforms their system anyway.<sep> We tried with less types in our system TESRK (Syn) + PR by removing all WordNet types but synonyms but got lower performance.<sep> This seems to indicate that a rich type system indeed helps capturing more complex sentence rewritings.<sep> Note that we needed for k = 1 to replace the type-enriched kb-SRK by the original kernel in the sum, otherwise the performance dropped significantly.<sep> Our conclusion is that including richer types is only beneficial if they are captured within a context of a couple of words.<sep> 7 Conclusion<sep> We developed a type extension for an already expressive class of sentence rewriting kernels.<sep> Types allow for an increased flexibility in counting common rewriting rules, and can also add a semantic layer to the rewritings.<sep> We have detailed an efficient method to compute the kernel of bijective string rewriting on k-grams with types.<sep> A SVM classifier with this kernel yields state-of-the-art results in paraphrase identification and textual entailment and outperforms comparable systems in recognizing textual entailment.<sep> We would like to look into the future at the applications of this core to other tasks, such as the automatic response to questions.